McCollum added 20 points on 8-of-18 shooting, while Hassan Whiteside was quiet, with eight points and five rebounds, in 23 minutes. The Trail Blazers shot 40 percent from the field, including 9-of-31 from long range. 

The Trail Blazers (23-28) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Spurs on Thursday. The Nuggets (35-16) will be right back in action, as they take on the Jazz in Utah on Wednesday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 126-102, at Staples Center on Tuesday.

While there were four ties and eight lead changes in the first quarter of this game, that was the only time it was competitive. In fact, Los Angeles rode a 30-22 second quarter to a 10-point halftime lead and held a double-digit lead for the final 14 minutes of play. In addition, the Lakers rode a 42-28 fourth quarter to this blowout scoreline. The Lakers ended up out-rebounding the Spurs, 58-28 while out-assisting them, 28-21. Los Angeles also shot 59 percent from the field while holding San Antonio to just 44 percent. 

The Spurs (22-28) were led by DeMar DeRozan, who tallied 28 points, nine rebounds and seven assists. LaMarcus Aldridge amassed just seven points and three rebounds. Bryn Forbes accrued 13 points, three assists and three steals. Dejounte Murray generated 12 points, four rebounds and two assists while Marco Belinelli and Lonnie Walker IV led the bench with 11 points apiece. 

The Lakers (38-11) were led by LeBron James and his 36 points, seven rebounds and nine assists. Anthony Davis totaled 18 points and five rebounds. JaVale McGee generated 14 points and five rebounds. Kyle Kuzma led the bench with 18 points, 12 rebounds and four assists. Rajon Rondo provided seven points and nine assists while Dwight Howard had 12 points and 11 rebounds off the bench as well. 

Both teams return to action on Thursday, with Los Angeles remaining home to face the Houston Rockets and San Antonio staying on their rodeo road trip to play the Portland Trail Blazers.

The Orlando Magic defeated the host Charlotte Hornets, 112-100, at Spectrum Center on Monday.

While this game stayed within a 10-point margin for the first three quarters, Orlando actually won each individual quarter. They did most of their damage in the second half, outscoring Charlotte, 56-46. The Magic ended up shooting 54 percent from the field and 47 percent from three-point range. The did that while out-assisting the Hornets, 35-24. 

The Magic (22-28) were led by Nikola Vucevic, who tallied 22 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Evan Fournier amassed 17 points and three boards. Aaron Gordon tallied 16 points, 12 rebounds, five assists and two steals. Markelle Fultz totaled 14 points, 12 assists and two steals. Terrence Ross led the bench with 13 points, five rebounds and two assists. 

The Hornets (16-34) were led by Terry Rozier and his 18 points, three rebounds and two assists. Cody Zeller generated 17 points, seven rebounds and two assists. Miles Bridges accrued 16 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Devonte' Graham finished with 15 points and five assists while Cody Martin led the bench with 13 points, eight rebounds, three assists and three steals. 

Charlotte has to play again on Tuesday, traveling to face the Houston Rockets. As for Orlando, they return to action on Wednesday when they face the Boston Celtics on the road as well.

The New York Knicks defeated the host Cleveland Cavaliers in overtime, 139-134, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Monday. 

There were 11 ties and 13 lead changes in this game with neither team ever leading by more than 10 points. That's why it took an overtime session to determine a winner, with the Knicks finishing the extra session on a 10-2 run to prevail. Both teams shot 56 percent from the field in this offensive showcase. The key for New York was their rebounding, winning that battle, 46-34. 

The Knicks (15-36) were led by Marcus Morris, who amassed 26 points and two boards. Elfrid Payton collected 17 points, 11 rebounds and 15 assists en route to a triple-double. Julius Randle generated 20 points, eight rebounds, three assists and two steals. Dennis Smith Jr led the bench with 15 points, three rebounds, six assists and four steals. 

The Cavaliers (13-38) were led by Kevin Love and his 33 points, 13 rebounds and six assists. Collin Sexton totaled 29 points, two rebounds and seven assists, Larry Nance Jr accrued 18 points, eight rebounds and six assists. Darius Garland finished with 14 points and five assists while Cedi Osman had 15 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

On deck for Cleveland is a road matchup versus the Oklahoma City Thunder on Wednesday. As for New York, they return home to play the Orlando Magic on Thursday for their next fixture.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the host Indiana Pacers, 112-103, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Monday evening. 

Despite missing Luka Doncic (ankle), the Mavs got out to a strong start on the road and led 25-22, after one quarter. The Pacers came out strong in the second and rallied ahead to a seven-point lead mid way through the quarter, but the Mavs brought it back to a two-point game by halftime. The Mavs came out strong in the third and rallied ahead, to the advantage for most of the quarter, before taking a five-point lead into the final frame. They continued with the momentum and pushed their lead to nine, early in the fourth. The Pacers kept it close rest of the way but could not overtake the Mavericks. This marks the second straight win for Dallas, while it marks the second straight loss for Indiana. 

Kristaps Porzingis led the Mavs with 38 points and 12 rebounds, in 36 minutes. Tim Hardaway Jr. added 25 points, five assists and four rebounds, while Dorian Finney-Smith finished with 15 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and a block. The Mavs shot 42 percent from the field, including 18-of-45 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Domantas Sabonis led the Pacers with 26 points, 12 rebounds, nine assists and a steal, in 36 minutes. Malcolm Brogdon tallied 14 points, six rebounds, three assists and a block, while Myles Turner finished with 11 points, five rebounds, three blocks and two steals. The Pacers shot 46 percent from the field, including 7-of-34 from long range. 

The Pacers (31-19) will look to bounce back as they take on the Raptors, in Toronto on Wednesday. The Mavericks (31-19) play host to the Grizzlies on Wednesday.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Washington Wizards, 125-117, at Capital One Arena on Monday evening.

The Warriors (12-39) were coming off a solid win at Cleveland the last time out, and they have extended their decent run with another victory against one of the weakest teams in the Eastern Conference such as the Wizards (17-32). Golden State dominated as soon as the ball started bouncing and quickly jumped to a 40-36 lead following the first quarter. They would boost that advantage even further in both the second (32-27) and third (27-23) quarters, so they built a 13-point lead with only 12 minutes to play. Washington won the final quarter by a 31-26 score, but that wouldn't be enough to mount a comeback in front of a 17,120 crowd at Capital One Arena. The Warriors shot 49.4 percent from the field and 50.0 percent from deep as they moved to 5-22 on the road. Meanwhile, the Wizards fell to 11-12 at home despite shooting an impressive 50.6 percent from the field.

Alec Burks led the way for the Warriors with 30 points in only 29 minutes off the bench. Glenn Robinson III ended with 22 points, seven assists and six rebounds, and Damion Lee chipped in with 19 points and six assists. Marquese Chriss contributed 13 points, five rebounds and two blocks, while Draymond Green filled the stat sheet with 12 points, 10 boards, seven assists, two steals and one block. Eric Paschall had 14 points and 10 boards off the bench.

Bradley Beal was the highest-scoring player in the game since he notched 43 points while shooting 15-30 from the field, and he also added six assists, two rebounds and two steals. Davis Bertans thrived off the bench since he chipped in with 19 points, five dimes and four boards. Rookie Rui Hachimura posted an 11-point, eight-rebound effort. Thomas Bryant had 11 points and seven rebounds off the bench.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 123-115, at State Farm Arena on Monday night.

The Hawks (13-38) came into the contest as clear underdogs, but they jumped on the Celtics (34-15) early to take a 34-28 first-quarter lead. However, Boston  came back to outscore their hosts in the middle periods, 67-50, to take an 11-point advantage into the fourth edge. Atlanta would then get as close as 110-107 with 3:57 remaining before the visitors finished on a 13-8 run to secure the road victory.

Jayson Tatum led the Celtics with 28 points, adding seven rebounds, three assists and one steal. Gordon Hayward provided 24 points, seven boards, six assists and one block. Jaylen Brown totaled 21 points, five rebounds and one steal. Brad Wanamaker supplied 16 points, five assists, three rebounds and four steals. Grant Williams registered 13 points, six rebounds, two assists, two blocks and one steal. 

Trae Young paced the Hawks with 34 points, supplementing them with seven assists, three rebounds and two steals. Kevin Huerter furnished 23 points, three rebounds and two assists. John Collins generated a 22-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included three assists, two blocks and one steal. Jeff Teague delivered 18 points, six assists, one rebound and four steals. 

The Celtics return home to face the Orlando Magic on Wednesday night, while the Hawks visit the Minnesota Timberwolves on Wednesday night as well.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Phoenix Suns, 119-97, at Barclays Center on Monday night.

The Nets (22-27) had to face the Suns (20-30) without Kyrie Irving but that didn't seem to matter, as the Nets cruised their way against a depleted Phoenix team and won rather easily in front of a 14,891 crowd at Barclays Center. Brooklyn quickly jumped to a 35-31 lead in the first quarter, and they would never look back afterwards. Even though the Suns won the second quarter by a 21-20 score, the Nets ran away with the game in the final two quarters -- winning 35-21 and 29-24 in the third and fourth quarters, respectively. The Nets continue to underperform and now own a 4-7 record in their last 11 games, but this was a promising performance as they moved to 14-12 at home after shooting 48.3 percent from the field and 44.1 percent from three-point range. Meanwhile, the Suns shot 43.3 percent from the field and 35.3 percent from three-point range while falling to 11-13 on the road.

Caris LeVert led the way for the Nets in this game, as he finished with 29 points, seven assists, three rebounds and two steals. Spencer Dinwiddie might have shot just 4-12 from the field, but he chipped in with 14 points, four dimes and three boards. Taurean Prince had 15 points and six rebounds, while Joe Harris notched 16 points. Timothy Luwawu-Cabarrot contributed 13 points and three rebounds in 25 minutes off the bench.

DeAndre Ayton ended with 25 points, 17 rebounds and five assists in 34 minutes of action. Ricky Rubio, who was questionable due to an ankle problem, contributed eight points while logging just 19 minutes. Devin Booker had 11 points while shooting a woeful 3-15 from the field. Kelly Oubre Jr. had 21 points and five boards in 38 minutes of action.

The Miami Heat defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 137-106, at American Airlines Arena on Monday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, but the Heat pulled ahead to take a four-point lead into the second quarter. The score stayed tight through the second, with multiple lead changes, before the Heat reclaimed a four-point lead by halftime. The Heat came out on another level in the third, as they outscored the visitors 41-25, to build a 20-point lead heading into the final frame. They kept the pressure on the in fourth, where they poured in another 40 points to leave no doubts about their second straight win, while this marks the third straight loss for Philly. 

Jimmy Butler led the way against his former squad, with 38 points, seven rebounds, three steals and two assists, in 29 minutes. Bam Adebayo added 18 points, 11 assists, eight rebounds and a steal, while Duncan Robinson added 19 points, three assists and two rebounds. The Heat shot 56 percent from the field, including 16-of-32 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Joel Embiid led the 76ers with 29 points, 12 rebounds and a steal, in 33 minutes. Ben Simmons added 16 points, eight rebounds and seven assists, while Mike Scott chipped in 17 points, off the bench. The 76ers shot 43 percent from the field, including 34 percent from deep. 

The Sixers (31-20) will look to bounce back as they take on the Bucks in Milwaukee on Thursday. The Heat (34-15) head to L.A. to battle the Clippers on Wednesday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Detroit Pistons, 96-82, at FedEx Forum on Monday night. 

The Grizzlies (25-25) and Pistons (18-34) both came out of the gates hot, leading to a combined 68 points being scored in the first quarter. Each squad then clamped down on defense in the second quarter, which produced a 53-53 deadlock at the half. Memphis would successfully separate in the second half, however, beginning by holding Detroit to a jaw-dropping 10 points in the third and following it up by adding another five points to their edge over the final 12 minutes.

Andre Drummond led the Pistons with a 25-point, 18-rebound double-double that also included four assists. Christian Wood and Langston Galloway generated matching 17-point tallies, with Wood also pulling down five rebounds. Bruce Brown produced 12 points, seven boards, four assists and one steal. 

Jonas Valanciunas paced the Grizzlies with 26 points, complementing them with 17 rebounds, two assists and four blocks. Dillon Brooks supplied 15 points, five assists, four rebounds and one block. Jaren Jackson, Jr. totaled 14 points, five boards, two assists, three blocks and one steal. Tyus Jones furnished 13 points, five assists, two rebounds and one steal. Ja Morant generated 12 points, seven assists and four rebounds.

The Pistons head back home to take on the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday night, while the Grizzlies visit the Dallas Mavericks on Wednesday night.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 113-109, at Golden 1 Center on Monday night.

The Kings (19-31) appeared set to make the second half a formality with their performance over the first two quarters, as they racked up 65 points while limiting the visiting Timberwolves (15-34) to 50. However, they began to see that 15-point halftime lead evaporate during a third quarter in which Minnesota put a six-point dent in its deficit, and the T-Wolves eventually would get as close as 112-109 with 4.7 seconds remaining in the contest after a Robert Covington three-pointer. Andrew Wiggins would go on to miss a 27-foot three-point jumper with 0.5 seconds left that would essentially seal the win for Sacramento.

Karl-Anthony Towns led the the Timberwolves with a 22-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included six assists, two blocks and one steal. Shabazz Napier supplied 17 points, seven assists and three rebounds. Covington registered 15 points, eight boards, two assists, three steals and one block. Kelan Martin and Josh Okogie posted matching 12-point tallies while pulling down five and four rebounds, respectively. Wiggins mustered 10 points, six rebounds, five assists, one steal and one block.

De'Aaron Fox paced the Kings with 31 points, complementing them with five assists, three rebounds and two steals. Bogdan Bogdanovic followed with 23 points, three assists and two rebounds. Buddy Hield totaled 16 points, three assists, two rebounds and one steal. Harrison Barnes posted 14 points, seven assists and five rebounds. Nemanja Bjelica delivered 12 points, three rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block.

The Timberwolves head back home to take on the Atlanta Hawks on Wednesday night, while the Kings are home against the Miami Heat on Friday night.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 108-105, at Staples Center on Monday.

While San Antonio led 102-97 with 3:04 remaining, Los Angeles finished the game on an 11-3 run to prevail. In fact, they overcame a 15-point second quarter deficit in this game, thanks to a 14-2 run to start the second half. With that said, there were 10 ties and 21 lead changes in this closely-fought game. The Clippers ended up winning the defensive rebounding battle, 46-40, while out-assisting the Spurs, 28-21. Los Angeles shot 46 percent from the field and 41 percent from three-point range while holding San Antonio to 42 percent from the field and 32 percent fro long range.

The Sours (22-27) were led by LaMarcus Aldridge and his 27 points, nine rebounds, five assists and two blocks. DeMar DeRozan accrued 26 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. Patty Mills led the bench with 18 points, two rebounds and two assists. Derrick White also provided four points, eight rebounds and six assists off the bench as well.

The Clippers (35-15) were led by Kawhi Leonard, who tallied 22 points, six rebounds, seven assists and two blocks. Paul George collected 19 points, 12 rebounds and eight assists. Patrick Beverley accrued 12 points, four rebounds and five assists. Lou Williams and Montrezl Harrell each scored in double figures off the bench. 

San Antonio has to play again on Tuesday, remaining in California to face the Los Angeles Lakers. As for the Clippers, they remain home to face the Miami Heat on Wednesday for their next fixture.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the Denver Nuggets, 128-123, at Little Caesars Arena on Sunday afternoon.

The Pistons (18-33) and the Nuggets (34-16) opened Sunday's slate and the game surpassed expectations. While Denver was the favorite on paper, Detroit fought all game long and ended winning after a thrilling overtime period. The game went back and forth, though. Denver quickly jumped to a massive 44-30 lead following the first quarter, but Detroit flipped the script with a 38-21 second quarter that gave them a three-point lead. The Nuggets, however, won both quarters after the second half (24-22 and 22-21) to extend the game into overtime. The Pistons were sharper during the final five minutes of action, though, and sealed the win rather comfortably.

Andre Drummond led the way for Detroit after notching 21 points and 17 rebounds before fouling out. Sekou Doumbouya chipped in with 17 points and five boards, while Tony Snell had 13 points and six assists. Reggie Jackson had 20 points and six dimes off the bench, while Christian Wood added 11 points. Bruce Brown flirted with a triple-double off the bench with 19 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists. Derrick Rose only had two points as a starter.

Nikola Jokic was Denver's focal point on offense once again and thrived, as he finished with 39 points, 11 assists and 10 boards. Will Barton had 20 points, nine rebounds and five dimes. Monte Morris added 19 points, seven assists and seven rebounds. Jerami Grant posted 14 points, and Malik Beasley chipped in with 12 points off the bench.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 117-109, at Toyota Center on Sunday evening. 

The Pelicans got out to a good start on the road, with an early 16-7 lead, but the Rockets battled back to take a two-point lead by the end of the quarter. The Pelicans kept it close through the second, but the Rockets held on to take five-point lead into halftime. The Pelicans started the third on a 7-0 run to take an edge, and they held the advantage for most of the quarter, before taking a one-point lead into the final frame. The Rockets picked up the intensity in the fourth and outscored the visitors 25-16 in the quarter, to walk away with their second straight win. 

James Harden led the Rockets with 40 points, 10 rebounds, nine assists and two blocks, in 39 minutes. Russell Westbrook added 22 points, seven assists, six rebounds and a steal, while Ben McLemore added 22 points on 6-of-12 shooting. The Rockets shot 39 percent from the field, including 16-of-51 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Brandon Ingram led the Pelicans with 28 points, 12 rebounds and three assists, in 38 minutes. Zion Williamson addled 21 points, 10 rebounds, a steal and a block, while Lonzo Ball tallied 10 points, 11 rebounds, nine assists, three steals and two blocks. The Pelicans shot 45 percent from the field, including 10-of-33 from long range. 

The Pelicans (20-30) will look to bounce back as they host the Bucks on Tuesday. The Rockets (31-18) play host to the Hornets on Tuesday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Phoenix Suns, 129-108, at Fiserv Forum on Sunday afternoon.

The interconference battle between two teams with disparate records started competitively enough, with the Bucks (42-7) holding just a four-point lead through the first 12 minutes. However, Milwaukee then added another 11 points to its advantage over the Suns (20-29) before halftime, which essentially put the game away. The second half saw Phoenix put up more of a fight, but ultimately the hosts still outscored them by a 62-56 margin over the final pair of quarters.

Devin Booker paced the Suns with 32 points, complementing them with seven rebounds and six assists. Deandre Ayton followed with a 20-point, 14-rebound double-double that also included two assists, one steal and one block. Kelly Oubre, Jr. and Jevon Carter produced matching 15-point tallies, with Oubre pulled down 10 rebounds. Cheick Diallo managed 11 points, seven rebounds and one assist. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 30 points, 19 rebounds, nine assists, one steal and one block. Khris Middleton supplied 25 points, eight rebounds, six assists and one block. Brook Lopez registered 17 points, four rebounds, one assist and nine blocks. Donte DiVincenzo furnished 15 points, two rebounds, one assist and two steals. Eric Bledsoe checked in with 12 points, seven boards, four assists and one block.

The Suns remain on the road and face the Brooklyn Nets on Monday night, while the Bucks visit the New Orleans Pelicans on Tuesday night.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the visiting Chicago Bulls, 129-102, at Scotia Bank Arena on Sunday.

While there were seven ties and 10 lead changes in the first 30 minutes of this game, Toronto rode a 35-22 third quarter to their victory. In fact, that allowed them to hold a double-digit lead for the entirety of the fourth quarter, carrying a 34-17 fourth quarter to a 27-point blowout. The Raptors ended up shooting 56 percent from the field and 47 percent fro three-point range while holding the Bulls to 39 percent from the field and 31 percent from long range. In addition, Toronto won the defensive rebounding battle, 34-24, while outscoring their bench, 66-30. 

The Bulls (19-33) were led by Thaddeus Young, who amassed 21 points, seven rebounds and two steals on 9-of-12 from the field. Zach LaVine collected 18 points, seven rebounds, seven assists and three steals. Chandler Hutchison totaled 17 points and five rebounds. Tomas Satoransky accrued eight points, five rebounds and five assists. 

The Raptors (36-14) were led by Terence Davis, who came off the bench to provide a career-high 31 points on 12-of-15 shooting. Pascal Siakam led the starters with 17 points, nine rebounds and five assists. Serge Ibaka generated 16 points, six rebounds and three blocks. Kyle Lowry accumulated 14 points, four rebounds and six assists while Fred VanVleet finished with 12 points, four rebounds and eight assists. 

On deck for Toronto is a home matchup versus the Indiana Pacers on Wednesday. As for Chicago, they're off until Thursday when they return home to face the New Orleans Pelicans.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 118-106, at Staples Center on Saturday afternoon.

The Clippers (34-15) came out of the gates highly efficient on offense, as they compiled 40 points in the first quarter alone. Los Angeles held an 18-point advantage at the half over the Timberwolves (15-33), and by adding five points to their advantage in the third, they essentially sealed the victory. 

Karl-Anthony Towns paced the Timberwolves with 32 points, complementing them with 12 rebounds, three assists and one block. Josh Okogie and Andrew Wiggins generated matching 13-point tallies while pulling down six and five rebounds, respectively. Robert Covington provided 12 points, five boards, three steals and two blocks. Shabazz Napier posted an 11-point, 10-assist double-double that also included four rebounds and two steals.

Kawhi Leonard led the Clippers with 31 points, complementing them with six rebounds and four assists. Paul George delivered 21 points, seven rebounds, two assists, two steals and one block. Lou Williams poured in 17 points and supplemented them with six assists, four rebounds and one steal. Montrezl Harrell managed 16 points, six rebounds, one steal and one block. Patrick Beverley checked in with 12 points, five boards, four assists, one steal and one block. 

The Timberwolves will remain on the road and next visit the Sacramento Kings on Monday night, while the Clippers remain home and take on the San Antonio Spurs on Monday night as well.

The New York Knicks defeated the Indiana Pacers, 92-85, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Saturday night.

The Knicks (14-36) came into the contest notably short-handed at point guard and facing one of the best home-floor teams in the NBA in the Pacers (31-18). However, New York established the tone with a dominant first quarter that they emerged from with a 13-point lead, and they still owned an 11-point edge at halftime. Indiana finally seemed to come to life in the third, wiping out all but one point from their deficit during the third quarter. However, after the hosts battled back to knot the score at 80 with 6:11 remaining, the Knicks finished on a 12-5 run to secure the win.

Marcus Morris led the Knicks with 28 points, complementing them with six rebounds and one steal. Julius Randle generated a 16-point, 18-rebound double-double that also included three assists and two steals. Taj Gibson turned in 10 points, seven rebounds and one assist. Damyean Dotson led the bench with eight points, while Dennis Smith, Jr. started at point guard and contributed seven points, four rebounds and two assists.

Domantas Sabonis led the Pacers with 25 points, supplementing them with eight rebounds and two assists. Myles Turner registered 12 points, six rebounds, one assist and one steal. Jeremy Lamb totaled nine points and two boards. Malcolm Brogdon furnished eight points, 12 assists and seven rebounds. 

The Knicks remain on the road and take on the Cleveland Cavaliers on Monday night, while the Pacers remain home and face the Dallas Mavericks on Monday night as well.

The Miami Heat defeated the Orlando Magic, 102-89, at Amway Center on Saturday night.

The Heat (33-15) and Magic (21-28) played a closely contested first half for the most part, but Miami owned a 57-49 lead by halftime. The visitors managed to add another point to their advantage during the third period, which would prove to be more than enough for the comfortable road victory. Neither team shot particularly well overall, but the Heat managed to drain an impressive 45.5 percent of their three-point attempts.

Jimmy Butler led the Heat with 24 points, complementing them with three rebounds, three assists, one steal and one block. Tyler Herro followed with 23 points and three boards. Meyers Leonard produced an 18-point, 14-rebound double-double that also included one assist. Goran Dragic provided 11 points and six boards. Bam Adebayo mustered just four points but also posted 14 rebounds, five assists, four blocks and three steals.

Aaron Gordon paced the Magic with 24 points and added five boards, one assist and two steals. Nikola Vucevic delivered 21 points, nine rebounds, four assists and two blocks. Evan Fournier totaled 12 points, four assists, one rebound and two steals. Markelle Fultz supplied 11 points, six assists, four rebounds and one steal. Michael Carter-Williams led the bench with 10 points.

The Heat return home to face the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday night, while the Magic hit the road and tangle with the Charlotte Hornets on Monday night as well.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 131-112, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Saturday evening. 

The contest got out to a hot start, as the Cavaliers held on to a 32-31 lead after one quarter. The pace kept up through the second, while the Warriors pulled ahead, as they outscore the host by three points in the quarter, to take a two-point lead into halftime. The story changed direction in the third, as the Warriors came out on fire and outscored the Cavaliers by 25 points in the quarter, to take a 27-point lead into the final frame. The Cavs put up a fight in the fourth and outscored the visitors by eight points in the quarter, but they could not avoid their third straight loss. 

Glenn Robinson III led the Warriors with 22 points on 9-of-13 shooting. D'Angelo Russell added 19 points, eight assists and seven rebounds, while Draymond Green totaled eight points, seven rebounds, 16 assists, two steals and two blocks. The Warriors shot 53 percent from the field, including 18-of-35 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Collin Sexton led the Cavs with 23 points, four assists, two rebounds and three steals, in 33 minutes. Kevin Love totaled 14 points, 11 rebounds, five assists and a steal, while Kevin Porter Jr. added 18 points, three rebounds and two assists. The Cavaliers shot 43 percent from the field, including 16-of-44 from long range. 

The Cavs (13-37) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Knicks on Monday. The Warriors (11-39) take on the Wizards in Washington on Monday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 113-107, at Capital One Arena on Saturday night.

The Nets (21-27) could hardly have gotten off to a better start, as they forged a nine-point lead through the first 12 minutes with a 36-point first quarter. The Wizards (17-31) began their comeback in the second quarter, however, erasing all but two points from their deficit during the second period. Brooklyn managed to emerge from the third with a slim three-point lead intact, and they were ahead by as much as nine with 7:34 remaining. Washington then mounted a furious rally that would propel them to victory, finishing on a 23-8 run that saw them take the lead for good with 2:13 left.

Spencer Dindwiddie led the Nets with 26 points, complementing them with six assists, four rebounds and one steal. Joe Harris delivered 22 points, three rebounds and three assists. Garrett Temple supplied 17 points, five rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Jarrett Allen generated a 13-point, 15-rebound double-double that also included five assists and two blocks. Kyrie Irving delivered 11 points, four rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block before exiting due to a knee sprain with 5:29 remaining.

Bradley Beal paced the Wizards with 34 points, supplementing them with six rebounds, two assists, three steals and three blocks. Thomas Bryant posted a 17-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one block. Isaiah Thomas turned in 12 points, three assists and two rebounds. Davis Bertans finished with 11 points, seven rebounds, three assists, one steal and one block. Ish Smith matched Bertans' scoring and also posted five boards and four assists.

The Nets remain home and take on the Phoenix Suns on Monday night, while the Wizards remain home to tangle with the Golden State Warriors on Monday night as well.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Charlotte Hornets, 114-90, at AT&T Center on Saturday.

While Charlotte took a 13-point lead into the half, San Antonio rode a monster second half to a blowout victory. In fact, they rode a 29-11 third quarter to recapture the lead and capped off their comeback victory with a 35-16 fourth quarter. The Spurs ended up shooting 52 percent from the field while holding the Hornets to 42 percent shooting. In addition, San Antonio out-rebounded Charlotte, 45-36, while winning the turnover battle, 16-10. Much of that can be attributed to the Spurs recording 12 steals and the Hornets having just five. 

The Hornets (16-33) were led by Miles Bridges, who tallied 25 points, six rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Cody Zeller accumulated 14 points, 12 rebounds and eight assists. Terry Rozier generated 10 points, five rebounds and three assists while DeVonte' Graham amassed eight points, nine assists and two steals. 

The Spurs (22-26) were led by DeMar DeRozan and his 24 points, three rebounds and six assists. Dejounte Murray totaled nine points, 10 rebounds, two assists and four steals. LaMarcus Aldridge had eight points, seven rebounds and two assists while Jakob Poeltl led the bench with 17 points, seven rebounds and two steals. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Charlotte returning home to face the Orlando Magic and San Antonio traveling to face the volatile Sacramento Kings.

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 116-95, at TD Garden on Saturday evening. 

The Celtics got out to a great start at home, with a 32-19 lead after one quarter. The Celtics maintained a double-digit lead through most of the second quarter, but the 76ers managed to cut it to an eight-point game by halftime. The Celtics came out strong in the third and outscored the visitors by 11 points in the quarter, to take a 19-point in the final frame. The Celtics stayed in control through the fourth and pushed their lead to 23 points, with three minutes left in the contest. This marks the third straight win for the Celtics and the second straight loss for the 76ers. 

Jaylen Brown led the Celtics with 32 points, nine rebounds and two steals, in 34 minutes. Jayson Tatum added 25 points, four assists, three rebounds, a steal and a block, while Marcus Smart chipped in 16 points, four rebounds, four rebounds and two steals. The Celtics shot 48 percent from the field, including 8-of-30 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Ben Simmons led the Sixers with 23 points, nine rebounds, five assists and a steal, in 37 minutes. Furkan Korkmaz added 14 points, four rebounds, two assists and a steal, while Joel Embiid was quiet with 11 points, five rebounds and two blocks, in 23 minutes. The 76ers shot 37 percent from the field, including 7-of-33 from long range. 

The 76ers (31-19) look to bounce back as they take on the Heat in Miami on Monday. The Celtics (33-15) take on the Hawks in Atlanta on Monday.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 123-100, at American Airlines Center on Saturday evening. 

Despite missing Luka Doncic (ankle) and Kristaps Porzingis (rest), the Mavericks got out to a great start at home and held on for the impressive home win. They led by 10 points after one quarter and maintained control through the second to carry a 13-point lead into halftime. The Cavs came out strong again in the third quarter and outscored the Hawks by 12 points in the quarter, to take a convincing 25-point lead into the final frame. The Hawks kept up their fight in the fourth but it was not enough, as the Mavs held on to end a two-game slide. 

Jalen Brunson led the Mavericks with 27 points, eight assists and four rebounds, in 27 minutes. Dorian Finney-Smith added 22 points, seven rebounds, four assists, two steals and a block, while Seth Curry chipped in 15 points, six rebounds and two assists. The Mavericks shot 47 percent from the field, including 20-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, John Collins led the Hawks with 26 points and 11 rebounds, in 33 minutes. Kevin Huerter added 20 points, three assists and a steal, while Trae Young finished with 12 points and six rebounds. The Hawks shot 41 percent from the field, including 10-of-33 from long range. Trae Young (ankle) and Cam Reddish (face) were both forced to leave the game early. 

The Hawks (13-37) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Celtics on Monday. The Mavericks (30-19) take on the Pacers in Indiana on Monday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 129-113, at Golden 1 Center on Saturday.

Los Angeles rode an 81-point first half to their victory, shooting 60 percent from the field and 58 percent from three-point range in that first half while recording 26 assists. For the game, the Lakers shot 51 percent from the field and 44 percent from long range while recording 33 total assists. They did that while holding the Kings to just 43 percent from the field, 32 percent from long distance and 21 assists. That allowed the Lakers to pick up a wire-to-wire win, leading by at least 14 points for the entirety of the second half. In addition, Los Angeles recorded 10 steals while winning the turnover differential, 16-14. 

The Lakers (37-11) were led by Anthony Davis and his 21 points, four rebounds, six assists and two steals. LeBron James finished with 15 points, 10 rebounds, 11 assists and two steals. Avery Bradley totaled 19 points and two boards. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope led the bench with 15 points, two rebounds and two assists while Rajon Rondo amassed 13 points and eight assists. 

The Kings (18-31) were led by De'Aaron Fox, who accumulated 24 points, six rebounds and five assists. Harry Giles played just 16 minutes but provided 16 points and eight boards. Buddy Hield led the bench with 22 points, four rebounds and two assists. Cory Joseph accrued nine points, six rebounds and five assists off the bench as well.

On deck for Sacramento is a home matchup against the Minnesota Timberwolves on Monday. The Kings actually overcame a 17-point deficit in the final three minutes against Minnesota last week in an overtime victory. As for Los Angeles. they play host to the San Antonio Spurs on Tuesday for their next fixture.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the visiting Utah Jazz, 124-107, at Moda Center on Saturday.

A 30-19 second quarter was the difference for Portland in this game, holding the lead for the entirety of the second half. In fact, they led by at least 11 points for the whole of the fourth quarter. The Trail Blazers shot 51 percent from the field and 52 percent from three-point range while holding the Jazz to 43 percent from the field and 44 percent from long range. In addition, Portland ended up out-rebounding Utah, 51-37. The Trail Blazers also doubled up the Jazz in free-throw attempts, 18-9. 

The Jazz (32-17) have now lost four-straight games, as Donovan Mitchell led the team with 25 points, two rebounds and four assists. Mike Conley accrued 22 points, four rebounds and four assists. Bojan Bogdanovic generated 22 points and two boards. Rudy Gobert amassed six points, 11 rebounds, two assists and three blocks. 

The Trail Blazers (23-27) got another gem from Damian Lillard, who collected 51 points and 12 assists on 17-of-29 from the field. Hassan Whiteside totaled 17 points, 21 rebounds and three blocks. Carmelo Anthony had 15 points and five rebounds while C.J. McCollum accumulated 14 points, three rebounds and two assists. 

Utah will look to end their four-game slide on Wednesday when they play host to the Denver Nuggets. Portland returns to action on Tuesday, traveling to face the same Nuggets team.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Detroit Pistons, 105-92, at Little Caesars Arena on Friday night.

The red-hot Raptors (35-14) set the tone early, forging a 10-point lead through one that they extended to 13 by halftime. The Pistons (17-33) played strong defense in the third and put a four-point dent into their deficit in the process, but Toronto retained control and made those points back up over the final 12 minutes to notch the double-digit road win. 

Pascal Siakam led the way for the Raptors with 30 points, adding seven rebounds, four assists and one block. Serge Ibaka furnished 21 points, six rebounds and three assists. Fred VanVleet bounced back from a rough shooting night Thursday to post 16 points, nine assists, eight rebounds and two steals. Norman Powell chipped in 12 points, seven boards, one assist, three steals and one block. Kyle Lowry mustered just seven points on 2-for-9 shooting.

Derrick Rose paced the Pistons with 21 points, supplementing them with three assists. Andre Drummond generated a 20-point, 20-rebound double-double that also included one assist and one steal. Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk poured in 13 points and also provided four rebounds and two assists. 

The Raptors head back home to face the Chicago Bulls on Sunday afternoon, while the Pistons remain home to take on the Denver Nuggets on Sunday afternoon as well.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Chicago Bulls, 133-118, at Barclays Center on Friday night.

The Nets (21-26) hit the ground running against the Bulls (19-32), jumping out to a 35-23 first-quarter lead. Brooklyn owned a 16-point advantage by halftime, and although Chicago managed to rack up 39 points in a third quarter during which they put a nine-point dent in their deficit, the 8-2 run the home squad opened the final period with essentially sealed the win. Kyrie Irving spearheaded the victory with a season-high 54 points. 

Zach LaVine paced the Bulls with 22 points, adding eight assists, two rebounds and one steal. Luke Kornet supplied 19 points, four rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Tomas Satoransky registered 15 points, eight assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block. Thaddeus Young delivered 14 points, four assists, two rebounds and one steal. Shaquille Harrison managed 12 points, while Coby White poured in 11.

Irving complemented his aforementioned game-high scoring tally with five rebounds, five assists and one steal. Spencer Dinwiddie totaled 20 points, seven assists, one rebound and one block. Taurean Price furnished 16 points, eight boards and three assists. Jarrett Allen contributed 12 points, five rebounds, five assists, two blocks and one steal. Garrett Temple netted 11.

The Bulls next pay a visit to the Toronto Raptors on Sunday afternoon, while the Nets hit the road and tangle with the Washington Wizards on Saturday night.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Dallas Mavericks, 128-121, at Toyota Center on Friday night.

A highly competitive first half culminated with the Rockets (30-18) holding a 65-60 halftime lead over the Mavericks (29-19). However, Houston seemed to take control for good by adding 11 points to its advantage during the third, but Dallas gave the hosts a scare by getting as close as 115-111 with 3:08 remaining. Ultimately, the Rockets were able to close matters out with a 13-10 run the rest of the way for the hard-fought home victory.

Kristaps Porzingis led the way for the Mavericks with 35 points, complementing them with 12 rebounds, two steals and one block. Seth Curry delivered 16 points, four assists and two rebounds. Tim Hardaway, Jr. delivered 15 points, four assists, and three rebounds. Dorian Finney-Smith totaled 12 points, eight rebounds and three assists. J.J. Barea managed 11 points, nine assists and five rebounds. Delon Wright compiled 10 points, three assists and two rebounds. 

James Harden paced the Rockets with 35 points, supplementing them with 16 rebounds, six assists and four steals. Russell Westbrook followed with 32 points, adding nine assists, six rebounds and three steals. Eric Gordon supplied 17 points, four assists, one rebound and one block. Danuel House, Jr. offered 14 points, three rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Ben McLemore poured in 13 points.

The Mavericks return home to take on the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday night, while the Rockets remain home and host the New Orleans Pelicans on Sunday afternoon.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the visiting Memphis Grizzlies, 139-111, at Smoothie King Center on Friday evening. 

The Pelicans got out to a great start at home with a 31-22 lead after one quarter. The pace picked up in the second, where they Grizzlies outscored the Pelicans 37-35, to cut it to a seven-point game by halftime. The Pelicans took it to another level in the third, as they outscored the visitors 44-27 in the quarter, to take a 24-point lead into the final frame. They stayed in control through the fourth and held on for their third straight win. 

Zion Williamson led the Pelicans with 24 points, six rebounds and three assists, in 29 minutes. Brandon Ingram added 20 points, seven rebounds, four assists and a steal, while Lonzo Ball finished with 19 points, eight assists, six rebounds and a steal. The Pelicans shot 54 percent from the field, including 15-of-34 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Jonas Valanciunas led the Grizzlies with 18 points, eight rebounds, four blocks and a steal, in 27 minutes. Ja Morant added 16 points and three assists, while Jae Crowder totalled 15 points, five rebounds and two steals. The Grizzlies shot 47 percent from the field, but they struggled from long range, where they went 6-of-31. 

The Grizzlies (24-25) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Pistons on Monday. The Pelicans (20-29) take on the Rockets in Houston on Monday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Milwaukee Bucks, 127-115, at Fiserv Forum on Friday evening. 

The contest got out to a hot start, while the Bucks powered their way to a 43-35 lead after one quarter. Things slowed down in the second, where the Nuggets outscored the hosts by one, to cut it to a seven-point game by halftime. The Nuggets came out on fire in the third quarter and poured in 40 points, while holding the Nuggets to 24 in the quarter, to take a 100-91 lead into the final frame. The Nuggets stayed in control down the stretch, as the Bucks had trouble cutting the deficit to single digits. This marks the second straight win for the Nuggets, while it marks the end of nine-game winning streak for the Bucks. 

Nine players scored in double digits for the Nuggets, led by Will Barton, who finished with 24 points, eight assists, seven rebounds and a steal, in 34 minutes. Nikola Jokic added 15 points, 10 rebounds, nine assists and a steal, while Malik Beasley added 16 points, four rebounds and two steals, off the bench. The Nuggets shot 48 percent from the field, including 22-of-46 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 31 points, 16 rebounds, nine assists, two blocks and a steal, in 32 minutes. Khris Middleton followed up with 24 points, nine assists and two rebounds, while Eric Bledsoe added 15 points, seven assists, three rebounds and two steals. The Bucks shot 45 percent from the field, including 12-of-40 from deep. 

The Bucks (41-7) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Suns on Sunday. The Nuggets (34-15) take on the Pistons in Detroit on Sunday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 111-107, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Friday. 

It's rare to see a game where neither team leads by more than 10 points but that was the case here. In fact, there were nine ties and 21 lead changes in total. Phoenix actually led 99-92 with 4:06 remaining but Oklahoma City scored 13 unanswered points to take control and prevail. In addition, the Thunder forced the Suns to miss eight of their final nine shots in that span while forcing two turnovers. Ball movement was the difference in the game, with the Thunder recording 26 assists to 12 turnovers while the Suns had 20 assists to 21 turnovers.  

The Thunder (30-20) were led by Danilo Gallinari, who amassed 27 points and four rebounds. Chris Paul collected 20 points, six rebounds, 10 assists and three steals. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander totaled 12 points, nine rebounds and four assists. Dennis Schroder led the bench with 24 points, four rebounds, six assists and two steals. 

The Suns (20-28) were led by Devin Booker, who generated 27 points, three rebounds and five assists. Kelly Oubre Jr matched those 27 points, adding 12 rebounds and two steals to his line. Deandre Ayton tallied 16 points, six rebounds and three blocks. Ricky Rubio had eight points, two rebounds, seven assists and two steals. 

On deck for Phoenix is a road matchup against the Milwaukee Bucks on Sunday. As for Oklahoma City, they're off until Wednesday when they return home to play the Cleveland Cavaliers.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the host Los Angeles Lakers, 127-119, at Staples Center on Friday. 

In the first game at Staples Center since the passing of Kobe Bryant, the Lakers could not prevail in what was an emotional game. With that said, there were 15 ties and 17 lead changes across the first 30 minutes, with Portland riding a 43-34 third quarter to victory. In fact, that allowed them to lead by at least four points for the entirety of the fourth quarter. The Trail Blazers ended up forcing 17 turnovers from the Lakers while committing just five on their end. That allowed Portland to shoot 51 percent from the field while holding Los Angeles below 47 percent.

The Trail Blazers (22-27) were led by Damian Lillard and his 48 points, nine rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Hassan Whiteside went 12-of-13 from the field to collect 30 points, 12 rebounds, two assists, two steals and five blocks. C.J. McCollum totaled 19 points, six rebounds and five assists. Trevor Ariza recorded five steals as well. 

The Lakers (36-11) were led by Anthony Davis, who tallied 37 points, 15 rebounds, six assists and five blocks. LeBron James amassed 22 points, eight rebounds and 10 assists. Kyle Kuzma came off the bench to provide 17 points and 15 rebounds. Avery Bradley accumulated 10 points, five rebounds and two assists. 

Los Angeles has to play again on Saturday, traveling to face the Sacramento Kings, Portland also plays again on Saturday, returning home to play the Utah Jazz.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 115-109, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Thursday evening.

The Raptors (34-14) and the Cavaliers (13-36) played a tight game and while many expected Toronto to dominate since they entered this matchup on an eight-game winning streak, they had to work harder than expected to get past a tough-as-nails Cleveland team. It seemed Toronto would cruise their way after jumping to a five-point lead after the first quarter, but Cleveland shortened the gap at the half-time break following a 26-25 second quarter. The Raptors extended their lead after a 32-24 third quarter and many believe the game was over with 12 minutes left on the clock. Cleveland worked hard in the final minutes and won the final quarter by a 33-27 score, but that wasn't enough and the Raptors sealed the win. Toronto shot 48.8 percent from the field and moved to 17-7 on the road, while the Cavaliers fell to 6-19 at home. Cleveland shot only 36.1 percent from deep in this game.

Serge Ibaka came out of nowhere for the Raptors and led the team offensively with 26 points while shooting 10-14 from the field. Pascal Siakam added 19 points but also filled the stat sheet with five rebounds, four steals and two assists. Kyle Lowry had 23 points with five rebounds, five assists and four steals. Fred VanVleet only scored eight points, but he added seven rebounds and 12 dimes. Norman Powell contributed 16 points off the bench.

Kevin Love and Collin Sexton each led the Cavaliers with 23 points -- while Love also added five rebounds and four assists, Sexton also chipped in with four rebounds and four dimes. Tristan Thompson grabbed 12 boards, but he only scored two points. Darius Garland chipped in with 16 points, eight assists and five rebounds. Larry Nance Jr. and Kevin Porter Jr. each added 13 points off the bench.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 121-107, at Capital One Arena on Thursday night.

The Hornets (16-32) got off to a surprisingly quick start against the defensively challenged Wizards (16-31), building a 33-26 first-quarter lead. However, Washington started its comeback in the second chipping two points off their deficit before intermission and then changing the dynamic of the game altogether by outscoring Charlotte, 31-19, in the third quarter. That gave the hosts a seven-point advantage heading into the final period, one they wouldn't relinquish.

Miles Bridges led the Hornets with 23 points, complementing them with six rebounds, three assists and two steals. Terry Rozier furnished 21 points, seven boards, three assists, one steal and one block. P.J. Washington delivered 15 points, while Willy Hernangomez supplied 12 points, four rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Devonte' Graham registered 11 points, eight assists, three rebounds and three steals. 

Bradley Beal paced the Wizards with 34 points, supplementing them with nine rebounds, nine assists and one block. Thomas Bryant turned in 21 points, eight rebounds, two assists and one block. Isaiah Thomas posted 18 points, six rebounds and one assist. Troy Brown, Jr. compiled 12 points, six boards, one assist and two steals. Ish Smith finished with 11 points, seven assists, five rebounds and one block. 

The Hornets remain on the road and take on the San Antonio Spurs on Saturday night, while the Wizards remain home against the Brooklyn Nets on Saturday night as well.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 127-117, at State Farm Arena on Thursday evening. 

Trae Young was on fire to start the game and racked up 29 points and 11 assists by halftime, to help give the Hawks a 74-67 lead at the break. Young cooled down in the third, but the 76ers could not cut the deficit, as they trailed by seven heading into the final frame. Young and the Hawks came out strong in the fourth and outscored the visitors by three points in the quarter, to seal their third straight home win. Young finished the contest with 39 points, 18 assists, six rebounds and two steals. 

The Hawks shot 48 percent from the field, including 11-of-35 from long range. They tallied 29 assists on 42 field goals, but they gave up 16 turnovers in the contest. John Collins had a big night, with 17 points and 20 rebounds, in 34 minutes. De'Andre Hunter finished with 15 points, four assists and two rebounds. 

Meanwhile, Ben Simmons led the 76ers with 31 points, six rebounds, five assists and four steals, in 42 minutes. Joel Embiid totaled 21 points, 14 rebounds, three assists and a block, while Shake Milton finished with 27 points, six assists, five rebounds and one steal. The 76ers shot 46 percent from the field, including 9-of-31 from long range. 

The 76ers (31-18) will look to bounce back as they take on the Celtics in Boston on Saturday. The Hawks (13-36) take on the Mavs in Dallas on Saturday.

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting Golden State Warriors, 119-104, at TD Garden on Thursday evening. 

The Celtics got out to a good start at home and led 29-22 after one quarter. They carried the momentum into the second and held a double-digit lead for most of the quarter and took a 10-point lead into halftime. The Celtics stayed in control through the third, while the Warriors could not cut into the lead and trailed by 12, heading into the final frame. The Celtics pushed their lead as high as 19, in the fourth quarter and held on for their second straight win, while this marks the fifth straight loss for the Warriors. 

Gordon Hayward led the Celtics with 25 points, eight rebounds, three assists, a steal and a block, in 32 minutes. Marcus Smart added 21 points, six assists, three rebounds, a steal and a block, while Jayson Tatum finished with 20 points, six rebounds, two assists, a steal and a block. Then Celtics shot 48 percent from the field, including 15-of-35 from long range.

Meanwhile, D'Angelo Russell led the Warriors with 22 points five assists, three rebounds and three steals, in 28 minutes. Alec Burks added 18 points, four rebounds and a steal, while Damion Lee and Glenn Robinson III tallied 11 points each. The Warriors shot 43 percent from the field, including 12-of-39 from long range. 

The Warriors (10-39) will look to bounce back as they take on the Cavs in Cleveland on Saturday. The Celtics (32-15) play host to the 76ers on Saturday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Utah Jazz, 106-100, at Pepsi Center on Thursday.

While Utah held the lead for the majority of the first three quarters, Denver dominated after that. In fact, they scored the final 15 points of the third quarter to take a six-point lead and then started the fourth quarter on a 12-1 run to take a game-high 17-point lead. That 27-1 run was too much for the Jazz to overcome despite getting it to a three-point margin in the final two minutes but failing to tie or recapture the lead. Denver ended up winning the turnover differential, 16-9, while winning the rebounding battle, 43-35.  

The Jazz (32-16) were led by Jordan Clarkson, who provided 37 points, two rebounds and two assists off the bench. Donovan Mitchell had a night to forget, scoring just four points on 1-of-12 shooting. Rudy Gobert amassed 21 points, 11 rebounds and three blocks on 9-of-10 from the field. Joe Ingles totaled eight points, four rebounds and eight assists. 

The Nuggets (33-15) were led by Nikola Jokic, who collected 28 points, four rebounds, 10 assists and three steals. Will Barton generated 18 points and five boards. Torrey Craig tallied 13 points, 10 rebounds and two blocks while Jerami Grant accrued 15 points and five rebounds. Michael Porter Jr led the bench with 12 points and 12 rebounds. 

Denver has to play again on Friday, traveling to face a dominant Milwaukee Bucks team. As for Utah, they're off until Saturday when they travel to play the Portland Trail Blazers.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the host Los Angeles Clippers, 124-103, at Staples Center on Thursday. 
'
While Los Angeles got out to a 10-point lead in the first quarter, that was the only time they were in this game. In fact, Sacramento rode a 36-14 second quarter to a 17-point halftime lead and the Clippers never got the game within a 13-point margin from there, The Kings ended up shooting 50 percent from the field and 51 percent from three-point range while holding the Clippers to 38 percent from the field and 42 percent from long range. In addition, Sacramento out-rebounded Los Angeles on the defensive end, 36-28 while out-stealing them, 11-6. 

The Kings (18-30) were led by De'Aaron Fox, who tallied 34 points, three rebounds, eight assists and four steals. Bogdan Bogdanovic amassed 15 points, six rebounds and three assists. Dewayne Dedmon collected 11 points, 11 rebounds, four steals and three blocks. Buddy Hied led the bench with 19 points and seven rebounds. 

The Clippers (33-15) leading scorer came off the bench, with Lou Williams providing 22 points and six assists. Montrezl Harrell also totaled 21 points, seven rebounds, three assists and three blocks off the pine. Landry Shamet led the starters with 15 points, two rebounds and three assists. Paul George made his return from injury to accrue eight points, four rebounds and four assists. Kawhi Leonard sat out because of a back issue. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Los Angeles remaining home to face the Minnesota Timberwolves and Sacramento returning home to play the Los Angeles Lakers.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Chicago Bulls, 115-106, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Wednesday evening.

This game between the Pacers (31-17) and the Bulls (19-31) needed five more minutes to settle since an overtime was needed to determine the winner. Indiana jumped to a 25-24 lead after the first quarter, and Indiana extended their lead to a four-point edge following a 30-27 score. Chicago evened things up after the third quarter, however, thanks to a 29-25 score. The final quarter ended with a 20-20 score so an overtime was needed to determine the winner. Indiana looked better in that five-minute stretch, however, and a 15-6 lead there allowed them the win. It was a huge win in what was Victor Oladipo's return after more than one year away from the court.

Victor Oladipo returned after almost 13 months away from the court, but he only had nine points in 21 minutes while shooting 2-8 from the field. T. J. Warren led the way with 25 points, while Domantas Sabonis chipped in with 15 points, 11 boards and five assists. Malcolm Brogdon sniffed a triple-double since he chipped in with 15 points, nine assists and eight rebounds.

Zach LaVine led the way for the Bulls since he ended with 20 points, but he went 7-23 from the field. Thaddeus Young had 16 points, while Tomas Satoransky had 11 four rebounds and four dimes. Chandler Hutchinson impressed off the bench since he had 21 points off the bench in 28 minutes. Cristiano Felicio had 11 points and eight boards off the bench.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Detroit Pistons, 125-115, at Barclays Center on Wednesday night.

The Nets (20-26) and Pistons (17-32) played a highly competitive first quarter before matching each other bucket for bucket in the second period. That left Brooklyn with a slim 70-68 lead. However, the hosts were able to carve out a six-point advantage going into the final 12 minutes, and they were able to hold Detroit at bay the rest of the way for the 10-point win. 

Reggie Jackson led the Pistons with 23 points, complementing them with five assists, three rebounds and one block. Derrick Rose provided 22 points, six boards and five assists. Christian Wood delivered 20 points, eight boards, one assist and two steals. Markieff Morris delivered 15 points, four assists, three rebounds and one block. Andre Drummond generated a 12-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included four assists, two steals and two blocks. 

Spencer Dinwiddie paced the Nets with 28 points, supplementing them with six assists and three rebounds. Taurean Prince supplied 22 points, seven rebounds, one assist and four steals. Kyrie Irving totaled 20 points, five assists, five rebounds and two steals. Jarrett Allen and Caris LeVert generated matching 11-point tallies, with Allen adding six rebounds and four blocks. Garrett Temple posted 10 points, five assists and one rebound.

The Pistons remain home and face the Toronto Raptors on Friday night, while the Nets remain home and tangle with the Chicago Bulls on Friday night as well.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the host New York Knicks, 127-106, at Madison Square Garden on Wednesday evening. 

The contest got out to a tight start, with the score tied at 32 after one quarter. The Grizzlies pulled ahead by 10, mid way through the second and held on to a seven-point lead at halftime. They carried the momentum into the third, where they rallied ahead to a 22-point lead mid way through the quarter, but the Knicks managed to trim it back to a 12-point game, heading into the final frame. The Grizzlies outscored the Knicks by nine in the fourth, as they held on the rest of the way for their fourth straight win. 

Dillon Brooks led the Grizzlies with 27 points on 9-of-17 shooting, in 31 minutes. Ja Morant tallied 18 points, 10 assists, a steal and a block, while Jae Crowder added 18 points, nine rebounds, two assists and a steal. The Grizzlies shot 50 percent from the field, including 13-of-28 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Marcus Morris Sr. led the Knicks with 17 points, six rebounds, a steal and a block, in 26 minutes. Julius Randle tallied 16 points, 15 rebounds and six assists, while Elfrid Payton added 15 points, 11 assists, six rebounds and two steals. The Knicks shot 43 percent from the field, including 9-of-28 from long range. 

The Knicks (13-36) will look to bounce back as they take on the Pacers in Indiana on Saturday. The Grizzlies (24-24) take on the Pelicans in New Orleans on Friday.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the Utah Jazz,127-120, at AT & T Center on Wednesday night.

The Spurs (21-26) got off to a quick start over the favored Jazz (32-15), establishing a 37-29 lead through the first 12 minutes. Utah bounced back to match San Antonio bucket for bucket in the second quarter, but that still left the hosts with an eight-point edge at halftime. Utah then managed to shave their deficit in half going into the final period, but the Spurs wouldn't relinquish their advantage the rest of the way.

Donovan Mitchell paced the Jazz with 31 points, complementing them with four assists, one rebound and one steal. Jordan Clarkson delivered 20 points, two rebounds and two steals. Rudy Gobert generated a 17-point, 19-rebound double-double. Bojan Bogdanovic registered 17 points, nine boards and four assists. Mike Conley poured in 12 points. 

DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 38 points, complementing them with five assists and five rebounds. Patty Mills contributed 18 points and two assists. Dejounte Murray turned in 16 points, four assists, three rebounds, three steals and one block. Rudy Gay, Derrick White and Marco Belinelli furnished matching 10-point tallies, with Gay also pulling down seven boards and dishing out four assists. 

The Jazz remain on the road and visit the Denver Nuggets on Friday night, while the Spurs remain home and tangle with the Charlotte Hornets on Saturday night.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the host Houston Rockets, 125-112, at Moda Center on Wednesday.

While Houston led for the entirety of the first quarter, that was the only time they were in this game. In fact, Portland rode a 41-24 second quartet to an 11-point halftime lead and led by at least seven points for the entirety of the second half after that. The Trail Blazers ended up shooting 52 percent from the field while holding the Rockets to just 43 percent. In addition, Portland out-rebounded Houston, 50-39. 

The Rockets (29-18) were led by Russell Westbrook and his 39 points, 10 rebounds, six assists and two steals. James Harden went just 5-of-18 from the field to generate 18 points, five rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks. Austin Rivers and Ben McLemore had 17 points apiece to lead the bench in otherwise empty stat lines. 

The Trail Blazers (21-27) got Damian Lillard the first triple-double of his career, collecting 36 points, 10 rebounds and 11 assists. C.J. McCollum amassed 22 points, five rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks. Trevor Ariza dropped 21 points while Hassan Whiteside generated 15 points, 10 rebounds and five blocks. Carmelo Anthony also had six points, 13 rebounds and five assists. 

On deck for Portland is a road matchup against the Los Angeles Lakers on Friday. As for Houston, they return home to play the Dallas Mavericks on Friday for their next fixture.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 120-100, at Golden 1 Center on Wednesday.

Oklahoma City won each of the first three quarters by at least five points apiece, winning in wire-to-wire fashion. The Thunder ended up shooting 50 percent from the field, 44 percent from three-point range and 85 percent from the free-throw line. They did that while holding the Kings to 46 percent from the field, 23 percent from long range and 64 percent from the charity stripe. In addition, Oklahoma City ended up out-assisting Sacramento, 32-22, while out-rebounding them, 45-39. 

The Thunder (29-20) were led by Dennis Schroder, who came off the bench to collect 24 points, four rebounds and nine assists. Luguentz Dort led the starters with 23 points and two rebounds. Danilo Gallinari totaled 19 points, four rebounds and four assists. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander accumulated 15 points, seven rebounds and six assists while Chris Paul finished with nine points, seven rebounds and 10 assists. 

The Kings (17-30) were led by Bogdan Bogdanovic, who tallied 23 points, five rebounds and two assists. De'Aaron Fix generated 19 points, five assists and two steals. Buddy Hield led the bench with 13 points, two rebounds and two assists. Dewayne Dedmon totaled six points and seven rebounds while Cory Joseph tallied five points, three rebounds and three assists off the bench.

Sacramento has to play the second half of a back-to-back set on Thursday, traveling to face the Los Angeles Clippers. As for Oklahoma City, they face the Phoenix Suns on Friday for their next fixture.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the New York Knicks, 97-92, at Spectrum Center on Tuesday evening.

The Hornets (16-31) got off to a slow start against the Knicks (13-34) and in fact, they were down by nine points once the first quarter came to an end with a 26-15 score. However, the Hornets managed to turn things around after the second quarter and they shortened the gap with a 32-24 score in the second quarter. The Knicks enjoyed a one-point lead entering the third quarter, but the Hornets flipped the score with a 21-16 third-quarter score that put them up by four points with only 12 minutes of action left on the clock. The Knicks attempted to turn things around, but Charlotte sealed the deal and denied New York with a 29-26 win in the final 12 minutes of action. The Hornets shot 38.6 percent from the field and improved to 8-15 at home, while the Knicks fell to 6-18 on the road despite shooting 44.2 percent from the field.

Terry Rozier led the way for Charlote thanks to a 30-point, 10-rebound performance, while Miles Bridges chipped in with 15 points. Cody Zeller had a double-double of 10 points and 10 rebounds. Malik Monk had 13 points, two rebounds and two assists, while Willy Hernangomez chipped in with 12 points and 10 boards off the bench. Devonte' Graham only had five points while shooting 1-8 from the field.

Julius Randle was the top scoring threat for the Knicks since he ended with 24 points, five rebounds and two assists. Marcus Morris Sr. chipped in with 23 points and four rebounds, while Elfrid Payton contributed 10 points, eight rebounds and eight assists. No other Knicks player scored in double digits, but every single New York that stepped on the hardwood scored a minimum of two points.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Golden State Warriors, 115-104, at Wells Fargo Center on Tuesday night.

The 76ers (31-17) came into the contest as double-digit favorites, with the fact they were getting Joel Embiid (finger) back from a nine-game absence only bolstering their case. However, the presumably overmatched Warriors (10-38) were the hotter team early, ending the first quarter with a slim one-point lead and entering halftime trailing by only five points. Golden State wouldn't go away, either, shaving off a point from their deficit entering the final period. However, a 9-0 run by Philadelphia to open the fourth quarter finally gave them some separation for the hard-fought home victory.

D'Angelo Russell led the way for the Warriors with 28 points, complementing them with seven assists, five rebounds and two steals. Glenn Robinson III furnished 20 points, five boards, three assists and one steal. Marquese Chriss delivered 15 points, five rebounds and two assists. Alec Burks poured in 12 points and added six rebounds off the bench, while Draymond Green mustered nine points, 12 assists, nine rebounds, three blocks and one steal.

Embiid paced the 76ers with 24 points, supplementing them with 10 rebounds, one assist and one block. Raul Neto supplied 19 points, two rebounds, two assists and one steal. Ben Simmons registered 17 points, five assists, four rebounds and one steal. Tobias Harris compiled 14 points, seven boards and four assists. Al Horford delivered a 12-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included eight assists and one steal. Shake Milton finished with 11 points.

The Warriors next pay a visit to the Boston Celtics on Thursday night, while the 76ers travel to face the Atlanta Hawks on Thursday night as well.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 125-110, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Tuesday night. 

The Pelicans (19-29) came into the contest trying to ride some recent momentum, and they opened the game displaying the same strong caliber of play that had given them that lift. New Orleans racked up 40 first-quarter points, and they added another 34 in the second to take a nine-point lead into halftime. The visitors then proceeded to tighten up their defense in the third, limiting the Cavaliers (13-35) to 25 points in the period while forging a commanding 14-point lead they wouldn't relinquish. 

Jrue Holiday paced the Pelicans with 28 points, complementing them with eight assists, two rebounds, four blocks and three steals. Brandon Ingram supplied 24 points, six assists, two steals and one rebound. JJ Redick furnished 15 points, three rebounds, three assists and one steal. Zion Williamson provided 14 points, nine rebounds and one assist. Nicolo Melli turned in 11 points, four boards and one assist. Derrick Favors and Frank Jackson posted matching nine-point tallies, with Favors also pulling down seven rebounds.

Collin Sexton led the Cavaliers with 24 points, supplementing them with four assists, three rebounds, two steals and one block. Kevin Porter, Jr. delivered 21 points, two rebounds, two assists and one steal. Larry Nance, Jr. generated a 17-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included seven assists and two steals. Cedi Osman generated nine points, four rebounds, four assists and one block.

The Pelicans will return home and take on the Memphis Grizzlies on Friday night, while the Cavaliers remain home to face the Toronto Raptors on Thursday night.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 130-114, at Scotiabank Arena on Tuesday night. 

The Raptors got out to a great start at home, with a 33-23 lead after one quarter. The Hawks picked up the pace in the second but could not cut into the lead, as the Raptors stayed in front and took an 11-point lead into halftime. Both teams came out strong in the third, but the Raptors stayed in control and pushed their lead to 14, heading into the final frame. The Raptors started the fourth on a tear and rallied to a 28-point lead, from which they would cruise the rest of the way to their eighth straight win. 

Serge Ibaka led the Raptors with 24 points, 10 rebounds and two steals, in 27 minutes off the bench. Pascal Siakam added 24 points, nine rebounds, two assists and a block, while Kyle Lowry finished with 12 points, 11 assists, eight rebounds and a steal. The Raptors shot 50 percent from the field, including 13-of-43 from long range. 

Meanwhile, John Collins led the Hawks with 28 points, 12 rebounds and a block, in 33 minutes. Trae Young added 18 points, 13 assists and two rebounds, while Cam Reddish finished with 18 points, six rebounds, a steal and a block. The Hawks shot 45 percent from the field, including 12-of-47 from long range. 

The Hawks (12-36) will look to bounce back as they play host to the 76ers on Thursday. The Raptors (33-14) head to Cleveland to take on the Cavaliers on Thursday.

The Boston Celtics defeated the host Miami Heat, 109-101, at American Airlines Arena on Tuesday evening. 

The Celtics got out to a great start on the road, with a 36-28 lead after one quarter. The game slowed down in the second, but the Heat were able to gain some ground and trim it to a five-point game by halftime. The Celtics came out strong in the third and managed to stay one step ahead through the entire quarter, while the Heat kept the pressure on and cut it to a four-point game heading into the final frame. The Celtics rallied to an 11-point lead early in the fourth and maintained the lead the rest of the way, to earn the impressive road win. 

Gordon Hayward led the Celtics with 29 points, nine rebounds, two assists and a block, in 38 minutes. Jaylen Brown added 25 points, five assists, three rebounds and a block, while Kemba Walker tallied 16 points, eight assists, four rebounds and a steal. The Celtics shot 47 percent from the field, including 13-of-36 from long range.

Meanwhile, Goran Dragic led the Heat with 23 points, four assists, two rebounds and two steals, in 30 minutes. Jimmy Butler finished with 20 points, six rebounds, two assists and three steals, while Bam Adebayo added 16 points, 10 rebounds, a steal and a block. The Heat shot 37 percent from the field, including 9-of-37 from long range. 

The Heat (32-15) will look to bounce back as they take on the Magic in Orlando on Saturday. The Celtics (31-15) play host to the Warriors on Thursday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the visiting Denver Nuggets, 104-96, at FedEx Forum on Tuesday.

A 31-18 first quarter really set the tone for the Grizzlies in this game, holding the lead for the final three quarters. In fact, they led by at least five points for those final three quarters, winning this game in wire-to-wire fashion. Memphis ended up shooting 56 percent from the field while holding Denver to just 37 percent shooting. They also ended up out-assisting them, 32-23, while recording 12 steals and 11 blocks. The Nuggets had just nine steals and four blocks while committing 19 turnovers. 

The Nuggets (32-15) were led by Nikola Jokic, who tallied 25 points, 13 rebounds and five assists. Jerami Grant totaled 21 points, four rebounds, four assists and two steals. Will Barton collected nine points, seven rebounds and five assists while Monte Morris led the bench with nine points, five rebounds and six assists. 

The Grizzlies (23-24) were led by Dillon Brooks and his 24 points and three assists. Jonas Valanciunas had 23 points, 12 rebounds and three assists. Ja Morant generated 14 points, six rebounds, seven assists and four steals. Jaren Jackson Jr had just 10 points and two rebounds but swatted away seven blocks. 

On deck for Memphis is a road matchup versus the New York Knicks on Wednesday. As for Denver, they return to action on Thursday when they go home to face the Utah Jazz.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the visiting Washington Wizards, 151-131, at Fiserv Forum on Tuesday night. 

With Giannis Antetokounmpo (shoulder) sidelined, Kris Middleton poured in 51 points to lead Milwaukee to its ninth straight win. The Bucks got out to a blistering start at home, with a 42-28 lead after one quarter. The offensive onslaught continued in the second, where the Bucks put up another 46 points, to take an 88-63 lead into halftime. The Wizards came out motivated in the third quarter and stunned the Bucks, outscoring them 41-29 in the quarter, to cut it to a 13-point game heading into the fourth. The Bucks got back on track in the fourth and did not take any chances, as they poured in 34 points, to ensure the home win.

Middleton shot 16-of-26 from the field and added 10 rebounds and six assists, in 36 minutes of action. Eric Bledsoe added 34 points, 10 assists, six rebounds and a steal, while Donte DiVincenzo chipped in 16 points, seven rebounds and two assists. The Bucks shot 56 percent from the field, including 19-of-37 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Bradley Beal led the Wizards with 47 points, six assists, a steal and a block, in 38 minutes. Thomas Bryant tallied 18 points, 10 rebounds, six assists, a block and a steal, while Isaiah Thomas added 16 points, three rebounds and two assists. The Wizards shot 47 percent from the field, including 14-of-32 from long range. 

The Wizards (15-31) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Hornets on Thursday. The Bucks (41-6) play host to the Nuggets on Friday.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the host Dallas Mavericks, 133-104, at American Airlines Center on Tuesday.

A 32-19 first quarter really set the tone for Phoenix in this game, winning in wire-to-wire fashion. In fact, they rode a 48-22 third quarter to a 31-point lead, leading by at least 28 points for the whole of the fourth quarter. The Suns shot 59 percent from the field and 43 percent from three-point range while holding the Mavericks to 45 percent from the field and 21 percent from long range.
