The Blazers shot 43 percent from the field, including 13-of-37 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Kyle Lowry led the Raptors with 24 points, 10 assists, four rebounds and a block, in 38 minutes. Serge Ibaka added 17 points, 11 rebounds and two assists, while Oshae Brissett and Chris Boucher chipped in 12 points each. 

The Raptors (24-13) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Wednesday. The Trail Blazers (16-22) take on the Timberwolves in Minnesota on Thursday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host Brooklyn Nets, 111-103, at Barclays Center on Tuesday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start but the Thunder managed to grab a four-point lead heading into the second. They pushed their lead to eight early in the second, but the Nets rallied back to make it a one-point game by halftime. The Thunder pushed ahead and held on for most of the third, but the Nets closed the quarter on a 10-4 run, to take a three-point lead into the final frame. The Nets held the lead through the fourth, but the Thunder kept chipping away, until Chris Paul hit the game-tying jumper, to send the game to overtime. The Thunder carried the momentum into halftime and outscored the hosts 10-2 in the period, to walk away with the road win. This marks the seventh straight loss for the Nets. 

Chris Paul led the Thunder with 28 points, six rebounds, three assists and two steals, in 38 minutes. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander tallied 22 points, four rebounds, two assists and two steals, while Dennis Schroder chipped in 14 points, five assists, four rebounds and a steal. The Thunder shot 41 percent from the field, including 11-of-37 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Taurean Prince led the Nets with 21 points, eight rebounds, an assist, a steal and a block, in 37 minutes. Caris LeVert finished with 20 points, six rebounds and three assists, while Jarrett Allen added 12 points, seven rebounds, two assists and two blocks. The Nets shot 41 percent from the field, including 11-of-37 from long range. 

The Nets (16-20) will look to bounce back as they host the Heat on Friday. The Thunder (21-16) play host to the Rockets on Thursday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 119-112, at FedEx Forum on Tuesday night.

The Timberwolves (14-22) were still playing without Karl-Anthony Towns (knee) on Tuesday, but they still managed to forge a 56-51 halftime lead thanks to some solid play on both ends of the floor. The Grizzlies (16-22) then began to claw back in the third quarter, bringing their deficit down to two points heading into the final period and finished on a 27-15 run over the final 6:38 to cinch the road victory. 

Jarrett Culver paced the Timberwolves with 24 points, adding five rebounds, one assist and two steals. Jeff Teague produced 18 points, six assists and two steals. Robert Covington produced 17 points, six boards, two assists and one steal. Andrew Wiggins generated 15 points, four rebounds, two assists and one block. Gorgui Dieng supplied 11 points, four assists, two rebounds and one steal. Naz Reid registered 10 points and five boards.

Dillon Brooks led the Grizzlies with 28 points, complementing them with three rebounds and one steal. Ja Morant followed with 25 points, seven assists, four rebounds and one steal. Jaren Jackson, Jr. totaled 21 points, seven rebounds, two assists, three blocks and one steal. Jae Crowder compiled 14 points, eight rebounds, three assists and five steals. 

The Timberwolves return home to face the Portland Trail Blazers on Thursday night, while the Grizzlies remain home and tangle with the San Antonio Spurs on Friday night.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 114-103, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Tuesday.

An 18-2 run to start the third quarter appeared to give Phoenix a victory after being tied at the half but they couldn't hold that lead. In fact, the Kings rode a 36-16 fourth quarter to their comeback victory, forcing a 33-point turnaround over the final 18 minutes of play. Sacramento actually finished the game on a 53-20 run in that span. With that said, there were seven ties and 12 lead changes in total. Sacramento's bench really changed the game, outscoring Phoenix's bench, 42-18. In addition, the Kings doubled up the Suns in steals, 8-4. 

The Kings (16-22) were led by De'Aaron Fox and his 27 points, three rebounds and six assists. Nemanja Bjelica amassed 19 points, seven rebounds and three steals. Buddy Hield didn't play the fourth quarter but still finished with 16 points, three rebounds and two assists. Trevor Ariza led the bench with 15 points, seven rebounds, two assists and two steals while Dewayne Dedmon recorded a double-double. 

The Suns (13-24) were led by Devin Booker, who tallied 34 points, four rebounds and seven assists. Kelly Oubre Jr collected 17 points and six boards. DeAndre Ayton accrued 21 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Ricky Rubio accumulated eight points, five rebounds and nine assists. No other player had more than six points or two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Friday, with Sacramento returning home to face a dominant Milwaukee Bucks team while Phoenix stays home to play the Orlando Magic.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting New York Knicks, 117-87, at Staples Center on Tuesday.

While this game stayed within a five-point margin for the first 15 minutes of action, that was really the only time it was competitive. In fact, Los Angeles rode a 36-24 second quarter to a 17-point halftime lead and held a double-digit lead for the entirety of the second half. The Lakers ended up shooting 50 percent from the field and 47 percent from three-point range while holding the Knicks to 39 percent from the field and 20 percent from long range. In addition, Los Angeles won the defensive rebounding battle, 43-33, while out-blocking New York, 11-3. 

The Knicks (10-27) were led by R.J. Barrett and his 19 points and five boards. Julius Randle accrued 15 points, 10 rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Elfrid Payton accumulated 12 points, eight rebounds, four assists and three steals. Mitchell Robinson led the bench with eight points, six rebounds and three steals. 

The Lakers (30-7) were led by LeBron James, who tallied 31 points, five rebounds, five assists and two steals. Anthony Davis collected five points, six rebounds, five assists, three steals and two blocks but departed in the third quarter after falling on his back. Rajon Rondo provided eight points and 10 assists off the bench while Dwight Howard totaled eight points, 13 rebounds and five blocks. 

New York has to play again on Wednesday, remaining on the road to face the Utah Jazz. As for Los Angeles, they're off until Wednesday when they face the Dallas Mavericks.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 115-104, at Spectrum Center on Monday evening.

The Pacers (23-14) and the Hornets (15-24) entered this game on similar runs of form  Indiana had lost five of their last seven, while Charlotte has dropped six of their last eight. It seemed the Hornets were primed to secure a third consecutive win after they jumped to a 29-27 lead following the first quarter, and they extended their two-point lead after a low-scoring second quarter that ended 15-15. The Pacers pulled away for good in the third quarter, however, thanks to a 37-21 score. Charlotte won the final 12 minutes of action with a 39-36 score, but it was too late for them and the Pacers cruised their way to a solid road win. With the victory, Indiana moved to 8-10 on the road while the Hornets fell to 7-12 at home.

T.J. Warren had one of his best games of the season, and he ended with 36 points (15-24 FG), five rebounds and three assists. Domantas Sabonis chipped in with 18 points, 12 rebounds and seven dimes. Myles Turner came one rebound shy of a double-double thanks to a 15-point, nine-rebound effort. Jeremy Lamb had 11 points and 10 rebounds. Indiana shot 52.8 percent from the field and 38.5 percent from deep as a team.

Terry Rozier extended his torrid scoring form since he ended with 28 points (8-17 FG) and six assists, while his backcourt teammate Devonte' Graham contributed 22 points, six assists and five rebounds while making seven of his 15 shot attempts. Miles Bridges added 18 points, seven rebounds, and four assists. No other Hornets player scored in double digits in this game.

The Orlando Magic defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 101-89, at Amway Center on Monday.

Orlando did almost all of their damage in the second and fourth quarters, outscoring Brooklyn, 58-35. In fact, that big fourth quarter allowed them to hold a double-digit lead for the final five minutes of action. In addition, the Magic finished the game on a 25-11 run across the final nine minutes of action. The key for the Magic was their defense, holding the Nets to just 33 percent from the field and 21 percent from three-point range. They did that while winning the defensive rebounding battler, 49-34. 

The Nets (16-19) were led by Joe Harris, who tallied 16 points, three rebounds, two assists and two steals. Spencer Dinwiddie finished with 16 points, five rebounds and three assists. No other player reached double figures in scoring. Wilson Chandler did lead the bench with nine points, nine rebounds, three assists and three steals though. 

The Magic (17-20) were led by Markelle Fultz and his 25 points, five rebounds, four assists and two steals. Nikola Vucevic amassed 11 points, 24 rebounds and four assists. Aaron Gordon totaled 11 points and 14 rebounds while D.J. Augustin led the bench with 16 points, four rebounds and six assists. Wes Iwundu and Evan Fournier had 11 points apiece. 

Brooklyn laces up again on Tuesday, playing host to the Oklahoma City Thunder. As for Orlando, they return to action on Wednesday when they play host to the Washington Wizards.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder, 120-113, at Wells Fargo Center on Monday evening.

The 76ers (24-14) entered this game losing seven of their last 10 against a red-hot Thunder (20-16) squad that had gone 9-1 over their last 10 matchups. However, Philadelphia looked in control right after the start of the contest and despite a 31-31 score following the first quarter, the Sixers pulled away for good in the second quarter with a 31-21 score. They would never relinquish that advantage, however, despite the fact the Thunder won the third quarter by a 34-28 score. The Sixers won the final quarter by a 30-27 score, and that was enough to give them a huge  and much-needed  win over a tough opponent at home. With the win, Philadelphia moved to 17-2 at home while the Thunder fell to 8-10 on the road.

Ben Simmons had a great performance since he ended with 17 points, 15 rebounds and eight assists. The teams top scoring threat, however, was Josh Richardson who chipped in with 23 points in 37 minutes. Joel Embiid had 18 points, nine rebounds and eight dimes, while Tobias Harris added 18 points as well while also chipping with six rebounds and four assists. Al Horford had 13 points, and Trey Burke added 12 off the bench.

Steven Adams was Oklahoma Citys top performer since he had 24 points, 15 rebounds and two blocks. Chris Paul filled the stat sheet admirably, and he ended with 18 points, eight rebounds and six dimes. Danilo Gallinari had 18 points and seven rebounds. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander added 14 points with nine rebounds, and Dennis Schroder contributed 21 points off the bench.

The Washington Wizards defeated the visiting Boston Celtics, 99-94, at Capital One Arena on Monday evening. 

Ish Smith poured in 27 points on 12-of-18 shooting, to held lead the Wizards to their second straight win. The Wizards got out to a great start at home, with a 26-17 lead after one quarter. They kept the upper hand through the fourth and pushed their lead to 11, by halftime. The Wizards held a solid lead for the first half of the third quarter, but the Celtics chipped away through the final portion of the quarter and cut it to a two-point game, heading into the final frame. The Wizards responded just in time to stay a step ahead and brought it back to an eight-point game, with five minutes to go. The Celtics cut it to back to four, with just under a minute left, but the Wizards came through clutch at the foul line to seal it. 

Jordan McRae added 19 points, seven assists, three blocks and two steals, while Isaiah Thomas added 17 points and three assists, against his former squad. The Wizard shot 46 percent from the field, including 7-of-21 from long range.

Meanwhile, Jaylen Brown led the Celtics with 23 points and 12 rebounds, in 33 minutes. Jayson Tatum added 17 points, two assists and two blocks, while Gordon Hayward added 10 points, 10 rebounds, four assists and a block. The Celtics shot 35 percent from the field, including 8-of-37 from long range.

The Celtics (25-9) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Spurs on Wednesday. The Wizards (12-24) take on the Magic in Orlando on Wednesday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Atlanta Hawks, 123-115, at State Farm Arena on Monday evening. 

Nikola Jokic put on a show, as he led the Nuggets with 47 points, eight rebounds, five assists, two steals and a block. Despite a strong start by the Nuggets, the Hawks held a two-point lead at the end of one quarter. The Nuggets picked up the pace in the second and outscored the hosts by 10 in the quarter, to take a 64-56 lead by halftime. The Hawks fought hard through the third but could not break ahead, as the Nuggets stayed in control and held onto a five-point lead heading into the final frame. The Hawks cut it to a one-point game early in the fourth, but the Nuggets used a 5-0 run to recreate some separation. The Nuggets got their lead up to nine with under two minutes to go and did not look back, as they held on for the road win. 

Will Barton added 28 points, nine rebounds, five assists and a block, while Jamal Murray finished with 16 points, eight assists, five rebounds, a block and a steal. The Nuggets shot 51 percent from the field, including 9-of-27 from long range. 

Meanwhile, five players scored in double digits for the Hawks, led by Trae Young, who tallied 29 points, 12 assists and four rebounds, in 39 minutes. Kevin Huerter added 22 points, eight rebounds and a steal, while John Collins tallied 17 points, five rebounds, three assists and two blocks. The Hawks shot 46 percent from the field, including 18-of-39 from long range. 

The Hawks (8-29) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Rockets on Wednesday. The Nuggets (25-11) take o the Mavs in Dallas on Wednesday.

The Utah Jazz defeated the New Orleans Pelicans, 128-126, at Smoothie King Center on Monday night.

The Jazz (24-12) were facing a depleted Pelicans (12-25) squad that was missing Jrue Holiday (elbow), but that nevertheless came out of the gate ready to match Utah bucket for bucket. New Orleans owned a one-point lead after one quarter, and although they trailed by five at halftime, that deficit had been replaced by a one-point edge going into the final period. Ultimately, the visitors held a slim two-point advantage with 1:12 remaining after a Donovan Mitchell bucket, and they were able to help force misses by Brandon Ingram and J.J. Redick in the final 58.6 seconds to escape with the victory, including a controversial game-ending block of Ingram by Rudy Gobert.

Bojan Bogdanovic paced the Jazz with 35 points. Joe Ingles followed with 22 points, six assists, two rebounds and two steals. Mitchell finished with 19 points, six assists, four rebounds and one steal. Jordan Clarkson poured in 17  points to lead the bench, while Gobert mustered nine points but pulled down 19 rebounds. 

Ingram led the Pelicans with 35 points, adding eight rebounds, five assists, one steal and one block. Redick posted 23 points and complemented them with three boards and one assist. Lonzo Ball totaled 21 points, eight rebounds and seven assists. E'Twaun Moore registered 13 points, seven rebounds, one assist and two steals.

The Jazz heads back home and takes on the New York Knicks on Wednesday night, while the Pelicans are home again versus the Chicago Bulls on Wednesday night as well.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Chicago Bulls, 118-110, at American Airlines Arena on Monday.

A 33-27 first quarter really set the tone for the Mavericks in this game, leading for all but a couple of minutes. In fact, Dallas won or tied all four individual quarters, leading by at least four points for the entirety of the fourth quarter. The Mavericks ended up shooting 52 percent from the field and 39 percent from three-point range while holding the Bulls to 47 percent from the field and 29 percent from long range. In addition, Dallas won the defensive rebounding battle, 32-28. 

The Bulls (13-24) were led by Lauri Markkanen and his 26 points and nine boards. Zach LaVine tallied 20 points, five rebounds, seven assists, three steals and two blocks. Tomas Satoranky collected 11 points, five rebounds and 14 assists. Coby White led the bench with 15 points while Thaddeus Young provided 11 points, nine rebounds and three steals. 

The Mavericks (24-13) got another monster triple-double from Luka Doncic, who accumulated 38 points, 11 rebounds and 10 assists. Dwight Powell totaled 16 points and seven rebounds. Tim Hardaway Jr accrued 15 points, four rebounds and two assists. Justin Jackson led the bench with 11 points and two rebounds. 

Both teams return to action on Wednesday, with Chicago traveling to play the resurgent New Orleans Pelicans and Dallas remaining home to play the Denver Nuggets.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Milwaukee Bucks, 126-104, at AT&T Center on Monday evening.

The Bucks got out to a good start and grabbed an early lead, but the Spurs rallied back to take a 27-22 lead after one quarter. The Spurs pushed their lead to double digits mid way through the second and held a 13-point lead by halftime. The Bucks came out stronger in the third but could only trim the deficit to 10, as the Spurs were able to stay a step ahead. The Spurs sealed the deal with a decisive fourth quarter, where they outscored the visitors by 12, to complete the impressive, 22-point home win. This marks the ends of a two-game slide for the Spurs and the end of a five-game winning streak for the Bucks. 

DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 25 points, seven assists and three rebounds, in 33 minutes. Patty Mills added 21 points on 6-of-10 shooting, in 23 minutes off the bench, while Rudy Gay added 17 points and eight rebounds, off the bench. The Spurs shot 51 percent from the field, including 19-of-35 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 24 points, 12 rebounds, eight assists, three steals and a block. Khris Middleton added 15 points, five rebounds and four assists, while Donte DiVincenzo chipped in 16 points and four rebounds. The Bucks shot 40 percent from the field, including 15-of-45 from deep. 

The Bucks (32-6) will look to bounce back as they visit the Warriors on Wednesday. The Spurs (15-20) take on the Celtics in Boston on Wednesday.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the Golden State Warriors, 111-98, at Golden 1 Center on Monday night.

The Kings (14-23) set a dominant tone early, establishing a 52-40 lead by halftime. Sacramento then increased its advantage over the Warriors (9-29) by another 14 points in the third quarter, sealing the double-digit home victory. The Kings enjoyed a particularly large advantage in the shooting department, draining 48.1 percent of their attempts, including 50.0 percent from distance, while limiting Golden State to a 39.5 percent figure overall.

Glenn Robinson III paced the Warriors with 16 points, adding five rebounds. Omari Spellman supplied 13 points, six boards, two assists and two steals. Eric Paschall managed 12 points, four rebounds, one assist and one steal. Alec Burks posted 10 points, six boards, three assists and one block. 

De'Aaron Fox and Buddy Hield co-led the Kings with matching 21-point tallies while dishing out seven and five assists, respectively. Harrison Barnes produced 18 points, four rebounds, two assists and one steal. Trevor Ariza matched Barnes' scoring total and also pulled down six rebounds and recorded three assists. Cory Joseph poured in 12 points, while Nemanja Bjelica mustered eight points and posted 10 boards. 

The Warriors return home to take on the Milwaukee Bucks on Wednesday, while the Kings travel to face the Phoenix Suns on Tuesday night.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting New York Knicks, 135-132, at Staples Center on Sunday. 

While New York led by 16 points after the first quarter, Los Angeles responded with a 47-24 second quarter. In fact, that allowed them to lead by at least three points for the entirety of the second half. The Clippers bench carried them to this win, outscoring the Knicks bench, 85-36. Los Angeles ended up out-rebounding New York, 42-37, while out-assisting them, 25-22. In addition, both clubs shot over 50 percent from both the field and from three-point range. The Clippers connected on 27-of-33 from the free-throw line while the Knicks hit just 24-of-37. 

The Knicks (10-26) were led by Marcus Morris, who amassed 38 points, five rebounds and two steals on 13-of-19 from the field. R.J. Barrett accrued 24 points and six rebounds on 7-of-11 shooting. Julius Randle finished with 16 points, eight rebounds, four assists and two steals. Taj Gibson totaled 11 points and six rebounds. 

The Clippers (26-12) had just one starter reach double figures in scoring, with Paul George collecting 32 points, four rebounds, three assists and two steals. Patrick Beverley generated six points, five rebounds and six assists. Montrezl Harrell led the bench with 34 points, six rebounds and three assists while Lou Williams accumulated 32 points, two rebounds and nine assists, JaMychal Green also provided 11 points, 10 rebounds and three assists off the bench as well. 

On deck for New York is another road game against the Los Angeles Lakers on Tuesday. As for the Clippers, they're off until Friday when they play host to the Golden State Warriors.

The Miami Heat defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 122-111, at American Airlines Arena on Sunday evening.

The Heat (26-10) and Trail Blazers (15-22) both came into the contest without a crucial component of their team, as Jimmy Butler (back) and C.J. McCollum (illness) were each ruled out earlier in the day. Miami opened the game much more prepared to handle their key absence, establishing a 31-19 lead after one quarter. The home squad added another seven points to its advantage by halftime, and although Portland was much more competitive in the second half, it wasn't enough to overcome the early hole. 

Damian Lillard paced the Trail Blazers with 34 points, adding 12 assists, a rebound and three steals. Hassan Whiteside generated a 21-point, 18-rebound double-double that also included two blocks. Anfernee Simons totaled 19 points, four boards and four assists. Carmelo Anthony supplied 11 points, three assists and two rebounds. Mario Hezonja produced 10 points.

Goran Dragic led the Heat with 29 points and 13 assists while adding three rebounds. Bam Adebayo furnished 20 points, eight rebounds, six assists, one steal and one block. Derrick Jones, Jr. registered 19 points, six boards, two assists, two blocks and one steal. James Johnson managed 12 points, six boards, two assists and two blocks. Meyers Leonard and Tyler Herro generated matching 11-point contributions while pulling down nine and five rebounds, respectively.

The Trail Blazers remain on the road and visit the Toronto Raptors on Tuesday night, while the Heat hit the road to tangle with the Indiana Pacers on Wednesday night.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the host Cleveland Cavaliers, 118-103, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Sunday evening. 

The Timberwolves jumped ahead with a great first half and held on for their second straight win. They took a four-point lead after one quarter and poured in 42 points in the second to push their lead to 66-48 by halftime. The Cavs came out stronger in the third but could only trim the deficit by three, as they trailed by 15, heading into the final frame. The Timberwolves held on through the fourth, handing the Cavs a fourth straight loss. 

Gorgui Dieng led the Timberwolves with 22 points, 13 rebounds, six assists and four blocks, in 29 minutes. Shabazz Napier added 21 points, seven assists, two rebounds and a steal, while Andrew Wiggins tallied 15 points, seven rebounds, four assists and two steals. The Timberwolves shot 50 percent from, the field, including 14-of-38 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Dante Exum led the Cavs with 28 points on 11-of-13 shooting, in 24 minutes off the bench. Collin Sexton added 19 points, three rebounds and two assists, while John Henson finished with seven points, 11 rebounds, three assists and a block. The Cavs shot 48 percent from the field, including 8-of-25 from long range. 

The Cavs (10-26) will look to bounce back as they host the Pistons on Tuesday. The Timberwolves (14-21) take on the Grizzlies in Memphis on Tuesday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 121-114, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Sunday evening. 

The Suns got out to a good start at home and held a four-point lead after one quarter. The Grizzlies picked up the pace in the second and outscored the hosts by nine points in the quarter, to take a 62-57 lead by halftime. The Grizzlies took it to another level in the third, where they outscored the Suns 34-20, to take 19-point lead into the final frame. The Suns made a push in the fourth but it was too little, too late, as the Grizzlies held on for their second straight win. 

Jonas Valanciunas led the Grizzlies with 30 points, eight rebounds, four assists, two blocks and a steal, in 27 minutes. Dillon Brooks added 19 points, four rebounds and two assists, while Jaren Jackson Jr. tallied 15 points, eight rebounds, three assists, three steals and a block. The Grizzlies shot 54 percent from the field, including 18-of-42 from long range.  

Meanwhile, Devin Booker led the Suns with 40 points, six assists and two rebounds, in 37 minutes. Kelly Oubre Jr. added 17 points, 10 rebounds, two assists and a steal, while Deandre Ayton 14 points, 12 rebounds, four assists, two blocks and a steal. The Suns shot 45 percent from the field, including 6-of-26 from deep.  

The Suns (14-22) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Kings on Tuesday. The Grizzlies (15-22) play host to the Grizzlies on Tuesday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 106-99, at Staples Center on Sunday.

While there were only five ties and four lead changes in this game, it came down to the wire. In fact, Los Angeles trailed by four heading into the fourth quarter but started on a 15-0 run. Detroit then responded with an 11-0 run and that made it close for the final few minutes. That big run to start the quarter was too much though, with Los Angeles outscoring Detroit, 31-20, in that final quarter. Rim protection was critical for the Lakers, recording 20 blocks to the Pistons six. Los Angeles ended up shooting 46 percent from the field while holding Detroit to just 37 percent shooting. 

The Pistons (13-24) were led by Derrick Rose, who generated 28 points, three rebounds and five assists off the bench. Andre Drummond led the starters with 12 points, 18 rebounds and four blocks. Langston Galloway also played well off the bench, providing 13 points, five rebounds, four assists and two steals. 

The Lakers (29-7) got a triple-double from LeBron James, who tallied 21 points, 14 rebounds and 11 assists. Anthony Davis finished with 24 points, 11 rebounds, three steals and eight blocks. Alex Caruso led the bench with 13 points, three rebounds and three assists. Dwight Howard and JaVale McGee combined for 11 blocks out of the center position as well. 

Both teams return to action on Tuesday, with Los Angeles remaining home to face the resurgent New York Knicks and Detroit staying on the road to play the Cleveland Cavaliers.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Los Angeles Clippers, 140-114, at Staples Center on Saturday afternoon. 

The Clippers (25-13) came into the contest without one of their best all-around players, as Paul George (hamstring) was forced to sit out. The Grizzlies (14-22) took advantage early, jumping out to a 40-27 lead through the first 12 minutes. Los Angeles was able to shave points off its deficit in the second quarter, but Memphis essentially put the game away for good by adding 16 points to its advantage during a 39-point third period that propelled them to a comfortable victory. The visitors were highly efficient offensively, shooting 51.0 percent, including 46.2 percent from three-point range.

Jae Crowder led the Grizzlies with 27 points, adding eight rebounds, seven assists, three steals and three blocks. Jaren Jackson Jr. tallied 24 points, six boards and four blocks. Ja Morant and Dillon Brooks generated matching 22-point contributions, with Morant also dishing out nine assists. Tyus Jones led the bench with 11 points and posted five assists, two rebounds and two steals.

Montrezl Harrell paced the Clippers with 28 points, complementing them with nine rebounds and three assists. Kawhi Leonard and Lou Williams delivered 24 points apiece, with Leonard also pulling down eight rebounds and Williams compiling seven assists. Landry Shamet managed 10 points and four rebounds, while Ivica Zubac registered eight points and 11 rebounds.

The Grizzlies remain on the road and face the Phoenix Suns on Sunday night, while the Clippers remain home and tangle with the New York Knicks on Sunday afternoon.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 121-102, at Barclays Center on Saturday evening.

The Raptors (23-12) were not quite up to the task of keeping pace with a red-hot Nets (16-18) squad in the first quarter, with Brooklyn forging a 33-24 lead through the first 12 minutes. However, Toronto would begin to chip away beginning in the second quarter, shaving five points off their deficit heading into halftime before eradicating it altogether and taking a three-point advantage during the third period. They then thrived on both ends of the floor in the fourth quarter, outscoring their hosts by a comfortable 38-22 margin to seal the road win.

Fred VanVleet paced the Raptors with 29 points, adding 11 assists, four rebounds and one block. Kyle Lowry supplied 26 points, five assists, four rebounds, two steals and one block. Serge Ibaka generated a 21-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included one block. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson posted 10 points, five rebounds, two assists and four steals.

Spencer Dindwiddie led the Nets with 23 points, complementing them with seven assists, three rebounds and one block. Joe Harris poured in 18 points and also collected five assists and three rebounds. Caris LeVert totaled 13 points in his return from a 24-game absence due to a thumb injury, while Garrett Temple managed 12 points, five rebounds, three assists and one steal. Taurean Prince furnished 10 points, six boards, two assists and one block.

The Raptors remain on the road and take on the Portland Trail Blazers on Tuesday night, while the Nets pay a visit to the Orlando Magic on Monday night.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the host Dallas Mavericks in overtime, 123-120, at American Airlines Center on Saturday. 

There were five ties and 10 lead changes in this game, as it took an overtime session to determine a winner. Luka Doncic actually had two opportunities to tie the game, missing a three at the end of regulation then missing a halfcourt prayer at the end of overtime. The key for the Hornets was their rebounding, out-rebounding the Mavericks, 53-41. In addition, Charlotte shot 49 percent from the field and 44 percent from three-point range while holding Dallas to 47 percent from the field and 30 percent from long range. The Hornets also went 28-of-31 from the free-throw line while the Mavs hit just 11-of-13. 

The Hornets (15-23) were led by Terry Rozier and his 29 points, six rebounds and eight assists. DeVonte' Graham tallied 27 points, two rebounds and 13 assists. P.J. Washington amassed 19 points, six rebounds and three assists. Bismack Biyombo and Mikal Bridges each recorded double-doubles, combining for 22 points and 24 rebounds. 

The Mavericks (22-13) got a triple-double from Luka Doncic, who collected 39 points, 12 rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Dorian Finney-Smith totaled 15 points and eight rebounds. J.J. Barea got a rare start and generated 11 points, three rebounds and nine assists. Maxi Kleber led the bench with 24 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Dallas remaining home to play the Chicago Bulls and Charlotte returning home to face the Indiana Pacers.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Orlando Magic, 109-96, at Amway Center on Saturday night. 

The Jazz (23-12) wasted no time getting off to a fast start, establishing a 33-25 lead through the first 12 minutes, but the Magic (16-20) showed plenty of fight over the middle periods. Orlando outscored Utah, 50-43, over the second and third quarters, leaving them just a point shy of the visitors going into the fourth. However, the Jazz opened on a 17-5 run over the first 4:23 of the period, setting the stage for their road victory.

Donovan Mitchell paced the Jazz with 32 points, adding six assists, three rebounds and one block. Georges Niang furnished 15 points, five boards and two assists. Bojan Bogdanovic totaled 14 points and five boards. Emmanuel Mudiay supplied 12 points, six rebounds and two assists. Joe Ingles registered 11 points, five assists, four rebounds and one steal.

Terrence Ross led the Magic with 24 points, complementing them with three boards. Nikola Vucevic followed with 22 points, 13 rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Aaron Gordon posted an 11-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included two assists and two steals. Evan Fournier and Wes Iwundu posted nine points apiece.

The Jazz pay a visit to the New Orleans Pelicans on Monday night, while the Magic remains home to tangle with the Brooklyn Nets on Monday night as well.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the visiting Indiana Pacers, 116-111, at State Farm Arena on Saturday evening. 

The Hawks got out to a great start at home with a 43-26 lead after one quarter. The Pacers bounced back in the second, as they outscored the hosts by 13 points in the quarter, to make it a four-point game by halftime. The Pacers kept up the momentum in the third, as they started the quarter with a 12-4 run. The Hawks got back on track and took a one-point lead heading into the final frame. The Hawks managed to stay one step ahead through the fourth and held on for their fourth home win of the season. 

Trae Young led the Hawks with 41 points, eight assists, four rebounds and two steals, in 37 minutes. Kevin Huerter added 26 points, six rebounds, five assists and two steals, while Alex Len chipped in chipped 16 points, nine rebounds and three blocks. The Hawks shot 51 percent from the field, including 10-of-32 from long range. 

Domantas Sabonis led the Pacers with 25 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and a steal, in 34 minutes. Justin Holiday 18 points, four rebounds and two steals, while Aaron Holiday chipped in 16 points, six assists, four rebounds, a steal and a block. The Pacers shot 41 percent from the field, including 10-of-27 from deep. 

The Pacers (22-14) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Monday. The Hawks (8-28) play host to the Nuggets on Monday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 121-106, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Saturday night.

The Thunder (20-15) set a positive tone from the opening tip, jumping out to a 66-53 lead through the first two quarters. The Cavaliers (10-25) arguably enjoyed their best stretch of play during a third period in which they shaved a point off their deficit, but Oklahoma City finished strong over the final 12 minutes for the double-digit road victory. The visitors forged a particularly impressive advantage on the boards, outrebounding Cleveland by a 52-42 margin.

Dennis Schroder led the Thunder with 22 points, adding three assists, two rebounds and one steal. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander followed with 20 points, seven rebounds and two steals. Danilo Gallinari delivered 19 points, five boards and three assists. Terrance Ferguson poured in 13 points, while Steven Adams generated a 10-point, 16-rebound double-double that also included four assists, one steal and one block. Hamidou Diallo matched Adams' scoring and pulled in four rebounds , recorded one assist, and supplied one steal.

Collin Sexton paced the Cavaliers with 30 points, complementing them with five rebounds and two assists. Cedi Osman registered 22 points and four rebounds. Darius Garland compiled 20 points, seven assists, one rebound and one steal. Kevin Love managed 12 points, three rebounds and one assist. Tristan Thompson mustered just three points but hauled in 14 boards.

The Thunder remain on the road and next visit the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday night, while the Cavaliers remain home and tangle with the Minnesota Timberwolves on Sunday night.

The Washington Wizards defeated the visiting Denver Nuggets, 128-114, at Capital One Arena on Saturday. 

While Denver led 101-99 with nine minutes remaining, Washington dominated from there. In fact, the Wizards finished the game on a 29-13 run to win by 14 points. They actually did almost all of their damage in the first and fourth quarters, outscoring Denver, 64-43. The Wizards bench was the difference, outscoring the Nuggets bench, 92-32. Washington also shot 55 percent from the field while holding Denver to just 46 percent shooting. That also allowed Washington to win the rebounding battle, 49-33. 

The Nuggets (25-10) were led by Jamal Murray, who tallied 39 points, four rebounds and two steals. Nikola Jokic amassed 14 points, 10 rebounds and four assists. Paul Millsap totaled 12 points and five boards while Will Barton generated 10 points and three boards. No other player had more than eight points or three assists. 

The Wizards (11-24) got a career-high 32 points from Ish Smith, who also provided three rebounds, eight assists and three steals to lead the bench. Troy Brown also tallied 25 points, 14 rebounds and three assists off the pine. Isaac Bonga also had 15 points and four rebounds off the bench too. Johnathan Williams led the starters with 12 points, eight rebounds and three blocks. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Denver remaining on the road to face the Atlanta Hawks and Washington remaining home to play the Boston Celtics.

The Boston Celtics defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 111-104, at United Center on Saturday evening. 

The Bulls got out to a good start at home with a 10-2 run, but the Celtics rallied ahead to take a two-point lead, heading into the second. The Bulls pulled ahead to start the second but the Celtics rallied back again to take a three-point lead into halftime. They carried the momentum into the third quarter, where they outscored the hosts by nine, to push their lead to 12, by the beginning of the final frame. The Celtics stayed on top through the fourth and held off a run by the Bulls, to earn their third straight win and improve to 11-6 on the road. 

Jayson Tatum led the Celtics with 28 points, seven rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks, in 36 minutes. Enes Kanter added 17 points, 12 rebounds, two blocks and an assist, while Gordon Hayward tallied 24 points, five rebounds, three assists and one steal. The Celtics shot 52 percent from the field, including 8-of-19 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Zach LaVine led the Bulls with 35 points, four steals, three assists and two rebounds, in 38 minutes. Kris Dunn added 13 points, seven assists, four rebounds and three steals, while Wendell Carter Jr. tallied 11 points, 14 rebounds, three steals, two blocks and two assists. The Bulls shot 42 percent from the field, including 13-of-34 from long range. 

The Bulls (13-23) will look to bounce back as they take on the Mavericks in Dallas on Monday. The Celtics (25-8) take on the Wizards in Washington on Monday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 127-118, at Fiserv Forum on Saturday evening. 

The Spurs got out to a good start on the road and held a two-point lead after a competitive first quarter. Things heated up in the second, where the Bucks outscored the visitors 42-35, to take a five-point lead into halftime. The Spurs came out strong in the third and tied the score at 79, but the Bucks outscored the Spurs 24-12 through the rest of the quarter to make it a 12-point game to start the fourth. The Bucks charged ahead and pushed their lead to 19, early in the fourth. The Spurs kept fighting but could not find the answer, as they fell for their second straight loss, while this marks the fifth straight win for the Bucks..

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 32 points and eight rebounds, in 29 minutes. Eric Bledsoe added 21 points, six assists, three rebounds and a steal, while Khris Middleton tallied 20 points, five rebounds and three assists. The Bucks shot 49 percent from the field, including 17-of-45 from long range.

Meanwhile, DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 26 points, five assists, four rebounds and a steal, in 32 minutes. LaMarcus Aldridge added 16 points, 10 rebounds and two assists, while Rudy Gay tallied 15 points and eight rebounds, off the bench. The Spurs shot 41 percent from the field, including 11-of-31 from long range. 

The Spurs (14-19) and the Bucks (32-5) will face-off again on Monday, in the second game of a home-and-home series.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the Golden State Warriors, 111-104, at Chase Center on Saturday evening. 

The Pistons got out to a solid start on the road, with an early 12-4 lead, but the Warriors fought back to make it a two-point game heading into the second. The Pistons led for most of the second, but the Warriors closed the quarter on a 10-7 run, to grab a three-point lead by halftime. The Pistons turned up the defense in the third quarter and built a 12-point lead late in the third, but the Warriors managed to keep it to a three-point game heading into the final frame. The Pistons kept their focus and pushed their lead back to 10, with six minutes left in the contest. They maintained a 10-point lead with a minute left and held on to end a three-game slide, while this marks the fourth straight loss for the Warriors.  

Derrick Rose led the Pistons with 22 points, two rebounds, two assists and a steal, in 28 minutes off the bench. Andre Drummond tallied 14 points, 18 rebounds, three assists, three steals and two blocks, while Sekou Doumbouya added 16 points, 10 rebounds, two assists, two steals and a block. The Pistons shot 52 percent from the field, including 11-of-27 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Alec Burks led the Warriors with 27 points, seven rebounds, five assists and a steal, in 31 minutes off the bench. Omari Spellman added 23 points and five rebounds, while Damion Lee chipped in 14 points, five rebounds, three assists, a steal and a block. The Warriors shot 40 percent from the field, including 11-of-22 from long range. 
 
The Warriors (9-28) will look to bounce back as they take on the Kings in Sacramento ok Monday. The Pistons (13-23) take on the Lakers in L.A. on Sunday.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 117-115, at Golden 1 Center on Saturday. 

There were 13 ties and eight lead changes in this game, with neither team leading by more than 14 points. A 20-5 run to start the fourth quarter was critical for the Pelicans, as they never relinquished the lead from there, despite Sacramento tying the game with 4.2 seconds left on a four-point play. J.J. Redick then played the hero, hitting a game-winning lay-up with 1.1 seconds left. Ball movement was the difference in the game, with New Orleans recording 28 assists to 15 turnovers while Sacramento had 20 assists to match their 20 turnovers. 

The Pelicans (12-24) were led by Lonzo Ball, who tallied 24 points, six rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Jrue Holiday collected 19 points, five rebounds and seven assists. Redick amassed 18 points, two rebounds and three assists. Brandon Ingram generated 16 points, five rebounds, three assists and three steals while Derrick Favors totaled 13 points and 11 boards. Josh Hart led the bench with 16 points. 

The Kings (13-23) were led by Harrison Barnes, who provided 30 points, four rebounds and three assists. De'Aaron Fox accrued 17 points, three rebounds and five assists. Buddy Hield collected 24 points, 12 rebounds, three assists and two steals while Richaun Holmes and Nemanja Bjelica each picked up double-doubles. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Sacramento playing host to the struggling Golden State Warriors and New Orleans returning home to play the Utah Jazz.

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 109-106, at TD Garden on Friday. 

While Atlanta got out to a 32-19 first quarter lead, Boston was able to prevail as a big favorite. In fact, they bounced back with a 34-23 second quarter and won each of the final three quarters. That led to 12 ties and six lead changes in total. Trae Young had an opportunity to tie the game with a three-pointer in the final seconds but had that shot blocked by Daniel Theis. Boston ended up out-rebounding Atlanta, 54-42, while holding them to 42 percent from the field and 36 percent from three-point range. 

The Hawks (7-28) were led by Young and his 28 points, five rebounds and 10 assists. Kevin Huerter amassed 17 points, seven rebounds and five assists. John Collins tallied 16 points and eight boards while Alex Len had five points, seven rebounds, two assists and two blocks off the bench. 

The Celtics (24-8) were led by Jaylen Brown, who collected 24 points, 10 rebounds, two assists and two steals. Gordon Hayward totaled 18 points and six boards. Marcus Smart accumulated 15 points, six rebounds, nine assists, three steals and two blocks. Enes Kanter led the bench with 14 points, 11 rebounds and two blocks. 

Boston has to play again on Saturday, traveling to face the Chicago Bulls. As for Atlanta, they also play again on Saturday, returning home to host the Indiana Pacers.

The Orlando Magic defeated the Miami Heat, 105-85, at Amway Center on Friday night.

The Magic (16-19) had played well at home all season, and they entered Friday's game against a formidable Heat (25-10) squad in fine form. Orlando forged a 56-44 halftime lead, but Miami managed to shave all but five points off its deficit during a 35-point third quarter. However, the hosts would then take it to a completely different level defensively, managing to hold the visitors to just six points in the final 12 minutes to notch what would eventually be a comfortable home win. 

Jimmy Butler paced the Heat with a 23-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included seven assists and three steals. Bam Adebayo posted 14 points, 10 rebounds, one assist, two blocks and one steal. Duncan Robinson delivered nine points and three boards, while Meyers Leonard produced eight points, seven rebounds, one assist and one steal. 

Terrence Ross led the Magic with 25 points, complementing them with two rebounds and two steals. Nikola Vucevic managed 20 points, 11 rebounds, seven assists and one block. Aaron Gordon delivered 16 points, eight rebounds and three assists. Evan Fournier poured in 15 points and posted three assists, two rebounds and one block. 

The Heat heads back home to face the Portland Trail Blazers on Sunday evening, while the Magic remain home and take on the Utah Jazz on Saturday night.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the Washington Wizards, 122-103, at Capital One Arena on Friday night.

The Trail Blazers (15-21) had the personnel advantage over an injury-racked Wizards (10-24) team that was without Bradley Beal (leg) in addition to its plethora of frontcourt absences, but they nevertheless trailed by a 31-27 margin after one quarter. That seemed to ignite Portland, which erased its deficit during the second and entered halftime with an eight-point edge. That lead stretched to 13 during the third quarter, and the visitors managed to add another five points before the final buzzer. Although their three-point shooting (24.0 percent) left plenty to be desired, the Blazers were excellent from in front of the arc, draining 61.9 percent of their two-point shots. 

Damian Lillard led the way for the Trail Blazers with 35 points, adding three rebounds, three assists and one steal. C.J. McCollum supplied 24 points, six assists, four rebounds and one steal. Hassan Whiteside generated a 23-point, 21-rebound double-double that also included five blocks and one assist. Carmelo Anthony registered 16 points, six boards, two assists and two steals. Mario Hezonja led the bench with 10 points.

Jordan McRae paced the Wizards with 35 points, complementing them with five rebounds, four assists and one block. Garrison Mathews followed with 18 points. Ish Smith tallied 16 points, five assists, two rebounds and one steal. Troy Brown, Jr. furnished 10 points, seven boards, one assist and one steal. Isaiah Thomas was ejected after just one minute for shoving a referee during a battle for a loose ball.

The Trail Blazers remain on the road and head down to South Florida to battle the Miami Heat on Sunday night, while the Wizards remain home to take on the Denver Nuggets on Saturday night.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 118-108, at Toyota Center on Friday. 

While Philly got out to a 27-20 lead after the first quarter, Houston responded with a 40-26 second quarter. In fact, that allowed them to hold the lead for the entirety of the second half, with Philadelphia never getting the game within a five-point margin after that. The Rockets went 12-of-32 from three-point range and 24-of-32 from the free-throw line while the Sixers went 6-of-27 from long range and 18-of-25 from the charity stripe.  

The Sixers (23-14) were led by Ben Simmons and his 29 points, 13 rebounds, 11 assists, three steals and four blocks. Tobias Harris totaled 24 points, two rebounds and two assists. Joel Embiid accumulated 20 points, 12 rebounds, three assists and two steals while Trey Burke led the bench with 11 points, three rebounds and three assists. 

The Rockets (24-11) got a triple-double from James Harden, who collected 44 points, 11 rebounds and 11 assists. Clint Capela accrued 30 points, 14 rebounds, three assists and two steals. Russell Westbrook collected 20 points, seven rebounds, four assists and three steals while Eric Gordon led the bench with 12 points, two rebounds and two assists. 

Philly is off until Monday when they play host to the Oklahoma City Thunder. Houston actually doesn't play again until Wednesday when they travel to play the Atlanta Hawks.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the visiting New York Knicks, 120-112, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Friday.

There were 12 ties and 26 lead changes in this tightly contested game but Phoenix took care of business in the fourth quarter. In fact, they finished the game on an 18-9 run across the final 5:38, outscoring the Knicks in the fourth quarter, 37-25. Ball movement was the difference, with the Suns recording 28 assists to 10 turnovers while the Knicks committed 15 turnovers to 19 assists. That allowed Phoenix to out-shoot New York from the field, from three-point range and from the free-throw line. 

The Knicks (10-24) were led by Marcus Morris, who tallied 25 points, three rebounds, two assists and two steals. Elfrid Payton collected 15 points, five rebounds and six assists. Julius Randle accrued 13 points, 13 rebounds, three assists and two blocks while Bobby Portis led the bench with 20 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

The Suns (13-21) were led by Devin Booker and his 38 points, three rebounds and seven assists. Kelly Oubre Jr accumulated 29 points, five rebounds and three steals. Aron Baynes totaled 20 points, 12 rebounds and two assists while DeAndre Ayton generated 15 points, 13 rebounds and five assists. Ricky Rubio also provided nine points, four rebounds and 10 assists. 

Both teams return to action on Sunday, with Phoenix playing host to the Memphis Grizzlies and New York traveling to face the Los Angeles Clippers.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 123-113, at Staples Center on Friday.

A 42-30 first quarter really set the tone for Los Angeles in this game, with the Lakers holding the lead for the final three quarters. In fact, the Lakers then outscored the Pelicans, 31-21, in the third quarter, leading by at least seven points for the final 20 minutes of play. Three-point shooting was the difference, with the Lakers hitting 14-of-29 and the Pelicans shooting just 11-of-37 from long range. In addition, Los Angeles out-rebounded New Orleans, 47-40, while out-assisting them, 29-24. 

The Pelicans (11-24) were led by Lonzo Ball, who tallied 23 points, two rebounds, five assists and two steals. Brandon Ingram generated 22 points, three rebounds, three assists and two blocks. Derrick Favors totaled 15 points, 14 rebounds, two assists and four blocks. E'Twaun Moore led the bench with 16 points, three rebounds and two assists. 

The Lakers (28-7) were led by Anthony Davis, who accrued 46 points, 13 rebounds and three steals on 15-of-21 shooting. Danny Green totaled 25 points, five rebounds, five assists and two steals. LeBron James accumulated 17 points, eight rebounds, 15 assists and two steals while Kyle Kuzma led the bench with 10 points. 

New Orleans has to play again on Saturday, remaining on the road to face the Sacramento Kings. As for Los Angeles, they play host to the Detroit Pistons on Sunday for their next outing.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 109-106, at Rocket Mortgage FieldHouse on Thursday evening.

The Hornets (14-23) and the Cavaliers (10-24) played a very tight encounter here, as neither side dominated the game and this game was decided at the very last minute. Charlotte jumped ahead 31-29 following the first quarter, but Cleveland flipped the score with a 30-21 second quarter. The Cavaliers were up by seven points into the halftime break, but the Hornets turned things around in the second half. A 30-26 third quarter made things close, and the Hornets also won the final 12 minutes by a 27-21 score. That was enough to give them a huge win on the road. With the win, Charlotte moved to 7-12 on the road while the Cavaliers fell to 6-11 at home.

Terry Rozier was the best player for the Hornets, as he ended with 30 points, six rebounds and three assists while shooting 11-22 from the field. Devonte' Graham had 16 points despite shooting 3-8 from the field, but he also added 11 assists. P.J. Washington had 14 points, and Dwyane Bacon ended with 15 points in 28 minutes off the bench. Cody Zeller ended with 11 points and seven boards.

Collin Sexton once again led the Cavaliers on offense, as he had 21 points despite shooting 8-17 from the field. Cedi Osman had 17 points, while Kevin Love chipped in with 18 points, eight boards and four assists. Rookie Darius Garland ended with 14 points, eight assists, and five rebounds. John Henson contributed 10 points and six rebounds while playing 15 minutes off the bench.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the Indiana Pacers, 124-116, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Thursday night.

The Pacers (22-13) came into the contest short-handed, as Malcolm Brogdon (back) was ruled out earlier in the day. However, Indiana jumped out to a rather surprising 37-27 lead through the first 12 minutes, but the Nuggets (24-10) had erased all but two points from their deficit by halftime. Denver continued to play well on both ends of the floor coming out of intermission and ultimately headed into the fourth quarter with a four-point advantage. Indiana would get as close as 107-104 with 6:33 remaining before the visitors pulled away.

Michael Porter, Jr. paced the Nuggets with a career-high 25 points, which he supplemented with five rebounds and one assist. Nikola Jokic and Jamal Murray followed with 22 points apiece, with Jokic pulling down seven rebounds and Murray dishing out seven assists. Will Barton generated a 16-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included five assists and two steals. Gary Harris supplied 12 points, five assists, three rebounds and one steal.

Jeremy Lamb led the Pacers with 30 points and also furnished six rebounds, two assists and one steal. Myles Turner totaled 21 points and five rebounds. T.J. Warren registered 20 points, five boards, two assists and two steals. Domantas Sabonis delivered 18 points, nine rebounds, nine assists, two steals and one block. Aaron Holiday mustered six points but dished out 10 assists.

The Nuggets remain on the road and tangle with the Washington Wizards on Saturday night, while the Pacers travel to face the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday night as well.

The Miami Heat defeated the Toronto Raptors, 84-76, at AmericanAirlines Arena on Thursday evening.

The Heat (25-9) and the Raptors (23-12) were set to play a marquee matchup between two of the best teams of the Eastern Conference this season, and the game didnt disappoint. Despite the fact it was a low-scoring affair, it seemed both teams were always going back and forth with no clear dominant force. Toronto jumped to a 20-18 lead after the first quarter, but Miami flipped the script with a 24-19 score in the second quarter to earn a three-point lead at the break. The third quarter ended with a 21-21 score, but Miami pulled away for good with a 21-16 score in the final 12 minutes of action. With the win, Miami extended their solid record at home to 16-1, while the Raptors fell to 9-7 on the road.

Only four players scored in double digits for the Heat, but the only starter who topped that figure was Bam Adebayo who ended with 15 points and 14 rebounds. Goran Dragic and Tyler Herro each had 13 points off the bench, while Derrick Jones Jr. ended with 10 points and six rebounds. Jimmy Butler struggled from the field since he had eight points (shooting 2-10) but added 12 rebounds and seven assists.

Serge Ibaka scored a game-high 19 points for the Raptors, and he also added 10 rebounds. OG Anunoby ended with a double-double of 12 points and 12 boards. Kyle Lowry finished with 15 points and eight assists. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson chipped in with 13 points in 29 minutes off the bench. Fred VanVleet struggled and scored seven points while shooting 3-16 from the field.

The Utah Jazz defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 102-98, at United Center on Thursday evening. 

Five players scored in double digits to lead the Jazz to their fourth straight win. The Bulls got out to a good start with an early 9-2 lead, but the Jazz rallied back to take a 25-22 lead by the end of the first quarter. The Jazz led by five with three minutes left in the half, but the Bulls used a 10-1 run to take a four-point lead into halftime. The Jazz came out strong in the third and outscored the hosts by 10 points in the quarter, to grab a six-point lead heading into the final frame. They pushed their lead to 10, early in the fourth, but the Bulls clawed back to tie it up at 96, with 1:27 to go. The Jazz came up clutch at the foul line with four makes in the final 90 seconds, to help them seal the road win. 

Bojan Bogdanovic led the Jazz with 19 points, six rebounds and a steal, in 34 minutes. Rudy Gobert tallied 17 points, 12 rebounds and three blocks, while Donovan Mitchell finished with 17 points, seven assists and four rebounds. Joe Ingles added eight points, five rebounds and 10 assists. The Jazz shot 49 percent from the field, including 11-of-30 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Zach LaVine led the Bulls with 26 points on 9-of-26 shooting, in 38 minutes. Wendell Carter Jr. finished with 18 points, 13 rebounds and four assists, while Lauri Markkanen added 18 points, eight rebounds, two assists and a steal. The Bulls shot 39 percent from the field, including 11-of-36 from long range. 

The Bulls (13-22) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Celtics on Saturday. The Jazz (22-12) take on the Magic in Orlando on Saturday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the Golden State Warriors, 99-84, at Target Center on Thursday night. 

The TImberwolves (13-21) came into the contest without their two best players in Karl-Anthony Towns (knee) and Andrew Wiggins, but they nevertheless opened the game on a 34-19 run through the first 12 minutes. Although the Warriors (9-27) were more competitive in the second quarter, Minnesota still owned a 17-point edge at halftime. Ultimately, Golden State narrowly outscored their hosts by a 43-41 margin in the second half, but thanks to the T-Wolves' considerable cushion, it wasn't near enough to overcome their early hole.

Glenn Robinson III paced the Warriors with 16 points, adding six rebounds and one assist. Eric Paschall tallied 13 points and seven rebounds. Omari Spellman and Damion Lee generated matching 10-point contributions, with Spellman also pulling down five boards. 

Robert Covington and Shabazz Napier led the Timberwolves with matching 20-point efforts, with Covington also posting 10 boards and Napier dishing out seven assists. Naz Reid totaled 13 points, six rebounds, one assist and one block. Kelan Martin provided 12 points, eight boards and one assist. Jarrett Culver pitched in 10 points, five rebounds, one assist and one steal. 

The Warriors head back home to take on the Detroit Pistons on Saturday night, while the Timberwolves pay a visit to the Cleveland Cavaliers on Sunday night.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 123-111, American Airlines Center on Thursday evening.

The Nets got out to a good start on the road, with an early 13-3 lead, but the Mavericks outscored the visitors 28-17 through the rest of the quarter, to take a one-point lead into the second. The Mavs pushed their lead to seven early in the second, but the Nets rallied to grab the lead with five minutes left in the quarter and held the advantage to take a five-point lead into halftime. The Mavs got out to a hot start in the third and tied the game within the first two minutes of the quarter. They held the advantage for most of the quarter, but the score was tied at 93, entering the final frame. The Mavs took over in the fourth, as they outscored the visitors by 12 points in the quarter. This marks the end of a two-game slide for the Mavs, while it marks the fourth straight loss for the Nets. 

Luka Doncic led the Mavericks with 31 points, 13 rebounds, seven assists and a block, in 34 minutes. Seth Curry added 25 points on 9-of-13 shooting, including 5-of-5 from long range, in 31 minutes off the bench. J.J. Barea chipped in 10 points, six assists and four rebounds. The Mavs shot 50 percent from the field, including 18-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Spencer Dinwiddie led the Nets with 19 points, five assists, two rebounds and a steal, in 23 minutes. Dzanan Musa added 14 points and three assists, in 17 minutes off the bench, while DeAndre Jordan toiled 10 points, 10 rebounds and two assists. The Nets shot 46 percent from the field, including 12-of-37 from deep. 

The Nets (16-17) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Raptors on Saturday. The Mavs (22-12) play host to the Hornets on Saturday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host San Antonio Spurs, 109-103, at AT&T Center on Thursday. 

There were nine ties and 14 lead changes in this game, with Oklahoma City making a late run to grab their win. In fact, the Thunder outscored the Spurs, 63-48, in the second half, overcoming a 14-point deficit. Taking care of the ball was the difference in the game, with Oklahoma City recording seven steals while committing just three turnovers. The Spurs failed to record a steal while committing eight turnovers. In addition, the Thunder shot 48 percent from the field while holding the Spurs to 42 percent shooting. 

The Thunder (19-15) were led by Shai Gilgeous-Alexander, who tallied 25 points, seven rebounds, five assists and two blocks. Chris Paul collected 16 points, eight rebounds, five assists and two steals. Steven Adams amassed 14 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Dennis Schroder led the bench with 19 points and three assists. 

The Spurs (14-19) were led by DeMar DeRozan and his 30 points, four rebounds and three assists. LaMarcus Aldridge was the only other starter in double figures, totaling 22 points, 11 rebounds and three blocks. Lonnie Walker IV led the bench with 16 points and seven boards. Derrick White also provided five points, seven rebounds and five assists off the bench.

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Oklahoma City traveling to face the Cleveland Cavaliers and San Antonio facing the Milwaukee Bucks on the road as well.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the host Memphis Grizzlies, 128-123, at Golden 1 Center on Thursday.

There were seven ties and 14 lead changes in this game, with Sacramento making the final run to decide the game. In fact, the Kings outscored the Grizzlies, 38-26, in the fourth quarter despite trailing by 20 points in the first half. It was a true tale of four quarters, with each one being decided by double-digit margins. Sacramento won the second quarter, 37-18 and the fourth quarter, 38-26, while Memphis won the first quarter, 42-26, and the third quarter, 37-27. Defense was the difference for the Kings, recording nine steals and eight blocks while the Grizzlies had just four combined steals and blocks. In addition, Sacramento won the turnover battle, 17-12.

The Grizzlies (13-22) were led by Ja Morant and his 23 points and seven assists. Jaren Jackson Jr accrued 18 points, seven rebounds and two assists before fouling out. Jonas Valanciunas amassed 18 points, 12 rebounds and two assists while Jae Crowder provided 19 points, four rebounds and six assists. De'Anthony Melton led the bench with 16 points and five boards.

The Kings (13-22) were led by De'Aaron Fox, who collected 27 points, four rebounds, nine assists and five steals. Buddy Hield tallied 26 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Richaun Holmes totaled 18 points, seven rebounds and two blocks while Harrison Barnes generated 17 points and three assists. Bogdan Bogdanovic led the bench with 16 points, two rebounds and two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Memphis traveling to face the Los Angeles Clippers and Sacramento remaining home to play the New Orleans Pelicans.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 126-112, at Staples Center on Thursday.

While there were 12 ties and 15 lead changes in the first half, Los Angeles rode a 37-16 third quarter to a blowout victory. In fact, Detroit never got the game within a single-digit margin in the fourth quarter. Los Angeles ended up shooting 54 percent from the field and 39 percent from three-point range while holding Detroit to 43 percent from the field and 21 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Clippers recorded 12 blocks to the Pistons one while out-assisting them, 29-20. 

The Pistons (12-23) were led by Bruce Brown Jr, who provided 15 points, two rebounds and six assists off the bench, Svi Mykhailiuk led the starters with 14 points, two rebounds and two assists. Andre Drummond amassed 10 points, 12 rebounds and three steals. Derrick Rose, Christian Wood, Langston Galloway and Thon Maker all reached double figures off the bench too. 

The Clippers (25-11) starters were led by Kawhi Leonard, who tallied 18 points, six rebounds, five assists and two steals. Paul George had just 12 points, three rebounds and three assists. Montrezl Harrell led the bench with 23 points, four rebounds and four blocks. Lou Williams generated 22 points, five rebounds and five assists while JaMychal Green totaled 12 points and 12 boards off the pine as well. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Detroit remaining on the road to play the Golden State Warriors and Los Angeles playing host to the Memphis Grizzlies in a day game.

The Orlando Magic defeated the Washington Wizards, 122-101, at Capital One Arena on Wednesday evening.

The Magic (15-19) dominated the game from start to finish, and they didnt have major issues to take advantage of a struggling Wizards (10-23) team that was seriously depleted by injuries. Orlando quickly took advantage following a 31-29 first quarter, and they repeated the same score in the second one, so they entered the half-time break up by four points. They pulled away late, however, with a 32-25 third quarter and a 28-18 fourth period. Orlando were on top during most of the contest, and easily defeated their Eastern Conference foes despite playing on the road. Orlando moved to 5-12 on the road and Washington fell to 5-9 at home. For what is worth, the Magic shot 47.4 percent from the field while the Wizards only converted 37.9 percent of their field goals.

D.J. Augustin led the way for the Magic and scored a season-high 25 points while adding nine assists, three rebounds and two steals. Nikola Vucevic had 20 points and 12 rebounds, while Evan Fournier chipped in with 18 points and Markelle Fultz added 16 points, eight assists and four boards. Terrence Ross contributed 15 points in 24 minutes off the bench. Wes Iwundu delivered a strong effort and finished with 10 points and six rebounds.

Bradley Beal scored 27 points for the Wizards, and he was the only starter who scored in double digits in this contest. Most of the heavy lifting was done by bench players, though. Ish Smith and Garrison Mathews had 10 points each, while Troy Brown Jr. added 14 points with seven boards. Jordan McRae had 15 points and seven rebounds.

The New York Knicks defeated the visiting Portland Trail Blazers, 117-93, at Madison Square Garden on Wednesday evening. 

The Knicks used a great team effort to spoil Carmelo Anthony's return to New York and hand the Trail Blazers their fifth straight loss. Five players scored in double digits to lead the Knicks, led by Mitchell Robinson and Julius Randle, who finished with 22 points each, while Carmelo Anthony led the Trail Blazers with 26 points on 11-of-17 shooting, in 31 minutes of action. 

The Blazers got out to a good start in the contest, as the led 27-25 after one quarter. The Knicks turned the tables in the second, as they rallied to take the lead early in the quarter and held on to take a three-point lead at halftime. They carried the momentum into the third and opened up a six-point lead early in the quarter. The Trail Blazers managed to cut it to two, but the Knicks pushed right back to end the quarter with a six-point lead. The Knicks took it to another level in the fourth, as they outscored the visitors by 18 in the quarter, to seal their third consecutive win. 

Marcus Morris Sr. added 18 points, seven rebounds and three assists, while Frank Ntilikina was big for the Knicks, with nine points, 10 assists, three rebounds, two blocks and a steal, in 23 minutes off the bench. 

Meanwhile, Hassan Whiteside added 17 points, 12 rebounds, three blocks and two assists. C.J. McCollum added 17 points, four rebounds and four assists, and Damian Lillard totalled 11 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists. 

The Trail Blazers (14-21) will look to bounce back as they take on the Wizards in Washington on Friday. The Knicks (10-24) take on the Suns in Phoenix on Friday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 106-104, at Fiserv Forum on Wednesday night.

The Bucks (31-5) seemingly came into the interconference matchup with every advantage, as not only did they own a markedly better record than the Timberwolves (12-21), but Minnesota came in with multiple key injuries as well. However, it was the visitors that owned a surprising 23-19 lead after one quarter, and that trailed by just one point at halftime. Milwaukee managed to create some modest distance during the third quarter by adding five points to their advantage, yet the game would still come down the buzzer. After the Timberwolves got to within two points with 46.2 seconds remaining, Gorgui Dieng missed a potential game-tying jumper and Giannis Antetokounmpo blocked a Robert Covington's desperation three-point attempt as time expired to seal the victory. 

Shabazz Napier led the Timberwolves with 22 points, adding six rebounds, three assists and one block. Dieng totaled 15 points, six boards, one assist and one block. Josh Okogie and Jaylen Nowell managed matching 12-point tallies while pulling down four and two rebounds, respectively. Naz Reid poured in 11 points, while Keita Bates-Diop supplied 10 points, three rebounds, one assist and one steal. Covington mustered just seven points but also posted 11 rebounds, three assists, three steals and one block.

Antetokounmpo paced the Bucks with 32 points and also compiled 17 rebounds, four assists and two blocks. Khris Middleton registered 13 points, eight rebounds, four assists and two steals. Brook Lopez collected 11 points, four boards, three assists, six blocks and one steal. Eric Bledsoe delivered 10 points, six rebounds, two assists and two blocks. 

The Timberwolves head back home and tangle with the Golden State Warriors on Thursday night, while the Bucks remain home and face the San Antonio Spurs on Saturday night.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Phoenix Suns, 117-107, at Staples Center on Wednesday.

A 43-17 first quarter really set the tone in this game for the Lakers, winning in wire-to-wire fashion. In fact, Los Angeles led by up to 36 points but Phoenix fought all the way back to get it to a seven-point margin in the final minute thanks to a 66-43 second half. With that said, that was the closest they got after the opening five minutes. Los Angeles was able to prevail despite losing the rebounding, assisting, field goal percentage, three-point shooting, fastbreak scoring and points in the paint battles. The only real advantage for the Lakers was their defense, recording nine steals and five blocks to the Suns seven steals and three blocks. 

The Suns (13-21) were led by Devin Booker, who tallied 32 points, two rebounds and seven assists. Kelly Oubre Jr amassed 26 points, six rebounds, three assists and three steals. Ricky Rubio accumulated six points, five rebounds and nine assists while DeAndre Ayton led the bench with 16 points and 14 rebounds. 

The Lakers (27-7) got a triple-double from LeBron James, who collected 31 points, 13 rebounds, 12 assists and two steals. Anthony Davis totaled 26 points, 11 rebounds and two assists. Avery Bradley generated 18 points, five rebounds and three steals on 9-of-11 shooting while Kyle Kuzma led the bench with 19 points. 

Both teams return to action on Friday against resurgent teams, with Phoenix returning home to play the New York Knicks and Los Angeles playing host to the New Orleans Pelicans.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 109-92, at Spectrum Center on Tuesday afternoon.

The Celtics (23-8) and the Hornets (13-23) aimed to end the year on a strong note, but it seemed the Celtics were the only team able to execute since they wasted no time to get the win here following a dominant performance on both ends of the court. Boston quickly jumped to a 24-18 lead in the first quarter, and they would never look back afterwards. Boston won the second quarter by a 26-25 score and while the third one ended with a 30-30 draw, both teams knew the game was essentially over heading into the final 12 minutes of action thanks to Boston's seven point lead. Charlotte couldn't bounce back down the stretch and the Celtics won the final quarter by 10 points, so Boston cruised their way and ended earning a 17-point victory over their Eastern Conference foes. With the win, the Celtics improved to 10-6 on the road while the Hornets fell to 7-11 at home.

Jayson Tatum, Kemba Walker and Gordon Hayward all surpassed the 20-point mark for the Celtics in this win. Walker had 22 points with seven assists and four rebounds, Hayward had 21 points with 10 boards and six dimes, and Tatum paced the team with 24 points and seven rebounds along with three steals. Enes Kanter produced off the bench and ended with 13 points and 14 boards in 23 minutes off the bench.

Six Charlotte players scored in double figures, but that didn't seem to matter once everything was said and done. Rookie P.J. Washington had 15 points for the Hornets, while Miles Bridges had 14 points with 10 rebounds for the losing cause. Terry Rozier had 10 points and Devonte' Graham chipped in with 11, but both players struggled from the field. The backcourt duo combined for a 28.0 percent from the field in this defeat.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 115-97, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Tuesday afternoon.

Both the Pacers (22-12) and the 76ers (23-13) entered this game riding two-game losing streaks, but Indiana ended that skid with a strong performance in front of their fans that saw them dominate through the first three quarters with absolute ease. The Pacers got ahead after the first 12 minutes of action by a 29-27 score, but they pulled away for good in the second quarter with a 38-16 score and they would never look back. Indiana also won the third quarter by a 29-23 score, so the final 12 minutes were nothing more than garbage time. Philadelphia won the final quarter 31-19, but the game was entirely decided and the Pacers ended their two-game losing run in style against one of the top teams in the Eastern Conference. With the win, Indiana moved to 15-3 at home while the Sixers fell to 7-11 on the road.

Domantas Sabonis was the best player for the Pacers, as the Lithuanian big man ended with 23 points, 10 rebounds and five assists. Myles Turner had 14 points and five rebounds, while T.J. Warren chipped in with 21 points. Jeremy Lamb had 13 points and T.J. McConnell had 11 points with 10 assists coming off the bench. Malcolm Brogdon only played eight minutes before exiting with a back injury.

The Sixers didn't have Joel Embiid and missed him dearly, as their leading scorer was Josh Richardson who ended with 20 points and five assists. Ben Simmons had 18 points and 10 rebounds, but he also committed six turnovers. No other Philadelphia player scored in double figures, as household names such as Al Horford (five points) and Tobias Harris (nine points) also struggled in this one.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 105-87, at Golden 1 Center on Tuesday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, but the Clippers took the early advantage, with a 28-23 lead heading into the second. They picked up the pace in the second and pushed the lead to double digits within minutes. The Clippers outscored the Kings by 12 in the quarter, to take a 17-point lead by halftime. The Kings came out stronger in the third quarter but only managed to trim the deficit by two points heading into the final frame. The fourth quarter was a low-scoring one, but the Clippers managed to maintain a comfortable lead and hold on for their 10th road win. This marks the eighth straight loss for the Kings. 

Kawhi Leonard led the Clippers with 24 points, seven assists, two rebounds and two steals, in 38 minutes. Paul George totalled 21 points, 11 rebounds, nine assists and three steals, while Maurice Harkless added 12 points, seven rebounds and a steal. The Clippers shot 41 percent from the field, including 12-of-36 from long range.
