Meanwhile, Richaun Holmes led the Kings with 22 points and 10 rebounds, in 31 minutes. Buddy Hield added 20 points, six rebounds and five assists, while De'Aaron Fox added nine points, six assists, four rebounds and two steals. The Kings shot 41 percent from the field, including 8-of-28 from deep. 

The Kings (12-22) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Grizzlies on Thursday. The Clippers (24-11) play host to the Pistons on Thursday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 117-97, at Scotiabank Arena on Tuesday night.

The Raptors (23-11) got a bit more than they likely bargained for early from a feisty Cavaliers (10-22) squad, as they managed only a 27-25 lead through one. However, the difference in talent rose to the forefront in a second quarter during which Toronto outscored Cleveland by a 32-18 margin. The home squad kept a step ahead of the visitors during the second half as well, leading to a lopsided home win.

Collin Sexton led the Cavaliers with 22 points. Tristan Thompson and Cedi Osman generated matching 14-point tallies, with Thompson also pulling down 11 boards. Kevin Porter, Jr. furnished 13 points, four rebounds and four assists. Darius Garland totaled 12 points, four assists, one rebound and one steal. Kevin Love generated a 10-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included two assists and two blocks.

Kyle Lowry paced the Raptors with 24 points, eight assists, one rebound and one block. Serge Ibaka contributed a 20-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included two assists, one steal and one block. Terence Davis supplied 19 points and four rebounds. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson turned in 14 points and five rebounds. Fred VanVleet and OG Anunoby posted matching 12-point tallies, with VanVleet also pulling in seven rebounds and recording four blocks and Anunoby dishing out seven assists.

The Cavaliers head back home and tangle with the Hornets on Thursday night, while the Raptors face off with the Miami Heat on Thursday night.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Denver Nuggets, 130-104, at Toyota Center on Tuesday.

While there were nine lead changes in the first quarter, that was actually the only time Denver had a lead. In fact, Houston rode a 69-52 first half to their big lead and really put it to bed with a 38-15 fourth quarter. The Rockets ended up shooting 53 percent from the field and 47 percent from three-point range while holding the Nuggets to 46 percent from the field and 32 percent from long range. 

The Nuggets (23-10) were led by Nikola Jokic, who collected 21 points, eight rebounds and four assists. Paul Millsap accrued 13 points, nine rebounds, three assists and two blocks. Jamal Murray amassed 12 points and six assists. Will Barton accumulated 10 points, nine rebounds, seven assists and two blocks. Monte' Morris led the bench with 18 points, three rebounds, four assists and three steals. 

The Rockets (23-11) were led by James Harden and his 35 points, three rebounds, six assists and two blocks. Russell Westbrook tallied 28 points, three rebounds and seven assists. Clint Capela totaled 16 points, 10 rebounds and three steals while Isaiah Hartenstein led the bench with 16 points and 12 rebounds. 

On deck for Denver is another road game against the Indiana Pacers on Thursday. As for Houston, they return to action on Friday when they play host to the Philadelphia 76ers.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Golden State Warriors, 117-113, at AT&T Center on Tuesday evening, 

The Warriors got out to a good start on the road, as they took a 32-25 lead after one quarter. The Spurs picked it up in the second but could not pull ahead, as they trailed by two at halftime. The Warriors stayed ahead to start the third, but the Spurs pulled ahead late in the quarter, to grab a two-point lead heading into the final frame. The Warriors took a brief lead mid way through the fourth but the Spurs came back to take a two-point lead with 17 seconds left. However, Glenn Robinson III came up with a clutch jumper for the Warriors to send the game to overtime. The Spurs made no mistake in overtime, as they jumped ahead early and led through the entire final period. This marks the second straight win for the Spurs and the second straight loss for the Warriors. 

DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 24 points, five rebounds, four assists and three steals, in 37 minutes. LaMarcus Aldridge added 17 points, 12 rebounds, four assists and three blocks, while Patty Mills added 18 points, four rebounds, four assists and a steal, in 32 minutes off the bench. The Spurs shot 47 percent from the field, including 14-of-31 from deep.  

Meanwhile, Alec Burks led the Warriors with 28 points, four rebounds, four assists, a steal and a block, in 38 minutes. Damion Lee added 20 points, seven rebounds and two assists, while Glenn Robinson III totalled 25 points, three rebounds and three assists. 

The Warriors (9-26) will look to bounce back as they take on the Timberwolves in Minnesota on Thursday. The Spurs (14-18) play host to the Thunder on Thursday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the visiting Dallas Mavericks, 106-101, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Tuesday.

There were seven ties and four lead changes in this game but Oklahoma City made the run that mattered most. In fact, they finished the game on a 14-2 run across the final three minutes, with Dallas missing two three-pointers in the final seconds that would have tied the game. Oklahoma City held Dallas to just 36 percent from the field and 29 percent from three-point range. 

The Mavericks (21-12) were led by Luka Doncic, who tallied 35 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists. Maxi Kleber started for Kristaps Porzingis and amassed 14 points, 14 rebounds and two assists. Dwight Powell accrued 11 points, four rebounds, two assists and two steals. No other player had more than nine points, our rebounds or two assists. 

The Thunder (18-15) were led by Danilo Gallinari and his 20 points, three rebounds and two assists. Shai Gilgeous-Alexnder accumulated 12 points, 10 rebounds, three assists and two steals. Chris Paul collected 17 points, eight rebounds and seven assists while Steven Adams totaled 10 points, 11 rebounds and two assists. Dennis Schroder led the bench with 20 points, seven rebounds and four assists while Nerlens Noel amassed 12 points and 12 boards. 

Both of these teams return to action on Thursday, with Dallas playing host to the Brooklyn Nets and Oklahoma City traveling to face the San Antonio Spurs.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the host Orlando Magic, 101-93, at Amway Center on Monday evening. 

Despite missing Trae Young (ankle), the Hawks outscored the Magic 54-36 in the second half, to snap a 10-game losing streak. The Hawks got out to a good start in the contest, as the led for most of the first quarter and took a 25-21 lead into the second. The Magic picked it up in the second and built an 18-point lead late in the quarter, where they outscored the visitors 36-22, to take a 10-point lead into halftime. The Hawks chipped away through the third and managed to grab a two-point lead heading into the final frame. The Hawks did not look back, as they held the lead the rest of the way, handing the Magic their second straight loss. 

Brandon Goodwin led the Hawks with 21 points, six assists, three rebounds, two steals and a block, in 22 minutes off the bench. Kevin Huerter added 19 points, six rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks, while Alex Len tallied 18 points, 12 rebounds and two assists, in 24 minutes off the bench. The Hawks shot 48 percent from the field, including 9-of-29 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Nikola Vucevic led the Magic with 27 points, six rebounds and two steals, in 35 minutes. Evan Fournier added 22 points, three rebounds and two assists, while Jonathan Isaac finished with 13 points, nine rebounds, three steals, two blocks and two assists. The Magic shot 42 percent from the field, including 5-of-25 from long range. 
 
The Magic (14-19) will look to bounce back as they take on the Wizards in Washington on Wednesday. The Hawks (7-27) head to Boston to face the Celtics on Friday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Miami Heat, 123-105, at Capital One Arena on Monday evening.

The Wizards (10-22) entered this game following a negative run of eight losses in their last 10 contests while the Heat (24-9) were on a five-game winning run, so it was clear Miami were heavy favorites ahead of this contest even if they were playing on the road. However, Miami didn't have a good performance in this contest and they only shot 45.2 percent from the field, while the Wizards converted 51.2 percent of their shots and 45.9 percent from three-point range. Washington, however, got off to a slow start since the Heat built a 39-29 lead following the first quarter. The Wizards turned things around as the game progressed and a 42-24 second quarter gave them a lead they would never relinquish. The Wizards won the remaning two quarters as well, 19-18 and 33-24 respectively, and ended clinching one of their biggest wins of the season. With the victory, the Wizards moved up to 5-8 at home while the Heat fell to 9-8 on the road.

The Wizards were quite depleted ahead of this game, but some role players stepped up big time to post impressive performances. Ian Mahinmi had 25 points, five rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Garrison Mathews chipped in with 28 points and four boards. Jordan McRae added 29 points, eight assists, four rebounds and two steals. Ish Smith finished with 19 points and seven dimes.

Jimmy Butler led the way for the Heat with 27 points, six rebounds and four assists -- he was the only Miami player to surpass the 20-point mark. Duncan Robinson had 16 points, while Bam Adebayo filled the stat sheet with 14 points, 14 rebounds, and five assists. Kendrick Nunn added 14 points, and Goran Dragic chipped in with 10 points off bench.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Chicago Bulls, 123-102, at United Center on Monday night. 

The Bucks (30-5) came into the day not knowing if they'd have Giannis Antetokounmpo (back) available, but the star big man was ultimately able to take the floor. He helped Milwaukee rack up 31 points in the first quarter, but the Bulls (13-21) battled back to cut an 11-point deficit to three by halftime. However, the visitors changed the dynamic of the contest in the third period, opening up their advantage to 18 points with a 40-point tally during the quarter. The Bucks ultimately shot a stellar 54.8 percent and won the battle of the boards by a 59-43 margin. 

Khris Middleton paced the Bucks with 25 points, adding six rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block. Antetokounmpo followed with 23 points, 10 rebounds and six assists. Eric Bledsoe provided 15 points, three rebounds, three assists and four steals. Ersan Ilyasova generated a 14-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included two assists. Robin and Brook Lopez posted matching 11-point tallies while pulling down six and four rebounds, respectively. 

Zach LaVine led the Bulls with 19 points, adding five assists and four rebounds. Lauri Markkanen and Coby White compiled 18 points each, with Markkanen also pulling in six rebounds and White recording four steals. Wendell Carter Jr. and Tomas Satoransky posted 10 points apiece. Carter added 11 rebounds while Satoransky dished out seven assists. 

The Bucks head back home to face the Minnesota Timberwolves on Wednesday night, while the Bulls remain home and tangle with the Utah Jazz on Thursday evening.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 122-115, at Target Center on Monday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, as the Nets took a 29-27 lead after one quarter. The score stayed tight through the second, but the Nets held the edge for the rest of the quarter, taking a 50-49 lead at halftime. The Nets built some momentum in the third and pushed their lead to six points by the start of the fourth. The Timberwolves chipped away in the fourth and tied the game at 96, with 3:30 to go. The teams traded buckets until overtime, where the Timberwolves poured in 19 points, to earn their fourth home win. This marks the third straight loss for the Nets 

Shabazz Napier led the Nets with 24 points, eight assists, three rebounds and two steals, in 34 minutes. Jarrett Culver finished with 21 points, five rebounds, three assists, three steals and a block, while Gorgui Dieng totalled 11 points, 20 rebounds, three steals, two assists and a block. The Timberwolves shot 40 percent from the field, including 17-of-44 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Spencer Dinwiddie led the Nets with 36 points, eight assists, five rebounds and a steal, in 40 minutes. Taurean Prince added 11 points, 14 rebounds, two steals and a block, while Joe Harris added 19 points and seven rebounds. The Nets shot 40 percent from the field, including 15-of-41 from long range. 

The Nets (16-16) will look to bounce back as they take on the Mavs in Dallas on Thursday. The Timberwolves (12-20) take on the Bucks in Milwaukee on Wednesday.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Detroit Pistons, 104-81, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Monday night.

The Jazz (21-12) may have been guilty of taking the struggling Pistons (12-22) too lightly at the onset, as they were surprisingly outscored by a 21-19 margin through the first 12 minutes. Utah still trailed by a one-point margin at halftime, but they changed the dynamic of the game in the third quarter by building a 10-point advantage going into the final period. The hosts then saw their offense come alive in the fourth quarter, as they outscored Detroit by a 36-23 margin to close out lopsided home win.

Derrick Rose paced the Pistons with 20 points, adding four assists, one steal and one block. Andre Drummond contributed a 15-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included three assists, five steals and three blocks. Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk poured in 13 points, while Christian Wood pitched in 11 points and nine rebounds. 

Donovan Mitchell led the Jazz with 23 points, complementing them with three rebounds, three assists and one steal. Jordan Clarkson posted 20 points. Bojan Bogdanovic supplied 17 points, four rebounds, two assists and one steal. Rudy Gobert furnished 13 points, 19 boards, one assist, three blocks and two steals. Joe Ingles registered 10 points, five boards, five assists and one block. 

The Pistons remain on the road to take on the Los Angeles Clippers on Thursday night, while the Jazz travel to tangle with the Chicago Bulls on Thursday night.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the host Portland Trail Blazers, 122-116, at Moda Center on Monday evening. 

The Trail Blazers got out to a great start at home, with a 38-19 lead after one quarter. They maintained a double-digit lead through most of the second, but the Suns cut it to a nine-point game by halftime. The Suns got out to a good start in the third and trimmed it to a five-point game early in the quarter. The Trail Blazers brought the lead back up to double digits, but the Suns cut it to a six-point game heading into the final frame. The Suns kept chipping away through the fourth and did a great job executing down the stretch, as they outscored the Trail Blazers 20-10 through the final five minutes to steal the impressive road win. 

Devin Booker led the Suns with 33 points, seven assists and six rebounds, in 38 minutes. Kelly Oubre Jr. added 29 points, five rebounds, three steals, two assists and a block, while Ricky Rubio totalled 18 points, 13 assists, five rebounds and a steal. Deandre Ayton played his first game back, after missing time with an ankle injury, and finished with six points and 12 rebounds, in 20 minutes off the bench. 

Meanwhile, Damian Lillard led the Trail Blazers with 33 points, seven assists, five rebounds and a steal, in 38 minutes. Hassan Whiteside totalled 16 points, 22 rebounds, three assists and three blocks, while C.J. McCollum added 25 points, six assists, two rebounds and a steal. The Trail Blazers shot 46 percent from the field, including 14-of-34 from deep. 

The Trail Blazers (14-20) look to bounce back as they take on the Knicks in New York on Wednesday. The Suns (13-20) take on the Lakers on Wednesday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Toronto Raptors, 98-97, at Scotiabank Arena on Sunday.

The Thunder (17-15) and the Raptors (22-11) played a very tight contest, as both sides went back and forth in the game that opened Sunday's slate. The Thunder jumped to a 22-20 lead in the first quarter, but Toronto turned things around with a 27-25 second quarter that evened things up at 47-47 after the first half. The Raptors seemed to pull away after three with a 33-29 score, but the Thunder came from behind to win this contest in the final 12 minutes of action. A 22-17 score in the final 12 minutes of action allowed Oklahoma City to secure a big win, as they extended their winning run and now they have won six of their last seven contests.

Shai Gilgeous-Alexander was Oklahoma City's best player, as he led the way with 32 points, seven rebounds, three steals and two assists. Chris Paul had another vintage performance, and he ended with 25 points, 11 boards and eight assists. Darius Bazley had a spot start, and he delivered with 12 points and five boards. Nerlens Noel came off the bench with 13 points in 19 minutes while going 5-of-5 from the field.

Five Toronto players scored in double digits in this game. Kyle Lowry and Fred VanVleet paced the way with 20 points each, although VanVleet also added eight assists to his name. Serge Ibaka delivered a strong double-double thanks to 12 points and 14 rebounds. Patrick McCaw had 13 points in 37 minutes of action. Terence Davis came off the bench to fill the stat sheet thanks to 11 points, six boards, three assists and two steals.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 117-104, at FedEx Forum on Sunday night. 

The Grizzlies (13-21) started their defense of home court in strong fashion, jumping out to a 31-20 lead through the first 12 minutes. The Hornets (13-22) were a lot more competitive over the middle periods, playing their hosts to a 55-55 draw over that span. However, that left them without making any inroads into their deficit, and Memphis was able to add another two points to their advantage during the final period for the double-digit home victory.

Malik Monk led the Hornets with 18 points, adding five rebounds, one steal and one block. P.J. Washington and Devonte' Graham produced matching 16-point efforts, with Graham also dishing out 10 assists. Cody Zeller turned in 14 points, three rebounds, one assist and one steal. Bismack Biyombo furnished 10 points, six boards and two blocks. Terry Rozier delivered nine points, eight assists, two rebounds and one steal. 

Dillon Brooks paced the Grizzlies with 20 points. Brandon Clarke followed with 18 points, four rebounds, three assists, three blocks and one steal. Jonas Valanciunas managed 16 points, nine boards and five assists. Grayson Allen contributed 15 points, five rebounds and two assists. Jaren Jackson, Jr. posted a 14-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included two blocks.

The Hornets head back home to face the Boston Celtics on Tuesday afternoon, while the Grizzlies visit the Sacramento Kings on Thursday night.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the visiting Houston Rockets, 127-112, at Smoothie King Center on Sunday evening. 

The Pelicans took advantage of the shorthanded Rockets, as James Harden (toe) and Russell Westbrook (rest) were both sidelined. Despite missing their top two players, the Rockets put up a fight, as they led 37-36 after one quarter. The Rockets kept the pressure on and held an edge for most of the second quarter, before the Pelicans tied it a 64 by halftime. The Rockets picked up the pace in the third and pushed ahead to a seven-point lead heading into the fourth. The Pelicans came alive in the fourth and poured in 41 points in the quarter to charge ahead for a convincing finish. This marks the fourth straight win for the Pelicans and the second loss in three games for the Rockets. 

Four players topped 20 points for the Pelicans, led by Lonzo Ball and Brandon Ingram, who had 27 points each, while E'Twaun Moore and Jrue Holiday tallied 25 points each. Derrick Favors added 12 points and 16 rebounds. The Pelicans shot 49 percent from the field, including 18-of-44 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Danuel House Jr. led the Rockets with 22 points, six rebounds and three assists, in 33 minutes. Isaiah Hartenstein added 19 points, nine rebounds and four assists, while Chris Clemons totalled 16 points and nine assists. The Rockets shot 52 percent from the field, including 15-of-39 from long range. 

The Rockets (22-11) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nuggets on Tuesday. The Pelicans (11-23) take on the Lakers in L.A. on Friday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 120-115, at Pepsi Center on Sunday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, with the Kings taking a one-point lead into the second quarter. The Kings kept the advantage early in the second, but Nuggets rallied ahead to grab a five-point lead by halftime. The Nuggets carried the momentum into the second half, as they held the lead through the third quarter and increased their cushion to seven points, heading into the fourth quarter. They pushed their lead to double digits early in the fourth and managed to hold off the Kings, who cut it to a three-point game with two minutes to go. This marks the second straight win for the Nuggets and the seventh straight loss for the Kings. 

Seven players scored in double digits for the Nuggets, led by Michael Porter Jr. and Will Barton, who had 19 points each. Nikola Jokic tallied 17 points, eight rebounds and four assists, while Jamal Murray chipped in 13 points, seven assists and four rebounds. The Nuggets shot 52 percent from the field, including 8-of-29 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Nemanja Bjelica led the Kings with 27 points, six rebounds and two assists, in 33 minutes. Buddy Hield added 20 points, eight assists and five rebounds, while De'Aaron Fox finished with 18 points and 13 assists. The Kings shot 53 percent from the field, including 13-of-34 from long range. 
 
The Kings (12-21) look to bounce back as they play host to the Clippers on Tuesday. The Nuggets (23-9) take on the Rockets in Houston on Tuesday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Dallas Mavericks, 108-95, at Staples Center on Sunday. 

A 25-19 first quarter really set the tone for the Lakers in this game, holding the lead for the final three quarters. In fact, Los Angeles rode a 29-24 second quarter to an 11-point halftime lead which allowed them to hold a double-digit lead for the entirety of the second half. Los Angeles' defense was critical, holding Dallas to 36 percent from the field and 30 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Lakers shot 49 percent from the field and 37 percent from long range while out-assisting the Mavericks, 28-17. 

The Mavericks (21-11) were led by Luka Doncic and his 19 points, four rebounds, seven assists and two steals. Dorian Finney-Smith generated 12 points, six rebounds and three assists. Dwight Powell amassed seven points, 11 rebounds, two assists and two steals while Kristaps Porzingis totaled 11 points and seven boards. 

The Lakers (26-7) were led by Anthony Davis, who tallied 23 points, nine rebounds, four assists and two steals. LeBron James collected 13 points, six rebounds, 13 assists and two steals. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope led the bench with 19 points, three rebounds and two assists. Dwight Howard also provided 15 points off the bench. 

On deck for Dallas is a road matchup versus the Oklahoma City Thunder on Tuesday. As for Los Angeles, they play host to the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday for their next outing.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 119-110, at Pepsi Center on Saturday afternoon.

A battle between two teams with drastically different records got off to an unsurprising start, as the home-court Nuggets (22-9) jumped out to a 26-11 lead through the first 12 minutes. The Grizzlies (12-21) managed to cut just four points into their deficit going into halftime, and after Denver pushed its edge back up to 14 entering the fourth quarter, the game appeared fairly well in hand. However, Memphis' offense came to life in the final period, accumulating 42 points and getting as close as 102-95 with 5:15 remaining before the home squad pulled away for good.

Jaren Jackson, Jr. led the Grizzlies with 20 points, adding four rebounds, one assist and one block. De'Anthony Melton supplied 17 points, four boards, one assist, two steals and one block. Ja Morant turned in 16 points, eight assists, three rebounds and one block. Brandon Clarke checked in with 15 points, five assists, two rebounds and one block. Jonas Valanciunas posted a 14-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one steal and one block. 

Nikola Jokic paced the Nuggets with a 31-point, 10-rebound, 10-assist triple-double that also included one steal. Will Barton delivered 20 points, seven assists, six rebounds, two steals and one block. Mason Plumlee and Jamal Murray generated matching 15-point tallies while pulling down seven and five rebounds, respectively. Gary Harris and Jerami Grant had 12 points apiece, while Michael Porter, Jr. furnished 11 points, four boards, two steals and one block.

The Grizzlies head back home to take on the Charlotte Hornets on Sunday evening, while the Nuggets remain home to tangle with the Sacramento Kings on Sunday night.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Boston Celtics, 113-97, at TD Garden on Saturday night.

The Raptors (22-10) set a different tone from where they'd left off against the Celtics (22-8) in their Christmas Day face-off, jumping out to a 36-25 lead through one quarter. Boston did manage to shave off six points from its deficit heading into halftime, but Toronto ultimately outscored them by a 54-43 margin in the second half to clinch the lopsided win. The visitors played effectively on both ends of the floor, shooting 52.4 percent (including 41.2 percent from distance) while limiting their hosts to a 39.7 percent figure. 

Kyle Lowry led the way with 30 points, adding seven assists, four rebounds and two steals. Serge Ibaka contributed a 20-point, 10-rebound double-double. Fred VanVleet and Patrick McCaw supplied 18 points each, with the latter also dishing out eight assists and pulling down seven rebounds. 

Kemba Walker paced the Celtics with 30 points and complemented them with two rebounds, two assists and two steals. Jaylen Brown delivered 17 points, five rebounds, three steals and one assist. Gordon Hayward totaled 13 points, six boards, three assists, two blocks and one steal. Jayson Tatum registered 12 points, four assists, three rebounds and one steal. Enes Kanter posted 11 points and six rebounds.

The Raptors head back home to take on the Oklahoma City Thunder on Sunday night, while the Celtics pay a visit to the Charlotte Hornets on Tuesday afternoon.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the visiting Indiana Pacers, 120-98, at Smoothie King Center on Saturday evening. 

The Pacers got out to a great start on the road, with a 32-19 lead after one quarter. The Pacers stayed on top to start the second but the Pelicans chipped away until they tied the score at 39, with 3:29 left in the half. The Pelicans outscored the visitors 9-6 in the final minutes of the half, to take a 48-45 lead into halftime. The Pelicans carried the momentum into the second half, as they outscored the Pacers by 15 points in the third quarter, to take an 86-68 lead into the final frame. The Pacers had no answers in the fourth, as they Pelicans led the rest of the way, earning their third straight win. This marks the second straight loss for the Pacers. 

Brandon Ingram led the Pelicans with 24 points, seven assists, five rebounds and two steals, in 34 minutes. Jrue Holiday added 20 points, seven assists, three rebounds, two steals and a block, while Derrick Favors added 10 points, 16 rebounds, two assists and a steal. The Pelicans shot 46 percent from the field, including 18-of-42 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Aaron Holiday led the Pacers with 25 points on 7-of-14 shooting, in 33 minutes. T.J. Warren added 20 points, while Domantas Sabonis totalled 15 points, 16 rebounds and four assists. The Pacers shot 39 percent from the field, including 6-of-28 from distance. 

The Pacers (21-12) will look to bounce back as they play host to the 76ers on Tuesday. The Pelicans (10-23) play host to the Rockets on Sunday.

The Miami Heat defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 117-116, in overtime at American Airlines Arena on Saturday night. 

The 76ers (23-12) knew they'd have a battle on their hands against a Heat (24-8) team that came in with only one home loss, but they took the fight to their hosts early to the tune of a 33-28 first-quarter lead. After the two teams matched each other bucket for bucket in the second quarter, Miami managed to open up a six-point lead entering the final period. Ultimately, Philadelphia mounted a comeback that culminated in a Ben Simmons basket with under a second remaining to send the game into overtime. The extra period was also a nip-and-tuck battle but the hosts escaped with a win when Tobias Harris' three-point attempt at the buzzer failed to find the net.

Joel Embiid led the 76ers with 35 points, adding 11 rebounds, two assists and one block. Josh Richardson supplied 17 points, five boards, two assists and one block. SImmons generated a 15-point, 11-assist double-double that also included seven rebounds, three steals and one block. Harris had 12 points and eight boards, while James Ennis and Trey Burke offered 11 points each off the bench.

Jimmy Butler paced the Heat with 25 points, complementing them with nine rebounds, nine assists, two steals and one block. Goran Dragic supplied 19 points, seven assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block. Duncan Robinson and Tyler Herro generated matching 16-point tallies. Bam Adebayo managed 11 points, three rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Kendrick Nunn checked in with 10 points, five boards, three assists and one steal.

The 76ers next visit the Indiana Pacers on Tuesday afternoon, while the Heat pay a visit to the Washington Wizards on Monday night.

The New York Knicks defeated the host Washington Wizards, 107-100, at Verizon Center on Saturday.

There were six ties and 19 lead changes in this competitive game, with almost all of them coming in the first half. The reason for that was because New York outscored Washington, 60-43, in the first and third quarters. The key for the Knicks was their defense, holding the Wizards to 34 percent from the field and 40 percent from three-point range. In addition, New York won the defensive rebounding battle, 45-35, while out-assisting Washington, 25-16. They won despite losing the turnover battle, 21-11.

The Knicks (9-24) were led by Julius Randle, who tallied 30 points, 16 rebounds and six assists. R.J. Barrett totaled 14 points and five rebounds. Gary Payton II accumulated 15 points, six rebounds, two assists and six steals, Ian Mahinmi generated nine points, 10 rebounds and two blocks while Troy Brown totaled nine points, eight rebounds, three assists and three steals. The Chicago Bulls defected the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 116-81, at United Center on Saturday evening. 

The Bulls got out to a great start at home, with a 35-19 lead after one quarter. The Hawks had no answer in the second, as the Bulls pushed their lead to 17, late in the quarter and took a 21-point lead into halftime. The Bulls held a comfortable lead through the third, while the Hawks managed to trim it to an 18-point game, heading into the final frame. The Bulls left nothing to question, as they outscored the visitors by 17 points in the fourth quarter, to earn their seventh home win. This marks the 10th consecutive loss for the Hawks. 

Six players scored in double digits for the Bulls, led by Lauri Markkanen, who finished with 25 points on 8-of-14 shooting. Zach LaVine added 19 points, seven rebounds, four assists and two steals, while Coby White added 18 points and five rebounds. The Bulls shot 49 percent from the field, including 15-of-31 from long range.

Alex Len added 10 points, five rebounds and two assists, while no other player scored in double digits for Atlanta. The Hawks shot 37 percent from the field, including 9-of-34 from long range. 

The Hawks (6-27) head to Orlando to take on the Magic on Monday. The Bulls (13-20) play host to the Bucks on Monday.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 108-98, at Toyota Center on Saturday evening. 

The Rockets got out to a great start at home, with a 42-20 lead after one quarter. The Nets responded in the second and chipped away through the quarter to make it a nine-point game by halftime. Things settled down in the third as the two teams played each other to a standstill through the quarter, with the Rockets taking an 88-79 lead into the final frame. The Nets started the fourth quarter with a 11-1 run, to take a one-point lead, with eight minutes to go. The Rockets then responded with a 10-2 run, to reclaim a seven-point lead, with just under three minutes to go. The Rockets held on down the stretch, to earn their 11th home win. 

James Harden led the Rockets with 44 points, 10 rebounds, six assists, three blocks and a steal, in 39 minutes. Russell Westbrook added 23 points, nine rebounds, seven assists, a steal and a block, while Austin Rivers chipped in 14 points, off the bench. The Rockets shot 44 percent from the field, including. 13-of-42 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Spencer Dinwiddie led the Nets with 17 points, 11 assists and two rebounds, in 33 minutes. Jarrett Allen added 16 points, 10 rebounds, two blocks and an assist, while Taurean Prince chipped in 16 points, six rebounds, two assists and a steal. The Nets shot 40 percent from the field, including 11-of-39 from long range. 

The Nets (16-15) will look to bounce back as they take on the Timberwolves in Minnesota on Monday. The Rockets (22-10) take on the Pelicans in New Orleans on Sunday.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 94-88, at Target Center on Saturday night.

The Cavaliers (10-22) caught a break when both Karl-Anthony Towns (knee) and Andrew Wiggins (illness) were both ruled out for the contest. Cleveland was able to jump out to a 49-43 halftime advantage over the Timberwolves (11-20), and they then limited Minnesota to 17 points in the third to add another point to their lead. The home squad would get as close as within a point with 4:12 remaining, but the Cavaliers finished on a 13-8 run from that point to seal the road victory. The visitors enjoyed a significant rebounding advantage, winning the battle of the boards by a 61-39.

Collin Sexton and Darius Garland co-led the Cavaliers with 18 points apiece, with Sexton also pulling down seven rebounds. Tristan Thompson generated a 12-point, 15-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one block. Kevin Porter, Jr. turned in 10 points, five rebounds, two assists and one steal, while Larry Nance, Jr. delivered nine points and nine boards. 

Jeff Teague paced the Timberwolves with 18 points and complemented them with four assists and one steal. Kelan Martin supplied 17 points, six boards and one steal. Robert Covington managed 14 points, seven rebounds, three assists, four steals and one block. Shabazz Napier registered nine points, three assists, two rebounds and one steal.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Orlando Magic, 111-100, at Fiserv Forum on Saturday.

A 37-25 first quarter really set the tone in this game, with Milwaukee leading for the final three quarters. In fact, the Bucks held a double-digit lead for the final eight minutes of play. They also out-assisted them, 30-21. 

The Magic (14-18) were led by Evan Fournier, who tallied 23 points, three rebounds and two assists. Nikola Vucevic collected 21 points, eight rebounds, four assists, three steals and two blocks. Jonathan Issac accumulated 19 points, nine rebounds, two assists and eight steals. D.J. Augustin led the bench with 12 points and four assists. 

The Bucks (29-5) were led by Khris Middleton, who accrued 21 points, five rebounds, seven assists and two steals. Ersan Ilyasova generated 17 points, 14 rebounds and five assists. The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 136-109, at AT&T Center on Saturday evening. 

The Spurs took an early 10-point lead, but the Pistons rallied back to make it a two-point game heading into the second quarter. The score stayed tight through the second, but the Spurs managed to edge the visitors, to take a four-point lead into halftime. The Spurs came out on fire in the third and outscored the Pistons 42-25 in the quarter, to push their lead to 21, entering the final frame. The Pistons had no answers in the fourth, as the Spurs held the upper hand the rest of the way, to improve to 9-8 at home. This marks the sixth loss in the last seven games for Detroit.

DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 29 points, eight assists and five rebounds, in 32 minutes. LaMarcus Aldridge added 25 points, 12 rebounds, two blocks and a steal, while Bryn Forbes finished with 18 points, three rebounds and three assists. The Spurs shot 57 percent from the field, including 18-of-35 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Derrick Rose led the Pistons with 24 points, four assists, four steals and three rebounds, in 27 minutes off the bench. Andre Drummond totalled 21 points, 18 rebounds, four blocks, three assists and a steal, while Langston Galloway chipped in 15 points on 6-of-9 shooting. The Pistons shot 44 percent from the field, including 12-of-36 from deep. 

The Pistons (12-21) will look to bounce back as they take on the Jazz in Utah on Monday. The Spurs (13-18) play host to the Warriors on Tuesday.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the Golden State Warriors, 141-121, at Chase Center on Saturday night.

The Mavericks (21-10) got a feisty and surging Warriors (9-25) squad's best shot early, as Dallas found itself down by a 74-72 margin at the half. That would prove to be more than enough for the hard-fought road win, one in which each team was extremely efficient -- the Mavericks drained 52.2 percent of their attempts (including 47.7 percent from three-point range), while Golden State boasted a 48.9 percent success rate, including 46.2 percent from behind the arc.

Luka Doncic led the way for the Mavericks with a 31-point, 15-assist, 12-rebound triple-double that also included two steals. Tim Hardaway, Jr. managed 25 points. Kristaps Porzingis supplied 18 points, seven boards, three assists and four blocks. Seth Curry poured in 17 points, while Delon Wright contributed 13 points, four assists, three rebounds, three steals and one block. Dwight Powell registered 10 points, eight boards, three assists and two steals.

D'Angelo Russell paced the Warriors with 35 points and complemented them with six assists and four rebounds. Damion Lee generated an 18-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included two assists. Marquese Chriss and Alec Burks posted 16 points apiece with Chriss also pulling down five rebounds, dishing out two assists and recording two blocks. Draymond Green totaled 10 points, eight assists, three rebounds and one steal.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 112-110, at Golden 1 Center on Saturday.

This win snapped an eight-game losing streak for the Suns but it still came down to the final shot. In fact, Harrison Barnes missed an open three-pointer at the buzzer that would have given the Kings a win. While there were eight ties and 12 lead changes in the first 20 minutes, Phoenix held the lead for the entirety of the second half, thanks to a 28-19 second quarter. The Suns ended up shooting 52 percent from the field while out-assisting the Kings, 30-19. In addition, Phoenix had 10 steals to Sacramento's three. 

The Suns (12-20) were led by Devin Booker, who tallied 32 points, three rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Kelly Oubre Jr collected 20 points, 16 rebounds, five assists and two steals. McCollum amassed 18 points, two rebounds and four assists while Carmelo Anthony accumulated 13 points, five rebounds and two assists. Anfernee Simons led the bench with 14 points and six boards.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 129-117, at TD Garden on Friday afternoon.

However, the Cavaliers (9-22) fought valiantly coming out of intermission, scoring 70 points in the second half alone. Unfortunately for Cleveland, its hosts nearly matched them basket for basket by ringing up 67 points of their own through the third and fourth quarters, leading to a double-digit road loss for the visitors.

Kevin Love paced the Cavaliers with 30 points, adding seven rebounds and four assists. Collin Sexton provided 21 points, four boards, two assists and one steal. Enes Kanter registered 14 points, nine boards, three assists, two steals and two blocks. The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host Charlotte Hornets, 104-102, at Spectrum Center on Friday evening. 

It took overtime to solve the contest, as Devonte' Graham capped off a Hornets' rally to tie the game with one second left in regulation. The Thunder led by seven points after three quarters, but the Hornets started the fourth on a 12-2 run, to grab a three-point lead with seven minutes to go. The Thunder came back and grabbed the edge in the final minutes, before Graham sent it to overtime. The Thunder caught a break heading into overtime, as the Hornets were assessed a technical foul at the end of regulation because Terry Rozier threw the ball into the stands. The Thunder hit their free throw to begin overtime with a one-point lead and went on to hold the advantage the rest of the way, earning their fifth win in their last six games. 

Shai Gilgeous-Alexander led the Thunder with 27 points, four rebounds and two steals, in 36 minutes. Dennis Schroder added 24 points, three assists and two rebounds, in 35 minutes off the bench, while Steven Adams tallied 14 points, 12 rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks. The Orlando Magic defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 98-97, at Amway Center on Friday night. 

The Magic (14-17) came into the contest having notched nine of their 13 wins on their home court, but it was clear from early on they'd be in for a tough task against the 76ers (23-11). Philadelphia forged a 21-19 lead through the first 12 minutes and owned a slim one-point lead at halftime. Orlando managed to erase that deficit and take a three-point lead into the fourth quarter, but Joel Embiid's three-pointer with 5.1 seconds remaining brought the visitors within one. A subsequent turnover by Aaron Gordon on the inbounds pass led to Ben Simmons feeding Embiid for a potential game-winning heave from just within half court that failed to find the basket, sending the hosts home winners.

Embiid and Tobias Harris paced the 76ers with matching 24-point, 11-rebound tallies. Josh Richardson followed with 15 points, six assists, three rebounds, three steals and one block. Ben Simmons supplied 13 points, nine rebounds, seven assists and four steals. Al Horford mustered seven points, five assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block.

Evan Fournier paced the Magic with 20 points, adding six assists, two rebounds and two steals. Aaron Gordon generated a 19-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one block. Terrence Ross delivered 17 points, seven boards and one steal. Nikola Vucevic posted a 16-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included seven assists. Markelle Fultz registered 13 points, six assists and three rebounds.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Atlanta Hawks, 112-86, at State Farm Arena on Friday evening. 

Despite missing Giannis Antetokounmpo (back), the Bucks got out to a great start on the road, with a 32-19 lead through one quarter. They kept control through the second, as they outscored the Hawks by 10 in the quarter, to take a 23-point lead into halftime. Unfortunately, Trae Young went down late in the second quarter and did not return. Nonetheless, the Hawks put up a fight in the third quarter and trimmed the deficit by two. They could not keep up the fight in the end, as the Bucks cruised to their 13th road win of the season. This marks the ninth straight loss for the Hawks. 

Khris Middleton led the Bucks with 23 points, eight rebounds and seven assists. Ersan Ilyasova totaled 18 points and 17 rebounds, while Brook Lopez added 19 points, five rebounds, three blocks and two rebounds. The Bucks shot 50 percent from the field, including 11-of-28 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Allen Crabbe stepped up with 20 points, four rebounds and three steals, in 21 minutes off the bench. Trae Young managed 12 points, in 15 minutes of action before leaving the game. The Miami Heat defeated the visiting Indiana Pacers, 113-112, at American Airlines Arena on Friday.

There were eight ties and 20 lead changes in this game, as it came down to the final shot. In fact, Goran Dragic hit a game-winning floater with 6.8 seconds left to urn a one-point deficit into a one-point lead and Aaron Holiday missed a floater of his own at the buzzer to give Miami the win. Neither team ever held a double-digit lead in this game. Rebounding was the difference for Miami, out-rebounding Indiana, 56-34. Much of that came on the offensive end, winning that battle, 14-2.

Warren totaled 16 points, four rebounds and two assists while Domantas Sabonis accrued eight points, seven rebounds and four assists.

Duncan Robinson accrued 18 points, three rebounds and two assists while Kendrick Nunn generated 17 points, four rebounds and four assists. Dragic led the bench with 14 points, three rebounds and six assists. 

Both teams have to play the second half of a back-to-back set on Saturday, with Indiana traveling to face the New Orleans Pelicans and Miami remaining home to play the Philadelphia 76ers,

The Golden State Warriors defeated the visiting Phoenix Suns, 105-96, at Chase Center on Friday. 

It's rare to see a team win the first four quarters by four points apiece and lose but that was the case here. In fact, Golden State rode a 39-18 fourth quarter to their comeback victory, turning a 12-point fourth quarter deficit into a nine-point victory. The Suns couldn't take care of the ball, committing 26 turnovers to the Warriors 10. In addition, Golden State recorded 10 steals and five blocks while Phoenix had just six steals and one block. That allowed the Warriors to win the points off turnovers battle, 28-7. The Warriors also held the Suns to just 7-of-33 from three-point range. 

The Suns (11-20) were led by Devin Booker, who tallied 34 points, three rebounds, four assists and two steals but committed eight turnovers. Ricky Rubio accrued 11 points, four rebounds and four assists. Dario Saric amassed 11 points, 10 rebounds and two assists while Aron Baynes totaled nine points and 10 boards. 

The Warriors (9-24) were led by D'Angelo Russell and his 31 points, five rebounds and six assists. Damion Lee accumulated 16 points, eight rebounds, two assists and three steals. Draymond Green collected 11 points, seven rebounds and four assists while Alec Burks led the bench with 13 points and five rebounds.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the Washington Wizards, 132-102, at Little Caesars Arena on Thursday.

The Pistons (12-20) and the Wizards (9-21) entered this game as two of the worst teams in the Eastern Conference, but that didnt seem to matter here since Detroit had no problems to win, as they delivered a strong performance on both ends of the court from start to finish. It seemed as if the Pistons were a contender, while the Wizards looked like a team that was seriously lacking talent throughout the entire contests. Detroit won the first three quarters  31-23, 37-25 and 38-28, respectively  and the final 12 minutes didnt have an impact in the outcome of the game. With the win, Detroit moved to 8-10 at home while the Wizards fell to 5-14 on the road.

Eight Pistons scored in double digits and the top scorer came off the bench, as Christian Wood ended with 22 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Andre Drummond had 14 points and 10 boards, while Blake Griffin chipped in with 14 points, 11 rebounds and four assists. Derrick Rose had 15 points and six dimes as substitute, while Bruce Brown added 12 points in 27 minutes.

Bradley Beal scored 15 points for the Wizards, and he was the only starter who topped the 10-point mark in this game. Anzejs Pasecniks led the way for the team with 17 points, while Jordan McRae chipped in with 15 points. Troy Brown Jr. had 13 points with six rebounds, while Gary Payton II filled the stat sheet once again thanks to 10 points, five rebounds, and five assists.

The New York Knicks defeated the host Brooklyn Nets, 94-82, at Barclay's Center on Thursday. 

While there were five lead changes in the first half, New York dominated the second half. In fact, they rode a 33-20 third quarter to their 12-point win, holding a double-digit lead for the entirety of the fourth quarter. The Knicks defense was the difference, holding the Nets to 27 percent from the field and 26 percent from three-point range. In addition, New York out-rebounded Brooklyn, 60-50. 

The Knicks (8-24) were led by Julius Randle, who tallied 33 points, eight rebounds and two assists on 14-of-26 shooting. Marcus Morris amassed 22 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Garrett Temple went 2-of-10 from the field to total seven points and nine boards. Taurean Prince went 1-of-10 from the field to accrue three points and five rebounds. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Brooklyn traveling to face James Harden and the Houston Rockets while New York faces the Washington Wizards on the road.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the host Oklahoma City Thunder, 110-97, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Thursday evening. 

The Thunder took the lead early, but the Grizzlies rallied ahead to take a 23-18 lead after one quarter. They pushed their lead to nine early in the second, before the Thunder tied it up halfway through the quarter. The Grizzlies used a 13-5 run to push ahead again, but the Thunder closed the half strong and a last-second three by Dennis Schroder cut it to a two-point game by halftime. The Grizzlies took control in the third, as they led through the entire quarter and took a 12-point advantage into the final frame. They kept the momentum going and pushed the lead to 20, with nine minutes left in the contest. The Thunder made one last rally and cut it to a nine-point game with two minutes left, but the Grizzlies closed confidently, for their sixth road win of the season. 

Jonas Valanciunas led the Grizzlies with 21 points on 9-of-11 shooting. Jaren Jackson Jr. added 20 points, four rebounds and four assists, while Tyus Jones tallied 15 points on 6-of-7 shooting. The Grizzlies shot 55 percent from the field, including 10-of-25 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Chris Paul led the Thunder with 23 points, 11 assists and six rebounds. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander added 21 points, while Dennis Schroder finished with 20 points. The Thunder shot 41 percent from the field, including 10-of-35 from deep. 

The Thunder (15-15) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Friday. The Grizzlies (12-20) take on the Nuggets in Denver on Saturday.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 102-98, at American Airlines Center on Thursday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the Sacramento Kings in double overtime, 105-104, at Golden 1 Center on Thursday night. 

The Timberwolves (11-19) and Kings (12-19) played a see-saw first half that saw each take a quarter and culminate in a narrow 50-48 halftime lead for Minnesota. However, Sacramento seemed to take control in a third quarter where they eliminated their deficit and built an eight-point lead going into the final period, The visitors then managed to force overtime, and after both teams deadlocked at seven points during the first extra period, Buddy Hield got the  Kings to within one point with a pair of buckets before missing a 26-foot three-point attempt at time expired, leaving the hosts just one point short.
