Hield registered 17 points, four rebounds, one assist and one steal while going just 6-for-20 from the field. Harrison Barnes posted an 11-point, 10-rebound double-double.

The Timberwolves head back home to face the Cleveland Cavaliers on Saturday night, while the Kings remain home and tangle with the Utah Jazz on Saturday night as well.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 121-115, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Thursday night.

The Jazz (19-12) seemed to be setting the tone for a comfortable home win early, forging a 37-22 lead through one quarter and keeping a 10-point advantage going into halftime. The Trail Blazers (14-18) weren't able to really get their offense humming until the final period, which they entered trailing by 20. Portland within two points on multiple occasions in the latter portion of the fourth quarter, but a quartet of free throws from Bojan Bogdanovic (three) and Donovan Mitchell (one) over the final 15.1 seconds helped Utah gain just enough separation for the victory.

Damian Lillard paced the Trail Blazers with 34 points, adding eight assists and four rebounds. C.J. McCollum furnished 25 points, four boards, two assists and one steal. Anfernee Simons managed 15 points and 10 rebounds.  Carmelo Anthony compiled 12 points, seven boards and one steal. Skal Labissiere supplied 10 points, seven rebounds and three assists. 

Mitchell led the Jazz with 35 points -- 28 of them in the second half -- while complementing them with seven assists and three rebounds. Joe Ingles registered 26 points, five boards, four assists and one steal. Rudy Gobert and Bogdanovic generated matching 16-point tallies, with Gobert also pulling down 15 rebounds, two assists and one block. 

The Trail Blazers head back home to take on the Los Angeles Lakers on Saturday night, while the Jazz pay a visit to the Los Angeles Clippers on Saturday night.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Toronto Raptors, 118-102, at Scotiabank Arena on Wednesday afternoon.

The Celtics (21-7) entered this game on a solid run of form, having won their last three and seven of their last 10 contests, while also securing three straight wins on the road. As such, its not a surprise that they didnt have problems to register another solid win against a struggling Raptors (21-10) team that was slightly depleted due to injuries. Boston jumped to a 28-19 lead in the first quarter, and they would never look back after that. Toronto won the second quarter by a 28-27 score, but Boston pulled away for good with a 33-22 third quarter that made the final 12 minutes a mere formality. The Raptors won the final quarter by a 33-30 score, but the game was over a while ago, and Boston secured a great win against another Eastern Conference contender. With the win, the Celtics moved to 9-6 on the road while the Raptors fell to 13-4 at home.

Jaylen Brown was the best player for the Celtics in this game, as he finished with 30 points, six rebounds and four assists. Kemba Walker chipped in with 22 points and four assists, while Gordon Hayward added 14 points and six dimes. Jayson Tatum came close to a double-double thanks to 11 points and nine rebounds, while also adding five assists. Enes Kanter had a double-double off the bench with 12 points and 11 rebounds.

Fred VanVleet led the way for Toronto with 27 points, six assists and four steals. Kyle Lowry had 14 points with eight dimes, while Serge Ibaka chipped in with 12 points and eight rebounds. Chris Boucher came off the bench and contributed 24 points and six rebounds in 28 minutes. No other Toronto player managed to score in double digits.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 121-109, at Wells Fargo Center on Wednesday afternoon.

The 76ers (23-10) and the Bucks (27-5) were slated to deliver one of the most thrilling matchups during the Christmas Day schedule, and its safe to say they delivered as expected. The 76ers, however, dominated with ease and they ended securing a huge win against one of the leagues top teams in front of their own crowd. Philadelphia jumped to a 38-30 lead after the first quarter, and they never looked back afterwards. Their 31-18 second quarter extended their advantage to double digits, and the 31-25 score in the third quarter iced the game for good. Milwaukee won the final 12 minutes by a 26-21 margin, but the game was already decided by then. The 76ers secured a huge win that should remind everyone they are one of the top teams in the Eastern Conference.

Joel Embiid (31 points, 11 rebounds), Ben Simmons (15 points, 14 assists and seven rebounds) and Al Horford (11 points, 11 rebounds, five assists) all had double-doubles for the 76ers, although Tobias Harris also contributed offensively thanks to a 22-point performance. Josh Richardson added 18 points and four assists, while Furkan Korkmaz impressed with 16 points while shooting 4-for-5 from deep off the bench.

Khris Middleton was Milwaukees top scoring threat since he had 31 points, eight rebounds and four assists. Giannis Antetokounmpo filled the stat sheet with 18 points, 14 rebounds and four assists, but he shot 8-27 from the field and 0-7 from three-point range. Brook Lopez had 11 points with five boards. George Hill impressed off the bench as he ended with 15 points while making all three of his three-point attempts.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the visiting Houston Rockets, 116-104, at Chase Center on Christmas Day. 

The Warriors got out to a good start at home, with an early 7-0 lead, but the Rockets rallied to take a 29-28 lead by the end of the quarter. The Rockets carried the momentum into the second and pushed their lead to eight points, four minutes into the quarter, and held on to a four-point lead at halftime. The Warriors picked up the pace in the third and overtook the Rockets with just over four minutes left in the quarter. They outscored the Warriors by nine points in the third, to take a five-point lead into the fourth. The Rockets clawed back to take a brief lead early in the fourth, but the Warriors used a 15-2 run, to take a 12-point lead with 3:30 to go. The Warriors held on to earn their third consecutive win, while this marks the end of a four-game winning streak for Houston. 

Three players topped 20 points for the Warriors, led by Damion Lee, who finished with 22 points, 15 rebounds, four assists and three steals. D'Angelo Russell added 20 points, four assists, three rebounds, a steal and a block, while Draymond Green finished with 20 points, 11 rebounds, three assists and a block.

Meanwhile, Russell Westbrook led the Rockets with 30 points, 12 rebounds and five assists, in 40 minutes. James Harden totalled 24 points, 11 assists, six rebounds and three steals, while Danuel House Jr. added 18 points, five rebounds, one steal and a block. Clint Capela tallied 10 points, 11 rebounds, a steal and a block.

The Rockets (21-10) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nets on Saturday. The Warriors (8-24) play host to the Suns on Friday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Los Angeles Lakers, 111-106, at Staples Center on Wednesday night. 

The Clippers (23-10) and Lakers (24-7) unsurprisingly engaged in a spirited battle for all four quarters, and a highly competitive first quarter foreshadowed what was to come. The Clippers held a narrow 33-31 lead after the first 12 minutes, but the Lakers bounced back to erase their two-point deficit and establish an eight-point edge going into halftime. The designated visitors flipped the tables on their hosts for the night in the third by reclaiming a four-point lead by quarter's end, and they ultimately clamped down on defense when it mattered most. Patrick Beverley's block of LeBron James' three-point attempt with 3.7 seconds left ultimately sealed the win, as the Lakers were forced to foul Paul George on the ensuing possession, which led to a pair of game-clinching free throws.

Kawhi Leonard led the way for the Clippers with 35 points, adding 12 rebounds, five assists and one steal. Montrezl Harrell furnished 18 points, six rebounds and one block. Paul George provided 17 points, five boards, three assists and three blocks. Ivica Zubac totaled 11 points, eight rebounds and one assist. Beverley supplied eight points, nine boards, four assists, one steal and his crucial block of James.

The Lakers were led by Kyle Kuzma, who contributed 25 points and complemented with four rebounds and one steal. Anthony Davis followed with 24 points, six rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks. James finished with a 23-point, 10-assist double-double that also included nine rebounds, two steals and one block. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope poured in 13 points. 

The Clippers remain home to tangle with the Utah Jazz on Saturday night, while the Lakers pay a visit to the Portland Trail Blazers on Saturday night as well.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the host Denver Nuggets, 112-100, at Pepsi Center on Wednesday.

New Orleans actually led for 40 minutes of this 48-minute game, winning in upset fashion. With that said, there were seven ties and six lead changes in the first half, but neither club led by more than seven points until the final minutes. In fact, New Orleans finished the game on an 18-8 run to cap off a 28-20 fourth quarter. The key for New Orleans was their defense, holding Denver to just 40 percent from the field and 32 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Pelicans outrebounded the Nuggets, 53-40. 

The Pelicans (9-23) were led by Brandon Ingram, who tallied 31 points, seven rebounds, two assists and two steals. Jrue Holiday collected 20 points, four rebounds, eight assists and six steals. Lonzo Ball amassed 10 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Derrick Favors accrued eight points, 13 rebounds, eight assists and three blocks. Josh Hart led the bench with 16 points and nine rebounds. 

The Nuggets (21-9) were led by Nikola Jokic, who tallied 23 points, 10 rebounds, four assists and two steals. Gary Harris totaled 15 points, three rebounds and four steals. Will Barton accumulated 10 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Jerami Grant led the bench with 17 points, two rebounds and one assist. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Denver remaining home to play the Memphis Grizzlies and New Orleans returning home to face the Indiana Pacers.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 121-118, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Monday evening. 

The Cavaliers got out to a great start at home, with a 42-32 lead after one quarter. The Hawks cut it to a two-point game mid way through the second, but the Cavs pushed ahead to take a seven-point lead into halftime. The Hawks started the third on a 12-3 run, to take a two-point lead. They held a slight edge for most of the quarter but Cavs tied the score at 94, heading into the fourth. The Cavs started the fourth on a 10-2 run and held a 14-point lead with five minutes to go. The Hawks made a push and brought it to a three-point game, with 49 seconds left in the contest, but neither team scored the rest of the way, as the Cavs held on for their third straight win. This marks the eighth straight loss for the Hawks. 

Collin Sexton led the Cavs with 25 points, six rebounds, three assists and a steal, in 36 minutes. Darius Garland added 21 points on 9-of-14 shooting, while Kevin Love tallied 20 points, eight rebounds, five assists, a steal and a block. The Cavs shot 52 percent from the field, including 11-of-29 from long range.

Meanwhile, Trae Young led the Hawks with 30 points, 11 assists, six rebounds and four steals, in 36 minutes. John Collins was great in his first game back from a 25-game suspension, as he finished with 27 points, 10 rebounds, two steals and two blocks. De'Andre Hunter added 23 points on 10-of-19 shooting, while Kevin Huerter chipped in 19 points. 

The Hawks (6-25) will look to bounce back on Friday, as they play host to the Bucks. The Cavaliers (9-21) take on the Celtics in Boston on Friday.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the host Detroit Pistons, 125-109, at Little Caesars Arena on Monday evening. 

The Sixers got out to a good start on the road and took a 30-23 lead after one quarter. The Pistons rallied to take a brief lead in the second, but the 76ers outscored the hosts 22-13 through the rest of the quarter, to take an eight-point lead into halftime. The Pistons came out strong and tied it up early in the third, but the Sixers reclaimed control, with a 94-86 lead, heading into the fourth. The Sixers held the momentum through the fourth and took a 22-point lead with just over two minutes to go. This marks their second straight win, while this marks the fifth straight loss for Detroit. 

Tobias Harris led the 76ers with 35 points, seven rebounds, three assists and two steals, in 34 minutes. Ben Simmons totalled 16 points, 17 assists and 13 rebounds, while Joel Embiid finished with 20 points, eight rebounds, three assists, three blocks and a steal. The 76ers shot 55 percent from the field, including 12-of-30 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Andre Drummond led the Pistons with 27 points nine rebounds, three assists and a steal, in 32 minutes. Derrick Rose added 16 points, seven assists, three rebounds, two steals and a block, while Svi Mykhailiuk chipped in 13 points, four assists and two rebounds. The Pistons shot 51 percent from the field, including 10-of-30 from long range. 

The Pistons (11-20) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Wizards on Thursday. The 76ers 22-10) play host to the Bucks on Wednesday.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the visiting Toronto Raptors in overtime, 120-115, at Banker's Life Fieldhouse on Monday.

While Indiana led for the majority of this game thanks to a 30-19 first quarter, it took an overtime session to determine a winner. In fact, there were 10 lead changes in the fourth quarter and overtime combined. The Pacers finished strong though, finishing the game on a 7-2 run to prevail. The key for Indiana was their ball movement, recording four more assists than Toronto while committing three fewer turnovers. The Pacers also shot 18-of-42 from three-point range while the Raptors hit just 11-of-40. 

The Raptors (21-9) were led by Kyle Lowry, who tallied 30 points, six rebounds and nine assists. Serge Ibaka totaled 23 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Fred VanVleet generated 21 points, two rebounds, 11 assists, two steals and two blocks. OG Anunoby totaled 15 points, 12 rebounds and two steals while Rondae Hollis-Jefferson led the bench with eight points, nine rebounds and six assists. 

The Pacers (21-10) were led by T.J. Warren, who tallied 24 points, eight rebounds, six assists and two blocks. Myles Turner accumulated 24 points, seven rebounds and three blocks. Aaron Holiday started and finished with 19 points and 10 assists. Domantas Sabonis accrued 12 points, 17 rebounds and three assists. 

Toronto's next game will be on Wednesday, playing host to the Boston Celtics, As for Indiana, they travel to face the Miami Heat on Friday for their next fixture,

The Washington Wizards defeated the New York Knicks, 121-115, at Madison Square Garden on Monday evening.

The Wizards (9-20) entered this game on a two-game losing streak on their current four-game road trip, but they managed to bounce back against a struggling Knicks (7-24) team that couldnt hold on despite a strong start to the game. Indeed, the Knicks jumped to a 37-32 lead after the first quarter, but that would be all the lead they would muster during the contest. Washington won both the second and third quarters by a 31-27 score, and they closed things out with a 27-24 fourth quarter. With the win, the Wizards improved to 5-13 on the road, while the Knicks fell to 4-12 at home.

Bradley Beal was the Wizards top scorer since he ended with 30 points, four rebounds and three assists. Ish Smith, who started in place of the suspended Isaiah Thomas, ended with 17 points, four assists and four boards. Troy Brown Jr. was one of Washingtons best players, and he finished with 26 points, nine rebounds and seven assists. Anzejs Pasecniks had 14 points, and recent signing Gary Payton II added 10 points and 11 rebounds.

Julius Randle led the Knicks with 35 points and five rebounds, while R.J. Barrett had 18 points, six boards and four assists. Mitchell Robinson only had six points, but he impressed on the paint thanks to 13 rebounds and six blocks. Damyean Dotson had 19 points off the bench, while Allonzo Trier chipped in with 11 points while shooting 5-for-7 from the field.

The Orlando Magic defeated the visiting Chicago Bulls, 103-95, at United Center on Monday.

While there were only three lead changes in this game, it stayed within a single-digit margin for the full 48 minutes. With that said, Orlando led for the final 20 minutes, outscoring Chicago in the second half, 52-41. The key for the Magic was their defense, holding the Bulls to 40 percent from the field and 35 percent from three-point range. In addition, their 10 steals and 13 blocks outdueled Chicago's six steals and six blocks. 

The Bulls (12-20) were led by Zach LaVine, who tallied 26 points, eight rebounds and two assists on just 8-of-26 from the field. Tomas Satoransky accrued 20 points, six rebounds and three assists. Lauri Markkanen amassed 10 points, three rebounds and two assists while Wendell Carter totaled six points and 10 boards. 

The Magic (13-17) were led by Nikola Vucevic and his 21 points, seven rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Aaron Gordon accumulated 16 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and three blocks. Jonathan Isaac generated 13 points, nine rebounds, five assists, four steals and three blocks while Terrence Ross led the bench with 26 points. 

On deck for Orlando is a home matchup versus the Philadelphia 76ers on Friday. As for Chicago, they play host to the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday for their next fixture.

The Miami Heat defeated the visiting Utah Jazz, 107-104, at American Airlines Arena on Monday evening. 

The Jazz got out to a good start on the road and led mid way through the first, but the Heat took control with a 32-28 lead heading into the second. The score stayed tight through the third, while the Heat held a slight edge through most of the quarter and took a one-point lead into halftime. The Heat stayed strong to start the third, but the Jazz turned it around to take a five-point lead into the fourth. The Heat came out strong in the fourth and overtook the lead, four minutes into the quarter. They pushed their lead to 10, halfway through the quarter and held an eight-point lead with 30 seconds left. The Jazz made one last push to bring it to a three-point game, but the Heat held on for their third straight win. 

Jimmy Butler led the Heat with 20 points, eight rebounds, two assists and two steals, in 34 minutes. Bam Adebayo added 18 points, 12 rebounds, six assists, three steals and three blocks. Tyler Herro chipped in 17 points, off the bench, while Goran Dragic tallied 15 points and six rebounds. The Heat shot 41 percent from the field, including 9-of-25 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Joe Ingles led the Jazz with 27 points on 9-of-16 shooting, in 38 minutes. Rudy Gobert added 18 points, 20 rebounds and five blocks, in 36 minutes. Bojan Bogdanovic chipped in 19 points, four rebounds and three assists. The Jazz shot 43 percent from the field, including 12-of-36 from long range. 

The Jazz (18-12) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Trail Blazers on Thursday. The Heat (22-8) play host to the Pacers on Friday.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the host Memphis Grizzlies, 145-115, at Fed Ex Forum on Monday.

While San Antonio didn't necessarily win in wire-to-wire fashion, a 46-31 first quarter really set the tone. In fact, the Grizzlies led by at least eight points from there, riding a 73-54 second half to their dominating 30-point victory, The Spurs ended up shooting 67 percent from the field and 63 percent from three-point range while recording 36 assists. They did that while winning the rebounding battle, 46-35.

The Spurs (12-17) were led by LaMarcus Aldridge, tallying 40 points, nine rebounds, five assists and three blocks. DeMar DeRozan amassed 26 points, three rebounds, 10 assists and three steals. Trey Lyles started and totaled 17 points, eight rebounds and four assists while Dejounte Murray accrued 14 points, six rebounds, four assists and two steals. 

The Grizzlies (11-20) were led by Jaren Jackson Jr and his 22 points, two rebounds and two assists. Ja Morant accumulated 19 points, three rebounds and four assists. Jonas Valanciunas provided 18 points, 12 rebounds and three assists while Tyus Jones led the bench with 11 points, three rebounds and three assists. 

Both teams return to action on Thursday, with San Antonio remaining on the road to face the Dallas Mavericks while Memphis travels to face the Oklahoma City Thunder.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 113-111, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Monday.

This game came down to the final shot, with Jamal Murray playing hero. In fact, he broke a tied game with 2.5 seconds left, hitting a step-back jumper to win the game. Devin Booker had a chance to re-take the lead at the buzzer with a three, but Jerami Grant blocked it. The Suns actually made a huge comeback in this game though, overcoming a 16-point deficit to lead for most of the fourth quarter. The key for Denver was their shooting, hitting 55 percent from the field and 54 percent from three-point range while holding Phoenix to 48 percent from the field and 35 percent from long range. 

The Nuggets (21-8) got a triple-double from Nikola Jokic, collecting 22 points, 12 rebounds and 10 assists. Murray finished with 28 points, three rebounds, seven assists and two steals. Will Barton accrued 13 points, six rebounds, five assists and two steals while Paul Millsap amassed 10 points, eight rebounds and two assists. 

The Suns (11-19) were led by Ricky Rubio and his 21 points, seven rebounds and nine assists. Booker totaled 11 points, three rebounds and six assists on just 3-of-12 shooting. Kelly Oubre Jr accumulated 14 points, three rebounds and three assists while Frank Kaminsky led the bench with 13 points and three boards. 

Denver will return to action on Wednesday, playing host to the New Orleans Pelicans. As for Phoenix, they return to action on Friday against the Golden State Warriors on the road.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 102-94, at Moda Center on Monday night.

The Pelicans (8-23) came into the contest with just three road wins and 14 losses in their previous 15 games, but they managed to set a positive tone early against the Trail Blazers (14-17). New Orleans matched Portland bucket for bucket in the first quarter on the way to a 31-31 deadlock, and they hung right with their hosts again in the second period to head into halftime with only a two-point deficit. The Pelicans then came out of intermission playing well on both ends of the floor, limiting the Blazers to just 38 points in the second half and putting up 48 of their own to clinch the road victory.

Jrue Holiday led the way for the Pelicans with 21 points, adding six rebounds, five assists and one steal. Brandon Ingram posted 19 points, 11 rebounds, five assists and two steals. J.J. Redick poured in 16 points and also furnished two rebounds and one assist. E'Twaun Moore provided 13 points off the bench, while Derrick Favors generated a 12-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included three assists, one steal and one block.

Carmelo Anthony overcame a questionable designation due to a knee issue to pace the Trail Blazers with 23 points, which he complemented with nine rebounds, two assists and one steal. C.J. McCollum delivered 20 points, four rebounds, three assists and one steal. Damian Lillard totaled 18 points, seven assists, three rebounds and two steals. Hassan Whiteside contributed an 11-point, 16-rebound double-double.

The Pelicans remain on the road and next tangle with the Denver Nuggets on Christmas Night, while the Trail Blazers pay a visit to the Utah Jazz on Thursday night.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Sacramento Kings, 113-104, at Golden 1 Center on Monday night.

The Rockets (21-9) opened the game threatening a blowout, as they jumped out to a 37-21 lead through the first 12 minutes. The Kings (12-18) managed to shave eight points off their deficit during the second, but Houston's play in the third quarter, during which they added another 10 points to their advantage, essentially put the game away. The visitors enjoyed particularly large advantages in three-point shooting (38.5 percent-23.3 percent), but they lost the rebounding battle by a 49-40 margin.

James Harden led the Rockets with 34 points, adding five rebounds, five assists, two steals and one block. Russell Westbrook followed with 28 points, seven boards, six assists and one steal. Clint Capela generated a 15-point, 14-rebound double-double that also included two assists and two blocks. Danuel House, Jr. delivered 14 points, while P.J. Tucker mustered five points but pulled down 11 boards.

De'Aaron Fox paced the Kings with 31 points and complemented them with nine rebounds, six assists and one steal. Richaun Holmes and Trevor Ariza contributed matching 12-point efforts while also pulling down 14 and six rebounds, respectively. Marvin Bagley III turned in 11 points and six boards, while Nemanja Bjelica posted 10 points.

The Rockets next pay a visit to the Golden State Warriors on Wednesday for a Christmas Day showdown, while the Kings remain home and take on the Minnesota Timberwolves on Thursday night.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 113-104, at Chase Center on Monday night.

The two spiraling squads matched each other bucket for bucket in the first quarter, before the Warriors (7-24) opened up a 14-point lead heading into halftime. Golden State managed to tack on another three points to its advantage during the third, but the Timberwolves (10-19) put a scare into their hosts in the fourth by getting as close as 95-89 with 5:02 remaining. Ultimately, Minnesota didn't quite have enough offensive firepower without Karl-Anthony Towns (knee), who missed his third straight game.

Andrew Wiggins led the way for the Timberwolves with 22 points, seven rebounds, two assists and one block. Jordan McLaughlin furnished 19 points, four assists, two rebounds and three steals. Jeff Teague supplied 12 points, four assists, one rebound and one block. Gorgui Dieng turned in 11 points, eight rebounds, one assist, three steals and one block. Keita Bates-Diop poured in 10 points.

D'Angelo Russell paced the Warriors with 30 points, complementing them with four rebounds and four assists. Alec Burks managed 25 points, eight assists, two rebounds, three steals and one block. Damion Lee registered 14 points, seven rebounds, three assists and one steal. Willie Cauley-Stein turned in 12 points, seven rebounds, one assist, three blocks and two steals.

The Timberwolves next pay a visit to the Sacramento Kings on Thursday night, while the Warriors await a Christmas Day visit from the Houston Rockets on Wednesday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Dallas Mavericks, 110-107, at Scotiabank Arena on Sunday.

The Raptors (21-8) delivered one of their best performances of the season as they erased a 30-point deficit to claim a huge home win over the Mavericks (19-10). Even though Dallas, who didnt have their star player in Luka Doncic, led most of the game, the shorthanded Raptors managed to turn things around when it mattered the most. Toronto didnt have Pascal Siakam, Norman Powell and Marc Gasol, but other players stepped things up. The biggest moment of the comeback came in the final quarter, as Dallas entered the final 12 minutes of action down by 23 points. However, a 47-21 score in the final quarter allowed Toronto to pull a huge win in front of their own crowd.

Kyle Lowry was the best player for the Raptors, as he finished the contest with 32 points (12-23 FG), 10 assists and eight rebounds, and Fred VanVleet scored 10 points while grabbing three rebounds but these two players were the only two to score in double digits from the starting unit. Chris Boucher had a solid performance off the bench since he had 21 points, seven rebounds, four blocks and two steals. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson finished with 18 points and nine rebounds in 29 minutes.

All five Mavericks in the starting lineup managed to score in double digits, but that didnt happen with any bench player. Jalen Brunson led the way for Dallas with 21 points and nine assists, but Kristaps Porzingis had a strong double-double with 19 points and 12 rebounds. Dorian Finney-Smith added 14 points, five boards and three assists. Tim Hardaway Jr. had 16 points, eight rebounds and five assists. Dwight Powell chipped in with 17 points and nine boards.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 119-93, at TD Garden on Sunday evening. 

The Celtics (20-7) may have suffered from a bit of overconfidence early, as the visiting Hornets (13-20) jumped out to a 37-30 first-quarter lead thanks to some efficient shooting. However, that initial scare seemed to wake Boston up, as the hosts erased their deficit altogether in the second and headed into halftime with a three-point edge. After tacking on another four points during the third period, the Celtics dominated on both ends of the floor over the final 12 minutes, outscoring Charlotte by a 35-16 margin in the fourth for the big home win.

Devonte' Graham paced the Hornets with 23 points, adding 10 assists and four rebounds. Bismack Biyombo followed with 18 points, three boards, two assists and two blocks. Miles Bridges turned in 15 points, six rebounds, three assists, one steal and one block. Terry Rozier tallied 14 points, four assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block against his former squad.

Jayson Tatum led the Celtics with 39 points, supplementing them with 12 boards, two assists, three blocks and one steal. Kemba Walker furnished 23 points, four assists and one rebound. Jaylen Brown supplied 16 points, nine rebounds and five assists. Grant Williams mustered 12 points, four boards, two assists, one steal and one block.

The Hornets head back home to face the Oklahoma City Thunder on Friday night, while the Celtics pay a visit to the Toronto Raptors on Wednesday for a  Christmas Day showdown.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Indiana Pacers, 117-89, at Fiserv Forum on Sunday night. 

A showdown between two of the Eastern Conference's finest started off in highly competitive fashion, with the Bucks (27-4) forging a modest 59-55 halftime edge. Milwaukee added another six points to its advantage during the third and put away the Pacers (20-10) for good in a final period during which they dominated on both ends of the floor. The hosts enjoyed a 34-16 edge during the last 12 minutes of the contest and won the rebounding battle by a healthy 61-48 margin.

Domantas Sabonis led the way for the Pacers with a 19-point, 18-rebound double-double that included five assists, two steals and two blocks. Doug McDermott turned in 15 points and three boards. Myles Turner and Aaron Holiday generated matching 11-point efforts, with Turner five rebounds. Malcolm Brogdon posted a 10-point, 10-assist double-double that also included three rebounds and one steal. 

Wesley Matthews paced the Bucks with 19 points. Giannis Antetokounmpo followed with an 18-point, 19-rebound double-double that also featured nine assists, two steals and two blocks. Brook Lopez supplied 17 points, eight boards, two assists and two blocks. George Hill matched Lopez's scoring and also registered nine rebounds, four assists and one steal. Robin Lopez mustered 13 points and three boards, while Khris Middleton compiled 12 points, five assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block.

The Pacers head back home to tangle with the Toronto Raptors on Monday night, while the Bucks hit the road and visit the Philadelphia 76ers on Wednesday afternoon for a Christmas Day showdown.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the visiting Los Angeles Clippers, 118-112, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Sunday evening. 

Despite playing without Kawhi Leonard (rest), the Clippers got out to a good start on the road and led 33-27 after one quarter. They pushed their lead to 18 mid way through the second, but the Thunder brought it back to a six-point game by halftime. The Thunder came out strong in the third and tied the score at 69, halfway through the third, but the Clippers reclaimed the edge and held a three-point lead at the end of the quarter. The Clippers pushed their lead to eight in the fourth, but the Thunder closed the game on a 28-14 run, to earn the impressive comeback win. This marks the fourth straight win for the Thunder, as they improve to 11-5 at home.

Shai Gilgeous-Alexander led the Thunder with 32 points, five assists, three rebounds and two steals, in 34 minutes. Steven Adams added 20 points, 17 rebounds, three steals and two assists, while Dennis Schroder poured in 28 points, six assists, five rebounds and a steal, in 33 minutes off the bench. The Thunder shot 47 percent from the field, including 9-of-27 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Lou Williams led the Clippers with 22 points, seven assists and three rebounds, in 36 minutes. Paul George and Montreal Harrell added 18 points each, while Landry Shamet added 14 points, off the bench. The Clippers shot 46 percent from the field, including 11-of-27 from long range. 

The Clippers (22-10) will look to bounce back as they take on the Lakers on Wednesday. The Thunder (15-14) play host to the Grizzlies on Thursday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Los Angeles Lakers, 128-104, at Staples Center on Sunday.

While there were eight ties and 12 lead changes in the first 30 minutes of this game, Denver took control from there. In fact, they outscored the Lakers, 36-25 in the third quarter and 37-26 in the fourth quarter. That allowed them to hold a double-digit lead for the final 11 minutes of play, leading by 26 points at times. Ball movement was the difference in the game, with the Nuggets recording 31 assists to eight turnovers while the Lakers committed 19 turnovers to 18 assists. A lot of that had to do with the 13 steals by Denver, with Los Angeles recording just seven. In addition, the Nuggets went 27-of-30 from the free-throw line while the Lakers hit just 16-of-22. 

The Nuggets (20-8) were led by Paul Millsap, who dropped 21 points in an otherwise empty line. Nikola Jokic collected 18 points, six rebounds and five assists. Will Barton accrued 14 points, 13 rebounds, five assists and two steals while Gary Harris amassed 19 points, five assists and four steals. 

The Lakers (24-5) had to play this game without LeBron James, as Anthony Davis led the way with 32 points, 11 rebounds and four blocks. He was the only starter in double figures, with Rajon Rondo accumulating five points, four rebounds, eight assists and three steals. Kyle Kuzma led the bench with 16 points, four boards and two blocks.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 114-107, at Spectrum Center on Saturday afternoon.

However, Utah managed to regroup at intermission and came into the second half a different team. They ultimately outscored Charlotte by a 58-43 margin over the third and fourth quarters for the comeback road win, with a Rudy Gobert dunk and a pair of Donovan Mitchell free throws helping seal the victory in the closing seconds.

Bojan Bogdanovic paced the Jazz with 26 points, adding three rebounds and three assists. Mitchell followed with 20 points, nine assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block. Gobert generated a 17-point, 19-rebound double-double that also included one assist, three blocks and one steal. Joe Ingles poured in 14 points and also provided seven assists and two rebounds. Royce O'Neale offered 11 points, four rebounds, four assists and two steals. Emmanuel Mudiay led the bench with 12 points.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 122-112, at Barclays Center on Saturday evening.

The first quarter opened up in a highly competitive fashion that belied the drastic swings to come. The Hawks (6-24) and Nets (16-13) matched each other bucket for bucket in the first quarter during which each scored 34 points. Atlanta then gained 13 points' worth of separation heading into halftime, and the two squads played to a 25-25 deadlock in the third. However that's when the light went on for Brooklyn, which dominated on both ends of the floor over the final 12 minutes to the tune of a 37-14 advantage.

Trae Young led the Hawks with 47 points, adding eight rebounds, six assists and one steal. Alex Len generated a 23-point, 14-rebound double-double. Garrett Temple delivered 25 points, six boards, three assists, one steal and one block. Taurean Prince and DeAndre Jordan contributed 12 points apiece while hauling in 10 and 20 rebounds, respectively.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the host Detroit Pistons, 119-107, at Little Caesars Arena on Saturday evening. 

The Bulls jumped out to a quick 7-0 lead, but the Pistons picked up the pace and outscored the visitors 28-18 through the rest of the quarter. The Bulls came out on fire in the third and outscored the hosts 40-30 in the quarter to take a held a four-point lead into the final frame. The Bulls led by three with six minutes left but closed the contest on a 20-11 run to earn their second consecutive win, while this marks the fourth straight loss for the Pistons. 

Zach LaVine led the Bulls with 33 points, five rebounds, five assists and a steal, in 37 minutes. Coby white added 19 points and five rebounds, off the bench, while Lauri Markkanen chipped in 15 points, seven rebounds, two blocks, two assists and a steal. The Bulls shot 52 percent from the field, including 18-of-35 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Markieff Morris led the Pistons with 23 points on 8-of-19 shooting, as he got the start in place of the injured, Blake Griffin (knee). Andre Drummond added 19 points, 14 rebounds, five steals, three assists and two blocks, while Luke Kennard added 16 points, four rebounds and three assists. The Pistons shot 46 recent from the field, including 16-of-35 from long range. 

The Pistons (11-19) will look to bounce back as they play host to the 76ers on Monday. The Bulls (12-19) take on the Magic in Orlando on Monday.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Washington Wizards, 125-108, at Wells Fargo Center on Saturday night.

The 76ers (21-10) came into the contest looking to avoid a rare third straight home defeat, and they got off to a strong start against a team they enjoyed a clear talent advantage over in the Wizards (8-20). Philadelphia built a 65-53 halftime lead, and despite Washington successfully shaving four points from its deficit in the third, the home squad put a stamp on the win with a 37-point fourth-point quarter. As their point total implies, the Sixers were efficient from the floor, shooting 52.1 percent, including 42.4 percent from three-point range.

Bradley Beal paced the Wizards with 36 points and added eight rebounds, six assists and two steals. Isaiah Thomas followed with 20 points, while Troy Brown, Jr. compiled 19 points and five boards. Anzejs Pasecniks poured in 11 points, while Davis Bertans had nine points and nine rebounds.

Joel Embiid and Josh Richardson co-led the 76ers with 21 points, with Embiid adding 13 rebounds, three assists and two blocks. Tobias Harris delivered 16 points, six boards, four assists and two steals. Ben Simmons managed 14 points, 11 assists, eight rebounds and four steals. Al Horford totaled 13 points, nine boards, three assists and one block, while Trey Burke registered 12 points to pace the bench.

The Wizards remain on the road and face off with the New York Knicks on Monday night, while the 76ers pay a visit to the Detroit Pistons on Monday night as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host New York Knicks, 123-102, at Madison Square Garden on Saturday evening. 

The Bucks took control early on and held a 37-23 lead after one quarter. The Knicks picked up their play in the second and matched the visitors with 31 points each in the second and trailed by 14 at halftime. The Bucks came out strong again in the third and outscored the Knicks by 11 in the quarter, to push their lead to 25, heading into the final frame. The Knicks kept fighting down to the wire, as they outscored the Bucks 32-28 in the fourth, but it was not enough, as they fell for their second straight loss, while this marks the second straight win for the Bucks.

Khris Middleton was the high-point man for the Bucks, with 23 points on 7-of-17 shooting. Giannis Antetokounmpo tallied 22 points, 11 rebounds, 10 assists and two steals, while Brook Lopez added 14 points, seven rebounds and seven blocks. The Bucks shot 48 percent from the field, including 18-of-43 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Julius Randle led the Knicks with 20 points, eight rebounds and two assists, in 31 minutes. Kevin Knox II followed up with 19 points, three blocks and two steals, while R.J. Barrett added 17 points, five rebounds and three assists. The Knicks shot 40 percent from the field, including 9-of-30 from long range. 

The Knicks (7-23) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Wizards on Monday. The Bucks (26-4) play host to the Pacers on Sunday.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 119-115, at FedEx Forum on Saturday evening. 

Seven players scored in double digits for the Grizzlies, as they held on for their fifth win in their last eight games, while this marks the third straight loss for the Kings. The contest got out to a competitive start with a back-and-forth first quarter, with the Grizzlies taking a 23-21 lead into the second. The Grizzlies turned it up in the second and outscored the visitors by eight points in the quarter, to take a 60-50 lead into halftime. The Grizzlies held a steady lead through the third and managed to expand their cushion to 13, heading into the final frame. They pushed their lead up to 17, early in the fourth. The Kings rallied to make it a seven-point game with 30 seconds left, but the Grizzlies held on for the home win.

Seven players scored in double digits for Memphis, led by Jaren Jackson Jr., who tallied 18 points, five rebounds, four blocks, three steals and two assists, in 31 minutes. Jae Crowder added 17 points, 10 rebounds and five assists, while Dillon Brooks finished with 16 points, six rebounds and three assists. The Grizzlies shot 48 percent from the field, including 15-of-35 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Harrison Barnes led the Kings with 25 points, five assists and four rebounds, in 37 minutes. Richaun Holmes added 18 points, 12 rebounds, two assists, a steal and a block, while De'Aaron Fox totaled 22 points, four assists, three steals and three rebounds. The Kings shot 43 percent from the field, including 11-of-36 from long range.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the host San Antonio Spurs, 134-109, at AT&T Center on Saturday.

While there were 10 ties and 11 lead changes in the first 18 minutes of this game, the Clippers dominated after that. In fact, Los Angeles rode a 39-30 second quarter to an 11-point halftime lead and then took control with a 38-22 third quarter. That allowed the Clippers to lead by at least 20 for the entirety of the fourth quarter. Los Angeles shot 55 percent from the field while out-assisting San Antonio, 32-24. In addition, the Clippers won the offensive rebounding battle, 13-4, and the turnover differential, 18-11. 

The Clippers (22-9) got a gem from Kawhi Leonard against his former team, collecting 26 points, seven rebounds, nine assists and four steals on 11-of-16 from the field. The Suns ended up shooting 52 percent from the field and 29 percent from three-point range. The six blocks recorded by Houston was big too, with Phoenix swatting away just one shot.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 119-105, at Banker's Life Fieldhouse on Friday.

McConnell led the bench with 15 points and eight assists.

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 114-93, at TD Garden on Friday.

While there were four ties and five lead changes in the opening 15 minutes of this game, Boston dominated from there. In fact, the Celtics outscored the Pistons, 63-43, in the second and third quarters, leading by at least 20 points for the entirety of the fourth quarter. The Celtics shot 52 percent from the field while holding the Pistons to just 40 percent shooting. In addition, Boston out-rebounded Detroit, 51-36 while out-blocking them, 9-2. The Pistons also committed 24 turnovers. 

The Pistons (11-18) were led by Andre Drummond, who collected 12 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and six steals. Markieff Morris amassed 10 points, six rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Bruce Brown accrued nine points, five rebounds and five assists while Thon Maker led the bench with 15 points and seven boards.

Daniel Theis generated eight points, six rebounds and four blocks while Kemba Walker led the team with 11 assists despite not making a shot. Enes Kanter led the team with 18 rebounds off the bench.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the visiting Washington Wizards, 122-118, at Scotiabank Arena on Friday.

While this wasn't necessarily a wire-to-wire win for the Raptors, they held the lead for the final 45 minutes of play. In fact, Toronto rode a 40-23 first quarter to a big first-half lead and Washington could never recapture it from there despite tying the game midway through the fourth quarter. Toronto ended up shooting 49 percent from the field and 40 percent from three-point range. While not winning by much, the Raptors won the rebounding, assists and block differentials as well.

Serge Ibaka accumulated 23 points, 10 rebounds and three blocks. OG Anunoby provided 18 points, seven rebounds and two assists while Fred VanVleet collected 18 points, nine rebounds and eight assists. 

On deck for Washington is another road game against the Philadelphia 76ers on Saturday. As for Toronto, they play host to the Dallas Mavericks on Sunday for their next outing.

The Miami Heat defeated the visiting New York Knicks, 129-114, at American Airlines Arena on Friday.

A 39-20 first quarter really set the tone in this game, with Miami winning in dominating fashion. In fact, the Heat led by at least 15 points for the final three quarters, leading by 34 at times in this lopsided result. Miami ended up shooting 56 percent from the field and 47 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Heat out-rebounded the Knicks, 51-41, while out-assisting them, 34-23.

Kelly Olynyk had a double-double off the bench as well.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the host Philadelphia 76ers, 117-98, at Wells Fargo Center on Friday evening. 

After starting the season 14-0 at home, the 76ers fell for their second consecutive home loss. The 76ers jumped out to an 11-5 lead early on, but the Mavericks rallied to take a 35-28 lead by the end of the first quarter. The Sixers closed in to start the second, but the Mavs pulled back ahead and took a six-point lead into halftime. Again the 76ers bought it back to a one-possession game early in the third, but the Mavs charged ahead and expanded their lead to 11 points, heading into the final frame. The Mavs held a double-digit lead through most of the fourth quarter, as they held on for the impressive road win. The Mavs shot 52 percent from the field, including 14-of-33 from long range.

Ben Simmons added 12 points, eight assists and six rebounds, while Josh Richardson chipped in 10 points, six rebounds, four assists and two steals. Tobias Harris had a tough night, as he finished with seven points on 3-of-11 shooting. 

The 76ers (20-10) will look to avoid a third consecutive loss, as they play host to the Wizards on Saturday. The Mavericks (19-9) take on the Raptors in Toronto on Sunday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Phoenix Suns, 126-108, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Friday night.

The Thunder (14-14) came in looking to finally even their record at .500 again after a rough start to the season, but they encountered a game Suns (11-17) squad early. OKC held only a 57-50 halftime lead before both teams combined for an 85-point tally in the third quarter. The hosts still managed to outscore Phoenix by a 44-41 margin during that period, and the 10-point lead they carried into the fourth quarter increased to 18 by game's end courtesy of a 25-17 edge for the Thunder in the final 12 minutes.

Dario Saric supplied 16 points, six rebounds, four assists and one steal. Kelly Oubre, Jr. delivered 13 points, four rebounds, two assists and one steal. Elie Okobo led the bench with 11 points.

Shai Gilgeous-Alexander paced the Thunder with a career-high 32 points, complementing them with four boards, three assists and one steal. Dennis Schroder followed with 24 points, nine boards and six assists. Danilo Gallinari registered 22 points, six rebounds, one assist and one block. Chris Paul managed 15 points, seven assists, two rebounds and one steal, while Steven Adams and Nerlens Noel went for 10 points apiece.

The Suns head back home and take on the Houston Rockets on Saturday night, while the Thunder remain home and face the Los Angeles Clippers on Sunday night.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Minnesota Timberwolves, 109-100, at Pepsi Center on Friday evening. 

The Nuggets got out to a great start at home, as they took a 33-20 lead after one quarter. They maintained a comfortable lead through the second, but the Timberwolves trimmed it to a 10-point game by halftime. The Timberwolves came out strong in the third and brought it to a two-point game with four minutes left in the quarter, but the Nuggets pushed it back to a seven-point game entering the final frame. The Nuggets kept their foot on the gas to start the fourth and pushed their lead to 16 points, with 5:11 left in the contest. The Nuggets held on to earn their fifth straight win, while this marks the ninth straight loss for Minnesota. 

Jamal Murray led the Nuggets with 28 points, six rebounds, five assists and three steals, in 36 minutes. Nikola Jokic added 22 points, 10 rebounds, 10 assists and two blocks, while Will Barton chipped in 13 points, four rebounds and two assists. The Nuggets shot 49 percent from the field, including 10-of-28 from long range. 

Meanwhile, in the absence of Karl-Anthony Towns (knee), Andrew Wiggins led the Timberwolves with 19 points, six assists, three rebounds, a steal and a block, in 37 minutes. Gorgui Dieng added 18 points and six rebounds, while Jeff Teague tallied 13 points, to rebounds and two assists. The Timberwolves shot 41 percent from the field, including 10-of-42 from long range. 

The Timberwolves (10-17) will look to bounce back as they take on the Trail Blazers on Saturday. The Nuggets (19-8) take on the Lakers in Los Angeles on Sunday.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the Orlando Magic, 118-103, at Moda Center on Friday night.

The Trail Blazers (13-16) came out of the gates playing stellar ball on both ends of the floor, as they jumped out to a 31-13 first-quarter lead. However, that wasn't nearly enough to erase the significant hole they'd dug from themselves, with Orlando suffering its 11th home loss in fairly convincing fashion.

Nikola Vucevic led the Magic with a 23-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included an assist, six steals and two blocks. D.J. Augustin followed with a bench-leading 17 points. Evan Fournier poured in 16 points and added three assists, two rebounds and one steal. Aaron Gordon provided 11 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and one block. Jonathan Isaac and Markelle Fultz generated matching 10-point tallies.

Kent Bazemore delivered 11 points, four boards, one steal and one block. Hassan Whiteside generated a 10-point, 17-rebound double-double that also included five blocks.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the New Orleans Pelicans, 106-102, at Chase Center on Friday night.

The Warriors (6-24) found some rare success in the first quarter, dominating the Pelicans (7-24) on both ends of the floor over the first 12 minutes to the tune of a 31-16 advantage. However, New Orleans subsequently outscored Golden State by a 65-47 margin over the middle periods, which sent the Pelicans into the fourth quarter with a three-point edge. JJ Redick and Lonzo Ball provided matching 14-point, four-rebound efforts, with Ball also recording six steals. Derrick Favors managed 10 points, nine rebounds, one assist and one block.

Alec Burks totaled 18 points, eight rebounds, three assists and four steals. Draymond Green supplied 10 points, eight assists, four rebounds and two steals. 

The Pelicans remain on the road and tangle with the Portland Trail Blazers on Monday night, while the Warriors remain home and face the Minnesota Timberwolves on Monday night.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 111-106, at State Farm Arena on Thursday evening.

The Jazz (17-11) managed to defeat the Hawks (6-23) despite the fact they didn't play very well for most of the game, and only managed to turn things around in the final 12 minutes of action. Atlanta jumped to a 30-28 lead after the first quarter, and they extended their advantage to four points following a 26-24 second quarter. Utah began their turnaround in the third quarter (31-28), but they completed the comeback in the final 12 minutes of action where a 28-22 score gave Utah a huge win on the road even if they weren't at their best. With the win, Utah improved to 6-8 away while the Hawks fell to 3-11 at home.

Donovan Mitchell led the way for the Jazz since he ended with 30 points, five rebounds and five assists, while Rudy Gobert delivered another strong double-double after chipping in with 20 points and 13 boards. Joe Ingles had 14 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Bojan Bogdanovic added 19 points and nine rebounds. Emmanuel Mudiay contributed 10 points and four rebounds in 19 minutes off the bench.

Trae Young was the Hawks top player since he had 30 points, eight assists and five boards. Kevin Huerter contributed 17 points, while Cam Reddish had 14 points, four rebounds and three steals. Jabari Parker was one of Atlantas top scorers despite coming off the bench, as the power forward contributed 23 points, nine rebounds and five assists despite playing just 24 minutes while coming off the bench.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Los Angeles Lakers, 111-104, at Fiserv Forum on Thursday night.

The Bucks (25-4) knew they had one of the biggest tests of the season in front of them in the form of the Lakers (24-5), which were getting Anthony Davis back from a one-game absence due to an ankle injury. However, Milwaukee set a dominant tone early, establishing a 23-17 lead after one quarter that had grown to 65-46 by halftime courtesy of a 42-point second period. While Los Angeles managed to shave 11 points from its deficit during the third quarter, the home squad hung tough in the final 12 minutes by essentially matching them bucket for bucket on the way to a tough home win.

Davis led the way for the Lakers with 36 points, adding 10 rebounds, five assists, three blocks and one steal. LeBron James followed with a 21-point, 12-rebound, 11-assist triple-double. Danny Green matched James' scoring and added four rebounds and a block. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope furnished 18 points, three assists, one rebound and one steal. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo paced the Bucks with a 34-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included seven assists, one steal and one block. George Hill delivered 21 points, three rebounds and one assist. Khris Middleton delivered 15 points, six boards and two assists. Wesley Matthews totaled 13 points, four rebounds, two assists, two steals and one block. Brook Lopez supplied 10 points, four rebounds, two assists, four steals and three blocks. 

The Lakers head back home to take on the Denver Nuggets on Sunday night, while the Bucks pay a visit to the New York Knicks on Saturday night.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 118-105, at AT&T Center on Thursday evening. 

The Nets got out to a great start on the road with an early 12-2 run and held on to take a six-point game by the end of the quarter. The Nets stayed in control and held a double-digit lead for much of the second, but the Spurs brought it back to a six-point game by halftime. The Nets stayed solid to start the third and held a 10-point lead with just over four minutes left in the quarter, but the Spurs closed the quarter on a 19-7 run, to take a two-point lead into the final frame. The Spurs pushed the momentum into the fourth and quickly built a nine-point lead. They stayed on top the rest of the way, while the Nets made it a two-point game with five minutes to go, the Spurs outscored the visitors by 11 points in the fourth quarter, to secure their eighth home win. 

Patty Mills led the Spurs with 27 points on 8-of-14 shooting, in 26 minutes off the bench. LaMarcus Aldridge totalled 20 points, 10 rebounds, two assists, four blocks and a steal, while Dejounte Murray and Derrick White chipped in 13 points each. The Spurs shot 45 percent from the field, including 13-of-33 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Spencer Dinwiddie led the Nets with 41 points and five assists, in 34 minutes. Jarrett Allen added 19 points, 13 rebounds, six assists, a block and a steal, while DeAndre Jordan tallied three points, 11 rebounds and a steal, off the bench. The Nets shot 42 percent from the field, including 7-of-36 from long range. 

The Nets (15-13) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Hawks on Saturday. The Spurs (11-16) play host to the Clippers on Saturday.

The Houston Rockets defeated the host Los Angeles Clippers, 122-117, at Staples Center on Thursday. 
 
While there were nine lead changes in the first 15 minutes of this game, Los Angeles rode a 41-27 second quarter to a big halftime lead. Houston then responded with a 36-18 third quarter to take a three-point lead going into the fourth quarter. The Rockets started that fourth quarter on an 11-2 run but the Clippers responded with a 22-4 run of their own to take a six-point lead with five minutes remaining. Houston then scored 15 unanswered points with less than two minutes remaining and never gave up the lead from there. All of those runs ultimately led to 14 lead changes in this game. The key for Houston was their shooting, connecting on 50 percent of their shots. 

The Rockets (19-9) got a season-high from Russell Westbrook, who collected 40 points, 10 rebounds and five assists. James Harden tallied 28 points, 10 assists and two steals. Clint Capela totaled 16 points, eight rebounds and four steals while P.J. Tucker amassed 10 points, 12 rebounds and two blocks. 

The Clippers (21-9) were led by Paul George, who accumulated 34 points, nine rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks. Kawhi Leonard finished with 25 points, nine rebounds and four assists. Patrick Beverley accrued 10 points, seven assists and four steals while Montrezl Harrell led the bench with 19 points and six boards. Beverley and Lou Williams were both ejected.

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Houston traveling to face the Phoenix Suns and Los Angeles playing the San Antonio Spurs on the road as well.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 100-98, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Wednesday evening.

The Cavaliers (7-21) were coming off a 1-2 road trip, and they used a strong first half to take care of a struggling Hornets (13-18) team that couldnt complete a comeback in the second half. Cleveland went up 29-21 following the first quarter, and they extended their lead to 12 points following a 24-20 second quarter (53-41). Charlotte tried to mount a comeback and while the third quarter ended tied at 23-23, the Hornets went on a scoring run and won the final 12 minutes by a 10-point margin (34-24). That was not enough, however, and Cleveland secured the win. With the win, the Cavaliers improved to 4-10 at home while the Hornets fell to 6-10 on the road.

Collin Sexton was the best player for the Cavaliers, as he ended with 23 points while shooting 10-for-14 from the field. Cedi Osman had 18 points, while Kevin Love sniffed a triple-double after posting 16 points, 14 rebounds and seven assists. Tristan Thompson added 14 points, 13 rebounds and two assists. Jordan Clarkson added 10 points off the bench.

Terry Rozier had perhaps his best game with the Hornets, as he ended with 35 points even though he needed 27 shots to reach that mark. Cody Zeller had 15 points with nine boards, while Marvin Williams had 10 points, four rebounds and four assists off the bench. One of the biggest disappointments was Devonte Graham, who ended with nine points and nine assists, but he made just three of his 16 shots from the field.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the host Detroit Pistons, 112-99, at Little Ceasar's Arena on Wednesday. 

While there were nine ties and 11 lead changes in the first half, Toronto never surrendered the lead after that. In fact, the Raptors outscored the Pistons in the middle quarters, 66-50, leading by at least nine points for the entirety of the fourth quarter. Three-point shooting was the difference in the game, with the Raptors hitting 13-of-35 and the Pistons connecting on just 6-of-35. In addition, Toronto out-assisted Detroit, 27-19. 

The Raptors (19-8) were led by Pascal Siakam, who tallied 26 points, five rebounds, three assists and four blocks. Kyle Lowry recorded a triple-double, collecting 20 points, 10 rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. OG Anunoby generated 19 points, eight rebounds and three assists while Serge Ibaka led the bench with 25 points and 13 boards. 

The Pistons (11-17) were led by Andre Drummond, collecting 22 points, 18 rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Blake Griffin totaled 15 points, two rebounds, four assists and two blocks. Bruce Brown amassed 12 points, three rebounds and two assists while Derrick Rose led the bench with 16 points, four rebounds and five assists. 

Both teams return to action on Friday, with Toronto playing host to the Washington Wizards and Detroit traveling to face the Boston Celtics.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Washington Wizards in overtime, 110-109, at Capital One Arena on Wednesday evening.

The Wizards (8-18) were coming off a win that snapped a four-game losing streak the last time out, but they found themselves in the losing end once again as the Bulls (11-19) made the game-winning shot with 9.1 seconds left in the overtime. The game seemed to go on the Wizards way all night long, as Washington won each of the first three quarters, but the Bulls stormed with a huge comeback in the final 12 minutes that forced the OT period. The Wizards were also leading in the overtime, but Zach LaVine found Wendell Carter Jr. and he made the winning bucket for Chicago. With the win, the Bulls moved to 5-9 on the road while the Wizards fell to 4-7 at home.

Lauri Markkanen was the best player for the Bulls, as he ended with 31 points (making 12 of his 19 field goals) and adding nine rebounds. Zach LaVine endured a rough night from the field since he went 6-for-23, but he also made all of his 11 free throws to finish with 24 points. Kris Dunn had 15 points, five assists, and five boards. Tomas Satoransky had 17 points. Wendell Carter Jr. had nine points and nine boards to go along with the game-winning shot.

Davis Bertans moved to the starting lineup and he delivered, as he finished with a team-high 26 points to go along with seven rebounds. Bradley Beal had 22 points, seven rebounds and seven boards. Isaiah Thomas had 16 points, and Ian Mahinmi had eight points with six rebounds in only 24 minutes. Troy Brown Jr. had 10 points off the bench.

The Miami Heat defeated the host Philadelphia 76ers, 108-104, at Wells Fargo Center on Wednesday evening. 

The Heat put on a great performance to hand the 76ers their first home loss of the season. The 76ers got out to a good start at home, as they led through the first quarter and took a 29-19 lead into the second. The Heat turned it up a notch in the second and outscored the hosts by 18 points in the quarter, to take a 56-48 lead into halftime. The Heat held a solid lead through the third but the Sixers brought it to a four-point game late in the quarter, before trailing by eight again, to start the fourth. The Heat caught fire to start the fourth and quickly pushed their lead to 16, but the 76ers had no quit, as they cut it to a two-point game with one second left. The Heat sealed the deal at the foul line to move to 9-7 on the road.  

Kendrick Nunn led the Heat with 26 points, five assists, four rebounds and a steal, in 41 minutes. Bam Adebayo finished tie 23 points, nine rebounds, five assists, two blocks and two steals, while Jimmy Butler added 14 points, seven rebounds, five assists and two steals. The Heat shot 47 percent from the field, including 12-of-31 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Joel Embiid led the 76ers with 22 points, 19 rebounds, three assists, two blocks and a steal, in 35 minutes. Tobias Harris tallied 20 points, four rebounds and two assists, while Josh Richardson and Ben Simmons added 17 points each. The Sixers shot 42 percent from the field, including 12-of-39 from long range. 

The Sixers (20-9) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Mavs on Friday. The Heat (20-8) play host to the Knicks on Friday.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the host Minnesota Timberwolves, 107-99, at Target Center on Wednesday.

A 32-25 first quarter really set the tone in this game for the Pelicans, with a 31-25 second quarter putting the game to bed. In fact, New Orleans led by at least eight points for the entirety of the second half. Rebounding was a huge factor, with the Pelicans out-rebounding the Timberwolves, 55-43. In addition, New Orleans shot 44 percent from the field and 43 percent from three-point range while holding Minnesota to 38 percent from the field and 26 percent from long range. 

The Pelicans (7-22) were led by Brandon Ingram, who collected 34 points, six rebounds, five assists and three steals. Jrue Holiday accrued 18 points, three rebounds, three assists and two steals. Derrick Favors totaled six points and 11 rebounds while Josh Hart led the bench with 11 points, six rebounds and two assists. Lonzo Ball accumulated 10 points, six rebounds and six assists off the pine as well. 

The Timberwolves (10-16) had to play this game without Karl-Anthony Towns, as Andrew Wiggins led the way with 27 points and seven rebounds. Gorgui Dieng started for Towns and amassed 13 points and eight rebounds. Jeff Teague went just 1-of-8 from the field to finish with five points and nine assists. Robert Covington led the bench with 15 points, seven rebounds and three steals. 

Both teams return to action on Friday, with New Orleans traveling to face the Golden State Warriors and Minnesota facing the Denver Nuggets on the road as well.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the visiting Memphis Grizzlies, 126-122, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Wednesday evening. 

The Grizzlies got out to a good start on the road, as they led for almost the entire first quarter and took a 32-27 lead into the second. The Grizzlies stayed on the attack and pushed their lead to 16, mid way through the second, before taking a nine-point lead into halftime. The Grizzlies carried the momentum into the third, as they pushed their lead to 24, with 7:10 left in the third. However, the Thunder closed the quarter on a 28-11 run, to make a seven-point game heading into the fourth. The Thunder continued to fight through the fourth and grabbed the lead early in the quarter. They outscored the visitors by 11 points in the fourth, to walk away with their fifth win in their last seven games. 

Dennis Schroder led the Thunder with 31 points, seven assists, three rebounds and a steal, in 32 minutes off the bench. Danilo Gallinari and Shai Gilgeous-Alexander added 20 points each, while Chris Paul finished with 18 points, five assists, four rebounds and two steals. The Thunder shot 55 percent from the field, including 7-of-24 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Brandon Clarke led the Grizzlies with 27 points ad seven rebounds, in 25 minutes off the bench. Jonas Valanciunas tallied 24 points, nine rebounds and three assists, while Ja Morant added 22 points, seven assists and five rebounds. The Grizzlies shot 51 percent from the field, including 10-of-25 from long range. 

The Grizzlies (10-18) will look to bounce back as they take on the Cavaliers in Cleveland on Friday. The Thunder (13-14) play host to the Suns on Friday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Orlando Magic, 113-104, at Pepsi Center on Wednesday.

While Orlando led by 19 points early in the second half, Denver was able to prevail. In fact, they ended up outscoring Orlando in the third quarter, 39-16, holding the lead for the entirety of the fourth quarter. Prior to that, there were six ties and eight lead changes in total. Denver dominated the boards, outrebounding Orlando, 52-35. In addition, the Nuggets shot 48 percent from the field and 41 percent from three-point range while holding the Magic to 43 percent from the field and 38 percent from long range. 

The Magic (12-16) were led by Nikola Vucevic, who collected 20 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Evan Fournier amassed 13 points and three assists. Aaron Gordon went just 4-of-14 from the field to finish with nine points, seven rebounds and three assists. D.J. Augustin led the bench with 18 points, three rebounds and seven assists. 

The Nuggets (18-8) were led by Jamal Murray, who collected 33 points and five rebounds. Nikola Jokic generated 18 points, nine rebounds and 12 assists. Paul Millsap accumulated 15 points, 12 rebounds and two assists. Will Barton totaled nine points, nine rebounds, three assists and two steals. Mason Plumlee led the bench with nine points, six rebounds and two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Friday, with Denver remaining home to face the Minnesota Timberwolves while Orlando stays on the road to play the Portland Trail Blazers.

The Boston Celtics take on the Dallas Mavericks at American Airlines Center on Wednesday night.

The Mavericks (18-9) had already notched one impressive victory over an elite Eastern Conference opponent in the Milwaukee Bucks on Monday night, and they got off to a good start in their quest for a second one by jumping out to a 55-50 halftime lead over the Celtics (18-7). However, the tide of the game changed in the third quarter, when Boston outscored Dallas by a 26-18 margin with strong play on both ends of the floor. The visitors ultimately made their advantage hold up, with a 12-7 run over the first 5:22 of the final period helping them to establish a solid cushion. Ryan Broekhoff helped the Mavs get as close as 107-103 with 20.3 seconds remaining with a pair of free throws, but Jaylen Brown sunk a pair of his own to seal the win.

Kemba Walker paced the Celtics with 32 points, adding five rebounds, three assists and one block. Brown finished with 26 points, nine boards, one block and one steal. Jayson Tatum delivered 24 points, eight rebounds, one assist and one block. 

Kristaps Porzingis led the Mavericks with a 23-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included two assists, three blocks and one steal. Seth Curry poured in 20 points and also offered four rebounds and two assists. Tim Hardaway managed 13 points, three rebounds, two assists and one steal. Jalen Bruson delivered a 10-point, 11-assist double-double that also included seven rebounds. 

The Celtics will head back home and face the Detroit Pistons on Friday night, while the Mavericks pay a visit to the Philadelphia 76ers on Friday night as well.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the Golden State Warriors, 122-112, at Moda Center on Wednesday night.

The Trail Blazers (12-16) looked ready to take care of business against an inferior opponent early, as they played a strong offensive opening period and headed into the second quarter with a 40-29 advantage. However, a game Warriors (5-24) battled back to narrow their deficit to one going into intermission. Ultimately, Portland regrouped at halftime and outscored Golden State by a 55-46 margin in the second half to seal a double-digit home win.

D'Angelo Russell paced the Warriors with 26 points, adding seven assists, one rebound, two blocks and one steal. Glenn Robinson III turned in 17 points and four rebounds. Alec Burks supplied 16 points, six rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block. Willie Cauley-Stein registered 12 points, seven rebounds, one assist and one steal. Eric Paschall managed 11 points and four boards, while Marquese Chriss generated a 10-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one assist and one block.

Damian Lillard led the Trail Blazers with a 31-point, 13-assist double-double that also included five rebounds, one steal and one block. C.J. McCollum furnished 30 points, five boards, three assists and one steal. Carmelo Anthony supplied 17 points, eight rebounds, two blocks and one steal. Hassan Whiteside contributed a 16-point, 23-rebound double-double that also included two blocks. Skal Labissiere turned in 10 points and seven rebounds off the bench.

The Warriors head back home to take on the New Orleans Pelicans on Friday night, while the Trail Blazers remain home and tangle with the Orlando Magic on Friday night as well.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the Sacramento Kings, 110-102, at Spectrum Center on Tuesday evening.

The Kings (12-15) entered this game coming off a win Sunday at Golden State, while the Hornets (13-17) were coming off a 2-1 road trip, so both teams carried some decent momentum going forward. Charlotte grabbed the lead early on, however, and they quickly jumped to a 26-21 lead following the first quarter. Charlotte also won the second quarter by a 27-26 score, but Sacramento didn't sit back and tried to flip the script with a 32-27 third quarter. The final 12 minutes were as tight as they could get since Charlotte entered the final frame with only a one-point lead, but the Hornets closed things out with a 30-23 score that didn't leave doubts. With the win, Charlotte moved to 7-8 at home while the Kings fell to 6-10 away from home.

Seven of nine Sacramento players scored in double digits, but DeAaron Fox led the way with a strong 19-point, eight-assist performance in 30 minutes off the bench. Marvin Bagley III chipped in with 14 points and seven boards off the bench, while Harrison Barnes and Buddy Hield each had 14 points. Nenad Bjelica contributed 12 points, five boards and three assists. Bogdan Bogdanovic had 10 points as well.

Malik Monk was Charlottes best player since he had 23 points, 10 rebounds and four assists while playing 27 minutes off the bench. Devonte Graham had 15 points, seven assists and four boards, while Cody Zeller came just one rebound away from a triple-double thanks to 17 points and nine rebounds. Marvin Williams had 16 points, and Bismack Biyombo chipped in with 10 points and 12 rebounds.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the visiting Los Angeles Lakers, 105-102, at Banker's Life Fieldhouse on Tuesday.

Los Angeles came into this matchup with an NBA-best 14-game road winning streak but that was snapped here. It was close throughout though, with as there were seven ties and five lead changes with neither team leading by more than 10 points. Los Angeles had an opportunity to tie at the buzzer with a three but missed. The key for Indiana was three-point shooting, with the Pacers hitting 10-of-25 and the Lakers connecting on just 8-of-31. In addition, Los Angeles went just 8-of-17 from the free-throw line. 

The Lakers (24-4) were led by LeBron James, who tallied 20 points, nine rebounds and nine assists. JaVale McGee amassed 10 points, eight rebounds and three blocks. Dwight Howard led the bench with 20 points, six rebounds and two blocks. Rajon Rondo accrued seven points, five rebounds and seven assists but missed the game-tying three at the buzzer. 

The Pacers (19-9) were led by Domantas Sabonis, who collected 26 points, 10 rebounds and four assists. Myles Turner totaled 16 points, seven rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Malcolm Brogdon generated 14 points, five rebounds and six assists while Aaron Holiday led the bench with 11 points, two rebounds and four assists. 

On deck for Los Angeles is a road game against the Milwaukee Bucks on Thursday. As for Indiana, they return to action on Friday playing host to the Sacramento Kings.

The New York Knicks defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 143-120, at Madison Square Garden on Tuesday evening. 

The Knicks got out to a great start at home, as they jumped to a 41-27 lead after one quarter. They kept the momentum going in the second and increased their lead to 24 points by halftime. The Hawks put up a fight in the third but could not cut into the deficit, as they were outscored by one point in the quarter and trailed by 15, heading into the final frame. The Knicks stayed in control through the fourth and cruised to their third win in their last four games, and their fourth home win of the season. This marks the fifth loss in a row for the Hawks. 

R.J. Barrett led the Knicks with 27 points on 10-of-13 shooting, in 28 minutes. Marcus Morris Sr. added 22 points, four rebounds and two assists, while Mitchell Robinson added 22 points, 13 rebounds, two blocks and a steal, in 29 minutes off the bench. The Knicks shot 56 percent from the field, including 13-of-28 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Trae Young led the Hawks with 42 points, eight assists and four rebounds, in 41 minutes. De'Andre Hunter followed up with 19 points, five rebounds, four assists and a steal, while Vince Carter added 15 points on 5-of-9 shooting, including 4-of-7 from long range, in 24 minutes off the bench. The Hawks shot 46 percent from the field, including 15-of-43 from deep. 

The Hawks (6-22) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Jazz on Thursday. The Knicks (7-21) take on the Heat in Miami on Friday.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the host New Orleans Pelicans, 108-101, at Smoothie King Center on Tuesday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start as the score was tied at 21, heading into the second. The Pelicans opened up an eight-point lead mid way through the second, but the Nets closed the quarter on a 15-0 run, to take a seven-point lead into halftime. The Pelicans came out strong in the third quarter and quickly closed the gap. They kept pushing and took a three-point lead into the final frame. The scored stayed tight through the fourth, with the Nets hitting a game-tying three, with 45 seconds left, sending the game to overtime. The Nets carried the momentum into the extra period, as they took the lead on their first shot and carried it the rest of the way to their second consecutive win. This marks the 13th straight loss for the Pelicans. 

Spencer Dinwiddie led the Nets with 31 points, seven assists, two rebounds and a steal, in 38 minutes. Joe Harris followed up with 24 points, six rebounds, three assists and a block, while Jarrett Allen totalled 12 points, 14 rebounds and six blocks. The Nets shot 42 percent from the field, including 11-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Brandon Ingram led the Pelicans with 22 points, 10 rebounds and two blocks, in 41 minutes. Jrue Holiday added 21 points, six assists five rebounds, two blocks and a steal, while Lonzo Ball finished with 10 points, eight rebounds and four assists. The Pelicans shot 34 percent from the field, including 11-of-40 from deep.
