Blake Griffin tallied 17 points and five rebounds, while Andre Drummond added seven points and 18 rebounds. The Pistons shot 43 percent from the field, including 14-of-38 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Terrence Ross led the Magic with 19 points on 7-of-14 shooting, in 30 minutes off the bench. Evan Fournier followed up with 17 points, while Markelle Fultz tallied 16 points, four rebounds, three assists and three steals. The Magic shot 39 percent from the field, including 8-of-26 from deep. 

The Magic (6-10) will look to bounce back as they take on the Cavs in Cleveland on Wednesday. The Pistons (6-11) take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Wednesday.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 126-114, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Monday night.

The Pacers wasted no time getting off to a fast start against one of the most defensively vulnerable teams in the league in the Grizzlies (5-11), building a 36-27 lead through one and expanding that advantage to 11 by halftime. Indiana ultimately held a 21-point edge going into the final period, which was enough to withstand occasional strong stretches of play by Memphis as the game wound down.

Jaren Jackson, Jr. paced the Grizzlies by furnishing 28 points, five rebounds and one assist. Ja Morant turned in a 19-point, 10-assist double-double that also included two rebounds, two steals and one block. Brandon Clarke delivered 17 points and four rebounds. Jonas Valanciuanas generated a 14-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included three blocks and one steal. Dillon Brooks and Jae Crowder had matching nine-point tallies. 

T.J. Warren led the Pacers with 26 points and added four rebounds. Jeremy Lamb poured in 19 points and also posted four rebounds, four assists and one steal. Aaron Holiday generated 16 points off the bench. Malcolm Brogdon registered 14 points, eight assists, six rebounds and one steal in his return from injury. Domantas Sabonis supplied a 13-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included six assists and two steals. T.J. McConnell had 11 points, six assists and five rebounds off the bench.

The Grizzlies return home and face the Los Angeles Clippers on Wednesday night, while the Pacers remain home to tangle with the Utah Jazz on Wednesday night as well.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 125-113, at Sttate Farm Arena on Monday night.

The game was projected to keep the scoreboard operator busy, with both teams sporting high-octane offense and suspect defense. The contest ultimately lived up to expectation in that regard and did so right from the jump, with the Hawks (4-13) jumping out to a 64-54 halftime lead after a big 34-point second quarter. However, the Timberwolves (9-8) managed to eliminate their deficit and build a three-point lead heading into the final period, adnd they ultimately took control by outscoring Atlanta, 32-23, over the last 12 minutes.

Karl-Anthony Towns led the Timberwolves with 28 points, adding 13 rebounds, eight assists and two blocks. Andrew Wiggins supplied 25 points, six boards, one assist and two steals. Jarrett Culver delivered 14 points, five rebounds, three assists and two steals. Keita Bates-Diop and Gorgui Dieng had matching 13-point tallies and pulled down five and two rebounds, respectively.

Trae Young paced the Hawks with 37 points while also dishing out nine assists and pulling down six rebounds. Jabari Parker registered 22 points, seven boards, two assists and two steals. Bruno Fernando came off the bench to tally 13 points, four rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. De'Andre Hunter, Cam Reddish and Damian Jones all had matching seven-point, three-rebound contributions.

The Timberwolves travel to meet the San Antonio Spurs on Wednesday night, while the Hawks also hit the road and face the Milwaukee Bucks on Wednesday night. 

The Timberwolves

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 103-102, at TD Garden on Monday evening. 

The contest got out to a tight start, but the Kings were able to take a three-point lead heading into the second quarter. The Kings led for most of the second, but the Celtics closed the half on a 9-2 run, to take a seven-point lead into the break. The Kings came out strong in the third and tied it up just minutes into the quarter. The teams played to a standstill from there, as the score was tied at 75, heading into the final frame. The Celtics pulled ahead by seven mid way through the fourth, but the Kings rallied back to tie it at 99, with one minute left. The Kings then managed a go-ahead basket, but the Celtics got the last laugh, thanks to Marcus Smart, who hit the game-wining layup and secured the win with a steal on the Kings' final possession. 

Smart finished with 17 points, seven assists, five steals, three rebounds and a block, in 37 minutes. Jaylen Brown was the high-point man for Boston, with 24 points on 9-of-16 shooting, in 34 minutes. Jayson Tatum added 20 points, six rebounds and three assists, while Enes Kanter chipped in 13 points and nine rebounds. 

Meanwhile, Buddy Hield led the Kings with 41 points on 15-of-26 shooting, including 11-of-21 from long range. Harrison Barnes added 20 points, while Bogdan Bogdanovic totalled 13 points and eight assists. The Kings shot 47 percent from the field, including 18-of-47 from long range. 

The Kings (7-9) will look to bounce back as they take on the 76ers in Philly on Wednesday. The Celtics (12-4) play host to the Nets on Wednesday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 101-96, at Scotiabank Arena on Monday evening. 

The Sixers got out to a good start on the road, as they closed the first quarter on a 17-11 run, to take a 34-28 lead into the second. The Raptors responded in the second quarter and rallied to take the lead halfway through the quarter, outscoring the visitors by eight in the period, to take a two-point lead by halftime. Both teams came out on fire in the third, with the Sixers outscoring the Raptors 31-30, to make it a one-point game entering the final frame. The Sixers pulled ahead early in the fourth and held a five-point lead with under four minutes left tin the contest. However, the Raptors came up clutch on both ends of the floor in the final minutes, as they closed the game on a 10-0 run, to stay undefeated at home and earn their fourth straight win. 

Pascal Siakam led the Raptors with 25 points, seven rebounds and three assists, while Fred VanVleet followed up with 24 points, eight assists, three rebounds and two steals. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson added 16 points and 10 rebounds, off the bench. The Raptors shot 45 percent from the field, including 11-of-34 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Josh Richardson led the Sixers with 25 points and six rebounds. Ben Simmons tallied 10 points, 14 assists, nine rebounds and two steals, while Joel Embiid was held scoreless, as he shot 0-of-11 from the field. The 76ers shot 41 percent from the field, including 15-of-40 from long range. 

The 76ers (11-6) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Kings on Wednesday. The Raptors (12-4) play host to the Knicks on Wednesday.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the Chicago Bulls, 117-94, at United Center on Monday night.

The Trail Blazers (6-12) were confronted with a feisty Bulls (6-12) squad right from the opening tip, and Chicago forged a 28-27 lead after one quarter. However, Portland managed to carry an eight-point lead into halftime and then separated for good during a third quarter in which they tallied 30 points and limited their hosts to just 18. The Blazers shot an impressive 51.7 percent and won the rebounding battle by a 55-37 margin.

Carmelo Anthony led the Trail Blazers with 25 points, adding eight rebounds, two assists and one steal. C.J. McCollum supplied 21 points, four assists, three rebounds and one block. Rodney Hood supplied 16 points, six rebounds, two assists and one steal. Damian Lillard and Hassan Whiteside generated matching 13-point contributions, with Lillard also dishing out 12 assists and Whiteside pulling down 12 rebounds. Skal Labissiere had 12 points and eight rebounds off the bench.

Zach LaVine paced the Bulls with 18 points, adding five assists, one rebound, two steals and one block. Wendell Carter, Jr. posted 12 points, nine rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Tomas Satoransky and Denzel Valentine had matching 11-point tallies, with Satoransky also pulling down five rebounds and dishing out five assists and Valentine recording four boards.

The Trail Blazers head back to home to tangle with the Oklahoma City Thunder on Wednesday night, while the Bulls pay a visit to the Golden State Warriors on Wednesday evening as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the visiting Utah Jazz, 122-118, at Fiserv Forum on Monday.

There were nine ties and nine lead changes in this closely fought battle, with Milwaukee prevailing. The key was a 10-0 run to end the third quarter, as that allowed the Bucks to hold the lead for the entirety of the fourth quarter, despite Utah getting it to a two-point game with less than 10 seconds remaining. Offensive rebounding was key for Milwaukee, winning that battle, 15-4. In addition, the Bucks connected on 23-of-29 from the free-throw line while the Jazz hit 11-of-12. They won despite Utah shooting 51 percent from the field and 47 percent from three-point range. 

The Jazz (11-6) were led by Bojan Bogdanovic, who collected 24 points, three rebounds and four assists. Donovan Mitchell finished with 20 points, three assists and two steals. Timothy Bradley started for Rudy Gobert, amassing eight points, 11 rebounds and two blocks. Joe Ingles led the bench with 15 points, five rebounds and four assists. 

The Bucks (14-3) got a career performance from Giannis Antetokounmpo, who tallied 50 points, 14 rebounds, six assists and two steals. Wesley Matthews accrued 19 points, four rebounds and two assists. Eric Bledsoe generated 13 points, three rebounds and five assists. Brook Lopez had five points, six rebounds and four blocks. 

Both teams return to action on Wednesday, with Utah traveling to face the Indiana Pacers and Milwaukee remaining at home to face the Atlanta Hawks.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the host San Antonio Spurs, 114-104, at AT&T Center on Monday.

While there were six ties and eight lead changes in the first 30 minutes, Los Angeles dominated from there. In fact, the Lakers outscored the Spurs in the second half, 60-48, leading by at least five points for the final 10 minutes of play. The only major difference in the stat sheet was the assist-to-turnover differential, with Los Angeles recording 28 assists to nine turnovers while the Spurs committed 13 turnovers to 23 assists. In addition, the Lakers won the points in the paint battle, 48-28 and the fastbreak scoring differential, 12-6. 

The Lakers (15-2) were led by LeBron James, who tallied 33 points, three rebounds and 14 assists. Anthony Davis finished with 19 points, 12 rebounds, six assists, two steals and two blocks. Rajon Rondo led the bench with 13 points, five rebounds and three assists. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope dropped 14 points in an otherwise empty stat line. 

The Spurs (6-12) were led by LaMarcus Aldridge, who generated 30 points and five rebounds. DeMar DeRozan accrued 24 points, four rebounds and five assists. Bryn Forbes amassed 13 points, three rebounds and five assists while Derrick White totaled 11 points and four assists. No other player had more than six points. 

Both teams return to action on Wednesday, with Los Angeles traveling to face the New Orleans Pelicans and San Antonio playing host to the Minnesota Timberwolves.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the host Golden State Warriors, 100-97, at Chase Center on Monday.

While Golden State led for the majority of this game, Oklahoma City was able to prevail. In fact, the Warriors held the lead between the end of the first quarter until the final minute of the fourth but the Thunder finished on a 22-5 run across the final eight minutes to narrowly win. In addition, the Thunder scored the final 13 points of the game. The Thunder ended up shooting 47 percent from the field while holding the Warriors to 42 percent shooting. OKC also out-blocked Golden State, 13-7, with many of those coming in the final stretch run. 

The Thunder (6-10) were led by Dennis Schroder, who came off the bench to provide 22 points and five assists. Chris Paul led the starters with 20 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Danilo Gallinari amassed 15 points, seven rebounds and six assists while Shai Gilgeous-Alexander totaled 12 points, five rebounds and three assists. Steven Adams generated 10 points, 10 rebounds, five assists and four blocks. 

The Warriors (3-15) got career-highs from Glenn Robinson III and Ky Bowman, with Robinson accruing 25 points, two rebounds, five assists and two steals while Bowman collected 24 points, three rebounds, five assists and three steals. Eric Paschall tallied 13 points and 10 rebounds while Jordan Poole led the bench with 11 points, six rebounds and four assists. 

Both teams return to action on Wednesday, with Oklahoma City traveling to face the Portland Trail Blazers and Golden State remaining home to face the Chicago Bulls.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the Houston Rockets, 137-123, at Toyota Center on Sunday afternoon.

The Mavericks (11-5) entered this game on a four-game winning streak and led by an early MVP candidate in Luka Doncic, but they faced a tough test in Houston since the Rockets (11-6) had also been one of the best teams in the Western Conference so far. But the Mavericks didn't want surprises here and quickly jumped to a 45-29 lead in the first quarter; that would set the tone for the rest of the game. Dallas also won the second quarter 33-31 and, due to Dallas' impressive lead at the break, it seemed as if the game was all but over. Houston bounced back with a 35-27 third quarter, but Dallas closed things out with a 32-28 fourth-quarter score. Dallas was just too much for the Rockets, and fully deserved the win here. With the win, Dallas moved to 5-2 on the road while Houston fell to 6-2 at home.

Luka Doncic had another stellar performance since he finished with 41 points, 10 assists, six rebounds, two steals and one block. Kristaps Porzingis added 23 points, 13 rebounds, three assists and two steals. Tim Hardaway Jr. had 31 points, five assists, four rebounds and two steals. Dorian Finney-Smith chipped in with 12 points and 10 boards. Maxi Kleber added 11 points off the bench.

James Harden was Houston's top player once again and he finished with 32 points, 11 assists and nine rebounds. Russell Westbrook had 27 points, six assists and five rebounds. Clint Capela put up a strong double-double since he ended with 21 points and 22 rebounds, but he also added three dimes and two steals. P.J. Tucker and Danuel House Jr. each had 16 points, while the bench combined for 11 total points on 5-of-16 shooting.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the New York Knicks, 103-101, at Madison Square Garden on Sunday evening.

The Nets (8-8) got off to a strong start early, forging a 29-22 lead through one. However, the Knicks (4-13) were more competitive in the middle periods, allowing Brooklyn to only add three points to their advantage during that span. Their never-say-die attitude paid off in the final quarter, when they came within two points on multiple occasions before the visitors escaped with the narrow win. 

Spencer Dinwiddie led the Nets with 30 points and added four rebounds and four assists. Jarrett Allen generated an 18-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one assist and one steal. Taurean Prince managed 14 points, 11 rebounds and five assists. Joe Harris poured in 13 points, while Garrett Temple totaled 12 points and two steals. 

Marcus Morris paced the Knicks with 26 points while also pulling down four rebounds and recording a steal. Julius Randle totaled 15 points, eight boards and four assists. Wayne Ellington pitched in 12 points, three rebounds and two assists, while Dennis Smith, Jr. furnished 10 points, five assists, two rebounds and one steal. Taj Gibson and Frank Ntilikina had matching eight-point tallies, with Gibson also pulling down eight boards.

The Nets remain on the road and face the Cleveland Cavaliers on Monday night, while the Knicks tangle with the Toronto Raptors north of the border on Wednesday.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the host Washington Wizards, 113-106, at Capital One Arena on Sunday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, as neither team could create much separation, before the Wizards took a three-point lead into the second quarter. The Kings started the second on a 12-2 run. The Wizards rallied back to take a seven-point lead with four minutes left in the half, but the Kings closed strong to tie it up at 57 by halftime. The third quarter started out close, but the Kings pulled ahead around the halfway mark and took a five-point lead into the final frame. The Kings managed to stay ahead through the fourth quarter, pushing their lead to as many as nine, en route to their third road win of the season. 

Harrison Barnes led the Kings with 26 points on 7-of-8 shooting, in 35 minutes. Bogdan Bogdanovic added 21 points, four rebounds, four assists and a steal, while Richaun Holmes totalled 16 points and 10 rebounds. The Kings shot 48 percent from the field, including 11-of-31 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Bradley Beal led the Wizards with 20 points and eight assists, in 41 minutes. Isaiah Thomas added 17 points, while Moritz Wagner chipped in 12 points and 11 rebounds, off the bench. The Wizards shot 46 percent from the field, including 13-of-34 from long range. 

The Wizards (5-9) will look to bounce back as they take on the Nuggets in Denver on Tuesday. The Kings (7-8) take on the Celtics in Boston on Monday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Phoenix Suns, 116-104, at Pepsi Center on Sunday.

While Phoenix led by five points at the half, Denver dominated from there. In fact, they rode a 27-20 third quarter to a small lead and then put the game away with a 37-27 fourth quarter. Prior to that, there were 12 ties and five lead changes in total. The key for the Nuggets was rebounding, winning that battle, 52-36. In addition, Denver connected on 14-of-31 from three-point range while Phoenix hit just 12-of-35. 

The Suns (8-8) were led by Dario Saric, who tallied 18 points, 17 rebounds and two assists. Devin Booker finished with 12 points, one rebound and five assists. Kelly Oubre Jr accrued 10 points, three rebounds and two assists. Cheick Diallo led the bench with 22 points and six rebounds. Elie Okobo amassed 16 points, two rebounds and four assists off the pine as well.

The Nuggets (12-3) were led by Paul Millsap, tallying 23 points and five rebounds. Will Barton accumulated 22 points, eight rebounds and four assists. Nikola Jokic collected eight points, 13 rebounds, five assists and two steals while Jamal Murray totaled 22 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Mason Plumlee led the bench with 14 points, seven rebounds and two assists. 

On deck for Denver is a home matchup versus the Washington Wizards on Tuesday. As for Phoenix, they return to action on Wednesday against the Wizards as well.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 134-109, at Staples Center on Sunday.

A 40-27 first quarter really set the tone for Los Angeles in this game, leading by at least five points for the final three quarters. In addition, they held a double-digit lead for the whole of the fourth quarter. leading by 27 points at times. Free-throw shooting was the difference in the game, with the Clippers hitting 26-of-33 and the Pelicans connecting on just 10-of-18. Los Angeles also won the rebounding battle, 56-45 while outscoring the Pelicans bench, 72-46. 

The Pelicans (6-11) were led by Brandon Ingram, who tallied 24 points, eight rebounds and five assists. Jrue Holiday finished with 18 points, seven rebounds and four assists. J.J. Redick amassed 12 points, four rebounds and two assists while E'Twaun Moore led the bench with 17 points, three rebounds, one assist and one block

The Clippers (12-5) starters were led by Kawhi Leonard, who totaled 26 points, four rebounds and six assists. Paul George accumulated 18 points, five rebounds, two assists and three steals. Patrick Beverley generated 10 points, seven rebounds, four assists and two blocks while Ivica Zubac amassed five points and 10 boards. Lou Williams and Montrezl Harrell were huge off the bench, with Williams accruing 19 points, three rebounds and four assists while Harrell finished with 34 points, 12 rebounds, two assists and two blocks. 

On deck for Los Angeles is a road matchup versus Luka Doncic and the Dallas Mavericks on Tuesday. As for New Orleans, they return to action on Wednesday when they host the Los Angeles Lakers.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the Minnesota Timberwolves, 100-98, at Target Center on Saturday afternoon.

The Suns (8-7) opened the game strong, building a 30-23 lead through 12 minutes and holding that same seven-point edge at halftime. Phoenix even managed to coax that advantage up another two points during the third, but a strong showing by the Timberwolves (8-8) in the final period brought them to 100-98 after a Karl-Anthony Towns' three-pointer with 2.2 seconds remaining. Minnesota was unable to get its hands on the ball again after that point, however, sending the Suns to a hard-fought road victory.

Devin Booker led the way for the Suns with 35 points, adding 12 rebounds, nine assists and one block. Kelly Oubre, Jr. furnished a 25-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included four steals and one assist. Frank Kaminsky provided nine points, five rebounds, three assists and one block. Dario Saric and Tyler Johnson turned in seven points apiece while pulling down five and four rebounds, respectively. 

Towns finished with 31 points, 17 rebounds, four assists and one block. Kelly Bates-Diop managed 22 points, four boards and two assists. Andrew Wiggins poured in 21 points and added four rebounds, three assists and three blocks. Jarrett Culver finished with 11 points, five boards, three assists and two blocks.

The Suns remain on the road and pay a visit to the Denver Nuggets on Sunday night, while the Timberwolves pay a visit to the Atlanta Hawks on Monday night.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 116-115, at Spectrum Center on Saturday night.

The Bulls (6-11) started the game off hot, forging an 11-point lead after one quarter. However, their advantage was whittled down to seven by halftime, and the Hornets (6-11) eliminated their deficit altogether in the third to head into the final period with a five-point advantage. That's when one of the wilder fourth quarters of the season thus far ensued, with each squad scoring over 40 points. Ultimately, Chicago managed the unlikely feat of six points over the final eight seconds courtesy of a pair of three-pointers from Tomas Satoransky and Zach LaVine to escape with the one-point road win.

LaVine led the way for the Bulls with a season-high 49 points, complementing them with four rebounds and one steal. Coby White followed LaVine with 28 points, adding three assists, two rebounds and two steals. Wendell Carter, Jr. produced 17 points, 11 rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks.  Satoransky furnished 10 points, eight assists, three rebounds, three steals and one block. 

Terry Rozier paced the Hornets with 28 points, supplementing them with five assists, one rebound and one steal. Marvin Williams registered 21 points and five rebounds off the bench. Devonte' Graham tallied 18 points, 10 assists and two rebounds. Cody Zeller delivered 14 points, nine boards, two assists and one block. Bismack Biyombo posted an 11-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included one assist, two blocks and one steal. Miles Bridges matched Biyombo's scoring tally and also pulled down eight rebounds. 

The Bulls return home to tangle with the Portland Trail Blazers on Monday night, while the Hornets head south to face the Miami Heat on Monday night as well.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the visiting Orlando Magic, 111-106, at Banker's Life Fieldhouse on Saturday. 

While Orlando had to play this game without Aaron Gordon and Nikola Vucevic, this game stayed close throughout. In fact, there were 10 ties and 11 lead changes in total, with the game staying within a single-digit margin for the final 20 minutes. Indiana did all of their damage in the second and fourth quarters, outscoring Orlando, 59-41. The Pacers ended up shooting 54 percent from the field and 42 percent from three-point range while out-rebounding the Magic, 42-33. 

The Magic (6-9) were led by Evan Fournier, who tallied 26 points and four assists. Jonathan Isaac amassed 25 points, nine rebounds, four steals and two blocks on 10-of-16 from the field. Markelle Fultz accrued 13 points, two rebounds and nine assists. D.J. Augustin totaled 11 points and four assists to lead the bench. 

The Pacers (9-6) were led by Domantas Sabonis, who accumulated 25 points, nine rebounds and four assists. Jeremy Lamb generated 14 points and five boards in his return from injury. Aaron Holiday finished with 13 points, four rebounds and four assists while Myles Turner accrued 10 points, five rebounds, two assists and three blocks. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Indiana playing host to the Memphis Grizzlies and Orlando traveling to face the Detroit Pistons.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the host Atlanta Hawks, 119-116, at State Farm Arena on Saturday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, as the Hawks took a one-point lead after one quarter.  The Hawks took the momentum in the second, as they outscored the visitors 34-26 in the quarter, to take a nine-point lead by halftime. The Raptors came out with a purpose in the third quarter and outscored the hosts by six, to cut it to a three-point game heading into the fourth. The Raptors carried the momentum into the fourth and managed to hold off the feisty Hawks, who took the game right down to the wire. This marks the third straight win for the Raptors and the sixth consecutive loss for the Hawks. 

Pascal Siakam led Toronto with 34 points, five rebounds, four assists, two blocks and one steal, in 40 minutes. Fred VanVleet followed up with 25 points and eight assists, while Norman Powell tallied 20 points on 8-of-15 shooting. The Raptors shot 46 percent from the field, including 13-of-37 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Trae Young led the Hawks with 30 points, 10 rebounds and 10 assists, in 41 minutes of action. DeAndre Hunter followed up with 26 points on 10-of-18 shooting, while Jabari Parker added 13 points, seven rebounds and five assists. The Hawks shot 52 percent from the field, including 14-of-34 from long range. 

The Hawks (4-12) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Timberwolves on Monday. The Raptors (11-4) play host to the 76ers on Monday.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the host New York Knicks, 111-104, at Madison Square Garden on Saturday evening.  

The Spurs got out to a great start on the road, as they took a 32-16 lead after one quarter. They kept the pressure on in the second, where they outscored the hosts by nine, to take a 68-43 lead into halftime. The Knicks came out stronger in the third and managed to trim the deficit to 18 points, entering the final frame. The Knicks kept fighting and outscored the visitors by 11 in the fourth, but it was too little, too late, as the Spurs held on for a much-needed win. The win marks the end of a eight-game slide for San Antonio, while it marks the second straight loss for the Knicks. 

LaMarcus Aldridge led the Spurs with 23 points, six rebounds, three assists and three steals, in 34 minutes. DeMar DeRozan followed up with 21 points, nine rebounds and four assists, while Patty Mills chipped in 17 points off the bench. The Spurs shot 53 percent from the field, including 12-of-23 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Marcus Morris led the Knicks with 20 points and seven rebounds, in 29 minutes. Bobby Portis added 16 points on 6-of-11 shooting off the bench, while Julius Randle totalled 14 points, eight rebounds and three assists. The Knicks shot 43 percent from the field, including 15-of 40 from long range. 

The Knicks (4-12) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nets on Sunday. The Spurs (6-11) play host to the Lakers on Monday.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Miami Heat, 113-86, at Wells Fargo Arena on Saturday night.

After a blazing hot start to the season that virtually no one outside their locker room likely saw coming, perhaps the Heat (11-4) was due for a clunker. Miami managed just 13 points in the first quarter while allowing the 76ers (11-5) to tally 28, setting the stage for what turned out to be a lopsided loss. The visitors did play much more competitively the rest of the way, but they had no answer for Philadelphia, which shot 50.6 percent, including 48.3 percent from three-point range.

Tyler Herro led the Heat with 20 points, adding two rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Goran Dragic followed with 18 points, three rebounds and one assist. Bam Adebayo delivered 12 points and five boards. Jimmy Butler totaled 11 points, five rebounds, three assists and two steals in his Philadelphia return. Chris Silva managed 10 points, six boards, three assists, one steal and one block.

Josh Richardson paced the 76ers with 32 points, complementing them with four assists, one rebound and one steal. Joel Embiid generated a 23-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included two assists, two steals and two blocks. Tobias Harris managed 19 points, eight boards, two assists and two steals. Al Horford provided 16 points, six rebounds and three assists.

The Heat returns home to face the Charlotte Hornets on Monday night, while the 76ers travel to face the Toronto Raptors on Monday night as well.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the visiting Portland Trail Blazers, 110-104, at Rocket Mortgage FieldHouse on Saturday evening.  

The contest got out to a slow start, as the score was toed at 19, after one quarter. The Cavs rallied ahead in the second, where they outscored the visitors by seven, to take a 49-42 lead into halftime. The Trail Blazers came out stronger in the third, but the Cavs played them to a stand still through the quarter, to maintain their seven-point lead heading into the final frame. The Trail Blazers kept up the fight through the fourth, but the Cavs did enough to stay on top and walk away with the home win. The win ends a six-game slide for the Cavs, while it marks the fourth straight loss for the Trail Blazers. 

Jordan Clarkson led the Cavs with 28 points on 6-of-9 shooting, in 31 minutes off the bench. Tristan Thompson followed up with 25 points, nine rebounds, two assists and two steals, while Collin Sexton chipped in 19 points on 7-of-14 shooting. The Cavs shot 43 percent from the field, including 10-of-31 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Damian Lillard led the Trail Blazers with 23 points, eight rebounds and eight assists, in 36 minutes. C.J. McCollum added 20 points, six rebounds and five assists, while Carmelo Anthony, Anfernee Simons and Rodney Hood chipped in 11 points each. The Blazers shot 45 percent fro, the field, including 14-of-40 from long range. 

The Trail Blazers (5-12) will look to bounce back as they take on the Bulls in Chicago on Monday. The Cavs (5-11) play host to the Nets on Monday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Memphis Grizzlies, 109-108, at FedEx Forum on Saturday.

While Memphis led for the entirety of the first half, Los Angeles was able to prevail with a victory. In fact, the Lakers rode a 30-21 third quarter to recapture the lead and that started their comeback. With that said, the Lakers trailed 105-100 with 3:24 remaining but went on a 9-0 run from there and never relinquished the lead. Free-throw shooting was key, with Los Angeles hitting 20-of-29 and Memphis connecting on just 8-of-13. Rim protection was also critical, with the Lakers out-blocking the Grizzlies, 7-3. 

The Lakers (14-2) were led by LeBron James, who tallied 30 points, six rebounds, four assists and two steals. Anthony Davis collected 22 points, four rebounds, three assists, three steals and five blocks. Rajon Rondo led the bench with 14 points, five rebounds and six assists while Dwight Howard amassed 10 points and nine boards.

The Grizzlies (5-10) were led by Ja Morant, who accrued 26 points, three rebounds, six assists and five steals. Jaren Jackson Jr finished with 20 points, seven rebounds and two steals. Jae Crowder accumulated 21 points, six rebounds and three assists. Kyle Anderson led the bench with 11 points, six rebounds and four assists. 

Both teams play again on Monday, with Memphis traveling to face the Indiana Pacers and Los Angeles playing the San Antonio Spurs on the road.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 104-90, at Fiserv Forum on Saturday. 

While no quarter was decided by more than six points, Milwaukee won all four of them en route to their wire-to-wire victory, In fact, that allowed the Bucks to hold a double-digit lead for the final 10 minutes of play. The key for Milwaukee was their defense, holding Detroit to 41 percent from the field and 29 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Bucks outrebounded the Pistons, 49-40, while out-blocking them 8-3. The two teams combined for just 15 made free-throws, which is the lowest combined total of the season. 

The Pistons (5-11) played this game without Blake Griffin, as Derrick Rose led the way with 20 points, three rebounds and six assists off the bench. Luke Kennard led the starters with 13 points, two rebounds and one assist. Andre Drummond finished with 12 points, 17 rebounds, four assists and two steals. Markieff Morris totaled 11 points and six boards.

The Bucks (13-3) were led by Giannis Antetokounmpo, who tallied 28 points, 10 rebounds, three assists and two steals. Wesley Matthews amassed 13 points and three assists. Eric Bledsoe accumulated 11 points, four rebounds, five assists and two steals while George Hill led the bench with nine points, two rebounds and three assists. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Detroit playing host to the Orlando Magic and Milwaukee remaining at Fiserv Forum to face the Utah Jazz.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 128-120, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Saturday.

A 44-31 first quarter really gave Utah plenty of momentum and then a 30-23 second quarter put the game to bed. In fact, the Jazz won this game in wire-to-wire fashion. With that said, the Pelicans outscored the Jazz, 66-54, in the second half to make the final scoreline respectable. The Jazz ended up winning the defensive rebounding battle, 42-29 while out-assisting the Pelicans, 29-21. In addition, Utah shot 51 percent from the field and 42 percent from three-point range while holding New Orleans to 42 percent from the field. 

The Pelicans (6-10) were led by Brandon Ingram, who tallied 33 points, four rebounds and five assists. Jrue Holiday generated 28 points, five rebounds, four assists, four steals and two blocks. J.J Redick amassed 20 points, seven rebounds, four assists and two steals. Lonzo Ball led the bench with 13 points, four rebounds and four assists. 

The Jazz (11-5) were led by Donovan Mitchell, who accumulated 37 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Bojan Bogdanovic finished with 28 points, five rebounds and five assists. Timothy Bradley started for Rudy Gobert and totaled 14 points and nine boards. Mike Conley accrued 11 points, four rebounds and five assists while Jeff Green led the bench with 15 points, four rebounds and three assists. 

New Orleans has to play again on Sunday, staying on the road to face the Los Angeles Clippers. As for Utah, they travel to face the Milwaukee Bucks on Monday for their next fixture,

The Detroit Pistons defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 128-103, at Little Caesars Arena on Friday night.

The Pistons (5-10) came into the contest looking to snap a five-game losing streak, and they seemed intent on doing so right from the opening tip. Detroit managed to establish a 10-point lead through the first 12 minutes, and courtesy of a 43-point second period, they owned a 19-point edge over the Hawks (4-11) by halftime. That was all the home squad would need to cruise to a comfortable home win that served as their largest of the season overall. 

DeAndre' Bembry paced the Hawks with 22 points, adding six assists, four rebounds and four steals. De'Andre Hunter followed with 18 points, complementing them with four assists, two rebounds and a block. Jabari Parker furnished 14 points, four rebounds, three assists and one steal. Damian Jones delivered 13 points, four boards and one assist. Alex Len led the bench with 12 points.

Blake Griffin led the Pistons with 24 points and added three rebounds, three assists and one block. Andre Drummond generated a 23-point, 15-rebound double-double that also included two assists, two steals and a block. Bruce Brown managed 14 points, seven assists, four rebounds, three steals and one block. Markieff Morris furnished 13 points and three boards, Langston Galloway poured in 12 points, while Christian Wood and Derrick Rose turned in matching 11-point tallies, with Wood also pulling down six boards. 

The Hawks head back home to face the Toronto Raptors on Saturday night, while the Pistons hit the road and tangle with the Milwaukee Bucks on Saturday evening as well.

The Washington Wizards defeated the visiting Charlotte Hornets, 125-118, at Capital One Arena on Friday evening. 

The contest got out to a tight start, with multiple lead changes through the first quarter and the Hornets taking a one-point lead into the second. The Hornets pulled ahead early in the second but the Wizards stayed close and tied it at 62, with two minutes left in the half. The Hornets closed the half on a 6-0 run to take a 68-62 lead into halftime. The teams played to a standstill through the third, with the Hornets taking a six-point lead into the fourth. The Hornets jumped out to a 13-point lead to start the fourth, but the Wizards rallied all the way back to take a two-point lead with three minutes left in the contest. They made no mistake and closed out the game on a 9-4 run, for their second straight win. This marks the third straight loss for the Hornets.

Bradley Beal led the Wizards with 30 points, 12 assists and five rebounds, in 42 minutes. Thomas Bryant followed up with 21 points and 11 rebounds, while Davis Bertans added 20 points, eight rebounds and four assists. The Wizards shot 53 percent from the field, including 14-of-34 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Miles Bridges led the Hornets with 31 points and eight rebounds, in 35 minutes. Devonte' Graham, Terry Rozier and Malik Monk added 19 points each. The Hornets shot 52 percent from the field, including 14-of-34 from deep. 

The Hornets (6-10) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Bulls on Saturday. The Wizards (5-8) play host to the Kings on Sunday.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Sacramento Kings, 116-97, at Barclays Center on Friday night.

The Nets (7-8) and Kings (6-8) played a highly competitive first half that culminated in a 56-49 lead for Brooklyn. A big third quarter for the home squad allowed them to add nine points to their advantage heading into the fourth quarter, which enabled a comfortable home win. The Nets held Sacramento to 15.4 percent shooting from three-point range and won the battle of the boards by a 48-33 margin.

Harrison Barnes led the Kings with 18 points, adding five rebounds. Buddy Hield provided 16 points, five assists and one rebound. Justin James managed 14 points, three rebounds, three assists and one steal. Nemanja Bjelica registered 13 points, seven boards, two assists and one steal. Richaun Holmes contributed 12 points, eight rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. 

Spencer Dinwiddie paced the Nets with 23 points, complementing them with seven assists, one rebound and two steals. Joe Harris poured in 22 points and also pitched in four boards, two blocks and one assist. Garrett Temple posted 18 points, four assists, three rebounds and two steals. Jarrett Allen had a near double-double with 11 points, nine rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Dzanan Musa filled out the stat sheet with 10 points, six rebounds, one assist and one steal. 

The Kings remain on their East Coast swing and tangle with the Washington Wizards on Sunday evening, while the Nets make the short trip to face the New York Knicks on Sunday evening as well.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 115-104, at Wells Fargo Center on Friday.

This marks San Antonio's eighth-straight loss, which is the longest such streak for this team since the '90s. A 29-22 first quarter really set the tone for Philadelphia, with the Sixers holding the lead for the final three quarters. That allowed Philly to win or tie all four individual quarters. Rebounding was key for Philly, winning the offensive rebounding battle, 13-3, and the defensive rebounding differential, 38-29. In addition, the Sixers shot 53 percent from the field while out-assisting the Spurs, 32-21. 

The Spurs (5-11) were led by DeMar DeRozan, who tallied 29 points, seven rebounds and two assists. LaMarcus Aldridge amassed 17 points, six rebounds and two assists. Dejounte Murray accrued nine points, two rebounds, four assists and four steals while Rudy Gay led the bench with 22 points and four boards. 

The Sixers (10-5) were led by Tobias Harris, who generated 26 points, six rebounds, four assists and two blocks. Joel Embiid accumulated 21 points, 14 rebounds and three assists. Ben Simmons recorded a triple-double, collecting 10 points, 10 rebounds, 13 assists and two steals. Furknan Korkmaz dropped 17 points in a rare start. 

Both teams have to play again on Saturday, with San Antonio staying on the road to face the New York Knicks and Philadelphia remaining home to face the Miami Heat.

The Miami Heat defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 116-108, at United Center on Friday evening. 

The Heat got out to got out to a great start on the road, as they took a 34-16 lead after one quarter. They kept the pressure on in the second and pushed their lead to 26, late in the quarter, before taking a 67-43 lead into halftime. The Bulls came out stronger in the third quarter and chipped away at the deficit, to make it an 18-point game heading into the fourth. The Bulls kept fighting and cut it to an eight-point game in the fourth, as they outscored the Heat 41-31 in the quarter, but the Heat maintained the advantage to secure their fifth consecutive win. 

Jimmy Butler led the Heat with 27 points, seven assists and four rebounds, in 34 minutes of action. Kendrick Nunn followed up with 21 points, while Bam Adebayo totalled 16 points, 14 rebounds, six assists, three steals and a block. The Heat shot 49 percent from the field, including 14-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, five players scored in double digits for the Bulls, led by Zach LaVine who finished with 15 points on 6-of-14 shooting. Coby White and Thaddeus Young tallied 12 points each, while Shaquille Harrison and Ryan Arcidiacono added 10 points each. The Bulls shot 45 percent from the field, including 10-of-30 from long range. 

The Bulls (5-11) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Saturday. The Heat (11-3) take on the 76ers in Philadelphia on Saturday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder, 130-127, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Friday night. 

The Lakers (13-2) got quite the fight from the Thunder (5-10), with OKC holding a 67-66 halftime lead and Los Angeles needing a pair of Anthony Davis free throws with 3.8 seconds remaining and a subsequent steal by LeBron James of a Danilo Gallinari inbounds heave to clinch the win. The game featured a shooting clinic by both squads, with each eclipsing the 50.0 percent mark.

Davis led the way with a 33-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included seven assists and one steal. James followed with a 23-point, 14-rebound double-double that also included six rebounds, one steal and one block. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope provided 17 points, five boards, two assists and one steal. Dwight Howard and Kyle Kuzma generated matching 10-point tallies, with Howard also pulling down seven rebounds.

Shai Gilgeous-Alexander paced the Thunder with 24 points, adding seven rebounds, four assists, one steal and one block. Steven Adams totaled 22 points, six rebounds and four assists. Chris Paul compiled 18 points, seven assists, four boards and one steal. Gallinari managed 15 points, four rebounds, three assists and one steal. Dennis Schroder tallied 13 points, four assists and three boards. Terrance Ferguson supplied 11 points, three assists and two rebounds. 

The Lakers remain on the road and take on the Memphis Grizzlies on Saturday night, while the Thunder will visit the Golden State Warriors on Monday night.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Cleveland Cavaliers, 143-101, at American Airlines Center on Friday.

It's rare to see a team win all four individual quarters in the NBA but that's what Dallas did here. In fact, they rode a 37-16 second quarter to a monster lead and put the game to bed with a 45-29 third quarter. The Mavericks actually led by at least 30 points for the whole of the fourth quarter. The key for Dallas was their offense, shooting 58 percent from the field and 54 percent from three-point range while recording 31 assists. The Mavericks also out-rebounded the Cavaliers, 49-34, while winning the turnover battle, 10-5. 

The Cavaliers (4-11) were led by Darius Garland, who tallied 23 points, and four assists. Cedi Osman accumulated 18 points, four rebounds and three assists. Collin Sexton generated 14 points, two rebounds and five assists while Tristan Thompson totaled 10 points, eight rebounds and four assists. Kevin Love finished with just eight points and seven boards. 

The Mavericks (10-5) were led by Luka Doncic, who tallied 30 points, seven rebounds and 14 assists. Kristaps Porzingis accrued 17 points, seven rebounds and four blocks. Tim Hardaway Jr amassed 16 points and four assists. Justin Jackson led the bench with 19 points and six rebounds while J.J. Barea dropped 12 points. 

Cleveland will play again on Saturday, welcoming the Portland Trail Blazers to Ohio. As for Dallas, they travel to face the Houston Rockets on Sunday for their next fixture.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Boston Celtics, 96-92, at Pepsi Center on Friday.

While Denver got out to a 27-13 lead after the first quarter, this game wasn't decided until the final seconds. In fact, Boston rode a 35-26 fourth quarter to make it a one-point game with less than three minutes remaining. With that said, they could never recapture the lead after that first quarter, with Denver winning in wire-to-wire fashion. The Nuggets held the Sixers to 41 percent from the field and 26 percent from three-point range. In addition, Denver won the offensive rebounding battle, 11-5. 

The Celtics (11-4) were led by Jaylen Brown, who amassed 22 points, 10 rebounds and four assists. Jayson Tatum totaled 16 points, two rebounds and three assists. Marcus Smart accrued 15 points, six rebounds, three assists and two steals. Kemba Walker was carted off in the third quarter because of a head/neck injury. 

The Nuggets (11-3) got a triple-double from Nikola Jokic, who collected 18 points, 16 rebounds, 10 assists and three steals. Jamal Murray led the team in scoring, accumulating 22 points, six rebounds and five assists. Will Barton generated 15 points and five assists while Paul Millsap tallied 14 points, 10 rebounds, two assists and two blocks. 

On deck for Denver is another home game against the Phoenix Suns on Sunday. As for Boston, they return to action on Monday against the Sacramento Kings.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting Golden State Warriors, 113-109, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Friday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, as the Jazz led by seven halfway through the first, before the Warriors rallied back to make it a two-point game by the end of the quarter. The Jazz pulled ahead in the second, outscoring the Warriors by 12 in the quarter, to take a 65-51 lead at halftime. The Jazz kept their focus in the third and pushed their lead to 18, entering the final frame. They pushed the lead to 21, early in the fourth, but the Warriors kept up the fight and cut it to a five-point game with two minutes to go. Despite getting outscored by 14 points in the fourth quarter, the Jazz managed to hang on for their second win in a row. 

Donovan Mitchell led the Jazz with 30 points, four rebounds, four assists and a steal, in 35 minutes. Mike Conley added 27 points, four rebounds, four assists and a steal, while Bojan Bogdanovic tallied 17 points, five rebounds, three assists and a steal. The Jazz shot 51 percent from the field, including 44 percent from deep. 

Meanwhile, seven players scored in double digits for the Warriors, led by Alec Burks, who finished with 20 points on 7-of-18 shooting. Glenn Robinson III and Ky Bowman added 17 points each. The Warriors shot 46 percent from the field, including 12-of-28 from long range. 

The Warriors (3-14) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Thunder on Monday. The Jazz (10-5) play host to the Pelicans on Saturday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting Houston Rockets, 122-119, at Staples Center on Friday. 

While Los Angeles held the lead for the entirety of the first half, this game came down to the final shot. In fact, the Rockets started the second half on a 19-4 run, which allowed eight lead changes and seven ties over the final 24 minutes of action. Kawhi Leonard was the hero, hitting a game-winning 17-footer to take the lead with 15 seconds left. Russell Westbrook missed a three on the prior possession to take the lead and James Harden has a turnover with 1.2 seconds left that capped off the win for Los Angeles. The key for the Clippers was their bench, outscoring the Rockets bench, 58-21. In addition, Los Angeles shot 52 percent from the field and 39 percent from three-point range while holding Houston to 46 percent from the field and 35 percent from long range. The Clippers also out-assisted the Rockets, 27-22.

The Rockets (11-4) were led by James Harden, who tallied 37 points, eight rebounds, 12 assists and two steals. Russell Westbrook collected 22 points, five rebounds, six assists and two steals. Clint Capela accrued 17 points, 19 rebounds and two blocks. Ben McLemore generated 14 points, two rebounds and two steals. 

The Clippers (10-5) were led by Lou Williams, who scored all 26 of his points in the second half, adding three rebounds and eight assists to his tally. Kawhi Leonard led the starters with 24 points, six rebounds, three assists and three steals. Paul George accumulated 19 points, eight rebounds, seven assists and two steals. 

On deck for Los Angeles is a matchup with the New Orleans Pelicans on Sunday. As for Houston, they also return to action on Sunday against the Dallas Mavericks.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 137-129, at Fiserv Forum on Thursday.

The Bucks had the best record in The Association in the 2018-19 season, and now Milwaukee are 12-3 in the current campaign while going 4-1 at home. Meanwhile, the Blazers struggled once again and looked outmatched on route towards complicating their record to 5-11. The Bucks quickly jumped to a solid 10-point lead and they would never look back afterwards. The second quarter ended 35-31, so they had a 14-point advantage heading into the final 24 minutes of action. Even though Portland won the remaining two quarters, 40-35 and 31-30, respectively, Milwaukee had created an extremely big cushion and ended winning with relative ease.

Giannis Antetokounmpo was Milwaukee's best player in this game since he finished with an impressive triple-double of 24 points, 19 rebounds and 15 assists. Eric Bledsoe was the Bucks' highest scorer since he finished with 30 points, as well as six assists and four boards. Every single starter for the Bucks scored 10 or more points. Brook Lopez had 10 points, Wesley Matthews had 12 points and Donte DiVincenzo ended with 16 points and six boards. Pat Connaughton had 18 off the bench.

C.J. McCollum was Portland's biggest threat since he ended with 37 points, 10 assists and six rebounds. Skal Labissiere had one of his best performances of his NBA career since he contributed 22 points in 28 minutes off the bench. Carmelo Anthony thrived and finished with 18 points despite his 6-15 shooting from the field.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 124-121, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Thursday.

This game was full of swings, as a 28-12 run to start the second half gave the Pelicans their victory. In fact, New Orleans connected on 13 of their first 14 shots to start that second half. Prior to that, there were eight ties and 11 lead changes in this game, with neither team leading by more than 12 points. New Orleans ended up shooting 53 percent from the field and 46 percent from three-point range while recording 28 assists. In addition, they doubled up the Suns in blocks, 6-3, while winning the turnover battle, 17-14. 

The Pelicans (6-9) were led by Brandon Ingram, who overcame a 1-of-7 first half to finish with 28 points, eight rebounds, five assists and two blocks. J.J. Redick amassed 26 points, five rebounds and two assists. Jrue Holiday collected 23 points, four rebounds, nine assists and three steals. E'Twaun Moore led the bench with 19 points, five rebounds and two assists. 

The Suns (7-7) were led by Kelly Oubre Jr, who tallied 25 points, six rebounds and four assists. Devin Booker totaled 19 points, five rebounds and seven assists. Frank Kaminsky accrued 14 points and five rebounds. Tyler Johnson accumulated six points, five rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks. Mikal Bridges, Cameron Johnson and Elie Okobo all reached double figures in scoring off the bench.

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Phoenix traveling to face the Minnesota Timberwolves and New Orleans playing the Utah Jazz on the road as well.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the visiting New York Knicks, 109-104, at Wells Fargo Center on Wednesday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, with the Sixers holding a two-point lead heading into the second. The 76ers pushed their lead to five early in the second, but the Knicks responded and pulled ahead, before the 76ers reclaimed their two-point advantage by halftime. The Knicks came out strong in the third quarter and built a 17-point lead late in the quarter, but the Sixers closed the quarter on a 14-2 run, to bring it back to five-point game by the start of the fourth. The Knicks held the edge for the first half of the fourth, but 76ers took control down the stretch, to secure their second straight win. 

Joel Embiid led the 76ers with 23 points, 12 rebounds, five assists and two blocks, in 34 minutes. Ben Simmons followed up with 18 points, 12 assists and eight rebounds, while Tobias Harris added 14 points, five rebounds and four assists. The 76ers shot 44 percent from the field, including 13-of-32 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Marcus Morris led the Knicks with 22 points, 13 rebounds and six assists, in 40 minutes. Julius Randle and Frank Ntilikina added 17 points, while Dennis Smith Jr. chipped in 13 points off the bench. The Knicks shot 48 percent from the field, including 13-of-25 from deep. 

The Knicks (4-11) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Spurs on Saturday. The 76ers (9-5) play host to the Spurs on Friday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the San Antonio Spurs, 138-132, at Verizon Center on Wednesday. 

The Wizards (4-8) didn't enter this game on a good run of form, but Washington managed to secure a positive result against a struggling Spurs (5-9) team that now has seven straight losses for the first time before the Tim Duncan era. This game was extremely tight, though. The Spurs jumped to a 38-35 lead in the first quarter, and they extended their lead to six points at the break thanks to a 31-28 second quarter. However, the Wizards turned things around after half time. A 38-29 third quarter put the Wizards up by three entering the final 12 minutes of action, and a 37-34 fourth quarter sealed the deal for the Wizards. With the win, Washington moved to 2-3 at home while the Spurs are now 1-6 on the road.

Bradley Beal was Washington's best player since he finished with 33 points, four rebounds and four assists. Ish Smith and Davis Bertans both thrived off the bench after finishing with 21 points each; Bertans added five rebounds and four dimes, while Smith grabbed four boards and delivered four dimes as well. Rookie Rui Hachimura had 15 points, seven rebounds and two assists. Thomas Bryant and Isaiah Thomas had 11 points each.

The eight Spurs players that scored netted 10 or more points. The scoring leader was DeMar DeRozan, who finished with 31 points, five assists and four rebounds. Patty Mills had 16 points and six assists, while LaMarcus Aldridge ended with a double-double of 12 points and 10 rebounds, while also adding five assists. Rudy Gay (18 points) and Dejounte Murray (15 points, five boards) thrived off the bench as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Atlanta Hawks, 135-127, at Philip's Arena on Wednesday.

A 34-26 first quarter really set the tone in this game, with Milwaukee winning by eight points. In fact, a 38-22 third quarter allowed the Bucks to lead by at least seven points for the entirety of the fourth quarter. With that said, the Bucks led by 19 with less than four minutes remaining and the Hawks made it look closer than it actually was with a late run. The Bucks dominated the rim, winning the defensive rebounding battle, 38-34, while out-blocking the Hawks, 8-2. In addition, Milwaukee shot 53 percent from the field while holding Atlanta to 46 percent shooting. Milwaukee also won the points off turnovers differential, 25-16. 

The Bucks (11-3) were led by Giannis Antetokounmpo, who tallied 33 points, 11 rebounds and four assists on 12-of-17 from the field. Eric Bledsoe accrued 28 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Brook Lopez amassed 12 points, five rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Donte DiVincenzo got a start and generated 11 points, five rebounds, three assists and two steals. 

The Hawks (4-10) got a career performance from DeAndre Hunter, who accumulated 27 points, 11 rebounds and two assists. Trae Young totaled 25 points, two rebounds, eight assists and three steals. Cam Reddish provided 17 points and three boards while Jabari Parker finished with 14 points, three rebounds, three assists and two steals. 

On deck for Atlanta is a road matchup versus the Detroit Pistons on Friday. As for Milwaukee, they return to action on Saturday, playing host to the Pistons as well.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 101-91, at Barclays Center on Wednesday night.

The Nets (6-8) came into the contest knowing they'd have to play another game without the services of Kyrie Irving, who remained out with a shoulder injury. However, with a capable replacement in Spencer Dinwiddie, Brooklyn came out firing and matched the Hornets (6-9) basket for basket in the first quarter. They then separated from Charlotte just a bit to forge a five-point lead going into halftime, and they added another four points to that edge heading into the final 12 minutes. Although the visitors would get as close as 86-83 with 6:28 remaining, the Nets would finish them off with a 15-8 run to close out the contest.

Terry Rozier paced the Hornets with 18 points, adding six rebounds and two assists. Devonte' Graham followed with 17 points, six assists, three rebounds and one block. Malik Monk led the second unit with 13 points and added three rebounds, one assist and two steals. Miles Bridges registered 12 points, five five rebounds, two steals and one block. Bismack Biyombo contributed 10 points, seven rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block.

Jarrett Allen led the Nets with a 22-point, 17-rebound double-double that also included two steals and one block. Spencer Dinwiddie and Taurean Prince delivered matching 20-point tallies while recording eight assists and eight rebounds, respectively. DeAndre Jordan managed 14 points and seven boards off the bench. 

The Hornets remain on the road and next face the Washington Wizards on Friday night, while the Nets remain home to tangle with the Sacramento Kings on Friday night as well.

The Miami Heat defeated the visiting Cleveland Cavaliers, 124-100, at Americans Airlines Arena on Wednesday evening. 

The Heat got out to a great start at home with a 32-22 lead after one quarter. They turned it up a notch in the second, as they outscored the Cavs by 17 in the quarter, to take a 27-point lead into halftime. The Cavaliers put up a better fight in the third, but could only trim the deficit by five, heading into the fourth. The Heat maintained control through the fourth and cruised to their fourth straight win. This marks the fifth straight loss for the Cavaliers. 

Duncan Robinson led the Heat with 29 points on 9-of-15 shooting, in 34 minutes. Tyler Herro added 22 points, while Jimmy Butler finished with 21 points, six rebounds and five assists. Four other players scored in double digits for Miami. The Heat shot 53 percent from the field, including 19-of-37 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Kevin Love led the Cavs with 25 points and 13 rebounds, in 33 minutes. Collin Sexton followed up with 19 points on 8-of-16 shooting, while Larry Nance Jr. added 16 points and nine rebounds. Jordan Clarkson chipped in 12 points, in 17 minutes off the bench. The Cavs shot 43 percent from the field, including 12-of-38 from long range. 

The Cavs (4-10) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Mavericks on Friday. The Heat (10-3) take on the Bulls in Chicago on Friday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Orlando Magic, 113-97, at Scotiabank Arena on Wednesday night.

The two squads engaged in a highly competitive first quarter, matching each other bucket for bucket on the way to a 32-32 deadlock. However, taking advantage of ankle injuries that forced the early exits of both Nikola Vucevic and Aaron Gordon for the Magic (6-8), the Raptors (10-4) built a 10-point lead going into halftime. Each team then stymied each other in a third quarter during which only 35 combined points were scored, but the Raptors pulled away for good in the final  period for the home win. 

Evan Fournier led the way for the Magic with 21 points, adding three assists, two rebounds and three steals. Jonathan Isaac supplied a 16-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included three assists, three blocks and one steal. Terrance Ross led the bench with 14 points. Markelle Fultz and Khem Birch provided matching 12-point tallies while recording four assists and four rebounds, respectively. 

Fred VanVleet paced the Raptors with 24 points and complemented them with seven assists, one rebound and two steals. Terence Davis came off the bench to offer 19 points, eight boards, five assists and one block. Pascal Siakam posted an 18-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included four assists, one steal and one block. Norman Powell mustered 15 points, while Chris Boucher turned in a 14-point, 11-rebound double-double, along with an assist and a block.

The Magic remain on the road and pay a visit to the Indiana Pacers on Saturday night, while the Raptors travel to face the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday night as well.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Golden State Warriors, 142-94, at American Airlines Center on Wednesday evening. 

The Mavs got out to a rocking start right from the jump and took a 44-16 lead, after one quarter. They kept their foot on the gas and outscored the visitors by eight point in the second, to build a 36-point lead by halftime. The Mavs showed no mercy, as they came out focused in the third and expanded their lead by four more points, heading into the final frame. The Mavs continued to dominate in the fourth and poured in 38 points in the quarter to conclude a very impressive home win. This marks the third straight win for Dallas. 

Luka Doncic led the Mavs with 35 points, 11 assists, 10 rebounds and three steals, in just 26 minutes. Kristaps Porzingis added 14 points, 10 rebounds, three blocks and two assists, while Tim Hardaway Jr. chipped in 20 points on 6-of-7 shooting. The Mavs shot 57 percent from the field, including 22-of-38 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Eric Paschall led the Warriors with 22 points and seven rebounds, in 40 minutes. Ky Bowman added 16 points on 7-of-10 shooting.  Alec Burks, Jordan Poole, Omari Spellman and Marquese Chriss tallied 11 points each. The Warriors shot 39 percent from the field, including 8-of-27 from long range. 

The Warriors (3-13) will look to bounce back as they take on the Jazz in Utah on Friday. The Mavs (9-5) play host to the Cavaliers on Friday.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Detroit Pistons, 109-89, at United Center on Wednesday night.

The two teams came out matching each other bucket for bucket, resulting in a 30-30 tie at the end of one quarter. The Bulls (5-10) managed to forge a slim four-point lead head into halftime, but the third quarter was critical. Chicago scored 25 points while limiting the Pistons (4-10) to 16 during the period and maintained a comfortable lead the rest of the way for the home win.

Derrick Rose led the way for the Pistons with 18 points, adding three rebounds, two assists and one steal. Blake Griffin followed with 16 points, eight boards, one assist and one steal. Luke Kennard delivered 14 points, four assists, one rebound and one steal. Langston Galloway registered 13 points, three rebounds and one assist. Christian Wood generated a 12-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three blocks.

Lauri Markkanen paced the Bulls with 24 points and also pulled down six boards. Shaquille Harrison and Tomas Satoransky had 15 points apiece, with Satoransky also pulling down 11 rebounds and Satoransky adding seven assists. Wendell Carter, Jr. managed a 12-point, 15-rebound double-double that also included one assist, one steal and one block. 

The Pistons head back home and face the Atlanta Hawks on Friday night, while the Bulls remain home and face the Miami Heat on Friday night as well.

The Utah Jazz defeated the host Minnesota Timberwolves, 103-95, at Target Center on Wednesday.

A 26-19 first quarter really set the tone for Utah in this game, holding the lead for all but a handful of minutes. With that said, there were 19 lead changes in total with Utah never leading by more than 11 points. Free-throw shooting killed Minnesota, shooting just 11-of-21 while Utah hit 19-of-27. The Jazz held the Timberwolves to just 39 percent from the field and 31 percent from three-point range while out-assisting them, 22-13. Utah also connected on 14-of-32 from long range while doubling them up in fastbreak points, 16-8. 

The Jazz (9-5) were led by Bojan Bogdanovic, who tallied 30 points, four rebounds and three assists. Donovan Mitchell amassed 26 points, seven rebounds and two assists. Those two combined to go 11-of-21 from three-point range. Mike Conley accrued 16 points, six rebounds and eight assists while Rudy Gobert amassed 12 points, 15 rebounds and five blocks. 

The Timberwolves (8-7) were led by Andrew Wiggins, who tallied 22 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Karl-Anthony Towns generated 14 points and 12 rebounds. Jeff Teague accumulated 12 points, four rebounds and six assists while Robert Covington finished with 11 points, three rebounds, two steals and three blocks. 

On deck for Utah is a home matchup versus the struggling Golden State Warriors on Friday. As for Minnesota, they stay home to face the Phoenix Suns on Saturday for their next fixture.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Houston Rockets, 105-95, at Pepsi Center on Wednesday.

There were one tie and two lead changes in this game, with Denver leading for all but a few minutes. In fact, the Nuggets held the lead for the entirety of the second half, outscoring the Rockets, 51-44, in that half. The assist-to-turnover differential was critical, with Denver recording 29 assists to 14 turnovers while Houston committed 20 turnovers to 19 assists. That allowed the Nuggets to shoot 47 percent from the field and 33 percent from three-point range while holding the Rockets to 42 percent from the field and 32 percent from long range, In addition. Denver outscored Houston in the paint, 60-38, while winning the points off turnover differential, 32-17. 

The Rockets (11-4) were led by James Harden, who collected 27 points, seven rebounds, seven assists and three steals. Russell Westbrook finished with 25 points, two rebounds and five assists. Clint Capela had his fourth-straight 20-rebound game, amassing 12 points and 21 rebounds. No other player had more than seven points, three rebounds or three assists. 

The Nuggets (10-3) were led by Nikola Jokic, who accumulated 27 points, 12 rebounds and four assists on 12-of-17 from the field. Will Barton totaled 15 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Paul Millsap tallied 11 points, six rebounds, two assists and three steals while Jamal Murray generated 10 points, nine assists and six steals. 

Both teams return to action on Friday against tough competition, with Denver playing host to the Boston Celtics and Houston traveling to face the Los Angeles Clippers.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Boston Celtics in overtime, 107-104, at Staples Center on Wednesday. 

While Boston started this game by missing its first 16 three-pointers, it stayed close throughout. In fact, the Celtics actually led 86-76 with 6:15 remaining and the Clippers ended regulation on a 21-11 run to send the game into overtime. While Boston scored the first bucket of overtime, Los Angeles finished it on a 10-5 run to prevail. The key for Los Angeles was their defense, holding Boston to 39 percent from the field and 27 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Clippers recorded nine blocks to the Celtics two.

The Celtics (11-2) were led by Jayson Tatum, who tallied 30 points, six rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks. Marcus Smart accrued 15 points, three rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Kemba Walker went just 4-of-17 from the field to finish with 13 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Daniel Theis accrued eight points, 14 rebounds and six assists. 

The Clippers (9-5) played their first game with Paul George and Kawhi Leonard both in uniform, as George led the team with 25 points, five rebound and eight assists. Leonard generated 17 points, six rebounds, three assists, three steals and two blocks. Patrick Beverley accumulated 14 points, 16 rebounds, seven assists and three steals. Lou Williams led the bench with 27 points, two rebounds and two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Friday against tough teams, with Los Angeles playing host to the Houston Rockets and Boston staying on the road to face the Denver Nuggets.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 114-95, at FedEx Forum on Tuesday night.

The Warriors (3-12) came into the contest in desperate need of a win but operating with the makeshift crew that's a byproduct of multiple injuries. The Grizzlies (5-9) outpaced Golden State by a bucket in the first quarter, yet the visitors' 33-point tally in the second erased their slim deficit and left them with a 15-point advantage heading into intermission. While Memphis got four points closer during the third, the Warriors were able to roar back with a 31-point fourth quarter to secure the much-needed road win. 

Alec Burks led the way for the Warriors with 29 points, adding eight rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Glen Robinson III turned in 20 points, two assists and one rebound. Eric Paschall and Marquese Chriss generated matching 17-point tallies while pulling down five and six rebounds, respectively. Draymond Green stuffed the stat sheet with eight points, 11 assists, 10 rebounds and two blocks.

Ja Morant paced the Grizzlies with 20 points, complementing them with six assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block. Dillon Brooks produced 18 points, three rebounds, two steals and one block. Brandon Clarke provided 17 points, five rebounds, three assists, one steal and one block. Jae Crowder furnished a 15-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included four assists.

The Warriors remain on the road and tangle with the Dallas Mavericks on Wednesday night, while the Grizzlies remain home and take on the Los Angeles Lakers on Saturday night.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 115-104, at Smoothie King Center on Tuesday night.

The Pelicans (5-9) got off to a slow start since the Blazers (5-9) jumped ahead on the score rather quickly, but New Orleans used a strong effort during the second half to get the win here. Portland was up 28-27 after the first quarter, and they maintained that one-point advantage heading into the break (54-53). However, New Orleans woke up in the second half, and had no problems to recover the advantage thanks to an impressive performance during the third quarter, where they flipped the script and put themselves up by nine points (88-79). The Pelicans also won the final quarter by just two points, and that gave them a double-digit win in front of their fans.

Brandon Ingram returned from injury, and he thrived thanks to his 21 points, seven rebounds, five assists and two steals. Jrue Holiday was New Orleans top scoring threat, however, as he finished with a double-double of 22 points and 10 assists. Kenrich Williams had eight points and 11 boards. J.J. Redick had 18 points and five rebounds. Nicolo Melli had 14 points off the bench, and ETwaun Moore contributed 11 points as substitute.

Carmelo Anthony played for the first time in more than a year and finished with 10 points and four rebounds, although he shot 4-of-14 from the field. C.J. McCollum was Portlands biggest scoring threat in Damian Lillards absence after finishing with 22 points and five assists. Hassan Whiteside had a double-double of 14 points and 14 rebounds. Anfernee Simmons had 13 points.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the visiting Phoenix Suns, 120-116, at Golden 1 Center on Tuesday evening. 

The Kings got out to a great start at home, with a 33-19 lead after one quarter. They stayed in control through the second quarter as they maintained a double-digit lead through the quarter and pushed their lead to 17, by halftime. The Kings came out strong in the third and pushed their lead to 26, with 7:10 left in the quarter, but the Suns closed the quarter on a 24-10 run, to cut the deficit to 12, entering the fourth. The Suns kept battling through the fourth and made it a nine-point game with 1:23 left. They gave the Kings a scare, as they played the final whistle and got within four points, but the Kings were able to escape with their second straight win, while this marks the second straight loss for the Suns.  

Bogdan Bogdanovic led the Kings with 31 points, seven assists, four rebounds and three steals, in 36 minutes off the bench. Richaun Holmes added 20 points and 15 rebounds, while Nemanja Bjelica chipped in 17 points and rebounds. The Kings shot 53 percent from the field, including 13-of-31 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Devin Booker led the Suns with 30 points, eight assists, five rebounds and two steals, in 39 minutes. Kelly Oubre Jr. followed up with 20 points, eight rebounds, five steals and two assists, while Mikal Bridges added 20 points, in 26 minutes off the bench. The Suns shot 43 percent from the field, including 12-of-36 from deep. Ricky Rubio (back) was sidelined after 16 minutes of action. 

The Suns (7-6) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Pelicans on Thursday. The Kings (6-7) take on the Nets in Brooklyn on Friday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Oklahoma City Thunder, 112-107, at Staples Center on Tuesday.

Oklahoma City hasn't won a road game yet this season and Los Angeles added to that here. In fact, the Lakers held the lead for the final 45 minutes of action, thanks to a 63-53 first half. With that said, Los Angeles never led by more than 12 points. The Lakers ended up winning the fastbreak differential, 30-16, while outscoring the Thunder in second-chance points, 22-4. Los Angeles also shot 45 percent from three-point range while holding Oklahoma City to 32 percent from long range. In addition, the Lakers quadrupled up the Thunder in blocks, 8-2, while out-assisting them, 29-22. 

The Thunder (5-9) were led by Danilo Gallinari, who totaled 25 points and six rebounds on 7-of-11 from the field. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander went just 5-of-16 from the field to amass 16 points, five rebounds and four assists. Chris Paul accrued four points, five rebounds, 10 assists and four steals on 1-of-7 shooting. Dennis Schroder was huge off the bench, providing 31 points and four boards. 

The Lakers (12-2) got a triple-double from LeBron James, who collected 25 points, 11 rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Anthony Davis generated 34 points, seven rebounds, four assists, four steals and two blocks. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope tallied 13 points, four rebounds and two assists while Rajon Rondo led the bench with eight points and 10 assists.

Both teams return to action on Friday, playing one another in a rematch in OKC.

The New York Knicks defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 123-105, at Madison Square Garden on Monday evening.

The Knicks (4-10) ended 2-1 during this three-game homestand and now they have improved to 3-4 at home, while the Cavaliers (4-9) fell to 2-5 on the road. David Fizdale's men controlled the game right from the start, as they jumped to a 32-20 lead after the first quarter and they would never look back. The second quarter ended with a 32-31 score for New York, but they pulled away for good in the third with a 30-20 score. The Cavaliers closed the gap in the final 12 minutes of action with a 34-29 lead in garbage time, but it wasn't enough and the Knicks cruised their way to a huge win.

Julius Randle was the best player for the Knicks, and he ended with 30 points on 12-17 shooting. Marcus Morris Sr. ended with 34 points and six rebounds, while R.J. Barrett had 15 points. Kevin Knox II scored six points while going 2-of-10 from the field. Damyean Dotson had 11 points off the bench.

Kevin Porter Jr. led the way for the Cavaliers with 18 points and four rebounds, while rookie Darius Garland chipped in with 10 points. Collin Sexton might have ended with 14 points and three rebounds, but he struggled from the field and only made five of his 13 field goal attempts. The bench players thrived, though, with three scoring in double figures: Alfonzo McKinnie (14 points, six rebounds), Jordan Clarkson (13 points) and Brandon Knight (12 points).

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 115-86, at Barclays Center on Monday evening.

The Pacers (8-6) were on a two-game losing streak entering this contest, but they have bounced back with a strong performance on both ends of the court to defeat a struggling Nets (5-8) team that has lost four of its last six contest.
