With the win, Indiana moved to 3-4 on the road while Brooklyn fell to 3-3 at home. Indiana quickly dominate right from the start and while the first quarter ended 18-18, the Pacers pulled away for good in the second quarter thanks to a 41-17 score. The Nets couldn't bounce back after that horrific second period and while they won the third quarter 33-25, it was too late for them. Indiana closed things out with a 31-18 fourth-quarter score.

Aaron Holiday was the top scoring threat for the Pacers since he finished with 24 points, 13 assists and six rebounds, as he did a great job to fill the gap left by Malcolm Brogdons absence. Domantas Sabonis chipped in with a strong double-double of 16 points and 18 rebounds. Justin Holiday had 20 points, while T.J. Warren contributed 19 points and six rebounds. Naz Mitrou-Long added 12 points, three rebounds and three assists off the bench.

Spencer Dinwiddie replaced the injured Kyrie Irving and produced a stellar outing thanks to a 28-point, eight-assist, five-rebound performance. Jarrett Allen chipped with a double-double after finishing with 10 points and 12 rebounds. Garrett Temple had 10 points while also adding six boards and three dimes. Eight of nine bench players scored, but neither reached the 10-point plateau.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 132-96, at Scotiabank Arena on Monday night.

The game was ultimately truly a tale of two halves. Early on, the Hornets (6-8) did not give the slightest indication they were a team set to fold in the second half, trailing only 60-56 at halftime. However, Charlotte managed just 18 points in the third quarter while the Raptors (9-4) put up 32, and matters were even worse during a final period during which Toronto enjoyed a 40-22 advantage on their way to their biggest margin of victory of the season.

Marvin Williams led the Hornets with 14 points, adding four rebounds, one assist and two blocks. Miles Bridges and Bismack Biyombo generated matching 13-point tallies while pulling down five and two rebounds, respectively. Devonte' Graham provided 11 points, six assists, two rebounds and one steal. Terry Rozier delivered 10 points, three rebounds and three assists. 

OG Anunoby paced the Raptors with 24 points, adding five rebounds, two assists, and two steals. Pascal Siakam managed 20 points, eight rebounds, five assists, one steal and one block. Norman Powell poured in 17 points and added six assists, two rebounds and two steals. Terence Davis finished with 16 points, seven assists, one rebound and one steal. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson furnished 15 points, eight boards and two assists. Fred VanVleet and Chris Boucher had matching 11-point contributions, with Boucher also pulling down 11 rebounds and VanVleet dishing out eight assists. 

The Hornets next pay a visit to the Brooklyn Nets on Wednesday night, while the Raptors remain and tangle with the Orlando Magic on Wednesday evening as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 115-101, at United Center on Monday evening. 

The Bucks opened up an eight-point lead mid way through the first, but the Bulls closed the quarter on an 8-3 run, to cut the deficit to three, heading into the second. The Bulls kept up the fight in the second and led by six, late in the quarter, but the Bucks closed the quarter on a 12-2 run, to take a four-point lead into halftime. The Bucks held the advantage through the third, while the Bulls cut it to a three-point game, heading into the fourth. The Bucks led by eight, early in the fourth, but the Bulls rallied back to take a one-point lead, with 5:41 to go. The Bucks turned it up a notch and outscored the Bulls 17-2, the rest of the way, to walk away with their fourth straight win. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 33 points, 10 rebounds, three steals, two assists and a block, in 34 minutes. Brook Lopez added 19 points, 10 abounds, five blocks, two steals and two assists, in 31 minutes. George Hill added 18 points, off the bench. The Bucks shot 46 percent from the field, including 15-of-41 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Daniel Gafford led the Bulls with 21 points on 10-of-12 shooting, in 20 minutes off the bench. Coby White added 13 points, while Zach LaVine finished with 11 points, eight rebounds and four assists. The Bulls shot 40 percent from the field, including 12-of-34 from long range. 

The Bulls (4-10) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Pistons on Wednesday. The Bucks (10-3) take on the Hawks in Atlanta on Wednesday.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 132-108, at Toyota Center on Monday night.

The struggling Trail Blazers got off an encouraging start, putting up 30 first-quarter points and taking a one-point lead through the first 12 minutes. However, the Rockets (11-3) began to distance themselves in the second, building up an 14-point advantage by halftime. They would add another nine points to their edge in the third, effectively sealing the win at that point. 

C.J. McCollum led the way for the Trail Blazers with 25 points, adding five rebounds, three assists and two steals. Skal Labissiere followed with 15 points and complemented them with six boards, two assists and two blocks. Damian Lillard generated a 13-point, 11-assist double-double that also included six rebounds. Nassir Little, Hassan Whiteside and Kent Bazemore all registered 11 points, with Little and Whiteside pulling down seven and eight rebounds, respectively. Anfernee Simons managed 10 points, two assists and one rebound.

James Harden paced the Rockets with 36 points, supplementing them with six boards, five assists, one steal and one block. Russell Westbrook delivered a 28-point, 13-rebound, 10-assist triple-double that also included two steals and one block. Clint Capela finished with a 22-point, 20-rebound double-double that also included four blocks and one steal. P.J. Tucker had 13 points, while Danuel House, Jr. went for 11 points, six rebounds, four assists and three steals. 

The Trail Blazers next pay a visit to the New Orleans Pelicans on Tuesday night, while the Rockets travel to take on the Denver Nuggets on Wednesday night.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 117-110, at American Airlines Center on Monday evening. 

The Mavericks got out to a great start at home, with a 36-22 lead after one quarter. The Spurs fell behind by as many as 18 points in the second, but battled to make it a 10-point game by halftime. The Mavericks came out strong in the third quarter and did not allow the Spurs a chance to get close, as they pushed their lead to 14, by the start of the fourth. The Spurs gave a last gasp in the fourth quarter, as they went on an 11-3 run, to make it a two-point game with four minutes left, but the Mavericks came through in crunch time to hold on for their second straight win. This marks the sixth straight loss for the Spurs. 

Luka Doncic led the Mavs with 42 points, 12 assists and 11 rebounds, in 35 minutes. Kristaps Porzingis added 18 points and 10 rebounds, while Dorian Finney-Smith tallied 22 points, five rebounds, three assists, a steal and a block. The Mavericks shot 50 percent from the field, including 17-of-41 from deep. 

Meanwhile, DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 36 points, eight rebounds, four assists and a steal. LaMarcus Aldridge added 16 points, nine rebounds and two assists, while Bryn Forbes added 13 points. The Spurs shot 46 percent from the field, including 8-of-24 from long range. 

The Spurs (5-9) will look to bounce back as they take on the Wizards in Washington on Wednesday. The Mavericks (8-5) play host to the Warriors on Wednesday.

The Boston Celtics defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 99-85, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Monday evening. 

The Suns got out to a good start, with an early 8-2 lead, but the Celtics caught up and ran ahead to take a 26-22 lead into the second quarter. The Suns rallied ahead again, mid way through the quarter, but the Celtics closed the quarter on a 21-4 run, to take a 15-point lead into halftime. The teams played to a standstill through the third, as the Suns could not cut into the deficit and trailed by 15, entering the fourth. The Celtics cruised through the fourth, as they held on for their sixth road win of the season.

Jayson Tatum led the Celtics with 26 points, 11 rebounds and three assists. Kemba Walker tallied 19 points and five assists, while Jaylen Brown added 14 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Marcus Smart added 17 points, four assists, three rebounds, two steals and a block. The Celtics shot 42 percent from the field, including 12-of-41 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Devin Booker led the Suns with 20 points and four assists, while Kelly Oubre Jr. finished with 15 points and six rebounds. No other players scored in double digits for the Suns, as they shot 40 percent from the field, including 10-of-36 from long range. The Suns were without Ricky Rubio (back), who was a late scratch. 

The Suns (7-5) will look to bounce back as they take on the Kings in Sacramento on Tuesday. The Celtics (11-2) head to L.A. to take on the Clippers on Wednesday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the host Utah Jazz, 112-102, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Monday.

There were 14 ties and 16 lead changes in this game, with neither team leading by more than seven points until the final minutes. Those final minutes were actually the difference, with Minnesota outscoring Utah in the fourth quarter, 36-24. The Timberwolves defense was key, holding the Jazz to 37 percent from the field and 39 percent from three-point range. Minnesota ended up shooting 46 percent from the field. Rim protection was also critical for the Timberwolves, doubling up the Jazz in blocks, 10-5. 

The Timberwolves (8-6) were led by Karl-Anthony Towns, who tallied 29 points, 13 rebounds, five assists, two steals and two blocks. Jeff Teague accrued 21 points, four rebounds and 11 assists. Robert Covington amassed 15 points, eight rebounds and two steals while Kelan Martin led the bench with 14 points and six boards. 

The Jazz (8-5) were led by Bojan Bogdanovic, who totaled 18 points, six rebounds and two assists. Donovan Mitchell accumulated 17 points, seven rebounds and two assists. Rudy Gobert generated 16 points and 14 rebounds. Mike Conley accumulated 15 points, six rebounds and six assists while Joe Ingles led the bench with 12 points, eight rebounds and five assists. 

These teams' next matchup will actually be a rematch in Minnesota on Wednesday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting Oklahoma City Thunder, 90-88, at Staples Center on Monday.

These two teams made a huge trade involving Paul George a few months ago and he ended up being the hero in this game. In fact, he hit a three-pointer with 26 seconds left to take the lead and win the game for the Clippers. In total, there were 12 ties and 10 lead changes with neither team ever leading by more than six points. Los Angeles' defense was critical, holding Oklahoma City to 37 percent from the field and 26 percent from three-point range. In addition, the Clippers out-assisted the Thunder, 23-17. 

The Thunder (5-8) were led by Chris Paul, who accumulated 22 points, four rebounds, four assists and four steals. Danilo Gallinari generated 14 points, five rebounds and two assists. Steven Adams accumulated nine points, 10 rebounds, six assists and two steals. Dennis Schroder led the bench with 12 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

The Clippers (9-5) were led by Montrezl Harrell, who provided 28 points, 12 rebounds and five assists off the bench. Lou Williams also tallied 11 points and nine assists off the pine. Paul George led the starters with 18 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Ivica Zubac amassed 12 points and 10 boards. Patrick Beverley was the only other player with more than three points, totaling nine points, four rebounds and three steals.

Oklahoma City will have to play the second half of a back-to-back set on Tuesday, staying on the road to face the Los Angeles Lakers. As for the Clippers, they play host to the Boston Celtics on Wednesday for their next fixture.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 114-95, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Sunday afternoon.

The 76ers (8-5) entered this game on the heels of a 2-5 stretch, but they bounced back admirably with a strong effort across the board to secure a big road win over the surging Cavaliers (4-8). Philadelphia quickly jumped to a 33-22 lead after the first quarter, and they further extended that advantage with a 35-22 second period that saw them go up by 24 points at the break. Philadelphia also won the third quarter 27-25 and it was clear the game was over with 12 minutes left to play. The Cavaliers won the final frame 26-19, but it wasn't enough and the Sixers cruised their way to a huge victory. With the win, the Sixers improved to 4-5 away from home while the Cavaliers fell to 2-4 at home.

Tobias Harris was the top scorer for the Sixers here since he finished with 27 points, five rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks. Joel Embiid registered 14 points with four rebounds and two assists in only 23 minutes of action. Ben Simmons had 10 points, 11 assists, and four boards. Al Horford had 11 points, six boards and seven assists. James Ennis III had 14 points off the bench, while Furkan Korkmaz had 13 points.

Collin Sexton was the top scorer for the Cavaliers since he finished with 17 points and four rebounds. Rookie point guard Darius Garland finished with 11 points. Tristan Thompson had 12 points with nine rebounds, while Kevin Love registered 12 points while also adding six boards. Cedi Osman only had five points while shooting 2-of-7 from the field.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the Boston Celtics, 100-99, at Golden 1 Center on Sunday afternoon.

The Kings (5-7) were coming off a two-game winning streak before losing to the Lakers on Friday, but they have bounced back admirably with a huge win over the Celtics (10-2), a franchise that own one of the best records in The Association. Sacramento jumped to a huge 30-18 lead in the first quarter, but the Celtics flipped the script quickly and a 28-20 edge in the second quarter put them down by just four points at the half-time break. Boston won the third quarter by a 29-21 score and had a four-point lead ahead of the final 12 minutes of the contest. Sacramento, however, came out of nowhere to mount an impressive rally. Their 29-24 fourth-quarter score helped them get the win at home, and Richaun Holmes sealed the win with two clutch free throws with 13.3 seconds left on the clock. With the win, Sacramento moved to 3-3 at home while the Celtics are 5-2 on the road.

Buddy Hield was the biggest star of the game as he finished with 35 points, six rebounds, four steals and two assists. Harrison Barnes had 13 points, three rebounds and three assists. Nenad Bjelica had an impressive double-double with 12 points, 14 rebounds and four assists in 31 minutes. Bogdan Bogdanovic thrived off the bench since he ended the contest with 12 points in 31 minutes despite shooting 5-for-14 from the field.

Jaylen Brown was the top scoring threat for the Celtics since he had 18 points with eight rebounds and two steals. Kemba Walker had 15 points with nine assists, while Jayson Tatum and Daniel Theis each finished with 14 points. Tatum also had six rebounds, while Theis grabbed 10 rebounds in 22 minutes of action. Enes Kanter had 10 points as a substitute.

The Orlando Magic defeated the Washington Wizards, 125-121, at Amway Center on Sunday night.

The Magic (6-7) came into the contest looking to notch a third straight home victory and continue their climb to .500. They set the tone early with a 29-point first quarter and held a nine-point advantage at halftime. They managed to coax that up to 11 points heading into the final period, but then had to withstand a furious rally by the Wizards (3-8) that saw them get to within 117-116 at the 1:01 mark of the fourth quarter.

Bradley Beal paced the Wizards with 34 points, adding eight assists, six rebounds and one steal. C.J. Miles poured in 21 points to lead the bench. Davis Bertans followed with 15 points, eight rebounds, one assist and two steals. Thomas Bryant turned in 14 points, six rebounds, four assists and one block. Isaiah Thomas furnished 13 points, five assists and two steals. Moritz Wagner tallied 12 points, three boards and three assists. 

Nikola Vucevic led the Magic with a 30-point, 17-rebound double-double that also included six assists and one block. Evan Fournier supplied 25 points, nine assists, one rebound and one steal. Markelle Fultz registered 19 points, three rebounds, two assists and one steal. Terrance Ross posted 15 points, four boards, one assist and two steals. Aaron Gordon and D.J. Augustin contributed matching 13-point tallies, with Gordon also pulling down nine rebounds.

The Wizards head back home to take on the San Antonio Spurs on Wednesday night, while the Magic hit the road and pay a visit to the Toronto Raptors on Wednesday night as well.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Memphis Grizzlies, 131-114, at FedEx Forum on Sunday evening. 

The Nuggets jumped out to an early 9-2 lead, but the Grizzlies battled back to take a four-point lead after one quarter. The Nuggets exploded for 44 points in the second and held the Grizzlies to just 17 in the quarter, to take a commanding 72-49 lead by halftime. The Nuggets pushed their lead to 30, early in the third and kept control to take a 28-point lead into the final frame. The Grizzlies kept fighting in the fourth and outscored the Nuggets by 11 in the quarter, but it was too little too late, as the Nuggets walked away with their second win in a row. 

Jamal Murray led the Nuggets with 39 points on 14-of-24 shooting, eight assists, four rebounds, three steals and a block, in 31 minutes. Paul Millsap followed up with 23 points and five steals, while Juancho Hernangomez chipped in 15 points off the bench. The Nuggets shot 55 percent from the field, including 18-of-32 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Jaren Jackson Jr. led the Grizzlies with 22 points and five rebounds. Brandon Clarke added 19 points and five rebounds, while Jonas Valanciunas tallied 16 points and 10 rebounds. The Grizzlies shot 46 percent from the field, including 16-of-36 from deep. 

The Grizzlies (5-8) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Warriors on Tuesday. The Nuggets (9-3) play host to the Rockets on Wednesday.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the Golden State Warriors, 108-100, at Smoothie King Center on Sunday evening. 

As has been the norm recently, the Pelicans (4-9) came into Sunday's contest notably short-handed due to the injury bug, with Derrick Favors (back), Jahlil Okafor (ankle), Josh Hart (knee), Frank Jackson (neck) and Brandon Ingram (knee) all sidelined. However, New Orleans still got off to a strong start against the similarly depleted Warriors (2-12), forging a 55-49 halftime lead. Golden State would keep the pressure on throughout the second half, but they could get no closer than within five points in the fourth quarter on their way to yet another loss.

Eric Paschall paced the Warriors with 30 points, adding seven boards and two assists. Ky Bowman provided 19 points, four assists, two rebounds and one steal. Glenn Robinson III turned in 14 points, six rebounds and two assists. Marquese Chriss was the only other double-digit scorer for the Warriors with 10 points and added seven rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block.

J.J. Redick delivered 26 points, three rebounds and three assists. Jrue Holiday tallied 22 points, nine assists, eight rebounds, one steal and one block. Nickeil Alexander-Walker collected 19 points, five rebounds, four assists and one steal. Nicolo Melli managed 16 points, five boards and three assists. E'Twaun Moore and Jaxson Hayes each drew starts and generated matching 10-point tallies while pulling down seven and 10 rebounds, respectively. Hayes added three blocks. 

The Warriors next pay a visit to the Memphis Grizzlies on Tuesday night, while the Pelicans remain home to tangle with the Portland Trail Blazers on Tuesday night as well.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 122-101, at Staples Center on Sunday.

Los Angeles took control with a 36-24 first quarter, winning this game in wire-to-wire fashion. In fact, they followed that up with a 33-17 second quarter and held a double-digit lead for the entirety of the second half. The Lakers ended up shooting 53 percent from the field and 43 percent from three-point range while holding Atlanta to 43 percent from the field and 29 percent from long range. In addition, the Lakers out-assisted the Hawks, 26-16, while recording 14 blocks to the Hawks two swats. 

The Hawks (4-9) were led by Trae Young, who accrued 31 points, three rebounds, seven assists and two steals. Jabari Parker accumulated 11 points, eight rebounds and four steals. Cam Reddish generated 13 points, three rebounds and three steals. Allen Crabbe led the bench with 11 points. De'Andre Hunter provided 11 points, two rebounds and three assists. 

The Lakers (11-2) were led by LeBron James, who tallied 33 points, seven rebounds and 12 assists. Anthony Davis finished with 14 points, five assists and four blocks. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope amassed 13 points, one rebound and one assist. Rajon Rondo led the bench with 15 points, two rebounds and three assists. Kyle Kuzma also amassed 17 points and five boards off the bench as well. 

On deck for Los Angeles is another home game against the Oklahoma City Thunder on Tuesday. As for Atlanta, they return home on Wednesday to face the Milwaukee Bucks.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 117-111, at United Center on Saturday.

While Brooklyn played this game without Kyrie Irving (shoulder), they were still able to prevail with a victory. There were seven ties and six lead changes in total, with neither team leading by more than 13 points. Brooklyn actually outscored Chicago in the first and fourth quarters, 73-52. The Nets defense was critical, holding the Bulls to 35 percent from the field and 23 percent from three-point range. In addition, Brooklyn doubled up Chicago in assists, 30-15  while shooting 46 percent from the field. The Bulls actually went 38-of-41 from the free-throw line while winning the rebounding battle, 56-40. 

The Nets (5-7) were led by Spencer Dinwiddie, who scored 18 of his 24 points in the fourth quarter to add to his four assists and two blocks. Joe Harris accumulated 22 points, four rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Taurean Prince totaled 13 points, five rebounds and two assists while Jarrett Allen generated 11 points, seven rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks. 

The Bulls (4-9) were led by Zach LaVine, who tallied 36 points and three rebounds. Wendell Carter Jr accrued 18 points, 14 rebounds and two assists. Lauri Markkanen amassed 16 points and 10 boards while Coby White provided seven points, nine rebounds and three assists off the bench. 

Both teams return to action on Sunday, with Chicago remaining at home to face the Milwaukee Bucks and Brooklyn welcoming the Indiana Pacers to Barclay's Center.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the New York Knicks, 103-102, at Madison Square Garden on Saturday night.

The Knicks (3-10) came into the contest in desperate need of extending their winning streak to two games, considering the 3-9 mark they were sporting. New York got off to a fine start in that regard, forging a 55-47 halftime lead over the Hornets (6-7). Charlotte whittled that deficit down to one point by the end of the third period, however, and ultimately, they utilized a 23-14 run over the final 5:49, which was capped off by a Devonte' Graham 28-foot three-pointer with 2.8 seconds remaining, to notch the road win.

Graham led the way for the Hornets with 29 points, adding four rebounds and two assists. PJ Washington followed with 19 points, five boards, three assists, one steal and one block. Terry Rozier poured in 16 points and also pulled down four rebounds, dished out two assists and recorded two steals. Marvin Williams totaled 13 points, five rebounds, two assists and one steal. Malik Monk furnished 12 points, five assists, four boards and one block.

RJ Barrett paced the Knicks with 22 points and also collected five boards and two assists. Mitchell Robinson generated a 17-point, 12-rebound double-double off the bench that included one assist, one steal and one block. Marcus Morris registered 14 points, six boards and three assists. Bobby Portis matched Morris' scoring and pulled down two rebounds. Julius Randle supplied 12 points, seven rebounds and six assists.

The Hornets remain on the road and pay a visit to the Toronto Raptors on Monday night, while the Knicks remain home and tangle with the Cleveland Cavaliers on Monday night as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Indiana Pacers, 102-83, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Saturday night.

The Pacers (7-6) had proven to be an above-average home team early in the season, just as had been the case during the entirety of last season. However, the Bucks (9-3), which had struggled defensively in the early going, brought their A-game on that side of the floor. Milwaukee established a 49-36 halftime lead, and although Indiana did manage to shave five points off that deficit in the third, the visitors re-established their dominance with a 31-point final period that sealed the comfortable road win.

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with a 26-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included six assists, one steal and one block. Brook Lopez supplied 15 points, eight rebounds, five blocks and one steal. Donte DiVincenzo drew the start and provided 14 points, four boards, one assist and two steals. Eric Bledsoe and Sterling Brown generated matching 10-point tallies while dishing out five and four assists, respectively.

Myles Turner led the Pacers in his return from an ankle injury, posting a 16-point, 11-rebound  double-double that also included two assists, four blocks and one steal. T.J. Warren poured in 15 points and also supplied five rebounds, two blocks and one steal. Domantas Sabonis managed an 11-point, 14-rebound double-double that also included two assists and one steal. Aaron Holiday turned in 11 points, five assists, four boards and three steals. 

The Bucks remain on the road and next visit the Chicago Bulls on Monday night, while the Pacers pay a visit to the Brooklyn Nets on that same night.

The Miami Heat defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 109-94, at American Airlines Arena on Saturday evening. 

The Heat got out to a strong start at home and held a seven-point lead after one quarter. The Pelicans put up a fight in the second and trimmed the deficit to five, at halftime. The Pelicans kept up the momentum to start the third and made it a one-point game early in the quarter, but the Heat turned it up a notch and closed the quarter on a 15-4 run, to take a 13-point lead into the fourth. The Heat held on through the fourth to walk away with their third straight win. 

The Heat (9-3) had six players score in double digits in the win, as Kendrick Nunn led the way with 22 points. Jimmy Butler and Bam Adebayo each tallied double-doubles, while Duncan Robinson chipped in 15 points. The Heat shot 54 percent from the field, including 9-of-24 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Nickeil Alexander-Walker led the Pelicans with 27 points on 10-of-18 shooting, in 30 minutes off the bench. E'Twaun Moore tallied 18 points, five assists and three steals, while Jrue Holiday added 14 points and four assists. The Pelicans shot 45 percent from the field, including 16-of-35 from deep. 

The Pelicans (3-9) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Warriors on Sunday. The Heat (9-3) play host to the Cavs on Wednesday.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Minnesota Timberwolves, 125-105, at Target Center on Saturday evening. 

The contest got out to a hot start, as the Rockets emerged with a 31-30 lead after one quarter. The high-scoring trend continued through the second quarter, where the Rockets outscored the visitors 33-32, to take a 64-62 lead into halftime. The Timberwolves came out strong in the third and took an edge early in the quarter, but the Rockets rallied back to take an eight-point lead into the final frame. The Rockets ran away in the fourth, outscoring the Timberwolves by 12 in the quarter, to seal their seventh straight win. 

James Harden led the Rockets with 49 points on 16-of-41 shooting, six assists and five rebounds. Ben McLemore followed up with 20 points on 7-of-16 shooting, while Austin Rivers and Chris Clemons chipped in 19 points each. The Rockets shot 46 percent from the field, including 19-of-49 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Karl-Anthony Towns led the Timberwolves with 27 points, 15 rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Jake Layman added 21 points and five rebounds, while Robert Covington tallied 17 points, five rebounds and three assists. The Timberwolves shot 12-of-38 from long range. 

The Timberwolves (7-6) will look to bounce back as they take on the Jazz, in Utah on Monday. The Rockets (10-3) play host to the Trail Blazers on Monday.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Toronto Raptors, 110-102, at American Airlines Center on Saturday evening. 

The Mavericks got out to a great start at home, with a 32-22 lead, after one quarter. The Raptors bounced back in the second and outscored the hosts by 17 in the quarter, to take a seven-point lead by halftime. The Mavs reclaimed control in the third and outscored the visitors by eight in the quarter, to take a one-point lead into the final frame. They pushed their lead to nine early in the fourth and kept the pressure on, to take a 14-point lead with five minutes to go. The Raptors managed to cut it down to a four-point game with 1:37 left, but the Mavericks closed it out their fourth home win of the season. 

Luka Doncic led the Mavs with 26 points, 15 rebounds, seven assists and two steals. Kristaps Porzingis added 20 points and 15 rebounds, while Delon Wright and Seth Curry added 15 points each. The Mavs shot 42 percent from the field, including 9-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Norman Powell led the Raptors with 26 points on 9-of-15 shooting, in 32 minutes. Fred VanVleet added 24 points, seven assists and five rebounds, while Pascal Siakam added 15 points, seven assists and three rebounds. The Raptors shot 42 percent from the field, including 17-of-41 from long range. 

The Raptors (8-4) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Hornets on Monday. The Mavericks (7-5) play host the Spurs on Monday.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the San Antonio Spurs, 121-116, at AT & T Center on Saturday night.

The Trail Blazers (5-8) came out of the gates blazing hot against the defensively challenged Spurs (5-8), racking up 41 points in the first quarter while limiting San Antonio to 23. The home squad was able to knock 10 points off that deficit before halftime, and they remained hot coming out of intermission. The Spurs were able to take a six-point lead into the final period, but Portland finished the game on a furious 31-15 run across the final 9:26 to notch the road win.

C.J. McCollum led the way for Portland with 32 points, a total he complemented with seven assists, six rebounds and one steal. Damian Lillard followed with 22 points despite shooting just 4-for-19 and also posted six rebounds and six assists. Hassan Whiteside generated a 21-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included three blocks. Rodney Hood contributed 16 points, four rebounds and two assists. Mario Hezonja and Kent Bazemore delivered matching eight-point tallies.

LaMarcus Aldridge paced the Spurs with 30 point and 13 rebounds, adding two assists, one steal and one block. Bryn Forbes poured in 17 points. DeMar DeRozan and Rudy Gay contributed matching 16-point tallies while also hauling in seven and four rebounds, respectively. Patty Mills turned in 11 points and five assists, while Derrick White delivered 10 points, five assists, three rebounds, two steals and two blocks.

The Trail Blazers remain on the road and pay a visit to the Houston Rockets on Monday night, while the Spurs tangle with the Dallas Mavericks on the road Monday night as well.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 150-101, at Staples Center on Saturday.

A 43-30 first quarter really set the tone for the Clippers in this game while a 76-39 second half put the game to bed. In fact, that gave them a 30-point lead headed into the final quarter, winning in wire-to-wire fashion and leading by 52 points at times in that final quarter. The Clippers shot 54 percent from the field, 52 percent from three-point range and 94 percent from the free-throw line while holding the Hawks to 38 percent from the field and 25 percent from long range. Los Angeles also out-rebounded Atlanta, 53-38, while out-assisting them, 30-19. 

The Hawks (4-8) were led by Trae Young, who totaled 20 points, five rebounds and six assists. De'Andre Hunter amassed 12 points and two boards. Jabari Parker accrued 11 points, eight rebounds and two steals. Damian Jones generated 11 points, three rebounds and four blocks while Evan Turner led the bench with 11 points, five rebounds and two steals. 

The Clippers (8-5) had to play this game without Kawhi Leonard for the fourth time this season, but they did pick up their first win without him. Paul George led the way, tallying 37 points, four rebounds, three assists and two steals. Ivica Zubac totaled seven points, nine rebounds, four assists and four blocks. Lou Williams led the bench with 25 points, six rebounds and six assists. Terrence Mann accumulated 13 points, six rebounds and eight assists.

On deck for Atlanta is another road game against the Los Angeles Lakers on Sunday. As for Los Angeles, they play host to the Oklahoma City Thunder on Monday for their next fixture.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the Detroit Pistons, 109-106, at Spectrum Center on Friday night.

The Pistons (4-9) came out of the gates seemingly intent on snapping their four-game losing streak, as they rode some hot shooting to a 65-51 halftime lead. However, the Hornets (5-7) came out of intermission a different team, outscoring Detroit by a 32-18 margin in the third to forge a tie heading into the final period. After a nip-and-tuck fourth quarter, a 26-footer from Malik Monk snapped a 106-106 tie with less than a second remaining to clinch the victory for the home squad.

Langston Galloway led the way for the Pistons with 32 points, complementing them with two rebounds and one assist. Blake Griffin furnished a modest 19 points and added six assists, three rebounds, one steal and one block. Andre Drummond generated a 16-point, 20-rebound double-double that also included two assists. Derrick Rose matched Drummond's scoring total off the bench. 

The Hornets were led by matching 19-point tallies from Terry Rozier and Monk. Devonte' Graham followed with 18 points, 10 assists and five rebounds. PJ Washington delivered 11 points, five rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Cody Zeller and Bismack Biyombo contributed 10 points apiece while pulling down seven and three rebounds, respectively. 

The Pistons remain on the road and pay a visit to the Chicago Bulls on Wednesday night, while the Hornets travel to the Big Apple to tangle with the New York Knicks on Saturday night.

The Orlando Magic defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 111-109, at Amway Center on Friday. 

While San Antonio dominated the first half thanks to a 31-24 first quarter, Orlando made it close with a 29-19 third quarter. In fact, that led to seven ties and 13 lead changes in this game, staying within a six-point margin for the entirety of the fourth quarter. With that said, Orlando finished the game on a 19-10 run to capture the win. Free-throw shooting was the difference in the game, with the Magic connecting on 27-of-34 while the Spurs hit just 6-of-10. San Antonio actually shot 50 percent from both the field and from three-point range while holding Orlando to 41 percent from both. 

The Spurs (5-7) were led by DeMar DeRozan, who tallied 21 points, two rebounds and five assists. LaMarcus Aldridge amassed 13 points, six rebounds, two assists and five blocks. Trey Lyles totaled eight points and 12 boards while Rudy Gay led the bench with 14 points and four rebounds. Dejounte Murray did finish with 10 points, five rebounds and six assists.

The Magic (5-7) were led by Evan Fournier, who accrued 26 points, four rebounds and three assists. Nikola Vucevic amassed 10 points, 13 rebounds, four assists and three blocks. Aaron Gordon accrued 14 points, eight rebounds and four assists while Al-Farouq Aminu collected 13 points and 13 rebounds in a rare start. 

On deck for San Antonio is a home matchup versus the Portland Trail Blazers on Saturday. As for Orlando, they play host to the Washington Wizards on Sunday for their next fixture.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Indiana Pacers, 111-102, at Toyota Center on Friday night.

The Rockets (9-3) came into the contest with an impressive 4-1 home record, and their play in the first half helped demonstrate why. Houston jumped out to a 54-49 halftime lead over the Pacers (7-5), with Malcolm Brogdon's exit after just nine minutes on the floor due to a back injury certainly helping the home team's cause. Indiana was able to shave its deficit down to one point entering the fourth quarter and then took the lead in the final period, but a 10-0 run by Houston helped it regain control and forge a lead it wouldn't relinquish.

The Pacers were led by matching 18-point tallies from Domantas Sabonis and Doug McDermott, with Sabonis also pulling down 13 rebounds, Aaron Holiday and T.J. McConnell posted 12 points apiece while dishing out five and seven assists, respectively. T.J. Leaf matched both their scoring tallies and also hauled in seven rebounds. Justin Holiday contributed 10 points, five rebounds and three assists.

James Harden paced the Rockets with 44 points, complementing them with eight rebounds, five assists and four steals. Ben McLemore poured in 21 points and posted three rebounds. Russell Westbrook totaled 17 points, eight boards, six assists and one steal. Austin Rivers led the bench with 10 points.

The Pacers make a quick trip back home to take on the Milwaukee Bucks on Saturday night, while the Rockets travel to take on the Minnesota Timberwolves on Saturday night as well.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Utah Jazz, 107-106, at FedEx Forum on Friday.

While there were only seven ties and nine lead changes in this game, it came down to the wire. In fact, Donovan Mitchell had a chance at the buzzer to win but had it stripped to give the Grizzlies a win. The key for Memphis was their defense, holding Utah to 40 percent from the field and 27 percent from three-point range. Ball movement was a big part of that, out-assisting the Jazz, 25-17. Memphis ended up winning the fastbreak scoring, 21-9, and the points in the paint battle, 56-48. 

The Jazz (8-4) were led by Mitchell, who finished with 29 points, nine rebounds, five assists and two steals. Rudy Gobert amassed 23 points, 17 rebounds and three blocks. Bojan Bogdanovic generated 20 points in an otherwise empty line. Mike Conley's return to Memphis led to him finishing with 15 points, four rebounds and three assists. 

The Grizzlies (5-7) were led by Ja Morant, who accrued 25 points, four rebounds and eight assists. Dillon Brooks totaled 20 points, two rebounds and two assists. Jae Crowder accumulated 11 points, 10 rebounds and four assists. Kyle Anderson led the bench with 13 points, seven rebounds and two assists. 

On deck for the Grizzlies is a home matchup versus the Denver Nuggets on Sunday. As for the Jazz, they play host to the Minnesota Timberwolves on Monday for their next fixture.

The Washington Wizards defeated the host Minnesota Timberwolves, 137-116, at Target Center on Friday.

While there were seven ties and seven lead changes in this game, Washington won in dominating fashion. In fact, they rode a 61-43 second half to their double-digit victory. The key for Washington was their offense, shooting 54 percent from the field while out-assisting Minnesota, 38-26. In addition, the Wizards won the fastbreak scoring, 18-9, while outscoring them in the paint, 76-62. Washington also out-rebounded Minnesota, 51-43 while winning the turnover battle, 20-13. 

The Wizards (3-7) were led by Bradley Beal, who tallied 44 points, three rebounds, 10 assists and two steals. Moritz Wagner had the best game of his career, collecting 30 points and 15 rebounds off the bench. Thomas Bryant amassed 12 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Davis Bertans also played well off the bench, providing eight points, five rebounds and three assists. 

The Timberwolves (7-5) had to play this game without Andrew Wiggins, as Karl-Anthony Towns led the team with 36 points, 10 rebounds and three assists. Jeff Teague amassed 13 points and 11 assists. Robert Covington accrued 20 points and six boards. Josh Okogie led the bench with 12 points, six rebounds and two assists. 

Minnesota will have to play again on Saturday, playing host to James Harden and the Rockets. As for Washington, they travel to face the Orlando Magic on Sunday for their next fixture.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 127-119, in overtime at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Friday night.

The two teams traded blows in the first half and won a quarter apiece,  leading to relatively 54-49 halftime lead for the Thunder (5-7). The 76ers (7-5) managed to erase all but one point from their deficit in the third quarter, setting up a nip-and-tuck fourth that culminated in a pair of Josh Richardson free throws with seven seconds left to send the game into overtime. Then, after Philadelphia closed to within 112-111 at the 3:05 mark of the extra period, a 9-0 run by OKC helped clinch the hard-fought win.

Joel Embiid led the 76ers with a 31-point, 12-rebound double-double that he complemented with two assists and one steal. Richardson followed with 28 points and added three rebounds, two assists and one steal. Tobias Harris delivered 21 points, six rebounds and three assists. Ben Simmons contributed 16 points, 11 rebounds, eight assists and one steal. Al Horford supplied 12 points, five assists, four rebounds and two steals.

Danilo Gallinari paced the Thunder with 28 points and also posted seven boards and two assists. Chris Paul compiled 27 points. eight boards and five dimes. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander tallied 24 points, three assists, two rebounds and two steals. Terrance Ferguson managed 19 points.

The 76ers remain on the road and pay a visit to the Cleveland Cavaliers on Sunday afternoon. The Thunder hit the road and face off with the Los Angeles Clippers on Monday night.

The Boston Celtics defeated the host Golden State Warriors, 105-100, at Chase Center on Friday evening. 

The Warriors got out to a great start at home, as they led by as many as 15 in the first quarter. They held a 32-23 lead to start the second and held the edge through most of the quarter, but the Celtics rallied ahead in the final minutes of the quarter to take a one-point lead into halftime. The Celtics carried the momentum into the third quarter and were able to increase their lead to five points, heading into the fourth. The Warriors did not back down and took a one-point lead, four minutes into the final quarter. They kept up the fight and built a five-point lead with two minutes to go, but the Celtics closed the game on a 13-3 run to earn their ninth straight win. 

Jayson Tatum led the Celtics with 24 points, eight rebounds and three steals. Jaylen brown tallied 22 points, eight rebounds, three assists and three steals. Kemba Walker finished with 20 points, five rebounds and five assists. The Celtics shot 41 percent from the field, including 13-of-33 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Alec Burks led the Warriors with 20 points, in 30 minutes off the bench. Draymond Green totalled 11 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and two steals, while Eric Paschall finished with 16 points and eight rebounds. The Warriors shot 42 percent from the field, including 5-of-28 from deep. 

The Warriors (2-11) will look to bounce back as they take on the Pelicans, in New Orleans on Sunday. The Celtics (10-1) head to Sacramento to take on the Kings, on Sunday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 99-97, at Staples Center on Friday evening. 

The Kings closed the first quarter on an 11-1 run to take a 10-point lead into the second. The Lakers responded in the second and brought it to a one-point game by halftime. They carried the momentum into the third, as they held a small advantage for almost the entire quarter and took a 74-71 lead into the final frame. The Lakers pushed their lead to eight, early in the fourth, but the Kings tied it up with 3:24 to go. The teams traded buckets down the stretch, until the Lakers got their winning points at the free-throw line, with five seconds left, as LeBron James hit 2-of-2 to seal their third straight win. 

James led the Lakers with 29 points, 11 assists, four rebounds and three steals, in 39 minutes. Anthony Davis finished with 17 points, five rebounds, four blocks two assists and a steal, while Kentavious Caldwell-Pope chipped in 16 points. The Lakers shot 42 percent from the field, including 11-of-37 from the field. 

Meanwhile, Buddy Hield led the Kings with 21 points, eight rebounds and three assists, while Bogdan Bogdanovic added 18 points, five assists, three rebounds and two steals, in 37 minutes off the bench. The Kings shot 44 percent from the field, including 16-of-39 from long range.

The Kings (4-7) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Celtics on Sunday. The Lakers (10-2) play host to the Hawks on Sunday.

The Miami Heat defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 108-97, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Thursday evening. 

The Heat (8-3) had no problems to secure another solid win thanks to a strong performance on the road against a struggling, inconsistent Cavaliers (4-7) team. Miami quickly jumped to a 34-22 lead following the first quarter, and they would never look back afterwards. Miami also won the second quarter by the same score, so they had an impressive 24-point lead at the break (68-44). Cleveland won the third and fourth quarters, 30-26 and 23-14, respectively, but that wasn't enough. Miami cruised their way to a win thanks to a solid effort on both ends of the court. With the win, Miami improved to 4-3 on the road while the Cavaliers dropped to 2-3 at home.

Kendrick Nunn was the best player for the Cavaliers since he ended with 23 points, eight assists, five rebounds, and two steals. Bam Adebayo registered 16 points and 15 rebounds, but also added five assists in 40 minutes. Jimmy Butler had 14 points, six assists, three steals and two blocks. Meyers Leonard had 12 points with seven assists. Tyler Herro looked impressive off the bench since he finished with 16 points in 22 minutes.

Kevin Love led the way for the Cavaliers with a strong double-double of 21 points and 10 rebounds, but he also added four steals. Collin Sexton had 15 points, four rebounds and three assists. Cedi Osman had 12 points and seven rebounds. Rookie Darius Garland had 11 points but shot 4-10 from the field. Larry Nance Jr. had 14 points and eight rebounds off the bench. Jordan Clarkson had 10 points.

The New York Knicks defeated the visiting Dallas Mavericks, 106-103, at Madison Square Garden on Thursday evening. 

The Knicks led through the entire first quarter, but the Mavs kept it close and trailed by four heading into the second. The Knicks stayed in front and pushed their lead to eight, before settled on a five-point lead by halftime. The Mavs came out strong in the third but trailed the whole quarter, until a put-back dunk at the buzzer by Kristaps Porzingis, to tie the game at 85, heading into he fourth. The Knicks reclaimed a slight advantage early in the third and kept one step ahead the rest of the way, as Marcus Morris hit a clutch three-pointer, with 13 seconds left, to help seal the Knicks' second home win of the season. 

Morris led the Knicks with 20 points on 7-of-19 shooting, including 5-of-7 from long range. Julius Randle finished with 17 points, 10 rebounds and three assists, while Dennis Smith Jr. added 13 points, eight assists and six rebounds, in 30 minutes off the bench. The Knicks shot 45 percent from the field, including 13-of-30 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Luka Doncic led the Mavericks with 33 points, 11 assists, 10 rebounds, three steals and a block. Kristaps Porzingis followed up with 20 points, 11 rebounds and three blocks, while Tim Hardaway Jr. and Dwight Powell added 12 points each. The Mavs shot 43 percent from the field, including 8-of-36 from deep. 

The Mavs (6-5) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Raptors on Saturday. The Knicks (3-9) play host to the Hornets on Saturday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Chicago Bulls, 124-115, at Fiserv Forum on Thursday night.

The Bucks (8-3) were playing their first full game in what is expected to be a multi-week absence for Khris Middleton (quadriceps), putting even more responsibility than usual on linchpins Giannis Antetokounmpo and Eric Bledsoe. Both players responded in fine fashion, but Antetokounmpo was especially impressive with a 38-point, 16-rebound double-double. The Bulls (4-8) admirably played a competitive game and even led 66-65 at halftime, but Milwaukee gained some separation in the third quarter and took an 11-point edge into the final period. Chicago would get as close as 117-114 with 1:53 remaining, but the hosts would finish on a 7-1 run to seal the win.

Coby White came off the bench to lead the Bulls in scoring for the second straight game, posting 26 points and adding five rebounds, three assists, and three steals. Zach LaVine was a close second with 25 points, complementing them with seven assists, three rebounds, three steals and one block. Wendell Carter, Jr. tallied 14 points, six boards and one assist. Lauri Markkanen and Thaddeus Young generated matching 11-point tallies while pulling down eight and seven rebounds, respectively.

Antetokounmpo added four assists, three steals and one block to his team-leading double-double. Bledsoe delivered 31 points, eight assists, four rebounds and two steals. Wesley Matthews managed 15 points and four boards. Brook Lopez contributed 13 points and six rebounds.

The Bulls return home to face the Brooklyn Nets on Saturday evening, while the Bucks pay a visit to the division-rival Indiana Pacers on Saturday night.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the Los Angeles Clippers, 132-127, at Smoothie King Arena on Thursday night.

What would have shaped up as a star-studded affair on the schedule prior to the season was instead a serious victim of attrition. The Pelicans (3-8) were particularly short-handed, with Zion Williamson (knee), Brandon Ingram (knee), Lonzo Ball (hip), Josh Hart (knee) and Jahlil Okafor (ankle) all out of action, while Kawhi Leonard (knee/load management) sat for the Clippers (7-5). However, Los Angeles did have their other prized offseason acquisition in action for the first time, as Paul George made his team/season debut after recovering from offseason surgery on both shoulders. George was spectacular, pacing the visitors with 33 points and adding nine rebounds and four assists. but New Orleans' 36-point fourth quarter was ultimately enough to garner them a tough home victory.

Lou Williams was a close second behind George with 31 points, adding eight assists, two rebounds and two steals. Rodney McGruder followed with 20 points, complementing them with three rebounds and two assists. Montrezl Harrell furnished 18 points, seven rebounds, six assists, two steals and two blocks. 

Jrue  Holiday paced the Pelicans with 36 points, supplementing them with seven assists, four rebounds, five steals and one block. Frank Jackson followed with a bench-leading 23 points and also posted five rebounds and two assists. Derrick Favors generated a 20-point, 20-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one block. J.J. Redick and E'Twaun Moore poured in 19 and 15 points in spot starts, respectively, while pulling down three rebounds apiece. 

The Clippers head back home to face the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday night, while the Pelicans pay a visit to the Miami Heat on Saturday night as well.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the visiting Atlanta Hawks, 128-112, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Thursday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start with multiple lead changes through the first quarter, before the Hawks took a two-point advantage into the second. The Hawks pulled ahead early in the second but the Suns closed the quarter on a 9-3 run, to take a six-point lead into halftime. The Suns carried the momentum into the second half, as they pushed their lead to 10, three minutes into the third quarter, and took a 14-point lead into the final frame. The Hawks had no answers and trailed by as many as 19 points, in the fourth quarter, while the Suns held on to move to 5-3 at home. 

Kelly Oubre Jr. led the Suns with 30 points, seven rebounds, three assists and two steals. Devin Booker totalled 27 points and seven assists, while Dario Saric added 23 points and six rebounds. The Suns shot 48 percent from the field, including 15-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Jabari Parker led the Hawks with 24 points, seven rebounds and three steals. Trae Young tallied 21 points and 13 assists, while Alex Len finished with 21 points and 10 rebounds, in 26 minutes off the bench. The Hawks shot 44 percent from the field, including 8-of-31 from long range. 

The Hawks (4-7) will look to bounce back as they take on the Clippers, in L.A. on Saturday. The Suns (7-4) play host to the Celtics on Monday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 101-93, at Pepsi Center on Thursday.

While Brooklyn led by 16 points early in the third quarter, Denver was able to prevail. In fact, the Nuggets rode a 52-32 second half to their win. Brooklyn didn't reach 20 points scored in either quarter of the second half, missing their final 19 three-pointers of the game. That was the difference, with the Nets hitting just from 8-of-38 from long range while shooting 38 percent from the field. Rebounding and ball movement was critical for Denver, out-rebounding Brooklyn, 62-51, while out-assisting them, 26-19.

The Nets (4-7) were led by Kyrie Irving, who tallied 17 points, six rebounds and nine assists on 8-of-20 from the field. Jarrett Allen amassed 17 points and 10 boards. Spencer Dinwiddie also scored 17 points, providing four assists to lead the bench. Taurean Prince totaled 12 points, eight rebounds and two assists. 

The Nuggets (8-3) were led by Paul Millsap, as he collected 18 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Nikola Jokic finished with 18 points, 10 rebounds and three assists. Will Barton accrued 17 points, six rebounds and four assists. Jerami Grant, Mason Plumlee and Monte' Morris all reached double figures in scoring off of the bench. 

On deck for Brooklyn is a road matchup versus the Chicago Bulls on Saturday. As for Denver, they return to action on Sunday when they travel to face the Memphis Grizzlies.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 119-117, at Spectrum Center on Wednesday night.

The Grizzlies (4-7) and the Hornets (4-7) endured a tightly-contested battle that ended with Memphis, and as a result, the Western Conference franchise are now riding a two-game winning streak following a sluggish start to the season. Charlotte jumped to a three-point lead after the first quarter (29-26) and they grabbed a one-point lead at the break despite Memphis' 37-35 lead in the second quarter, which left the score 64-63. Charlotte won the third quarter 32-31 so they had a two-point edge after three, but Memphis stormed back in the final 12 minutes of action. Their 25-21 win in the final period sealed the deal, and extended Charlotte's losing streak to four contests. The Grizzlies improved to 2-3 on the road, while the Hornets are now 2-4 at home.

Ja Morant led the way for the Grizzlies with 23 points and 11 assists, while Jonas Valanciunas chipped in with 18 points and 13 rebounds. Jaren Jackson Jr. had 16 points and grabbed six boards, and Dillon Brooks filled the stat sheet after tallying 15 points, four assists, three rebounds and two steals. Marko Guduric had a solid 17-point effort off the bench, while Brandon Clarke added 13 points in only 21 minutes.

Terry Rozier led the way for Charlotte with 33 points, six assists and five rebounds. Devonte Graham had 19 points and four assists, while Cody Zeller contributed 16 points, eight rebounds, two assists and two steals. Miles Bridges had 20 points and seven assists. Malik Monk thrived off the bench, finishing with 20 points, eight rebounds and five assists.

The Orlando Magic defeated the Philadelphia 76ers, 112-97, at Amway Center on Wednesday night.

Despite having a notably poorer record than the 76ers (7-4) coming in, the Magic (4-7) did have a rest advantage over the visitors. While Philadelphia had just played Tuesday night, Orlando had been off the prior two days. However, neither team gave an inch during a hotly contested first half that ended in a 53-53 tie. Philadelphia even entered the final period with a slight two-point edge, but the home squad's 32-15 run over the final 12 minutes ensured a comfortable home victory.

Josh Richardson paced the 76ers with 19 points, adding six rebounds, five assists and one steal. Ben Simmons supplied 18 points, eight rebounds and five assists. Al Horford registered 14 points, eight boards and two assists. James Ennis led the bench with 10 points, while Furkan Korkmaz furnished nine points and one steal. Tobias Harris mustered eight points, 10 rebounds, six assists, two steals and one block.

Nikola Vucevic led the Magic with a 25-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included two assists. Aaron Gordon followed with 18 points, 13 rebounds, seven assists, one steal and one block. Evan Fournier and Terrance Ross mustered matching 13-point tallies while dishing out three assists and pulling down three rebound, respectively. Jonathan Isaac and D.J. Augustin each pitched in 12 points and five rebounds, with Augustin also dishing out eight assists. 

The 76ers next pay a visit to the Oklahoma City Thunder on Friday night, while the Magic remain home and welcome in the San Antonio Spurs on Friday evening as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Washington Wizards, 140-133, at TD Garden on Wednesday night.

The Celtics (9-1) are arguably the hottest team in The Association and currently own the league's best record with an 8-1 mark following their eighth straight victory against a struggling Wizards (2-7) team that continues to slip down the Eastern Conference standings week after week. Things were quite even after the first quarter, however, as the first 12 minutes of action ended with a 34-34 tie although Boston would take control afterwards. The Celtics won each of the remaining three quarters (34-32, 34-30 and 38-37, respectively) and both teams combined for 273 points in total. The Wizards fought hard, but the Celtics were too much for them and as a result, Boston kept their sizzling winning run alive. With the win, Boston moved to 5-0 at home while the Wizards dropped to 1-4 on the road.

All five Boston starters scored in double digits and Kemba Walker was the team's leading scorer with 25 points, five rebounds and five assists. Jaylen Brown chipped in with 22 points, five boards and four dimes, while Jayson Tatum had 23 points, four assists and three rebounds. Marcus Smart finished with 17 points, five assists and four boards, while Enes Kanter had 13 points and nine boards. Carsen Edwards (18 points, four boards, three assists) and Brad Wanamaker (10 points) looked good off the bench.

Bradley Beal was Washington's best player thanks to a 44-point performance, but he also added six assists and four boards. Rui Hachimura had 21 points, four rebounds and two assists. Isaiah Thomas had 18 points and seven dimes, while Thomas Bryant registered 14 points with seven boards. Moritz Wagner had 12 points in 18 minutes off the bench.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Los Angeles Clippers, 102-93, at Toyota Center on Wednesday evening. 

The Rockets got out to a great start at home, with a 31-15 lead after one quarter. The Clippers picked it up in the second and a made it a single-digit game half way through the second, but the Rockets held the advantage and took a 12-point lead into halftime. The Clippers carried the momentum in the third, as they cut it down to a three-point game, minutes into the quarter. The Rockets held their position and pushed ahead again to take a six-point lead into the final frame. The Clippers started the fourth with a run to tie it up at 75, with nine minutes to go. The Clippers briefly took the advantage, but the Rockets closed the game on a 22-9 run, to secure their fifth straight win. 

James Harden led the Rockets with 47 points, seven assists, six rebounds and three steals, in 44 minutes. Russell Westbrook tallied 17 points, two rebounds and two assists, while Clint Capela added 12 points, 20 rebounds and two blocks. The Rockets shot 38 percent from the field, including 14-of-42 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Kawhi Leonard led the Clippers with 26 points, 12 rebounds, seven assists, a steal and a block, in 41 minutes. Lou Williams added 20 points, seven rebounds and four assists, while JaMychal Green tallied 14 points and 14 rebounds, off the bench. The Clippers shot 39 percent from the field, including 10-of-33 from long range. 

The Clippers (7-4) will look to bounce back as they take on the Pelicans in New Orleans on Thursday. The Rockets (8-3) play host to the Pacers on Friday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 129-114, at Target Center on Wednesday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, while the Timberwolves held the edge through most of the first quarter and took a two-point lead into the second. Both teams turned it up a notch in the second, where the Timberwolves outscored the visitors, 40-35, to a take a seven-point lead into the break. The pace kept up in the third, where the Timberwolves poured in another 40 points, to push their lead to 11, heading into the final frame. The Timberwolves did not let the Spurs have a chance in the fourth, as they pushed their lead up to 22, with three minutes left, before settling on the 15-point home win. This marks the second straight win for Minnesota and the third straight loss for the Spurs, 

Andrew Wiggins led the Timberwolves with 30 points, eight rebounds, seven assists, two steals and a block, in 32 minutes. Karl-Anthony Towns added 28 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and two steals, while Jeff Teague added 18 points and six assists, off the bench. The Timberwolves shot 50 percent from the field, including 11-of-34 from deep. 

Meanwhile, DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 27 points on 12-of-18 shooting, five rebounds, four assists, two steals and a block, in 33 minutes. LaMarcus Aldridge totalled 23 points on 10-of-16 shooting, while four other player scored in double digits for San Antonio. The Spurs shot 49 percent from the field, but shot just 3-of-17 from deep. 

The Spurs (5-6) will look to bounce back as they take on the Magic in Orlando on Friday. The Timberwolves (7-4) play host to the Wizards on Friday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Golden State Warriors, 120-94, at Staples Center on Wednesday. 

This is a new era for these franchises and a 26-point victory vindicates that notion. In fact, the Lakers ended the first quarter with a 38-26 lead and then held a double-digit lead for the entirety of the second half. Los Angeles shot 54 percent from the field and 45 percent from three-point range while holding Golden State to 40 percent from the field and 26 percent from long range. In addition, the Lakers out-rebounded the Warriors, 51-33 while out-scoring them in the paint, 64-36. 

The Warriors (2-10) were led by D'Angelo Russell, who tallied 21 points, two rebounds and eight assists. Draymond Green amassed 10 points and five assists. Willie Cauley-Stein generated 10 points, five rebounds, three assists and two blocks. Eric Paschall led the bench with 15 points and three boards. Glenn Robinson amassed nine points, four rebounds, five assists and three steals. 

The Lakers (9-2) were led by LeBron James, who collected 23 points, six rebounds and 12 assists in just 26 minutes of action. Kyle Kuzma totaled 21 points, five rebounds and two assists. JaVale McGee finished with 18 points, 17 rebounds, two assists, three steals and three blocks. Dwight Howard led the bench with 15 points, eight rebounds and three assists. 

Both teams return to action on Friday, with Los Angeles playing host to the Sacramento Kings while Golden State welcomes the Boston Celtics to Chase Center.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the host Portland Trail Blazers, 114-106, at Moda Center on Wednesday.

While this game remained close through the first three quarters, a 14-0 run by Toronto in the middle of the fourth quarter decided the game. In fact, that gave the Raptors a game-high 14-point lead and the Blazers could never recover from that. With that said, there were six ties and nine lead changes in total. Toronto ended up shooting 46 percent from the field, 44 percent from three-point range and 94 percent from the free-throw line while Portland shot 40 percent from the field, 35 percent from long range and 81 percent from the charity stripe. In addition, the Raptors out-rebounded the Trail Blazers, 50-43, while outscoring them in the paint, 50-22. 

The Raptors (8-3) were led by Pascal Siakam, as he tallied 36 points, six rebounds and three assists. Fred VanVleet accrued 30 points, four rebounds, seven assists and two steals. Marc Gasol collected nine points, five rebounds, five assists and four steals. Rondae Hollis-Jefferson led the bench with 16 points and 11 rebounds. 

The Trail Blazers (4-8) were led by Rodney Hood, who dropped 25 points. C.J. McCollum accumulated 19 points, six rebounds and four assists. Damian Lillard went just 2-of-12 from the field to finish with nine points and 10 assists. Hassan Whiteside amassed 12 points, nine rebounds and three assists while Anfernee Simons led the bench with 17 points. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Portland traveling to face the San Antonio Spurs and Toronto staying on the road to face the Dallas Mavericks.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder, 111-85, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Tuesday night.

The Pacers (7-4) entered this on a strong run of form with six wins over their last seven contests, and remain hot with another strong effort against a sluggish Thunder (4-7) team that didn't have enough weapons to control the Pacers' high-octane offense. Indiana quickly jumped to a 31-25 lead following the first quarter, and they would never look back. The Pacers won the next two quarters 21-17 and 34-20, essentially sealing the game with 12 minutes left to play. But despite the huge lead on the score, Indiana didn't sit back and also won the final quarter by a 25-23 score. With the win, the Pacers moved to 5-1 at home while the Thunder remain winless on the road thanks to a 0-4 record.

T.J. Warren was the top scoring threat for the Pacers after finishing with 23 points, but he also added three rebounds, three assists and two steals. Malcolm Brogdon had 20 points, six boards and five assists. Domantas Sabonis posted a strong double-double after notching 18 points with 16 rebounds. Aaron Holiday had 17 points, four assists and three boards. 12 of 13 Indiana players that stepped on the hardwood scored at least two points.

Only four Oklahoma City players scored in double digits in this game. Danilo Gallinari led the way with 14 points and four rebounds, while Shai Gilgeous-Alexander contributed 11 points and six rebounds. Steven Adams had 10 points with five rebounds. Deonte Burton chipped in with 13 points and three rebounds in 18 minutes off the bench. Chris Paul filled the stat sheet, and he finished with seven points, eight assists, five rebounds and three steals.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 98-97, at Wells Fargo Center on Tuesday night. 

The 76ers (7-3) got a nice boost in the form of an earlier-than-expected return from Ben Simmons, who was able to take the floor for his usual workload Tuesday after not having been expected back until later in the week. With Al Horford sitting the game out for rest, Philadelphia had trouble separating from the Cavaliers (4-6) in the first half. Cleveland then knocked two points off their six-point deficit during the third quarter, setting up a nip-and-tuck final period. Ultimately, Kevin Love failed to drain a 29-foot three-point jumper with 3.8 seconds remaining that would have erased the Sixers' 98-97 lead, essentially sealing the win for Philadelphia.

Love and Jordan Clarkson co-led the Cavaliers with matching 20-point tallies, with Love notably pulling down eight rebounds. Collin Sexton furnished 18 points, five rebounds, four assists and two steals. Tristan Thompson generated a 17-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included one steal. No other Cleveland player was able to score in double digits.

Joel Embiid paced the 76ers with a 27-point, 16-rebound double-double that also included four assists, two blocks and one steal. Josh Richardson tallied 17 points, five assists, one rebound and one steal. Simmons produced 15 points, six assists, five rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Furkan Korkmaz started and posted 10 points, four boards and one assist.

The Cavaliers return home to host the Miami Heat on Thursday night, while the 76ers pay a visit to the Orlando Magic on Wednesday evening.

The Miami Heat defeated the Detroit Pistons, 117-108, at American Airlines Arena on Tuesday evening.

The Heat (7-3) entered this game following a three-game road trip where they went 1-2, but they showed once again why they are one of the best teams in the league at home -- Miami led the way from start to finish, and cruised their way against a Pistons (4-8) squad that never had answers to slow down a depleted Miami squad that featured several absences. The Heat jumped to a 28-17 lead following the first quarter, and they would never look back afterwards since they also won the second quarter by a 31-20 score. With a 22-point lead entering the second half, Detroit required magic to turn things around. Even though the Pistons won the subsequent two quarters, 35-33 and 36-25 respectively, Miami tightened things up down the stretch and won the contest. With the win, Miami improved to 4-0 at home while the Pistons fell to 1-5 on the road. It was also Detroit's third straight defeat.

Jimmy Butler led the way for the Heat with an impressive double-double of 20 points and 13 assists, while also adding three boards and two steals in 39 minutes. Kendrick Nunn also had 20 points, and he added five assists, three rebounds and two steals. Bam Adebayo had 18 points with 14 rebounds, but he was ejected from the game in the second half. Goran Dragic came off the bench and delivered 18 points with six assists in 33 minutes.

Luke Kennard led the way for the Pistons since he finished with 22 points and five assists. Andre Drummond had 16 points, nine rebounds, two steals and two blocks. Markieff Morris had 13 points, three rebounds and three dimes. Christian Wood had 16 points off the bench, while Thon Maker chipped in with 12 points and three blocks in only 20 minutes off the bench.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the New York Knicks, 120-102, at United Center on Tuesday night.

The Bulls (4-7) appeared to set an early tone with a 30-point first quarter, and the Knicks (2-9) only managed to knock two points off an eight-point deficit heading into halftime. New York's best quarter was the third, when it managed to draw even with Chicago heading into the final period. However, a 19-0 run by the home squad between the 11:00 and 5:51 marks of the fourth quarter put the game out of reach.

Marcus Morris led the Knicks with 22 points, adding nine rebounds, one assist and one block. R.J. Barrett rebounded from a recent slump to generate 21 points, nine assists, six rebounds and two steals. Julius Randle and Taj Gibson had matching 17-point tallies while pulling down six and five rebounds, respectively. Kevin Knox led the bench with 10 points. 

Coby White paced the Bulls with 27 points, adding three rebounds, one assist and one steal. Zach LaVine followed with 25 points, complementing them with six assists, two rebounds and one steal. Wendell Carter, Jr. generated a 17-point, 12-rebound double-double. Lauri Markkanen and Kris Dunn had matching 13-point contributions while hauling in eight and five rebounds, respectively. 

The Knicks head back home to face the Dallas Mavericks on Thursday night, while the Bulls pay a visit to the Milwaukee Bucks on Thursday evening as well.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the host Denver Nuggets, 125-121, at Pepsi Center on Tuesday evening. 

The Nuggets got out to a great start at home, with an early 12-0 lead, but the Hawks fought back to make it a nine-point lead at the end of one quarter. The Hawks carried the momentum into the second and outscored the hosts by 18 in the quarter, to take a nine-point lead into halftime. The contest tightened up in the third, as both teams battled to a stand still, resulting in the Hawks taking a nine-point lead into the final frame. The Nuggets attacked quickly to start the fourth and tied the game at 101, with eight minutes to go. The Hawks responded and took the lead again, this time refusing to let the home team have another chance, as they held on to end a three-game slide. 

Trae Young led the Hawks with 42 points, 11 assists and four rebounds. Jabari Parker added 20 points, nine rebounds and four assists, while Alex Len chipped in 17 points and seven rebounds. The Hawks shot 53 percent from the field, I including 15-of-34 from long range. 

Meanwhile, seven players scored in double digits for the Nuggets, led by Will Barton, who finished with 21 points, nine rebounds, four assists and a steal. Nikola Jokic added 20 points, seven assists, six rebounds and three steals, while Jamal Murray tallied 18 points and eight assists. The Nuggets shot 44 percent from the field, including 11-of-41 from deep. 

The Nuggets (7-3) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nets on Thursday. The Hawks (4-6) take on the Suns in Phoenix on Thursday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the Phoenix Suns, 123-115, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Tuesday.

In one of the most competitive games of the season, it took 14 ties and 29 lead changes to determine a winner. In fact, neither club ever attained a double-digit lead. With that said, the Lakers finished the game on a 9-2 run after the game was 114-113 with three minutes remaining.  The Lakers dominated in the paint, winning the points in the paint battle, 70-42. In addition, Los Angeles ended up shooting 54 percent from the field while winning the rebounding differential, 44-39. The Lakers also out-assisted the Suns, 39-32.

The Lakers (8-2) were led by Anthony Davis, who tallied 24 points, 12 rebounds, four assists and two steals. LeBron James accrued 19 points, seven rebounds and 11 assists. Danny Green amassed 14 points and three assists while JaVale McGee totaled 11 points, three rebounds and three assists. Kyle Kuzma led the bench with 23 points and four boards.

The Suns (6-4) were led by Ricky Rubio, who collected 21 points, four rebounds and 10 assists. Devin Booker accrued 21 points, three rebounds and nine assists. Aron Baynes generated 20 points, six rebounds and three assists while Dario Saric accumulated 18 points, seven rebounds and two assists. Frank Kaminsky led the bench with 16 points, nine rebounds and three assists. 

Los Angeles will have to play again on Wednesday, playing host to the Golden State Warriors. As for Phoenix, they host the Atlanta Hawks on Thursday for their next fixture.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting Brooklyn Nets, 119-114, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Tuesday evening. 

The Nets got out to a great start on the road with a 35-29 lead after one quarter. They kept the pressure on through the second and managed to push their lead to 15 by halftime. The Jazz came out stronger in the third quarter and were able to trim the deficit down to eight, heading into the final frame. The Jazz absolutely took over in the fourth, as they tied it up at 94, minutes into the quarter and went on to outscore the visitors 25-20, the rest of the way to move to 6-0 at home. 

Donovan Mitchell led the Jazz with 30 points on13-of-26 shooting, in 38 minutes. Rudy Gobert tallied 18 points, 15 rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks, while Mike Conley finished with 18 points, five assists and four rebounds. The Jazz shot 47 percent from the field, including 6-of-26 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Kyrie Irving led the Nets with 27 points, five assists and three rebounds. Spencer Dinwiddie followed up with 21 points, off the bench, while DeAndre Jordan totalled 15 points, 17 rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks, off the bench. The Nets shot 46 percent from the field, including 11-of-37 from long range. 

The Nets (4-6) will look to bounce back as they take on the Nuggets in Denver on Thursday. The Jazz (8-3) head to Memphis to take on the Grizzlies on Friday.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the visiting Portland Trail Blazers, 107-99, at Golden 1 Center on Tuesday.

This was a true tale of two halves, with Portland leading for most of the first half and Sacramento taking control in the second half. In fact, Portland led by 11 points in the first quarter but a 35-21 third quarter allowed the Kings to lead by at least five points for the final 20 minutes of play. The key for Sacramento was their bench, outscoring the Trail Blazers bench, 38-17. In addition, the Kings out-assisted the Blazers, 24-15, while out-rebounding them, 46-40. Both teams shot exactly 44.2 percent from the field.

The Trail Blazers (4-7) were led by Damian Lillard, who tallied 27 points, four rebounds, five assists and two steals. C.J. McCollum amassed 24 points and five rebounds. Hassan Whiteside finished with 17 points and seven boards in 20 foul-troubled minutes. Kent Bazemore was the only other player in double figures, tallying 12 points, five rebounds and three assists.

The Kings (4-6) were led by Bogan Bogdanovic, who came off the bench to provide 25 points, four rebounds, 10 assists and four steals. Buddy Hield totaled 20 points and four rebounds. Nemanja Bjelica accumulated 19 points, 12 rebounds and four assists. Harrison Barnes generated 16 points, four rebounds and two assists while Richaun Holmes picked up 11 points and 10 rebounds en route to a double-double.

Portland will have to play again on Wednesday, playing host to the shorthanded Toronto Raptors. As for Sacramento, they travel to face the Los Angeles Lakers on Friday for their next fixture.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the host Detroit Pistons, 120-114, at Little Caesars Arena on Monday evening.
