The contest got out to a tight start with the score tied at 18, half way through the first quarter, but Timberwolves outscored the hosts 23-8 through the rest of the quarter, to take a 15-point lead into the second. The Pistons stabilized in the second but could not cut into the lead and trailed by 15 at halftime. They remained resilient in the third quarter and made it an 11-point game by the start of the final frame. The Pistons trailed by double digits for most of the fourth but made the Timberwolves grind right until the end to earn their fourth road win of the season. This marks a second straight loss for Detroit. 

Andrew Wiggins led the Timberwolves with 33 points, six rebounds and five assists, in 36 minutes. Karl-Anthony Towns finished with 25 points, eight rebounds and six assists, while Jake Layman chipped in 16 points on 6-of-9 shooting. The Timberwolves shot 51 percent from the field, including 15-of-34 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Luke Kennard led the Pistons with 25 points, seven rebounds and two assists. Blake Griffin tallied 19 points, seven rebounds and six assists, in his first action of the regular season. The Pistons shot 45 percent from the field, including 16-of-32 from long range. 

The Pistons (4-7) will look to bounce back as they take on the Heat in Miami on Tuesday. The Timberwolves (6-4) play host to the Spurs on Wednesday.

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting Dallas Mavericks, 116-106, at TD Garden on Monday. 

While Boston led for all but two minutes of this game, it was close down to the wire. In fact, there were four ties in the second half and two lead changes in the fourth quarter alone. With that said, Boston did end the game on a 22-13 run across the final five minutes when it was a one-point game. The Celtics ended up shooting 48 percent from the field and 43 percent from three-point range while holding the Mavericks to 42 percent from the field and 26 percent from long range.

The Houston Rockets defeated the host New Orleans Pelicans, 122-116, at Smoothie King Center on Monday evening. 

The Rockets pulled ahead late in the first quarter to take a seven-point lead into the second. The Utah Jazz defeated the Golden State Warriors, 122-108, at Chase Center on Monday night.

Alec Burks delivered 10 points off the bench, while Willie Cauley-Stein mustered just eight points but also pitched in 11 rebounds, two assists, two steals and one block.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Toronto Raptors, 98-88, at Staples Center on Monday night.

Towns also added 16 rebounds and six assists, while Wiggins chipped in with five assists and four boards. Isaiah Thomas managed 11 points, five assists and two rebounds.

The Cavaliers next pay a visit to the New York Knicks on Sunday night, while the Wizards are off until Wednesday night, when they'll tangle with the Boston Celtics at TD Garden.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 121-109, at State Farm Arena on Friday night.

The Kings (3-6) came into the contest looking to start a new winning streak after seeing their first one of the season snapped their last time on the court. Sacramento got off to a good start in that regard, building a 31-24 first-quarter lead that they'd expanded to 16 points by halftime. That cushion would prove to be pivotal, as the Hawks (3-5) came out strong out of intermission and outscored Sacramento by a 36-28 margin in the third to slice their deficit in half. That surge woke the Kings back up, as they finished with a 30-26 advantage over the final 12 minutes to notch the double-digit road win.

Buddy Hield paced the Kings with 22 points, adding five rebounds, one assist and one block. Bogdan Bogdanovic led the bench with 20 points and complemented them with five assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block. De'Aaron Fox followed with 17 points, nine assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block. Harrison Barnes contributed 16 points, four rebounds, four assists and two steals, while Trevor Ariza (14 points) and Nemanja Bjelica (13 points) were also in double digits. 

Trae Young paced the Hawks with a 30-point, 12-assist double-double that also included two rebounds and five steals. Jabari Parker delivered 25 points, eight rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Kyle Huerter led the bench with 17 points, and no other Atlanta player managed to score in double digits. 

The Kings return home to face the Portland Trail Blazers on Tuesday night, while the Hawks pay a visit to those same Blazers on Sunday night.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the visiting Golden State Warriors, 125-119, at Target Center on Friday evening. 

The contest got out to an exciting start with a back-and-forth first quarter, where the Warriors emerged with a two-point lead heading into the second. The teams stayed neck-and-neck through the second, as the Timberwolves trimmed it to a one-point game by halftime. After a close third quarter, the Warriors created some separation with a 5-1 run to end the quarter and take a six-point lead into the fourth. The Warriors held the edge and led by is with two minutes to go, but the Timberwolves closed the quarter on an 8-2 run to tie it up and send it to overtime. The Timberwolves carried the momentum into overtime, where they outscored the visitors by 15-9 to claim the six-point home win. 

Andrew Wiggins put up 40 points on 17-of-33 shooting, to lead the Timberwolves in the win. Karl-Anthony Towns finished with 20 points, 14 rebounds and four assists, while Robert Covington added 17 points, 11 rebounds, five steals and three blocks. The Timberwolves shot 44 percent from the field, including 9-of-36 from long range. 

Meanwhile, D'Angelo Russell tallied a career-high 52 points in his first game back after returning from an ankle injury. Russell shot 19-of-37 from the field and hit 7-of-8 free throws, in 40 minutes of action. Alec Burks chipped in 18 points, nine rebounds and two blocks, while Eric Paschall finished with 12 points on 3-of-10 shooting. 

The Warriors (2-6) will look to bounce back as they take on the Thunder in OKC on Saturday. The Timberwolves (5-3) play host to the Nuggets on Sunday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the host New Orleans Pelicans, 122-104, at Smoothie King Center on Friday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start with the score tied at 30 after one quarter. The Raptors started the second quarter on a 15-0 to blow the game open and held an 18-point lead at halftime. The Raptors pushed their lead to 29 late in the third but the Pelicans closed the quarter on a 10-3 run to make it a 22-point game heading into the fourth. The Pelicans kept scrapping in the fourth but it was not enough as they fell for their third straight loss. This marks the second straight win for the Raptors. 

Pascal Siakam led the Raptors with a career-high 44 points on 17-of-28 shooting, 10 rebounds and four assists, in 39 minutes. O.G. Anunoby added 21 points, seven rebounds, four assists, a steal and a block, while Fred VanVleet tallied 12 points, 11 assists, five rebounds and two steals. The Raptors shot 45 percent from the field, including 19-of-43 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Brandon Ingram led the Pelicans with 27 points and seven rebounds, in 31 minutes. Jrue Holiday added 16 points, six rebounds, six assists and three steals, while Frank Jackson chipped in 13 points, off the bench. The Pelicans shot 40 percent from the field, including 10-of-41 from deep. 

The Pelicans (1-7) will look to end a three-game slide as they take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Saturday. The Raptors (6-2) head to L.A. for a matchup against the Lakers on Sunday.

The New York Knicks defeated the host Dallas Mavericks, 106-102, at American Airlines Center on Friday. 

This game was actually tied 92-92 with six minutes remaining but New York finished the game on a 14-10 run to prevail. In fact, New York scored nine unanswered points from that point, as Dallas didn't hit a shot until the final minute. In total, there were seven ties and nine lead changes with neither team leading by more than 12 points. Three-point shooting was the difference for the Knicks, connecting on 14-of-28 while the Mavericks hit just 14-of-44. In addition, New York doubled up Dallas in offensive rebounds, 14-7. 

The Knicks (2-7) were led by Marcus Morris, who tallied 29 points, nine rebounds and three assists. Julius Randle accrued 21 points, eight rebounds and four assists. Frank Ntilikina finished with 14 points, six rebounds, four assists, four steals and three blocks. Bobby Portis led the bench with 14 points and 12 boards. 

The Mavericks (5-3) got another triple-double from Luka Doncic, who collected 38 points, 14 rebounds and 10 assists. Kristaps Porzingis was the only other starter with more than three points, amassing 28 points, nine rebounds and five blocks. Tim Hardaway Jr led the bench with 14 points, two rebounds and one assist.

Dallas will have to play again on Saturday when they travel to face the Memphis Grizzlies. As for New York, they play host to the Cleveland Cavaliers on Sunday for their next outing.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 100-97, at Pepsi Center on Friday. 

This ended up being the largest fourth-quarter comeback in Nuggets history, as they overcame a 21-point deficit with just 10 minutes remaining. In fact, the Nuggets ended up outscoring the Sixers in the fourth quarter, 35-13. Nikola Jokic was the hero, hitting a long-range two with less than two seconds remaining to take the Nuggets first lead since the opening minutes of the first quarter. Free-throw shooting was key for the Nuggets, connecting on 12-of-16 while the Sixers hit just 8-of-17. Turnovers were also critical, with Denver winning that battle, 16-10. 

The Sixers (5-3) were led by Joel Embiid, who tallied 19 points, 15 rebounds and two assists. Tobias Harris accrued 13 points, 10 rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks. Raul Neto started and amassed 13 points, two rebounds and six assists. Al Horford generated eight points, 10 rebounds, four assists and two blocks

The Nuggets (6-2) were led by Jokic, who collected 26 points, 10 rebounds, six assists, two steals and two blocks. Jamal Murray totaled 22 points, six rebounds, 11 assists and two blocks. Will Barton accumulated 20 points, seven rebounds and two steals. Paul Millsap finished with 15 points, eight rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks. 

Both teams return to action on Sunday, with Philly returning home to face the struggling Charlotte Hornets and Denver traveling to face the Minnesota Timberwolves.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting Milwaukee Bucks, 103-100, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Friday evening. 

The Jazz got out to a great start at home with a 30-16 lead after one quarter. They kept the upper hand through the second and pushed their lead to 22 points late in the quarter, before taking a 20-point lead into halftime. The Bucks picked up the pace in the third and outscored the Jazz by 13 in the quarter to make it a seven-point game entering the fourth. The Bucks kept pushing and had it down to a one-point game just minutes into the fourth quarter. The Jazz kept an edge for most of the quarter but thanks to a relentless effort the Bucks had the game tied at 100 with just one second left. The Jazz had one chance to end it and were successful, as they went to Bojan Bogdanovic off the side inbound for the game-winning three pointer.

Bogdanovic led the Jazz with 33 points on 9-of-19 shooting, in 37 minutes of action. Mike Conley added 20 points, three rebounds and three assists, while Donovan Mitchell chipped in 19 points, six assists, five rebounds and a steal. The Jazz shot 40 percent from the field, including 15-of-36 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 30 points, 13 rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks, in 36 minutes. Khris Middleton followed up with 26 points and 11 rebounds, while Eric Bledsoe tallied 22 points, eight rebounds, five assists and a block. The Bucks shot 36 percent from the field, including 10-of-36 from long range. 

The Bucks (6-3) will look to bounce back as they take on the Thunder in OKC on Sunday. The Jazz (6-3) take on the Warriors in Golden State on Monday.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the host Portland Trail Blazers, 119-115, at Moda Center on Friday.

A 26-20 first quarter in favor of Brooklyn really set the tone in this game, as they led for all but a few minutes after that quarter. With that said, there were seven ties and nine lead changes in total, with Brooklyn never leading by more than 10 points. Ball movement was the difference for Brooklyn, out-assisting Portland, 16-10. All of the other statistics like field goal percentage, rebounding, turnovers and blocks were all decided within two. Damian Lillard did drop a career-best 60 points despite the loss. In addition, the Nets bench outscored the Trail Blazers bench, 50-31. 

The Nets (4-4) were led by Kyrie Irving, who tallied 33 points, three rebounds and six assists. Spencer Dinwiddie led the bench with 34 points, five rebounds and four assists. Joe Harris totaled 14 points and five boards. Jarrett Allen accumulated 12 points, nine rebounds and five blocks. Caris LeVert accrued seven points, nine rebounds and five assists.

The Trail Blazers (3-6) got a gem from Damian Lillard, who collected 60 points, four rebounds and five assists on 19-of-33 from the field. Hassan Whiteside finished with 10 points, 15 rebounds and five blocks. C.J. McCollum went just 4-of-19 from the field to amass eight points, five rebounds and two blocks. Anferenee Simons led the bench with 15 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Sunday, with Portland staying home to face the Atlanta Hawks and Brooklyn remaining on the road to face the resurgent Phoenix Suns.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Miami Heat, 95-80, at Staples Center on Friday.

Los Angeles has been the best defense in the NBA according to efficiency ratings and they had yet another defensive gem here. In fact, the Lakers held the Heat to 35 percent from the field and 17 percent from three-point range while out-assisting Miami, 30-18. In fact, Miami missed 13 of their final 14 shots of the night, scoring just 14 points in the fourth quarter. The Lakers also out-rebounded the Heat, 48-37. That allowed Los Angeles to lead for all but one minute of this game. 

The Heat (6-3) were led by Jimmy Butler, who tallied 22 points, six rebounds, three assists and two steals. Bam Adebayo accrued 11 points, nine rebounds, four assists and three steals. Goran Dragic led the bench with 19 points, six rebounds and seven assists. Kendrick Nunn amassed 10 points, three rebounds and two steals. 

The Lakers (7-1) were led by Anthony Davis, who provided 26 points, eight rebounds, seven assists, two steals and three blocks on 11-of-17 from the field. LeBron James totaled 25 points, four rebounds and six assists. No other player reached double figures in scoring. JaVale McGee did have nine points and 10 boards while Kyle Kuzma led the bench with seven points and five rebounds.

On deck for Los Angeles is a home matchup versus the Toronto Raptors on Sunday. Miami will be off until Tuesday when they play host to the Detroit Pistons.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 108-87, at Spectrum Center on Thursday night.

The Celtics (6-1) are on an absolute roll and they have secured their sixth consecutive win after losing in the season opener, and they didn't have problems to defeat a Hornets (4-4) team that finished with 20 turnovers while dishing out just 21 assists. Boston were in absolute control of the game right from tip off, and they quickly jumped to a 30-20 lead after the first quarter. They would never look back, and they cruised the rest of the way while limiting every comeback attempt made by Charlotte, although the Hornets did won the second quarter 23-22. Boston's nine-point lead at the break extended in the second half, and the Celtics won the third and fourth quarter, 33-24 and 23-20, respectively. With the win, the Celtics improved to 3-1 away, while the Hornets are now 2-2 at home.

Kemba Walker went 0-for-6 in the first half, but settled down afterwards and finished with 14 points and six assists. Gordon Hayward was the Celtics' best player, however, as he came quite close to a triple-double after posting 20 points, 10 rebounds and six assists. Jayson Tatum was Boston's top scorer since he had 23 points with nine rebounds and two steals. Jaylen Brown had 12 points, and Javonte Green chipped in with 12 points off the bench.

The Hornets struggled offensively, and the best example of that was the fact that only two Hornets scored in double digits in this game. The main scorer was Miles Bridges, who had 18 points with 10 rebounds, while Devonte Graham contributed 15 points, nine assists and four rebounds. Cody Zeller grabbed 10 rebounds. Terry Rozier struggled, scoring just three points while going 1-for-11 from the field.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the Oklahoma City Thunder, 121-112, at AT & T Center on Thursday night.

The Spurs (5-3) and Thunder (3-5) played a highly competitive first half, resulting in a razor-thin 57-56 advantage for Oklahoma City. However, San Antonio erased that deficit and built an eight-point edge going in the final 12 minutes, and they then remained a step ahead of the visitors over the final 12 minutes to notch the victory. Both teams exceeded 50.0 percent shooting, but the Spurs won the battle of the boards by a healthy 47-31 margin.

Danilo Gallinari paced the Thunder with 27 points, adding five rebounds, one assist and two steals. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander followed with 21 points, adding three assists and one rebound. Chris Paul totaled 19 points, five assists, two rebounds and one steal. Dennis Schroder and Hamidou Diallo generated matching 11-point tallies off the bench, with Schroder notably dishing out nine assists as well. Steven Adams managed 10 points, five rebounds and three assists. 

LaMarcus Aldridge led the Spurs with 39 points, supplementing them with six rebounds, four assists, two steals and one block. Dejounte Murray posted a 17-point, 10-assist double-double that also included eight rebounds and a steal. DeMar DeRozan contributed 16 points, nine assists, six boards and one steal. Bryn Forbes poured in 14 points and also tallied six rebounds and two assists. Patty Mills led the bench with 10 points.

The Thunder will head back home to face the Golden State Warriors on Saturday night, while the Spurs host the Boston Celtics on Saturday afternoon.

The Miami Heat defeated the host Phoenix Suns, 124-108, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Thursday evening.

The Heat got out to a good start and built a 12-point lead halfway through the first quarter but the Suns rallied their way back to make it a one-point game heading into the second. The Heat pushed their lead to 12 again mid way through the second and held on to take a seven-point lead by halftime. The Heat pushed their lead to double digits early in the third and held the advantage through the quarter. The Suns trimmed the deficit to two late in the quarter but slipped back to trail by seven heading into the fourth. The Heat ran away with the score in the fourth as they widened their lead to 19 points with five minutes left and cruised to the road win. 

Jimmy Butler led the Heat with 34 points on 11-of-16 shooting, five rebounds and four assists, in 34 minutes. Goran Dragic added 25 points, six rebounds and four assists, in 31 minutes off the bench. Bam Adebayo filled the stat sheet with 15 points, 10 rebounds, six assists, five steals and a block. The Heat shot 55 percent from the field, including 15-of-28 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Aron Baynes led the Suns with 23 points on 10-of-17 shooting. Devin Booker followed up with 22 points, five assists, three rebounds and a steal, while Kelly Oubre Jr. chipped in 15 points, three assists, two rebounds and two blocks. The Suns shot 44 percent from the field, including 11-of-32 from deep. 

The Suns (5-3) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nets on Sunday. The Heat (6-2) take on the Lakers in L.A. on Friday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting Portland Trail Blazers, 107-101, at Staples Center on Thursday.

While Los Angeles led by seven points at the half, a 36-23 third quarter in favor of Portland made it a close game. The Clippers were able to prevail though, outscoring the Trail Blazers in the fourth quarter, 33-25 while finishing the game on a 23-11 run. There were five ties and six lead changes in total, with neither team leading by more than 11 points. The key for Los Angeles was defensive rebounding, winning that battle, 43-34. In addition, the Clippers tripled up the Blazers in blocks, 12-4. 

The Trail Blazers (3-5) were led by Damian Lillard, who tallied 22 points, six rebounds, six assists and three steals. C.J. McCollum totaled 22 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Hassan Whiteside accumulated 17 points, 19 rebounds and two blocks while Anfernee Simons led the bench with 17 points, two rebounds and two assists. 

The Clippers (6-3) were led by Kawhi Leonard and Lou Williams, who combined to score the final 19 points for Los Angeles. Leonard led the team with 27 points, 13 rebounds, four assists and two blocks while Williams led the bench with 26 points, three rebounds, eight assists and three blocks. Ivica Zubac totaled 15 points and 13 rebounds while Montrezl Harrell provided 15 points, six rebounds and three blocks off the bench.

On deck for Portland is a home game against the Brooklyn Nets on Friday. As for Los Angeles, they return to action on Monday when they play host to the Toronto Raptors.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the New York Knicks, 122-102, at Little Caesars Arena on Wednesday night.

The Pistons (4-5) didn't have major problems to take care of a struggling Knicks (1-7) team this Wednesday, dominating the contest on both ends of the court while cruising their way towards a dominant win. With the win, Detroit improved to 3-2 at home, while the Knicks are 0-5 and remain winless on the road. Detroit jumped ahead to a 33-25 lead in the first quarter, and they would never look back afterwards. Even though New York reduced the lead thanks to a 34-31 in the second quarter, the Pistons destroyed their rivals during the second half with scores of 32-26 and 26-17 in the remaining two quarters, respectively.

Andre Drummond was the best player for the Pistons since he finished with 27 points, 12 rebounds, seven assists and one steal. Tony Snell managed to score 24 points, and Luke Kennard came close to a triple-double after registering 12 points, nine rebounds and seven assists. Markieff Morris had 22 points, five assists, four rebounds and two steals. Langston Galloway had 12 points off the bench. Bruce Brown had nine points and six assists.

Julius Randle led the way for the Knicks with 20 points, three boards and two assists. Marcus Morris Sr. had 18 points, four rebounds, and three steals. R.J. Barrett contributed 15 points, eight assists and six rebounds, as well as two steals. Frank Ntilikina chipped in with 11 points and four assists. Kevin Knox II added 14 points off the bench.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Washington Wizards, 121-106, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Wednesday night.

The Pacers (4-4) came into the contest having just narrowly missed a fourth consecutive win against the Hornets in overtime Tuesday night. There may have been a bit of fatigue at play early, with the two teams battling to a 26-26 tie through the first 12 minutes. However, Indiana would go on to outscore the Wizards (2-5) by a 68-54 margin over the second and third quarters, giving them the separation they'd need to clinch a double-digit home win. 

Bradley Beal led the Wizards with 30 points despite shooting just 1-for-12 from three-point range, adding five rebounds and five assists. Thomas Bryant generated an 20-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included two assists. C.J. Miles poured in 15 points and also turned in three assists, two rebounds and two blocks. Davis Bertans compiled 11 points, four rebounds, two assists and one steal. Isaiah Thomas registered 10 points and four assists. 

T.J. Warren set the pace for the Pacers with 21 points, complementing them with four boards, two assists and one steal. Doug McDermott led the bench with 19 points and also supplied seven rebounds, four assists and one steal. Jakarr Sampson drew another start and provided 14 points, six rebounds, one assist, two steals and one block. Domantas Sabonis overcame his recent calf injury to contribute a 13-point, 17-rebound double-double that also included seven assists, two steals and one block. Goga Bitadze matched Sabonis' scoring tally and added three rebounds and an assist, while Malcolm Brogdon registered a 12-point, 13-assist double-double that also included one steal. 

The Wizards head back home to face the Cleveland Cavaliers on Friday night, while the Pacers remain home to tangle with the Detroit Pistons on Friday evening as well.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 113-93, at State Farm Arena on Wednesday night.

The Bulls (3-6) came into the contest a frustrated bunch after having blown a double-digit fourth-quarter lead to the Lakers on Tuesday night, but they quickly put the disappointment in the rear view mirror by building a 14-point lead through the first 12 minutes. After the Hawks (3-4) recovered to essentially keep pace in the second quarter, Chicago put the game away for good in the third by adding another 11 points to their edge, sealing their second road victory of the campaign. 

Tomas Satoransky led the way for the Bulls with 27 points, adding eight assists, seven rebounds and one steal. Lauri Markkanen totaled 17 points, six rebounds, four assists and three blocks. Otto Porter, Jr. supplied 13 points, four rebounds, two assists, two steals and one block. Kris Dunn matched Porter's scoring off the bench and recorded five steals among his other contributions. Zach LaVine and Colby White pitched in matching 10-point tallies, with LaVine notably adding eight rebounds, four assists, two steals and two blocks.

Jabari Parker paced the Hawks with 18 points and complemented them with five rebounds, one assist, two steals and two blocks. Vince Carter pitched in 14 points, five boards, one assist and one steal. Kevin Huerter was the only other double-digit scorer for Atlanta with 12 points. Trae Young delivered only nine points on 3-for-12 shooting, including an 0-for-8 tally from three-point range. He added three rebounds and three assists. 

The Bulls head back home to tangle with the Houston Rockets on Saturday night, while the Hawks remain home to face the Sacramento Kings on Friday night.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 124-120, at Scotiabank Arena on Wednesday evening. 

The Raptors got out to a great start at home as they outscored the Kings 36-23 in the first quarter. The Raptors held their lead through the second, while the Kings brought it to a five point-game before trailing by eight at halftime. The Kings came out strong in the third and trimmed the lead down again, but the Raptors pushed it back to a seven-point game heading into the fourth. The Raptors held a slight edge through the fourth as the Kings kept the pressure on. The Raptors pushed their lead to eight with two minutes left and held on to move to 4-0 at home this season. 

Kyle Lowry led the Raptors with 24 points on 8-of-15 shooting, in 40 minutes. Pascal Siakam added 23 points, 13 rebounds, five assists and two steals, while O.G. Anunoby tallied18 points, six rebounds, five assists and three blocks. The Raptors shot 54 percent from the field, including 14-of-29 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Harrison Barnes led the Kings with 26 points, four rebounds, four assists and a block. Buddy Hield added 21 points and eight rebounds, while Bogdan Bogdanovic totaled 22 points on 7-of-14 shooting off the bench. The Kings shot 44 percent from long range, including 20-of-44 from long range. 

The Kings (2-6) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hawks in Atlanta on Friday. The Raptors (5-2) take on the Pelicans in New Orleans on Friday.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Golden State Warriors, 129-112, at Toyota Center on Wednesday night.

The Rockets (5-3) had no problems to take on a depleted Warriors (2-6) team, to the point they won each single quarter separately towards a dominant 17-point win over the reigning Western Conference champions. Houston jumped to a 30-29 lead following the first 12 minutes of action and while Golden State tried to keep things tight, Houston improved their lead to 12 points after a 33-23 second quarter. Houston would extend their lead even further in the second half, winning the remaining two quarters 35-31 and 31-29, respectively, as they dominated the contest entirely. With the win, the Rockets improved to 3-1 at home, while the Warriors own a 1-2 mark on the road.

James Harden led the way for Houston since he finished with 36 points, 13 assists, four rebounds, three steals and three blocks. Russell Westbrook contributed 18 points, eight rebounds, and six assists. Clint Capela had 19 points with 16 rebounds and six blocks, while P.J. Tucker chipped in with 22 points, 11 rebounds and four steals. Danuel House Jr. added 17 points and six boards. Austin Rivers had 12 points off the bench.

Eric Paschall had 19 points and six rebounds for the Warriors, although the leading scorer came off the bench since Alec Burks scored 28 points in only 31 minutes of action. Glenn Robinson III had 15 points with 11 rebounds. Two bench players scored in double digits as well. Omari Spellman delivered 13 points with seven boards, while Damion Lee had 13 points, six rebounds and three assists.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the visiting Minnesota Timberwolves, 137-121, at FedEx Forum on Wednesday evening. 

The Grizzlies got out to a great start at home, with a 37-26 lead after one quarter. The Timberwolves picked up the pace in the second but could only cut the deficit by three, as they trailed by eight at halftime. The Grizzlies held their ground through the third but the Timberwolves continued to fight and managed to cut the lead to five, heading into the final frame. The Timberwolves made it a two-point game early in the fourth, but the Grizzlies closed the contest on a 29-15 run to put it out of reach. 

Dillon Brooks led the Grizzlies with 31 points on 9-of-16 shooting, in 30 minutes. Ja Morant had a big night as well, with 26 points, four rebounds and four assists. Jae Crowder tallied 18 points on 6-of-8 shooting, including 4-of-6 from long range. The Grizzlies shot 57 percent from the field, including 12-of-23 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Andrew Wiggins led the Timberwolves with 30 points, six assists, two rebounds, two steals and a block, in 34 minutes. Karl-Anthony Towns followed up with 25 points, 13 rebounds, two assists and two blocks, while Jarrett Culver finished with 15 points, seven assists and five rebounds. The Timberwolves shot 45 percent from the field, including 16-of-45 from deep. 

The Timberwolves (4-3) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Warriors on Friday. The Grizzlies (2-5) take on the Magic in Orlando on Friday

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the visiting Orlando Magic, 107-106, at American Airlines Center on Wednesday.

While Orlando led for 28 of the first 30 minutes of this game, Dallas was able to prevail thanks to a 32-23 third quarter. With that said, this game stayed within a five-point margin for the final 10 minutes of action. Nikola Vucevic had a chance to win the game as the buzzer but missed that three-pointer after Seth Curry missed two free-throws for Dallas. Three-point shooting was the difference for the Mavs, connecting on 11-of-31 while holding the Magic to 6-of-24. Orlando did record 14 steals and 10 blocks to Dallas' four steals and one block. 

The Magic (2-6) were led by Aaron Gordon, who accrued 23 points, four rebounds and two steals. With that said, he committed two offensive fouls in the final minute to foul out. Nikola Vucevic generated 19 points, 11 rebounds and seven assists. Jonathan Issac accumulated 13 points, 10 rebounds, five assists, four steals and six blocks. 

The Mavericks (5-2) were led by Luke Doncic, whi tallied 27 points, seven rebounds and seven assists. Dwight Powell amassed 12 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Kristaps Porzingis amassed 10 points and eight boards on 4-of-14 shooting. Maxi Kleber led the bench with 14 points, three rebounds and two assists. 

Both teams return to action on Friday, with Dallas playing host to the struggling New York Knicks and Orlando welcoming the Memphis Grizzlies to Amway Center.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 106-104, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Wednesday. 

While there were six ties and nine lead changes in the first half, a 26-17 third quarter in advantage of Utah snatched them the win. In fact, Philly never recaptured the lead after that despite outscoring Utah in the fourth quarter, 31-22. Offensive rebounding was the difference for the Jazz, winning that battle, 14-7. In addition, Utah ended up shooting 46 percent from the field while holding Philadelphia to 41 percent shooting. Free-throw shooting kept the Sixers in the game, connecting on 30-of-34.

The Sixers (5-2) were led by Joel Embiid, who finished with 27 points, 16 rebounds, three assists and two blocks on 16-of-18 from the free-throw line. Josh Richardson totaled 24 points, four rebounds, four assists and three steals. Tobias Harris accrued 16 points, seven rebounds and three assists. Ben Simmons departed in the first half because of a shoulder injury and didn't return. 

The Jazz (5-3) were led by Donovan Mitchell, who tallied 24 points, five rebounds and eight assists. Bojan Bogdanovic accumulated 20 points, six rebounds and five assists. Mike Conley amassed 15 points, six rebounds and two assists while Rudy Gobert totaled 14 points, 16 rebounds, three assists and three steals. Joe Ingles led the bench with 16 points, three rebounds and two assists.

Both teams return to action on Friday, with Philly staying on the road to face the Denver Nuggets and Utah remaining at home to face the surging Milwaukee Bucks.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Los Angeles Clippers, 129-124, at Staples Center on Wednesday.

While Milwaukee led for all but a few minutes of this game, it came down to the final seconds. In fact, the Clippers got the game to a two-point margin with a minute remaining but were unable to recapture the lead after Milwaukee led by 14 points with five minutes left. A 42-29 second quarter really put that margin between the teams, as Los Angeles never regained the lead after that. Rim protection was key for the Bucks, recording 11 blocks to the Clippers three. Turnovers were also critical, with Milwaukee winning that battle, 19-15. 

The Bucks (6-2) got another monster performance from Giannis Antetokounmpo, who finished with 38 points, 16 rebounds, nine assists, two steals and two blocks. Eric Bledsoe accrued 20 points, six rebounds and two assists. Khris Middleton amassed 13 points, three rebounds, two assists and two steals while George Hill led the bench with 24 points. 

The Clippers (5-3) had to play without Kawhi Leonard (rest), as Lou Williams got a rare start and led the team with 34 points, six rebounds and 11 assists. Montrezl Harrell generated 34 points, 13 rebounds and five assists in a starting role. Patrick Beverley tallied 20 points, 10 rebounds, three assists and two steals. 

On deck for the Clippers is another home game against the Portland Trail Blazers on Thursday. As for Milwaukee, they stay on the road to face the Utah Jazz on Friday for their next fixture.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the Indiana Pacers in overtime, 122-120, on Tuesday night.

The Hornets (4-3) were coming off a two-game winning streak ahead of this contest, but now they have won three games in a row. And while the Pacers (3-4) put up a fight and extended the game all the way to overtime, Indiana ended losing the match quite deservedly. Things weren't easy for the Charlotte franchise, however, as they were down by 15 points after the first quarter. The Hornets bounced back with a 37-29 win in the second quarter, but Indiana won the third quarter 28-21. Down by 14, Indiana managed to flip the script and later won this on overtime.

Charlottes main scoring threat here was Devonte Graham, who only needed 42 minutes of playing time coming off the bench and scored 35 points after going 10-of-21 FG, 4-9 3PT and 11-15 FT. Terry Rozier had another solid performance with 22 points, five rebounds and four assists in this game. Miles Bridges had 18 points and P.J. Washington contributed 16 points and three assists.

The Pacers didnt have Myles Turner or Domantas Sabonis for this game, but Malcolm Brogdon and T.J. Warren stepped up  while the point guard had 31 points with six assists and five rebounds, T.J. Warren had 33 points while going 15-of-18 from the field. Jeremy Lamb had 18 points, and he also dished out five assists. Indiana didnt have another player capable of also producing at least 10 points in total.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 119-113, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Tuesday afternoon. 

The Celtics (5-1) set a positive tone early in their quest for a fifth straight win, notching a 32-24 lead through one and a 61-52 advantage at the half. The Cavaliers managed to reduce their deficit by three heading into the final period, but Gordon Hayward, who tied a career high with 39 points on the night, fittingly crashed the boards for a key bucket off a Kemba Walker miss with 22.8 seconds remaining to extend Boston's lead after the Cavaliers (2-5) had closed to within 116-113.

Hayward added eight assists and seven rebounds to his game-high scoring tally. Walker followed with 25 points and complemented them with eight rebounds, three assists, two blocks and one steal. Jayson Tatum totaled 18 points, seven rebounds, one assist, two blocks and one steal. Carson Edwards led the bench with 13 points, while Marcus Smart filled out the stat sheet with eight points, five rebounds, four assists and one steal.

Collin Sexton paced the Cavaliers with 21 points, adding three assists, two rebounds and one block. Tristan Thompson generated a 19-point, 13-rebound double-double that also included four assists and one block. Kevin Love contributed 17 points, nine rebounds, three assists, two blocks and one steal. Larry Nance, Jr. furnished 15 points to lead the bench, while Jordan Clarkson and Cedi Osman pitched in 12 points apiece.

The Celtics remain on the road and pay a visit to the Hornets on Thursday night, while the Cavaliers tangle with the Washington Wizards on Friday night.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the San Antonio Spurs, 108-100, at State Farm Arena on Tuesday evening.

The Hawks (3-3) clearly felt the absence of Trae Young since they were 2-0 with him, and 0-3 since he got injured. The star point guard returned to action this Tuesday at home against the Spurs (4-3) and was pivotal for the win with an impressive showing. The game was tight during the first half, as the Spurs built a 45-44 lead following the first two quarters. Gregg Popovich's men built an eight-point lead (78-70) with 12 minutes left to play, but the Hawks turned things around in the final 12 minutes of action. A 38-22 win for Atlanta in the fourth quarter was enough to lift the Eastern Conference franchise on top in this game.

Trae Young was magnificent for the Hawks, since he finished with 29 points and 13 assists in his return from injury. Jabari Parker had 19 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Rookie Cam Reddish had 12 points, while DeAndre Hunter chipped in with 16 points and eight boards. The 11 players that featured for Atlanta scored at least one point.

DeMar DeRozan continues to lead the Spurs in scoring, and such was the case here once again since he finished with 22 points, four assists, four rebounds, three steals and two blocks. LaMarcus Aldridge had 14 points, and Bryn Forbes provided a strong scoring touch with 17 points in 31 minutes. Patty Mills delivered 16 points off the bench. Dejounte Murray struggled, however, and only managed to score three points in 19 minutes of action.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 118-112, at United Center on Tuesday evening. 

The Bulls got out to a strong start at home and held a 29-24 lead after one quarter. They carried the momentum into the second and outscored the Lakers 36-24 in the quarter, to take an impressive 65-48 lead at halftime. The Bulls had control to start the third and held an 18-point lead with four minutes left in the quarter. The Lakers closed the quarter strong and cut it to a 13-point game by the start of the fourth. They continued their push into the fourth, where they took their game to another level, outscoring the Bulls 38-19 in the quarter, to achieve an impressive comeback win. This marks the sixth straight win for the Lakers. 

LeBron James led the Lakers with 30 points, 11 assists, 10 rebounds, two steals and a block, in 35 minutes. Anthony Davis finished with 15 points, seven rebounds, three assists, three blocks and a steal, while Quinn Cook added 17 points on 6-of-9 shooting, off the bench. The Lakers shot 49 percent from the field, including 11-of-33 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Zach LaVine led the Bulls with 26 points, seven rebounds, seven assists and two steals, in 33 minutes. Otto Porter Jr. tallied 18 points on 58 percent shooting, while Coby White tallied 18 points, five rebounds, four assists and a steal. The Bulls shot 51 percent from the field, including 14-of-32 from long range. 

The Bulls (2-6) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hawks in Atlanta on Wednesday. The Lakers (6-1) play host to the Heat on Friday.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the visiting Orlando Magic, 102-94, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Tuesday.

While Oklahoma City led for all but a few minutes, this game stayed close throughout. In fact, there were eight lead changes, with neither team leading by more than 11 points. With that said, the Thunder led for 44 minutes of this 48-minute game. The key for Oklahoma City was three-point shooting, connecting on 13-of-32 while holding Orlando to 3-of-22 from long range. In addition, the Thunder won the rebounding battle, 53-38, while out-assisting the Magic, 21-15. 

The Magic (2-5) were led by Aaron Gordon, who tallied 15 points, eight rebounds and three assists. Markelle Fultz accrued 13 points, three rebounds and four assists. Jonathan Issac generated 13 points, 10 rebounds and three blocks while Nikola Vucevic finished with 10 points, 11 rebounds, two assists and two blocks.

The Thunder (3-4) were led by Shai Gilgeous-Alexander, who provided 24 points, three rebounds and two assists. Chris Paul amassed 20 points, two rebounds, six assists and three steals. Danilo Gallinari totaled 16 points, three rebounds and two assists while Steven Adams accumulated 11 points, 11 rebounds and three assists.

Orlando will have to play again on Wednesday, staying on the road to face the Dallas Mavericks. As for Oklahoma City, they travel to face the San Antonio Spurs on Thursday for their next fixture.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the visiting Miami Heat, 109-89, at Pepsi Center on Tuesday evening. 

The contest got out to a tight start, with the Nuggets holding a one-point advantage after one quarter. The Heat took a slight edge early in the fourth but the Nuggets rallied ahead and ended the half with a 10-point advantage. The Nuggets carried their momentum into the second half as they pushed ahead by another 10 points through the third, to take a 20-point lead into the final frame. The Heat put up a fight in the fourth but the Nuggets matched them for every bucket as they held their lead to the end. This marks the second straight win for the Nuggets, and the end of a three-game winning streak for the Heat. 

Jamal Murray led the Nuggets with 21 points, five rebounds, four assists and two steals. Will Barton tallied a double-double with 15 points and 10 rebounds, while Jerami Grant added 15 points, five rebounds, three assists and two steals, off the bench. The Nuggets shot 52 percent from the field, including 9-of-23 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Jimmy Butler was the high-point man for Miami, with 16 points on 2-of-12 shooting, in 29 minutes. Kendrick Nunn tallied 11 points, four assists, two steals and two rebounds, while Justise Winslow finished with 10 points and six rebounds. The Heat shot 36 percent from the field, including 9-of-29 from long range. 

The Heat (5-2) will look to bounce back as they take on the Suns in Phoenix on Thursday. The Nuggets (5-2) play host to the 76ers on Friday.

The Washington Wizards defeated the Detroit Pistons, 115-99, at Capital One Arena on Monday night.

The Pistons (4-4) and the Wizards (2-4) haven't been able to show a lot of consistency in their games so far, but in this occasion, the home side was miles better and didn't have many issues to secure the win here.  The first half of the game was quite even, though. Washington won the first two quarters, 31-30 y 32-31, respectively, but they would break free in the third quarter. A 30-17 win for Washington in the third quarter gave the Wizards a double-digit lead after three quarters, and a 22-21 in the final 12 minutes of action allowed them to close things out. Washington won three of four quarters by just one point. But the third quarters was the main difference here.

Bradley Beal led the way for the Wizards since he finished with 22 points, six assists and five rebounds. Thomas Bryant had 14 points with seven boards, and rookie Rui Hachimura ended with 12 points, four boards and three dimes. Troy Brown Jr. (14, 10 rebounds), Moritz Wagner (12 points) and C.J. Miles (12 points) thrived off the bench. Isaiah Thomas moved to the starting five and had nine points with six assists.

Andre Drummond paced the Pistons thanks to a 15-point, 24-rebound, four-assist and two-block performance. Luke Kennard had 24 points, five assists and four rebounds. Bruce Brown had 14 points, seven rebounds and seven assists. Tony Snell delivered 11 points with 4-14 from the field. Christian Wood had 15 points and four rebounds in 21 minutes off bench. Langston Galloway had 10 points.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the New Orleans Pelicans, 135-125, at Barclays Center on Monday night.

What promised to be a high-scoring matchup between fast-paced teams lived up to its billing, thanks in part to a massive 48-point third quarter on the part of the Pelicans (1-6). Things didn't start anywhere near as productively for New Orleans, with the Nets jumping out to a 67-50 halftime advantage. Ultimately, the visitors got as close as 121-119 with 4:43 remaining, but Brooklyn was able to close things out on a 14-6 run for the victory.

Brandon Ingram led the way for the Pelicans with 40 points, adding five rebounds, five assists and two steals. Lonzo Ball and Jrue Holiday were distant seconds with matching 15-point, three-assist tallies, with Holiday adding three assists and four steals. Josh Hart followed with 14 points, seven boards, one assist and four steals. Frank Jackson and J.J. Redick poured in 12 points apiece off the bench.

Kyrie Irving paced the Nets with 39 points complementing them with nine assists, four rebounds and three steals. Caris LeVert furnished 23 points, seven rebounds and five assists. Joe Harris tallied 19 points, four assists, three rebounds and one steal. Jarrett Allen generated an 18-point, 10-rebound double-double that also includes one assist and one steal. Garrett Temple offered 13 points off the bench, while Taurean Prince contributed a 12-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included four assists and four steals.

The Pelicans head back home and await a visit from the Toronto Raptors on Friday night, while the Nets hit the road and face the Portland Trail Blazers on Friday evening as well.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Memphis Grizzlies, 107-100, at FedEx Forum on Monday night.

The Rockets (3-3) were coming off a 129-100 drubbing at the hands of the Heat on Sunday that was actually much worse than the final score indicated, but coach Mike D'Antoni stuck to his plan of letting Russell Westbrook sit for rest Monday. The star point guard's absence helped lead to a tight 62-60 halftime lead for Houston, but the Rockets managed to turn the defense on in the third quarter. They limited the Grizzlies (1-4) to 16 points during the period and then hung on in the final period as Memphis bounced back with 24 points. As expected, James Harden shouldered extra offensive responsibility with Westbrook out and put up a game-high 44 points.

Harden added 10 rebounds, six assists, two steals and one block to his team-high scoring tally. Eric Gordon drew the start with Westbrook out and finished with 16 points, five boards, one assist and one steal. Danuel House, Jr. tallied 15 points, nine boards, one assist, three blocks and one steal. Ben McLemore poured in 12 points off the bench, while Clint Capela mustered a 10-point, 13-rebound double-double that included two assists and one steal.

Ja Morant paced the Grizzlies with 23 points, supplementing them with six assists, five rebounds and one steal. Dillon Brooks collected 17 points, nine boards, one assist and two steals. Bruno Caboclo posted 11 points, five rebounds, one assist, two steals and two blocks. Jonas Valanciunas contributed a 10-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one block. Kyle Anderson and Tyus Jones managed matching 10-point, five-rebound tallies. 

The Rockets head back home to take on the Golden State Warriors on Wednesday night, while the Grizzlies remain home to tangle with the Minnesota Timberwolves on Wednesday evening as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Minnesota Timberwolves, 134-106, at Target Center on Monday evening. 

The Bucks got out to a 10-point lead halfway through the first, but the Timberwolves rallied back to make it a three-point game by the end of the quarter. The Bucks pushed their lead back to 10, a few minutes into the second, and held the advantage for the rest of the quarter, taking a 64-57 lead into halftime. The Bucks came out on another level in the third and outscored the hosts 38-25 in the quarter, to take a 20-point lead into the final frame. The Bucks were able to cruise through the fourth on way to a third straight win, and their third road win of the season. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 34 points, 15 rebounds and six assists, in 27 minutes. Khris Middleton added 26 points on 9-of-15 shooting, while Eric Bledsoe added 22 points, nine rebounds and six assists. The Bucks shot 54 percent from the field, including 14-of-39 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Andrew Wiggins led the Timberwolves with 25 points on 10-of-21 shooting, in 31 minutes. Robert Covington added 15 points on 5-of-9 shooting, while Jordan Bell tallied 12 points, six rebounds and three assists, in 14 minutes off the bench. The Timberwolves shot 36 percent from the field, including 13-of-43 from deep. 

The Timberwolves (4-2) will look to bounce back as they take on the Grizzlies in Memphis on Wednesday. The Bucks (5-2) take on the Clippers in L.A. on Wednesday.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the visiting Philadelphia 76ers, 114-109, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Monday.

While Philly came into this game as the only undefeated team remaining in the NBA, Phoenix ended that here. It was close throughout though, as there were 11 ties and nine lead changes in total, with neither team attaining a double-digit lead. With that said, the Suns rode a 33-27 fourth quarter to victory, holding the lead for the final 10 minutes of action. Phoenix ended up shooting 53 percent from the field and 78 percent from the free-throw line while holding the Sixers to 48 percent from the field and 60 percent from the charity stripe. In addition, the Suns out-rebounded the Sixers, 40-38 while out-assisting them, 24-21. 

The Sixers (5-1) were led by Al Horford, who accrued 32 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. Tobias Harris finished with 24 points, 10 rebounds, two assists and two steals. Furknan Korkmaz got another start and tallied 20 points, five rebounds and two assists. Ben Simmons collected six points, five rebounds, six assists and seven steals. 

The Suns (5-2) were led by Devin Booker, who went 15-of-19 from the field to total 40 points, four rebounds and three assists. Ricky Rubio accumulated 21 points, seven rebounds and 10 assists. Aron Baynes finished with 15 points, seven rebounds, six assists and two blocks while Kelly Oubre Jr generated 14 points and six rebounds. 

On deck for the Sixers is a road matchup with the Utah Jazz on Wednesday. As for the Suns, they return to action on Thursday when they stay home to play the Miami Heat.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the visiting Portland Trail Blazers, 125-116, at Chase Center on Monday.

Golden State has an uphill battle with all of the injuries they've suffered but this was easily their best performance of the season. It was competitive throughout though, as there were nine ties and 11 lead changes in total. In fact, the Warriors largest lead came with less than five minutes remaining, outscoring the Trail Blazers in the second half, 67-55. The free-throw shooting was the difference in the game, with Golden State hitting 33-of-36 and Portland connecting on just 11-of-14. In addition, the Warriors out-rebounded the Blazers on the defensive end, 39-28 while out-assisting them, 28-16. 

The Trail Blazers (3-4) were led by Damian Lillard, who tallied 39 points, two rebounds and four assists. C.J. McCollum totaled 14 points and six assists. Hassan Whiteside returned from his one-game absence to amass 22 points, 11 rebounds and two blocks on 10-of-14 from the field. Anfernee Simons led the bench with 14 points, two rebounds and two steals.  

The Warriors (2-5) were led by Eric Paschall, who accrued 36 points and 13 rebounds. Ky Bowman got another start at point guard and finished with 19 points, four rebounds and eight assists. Jordan Poole went just 3-of-16 from the field but still accumulated 16 points, three rebounds and five assists. Damion Lee led the bench with 16 points, four rebounds, three assists and two steals.

On deck for Golden State is a road matchup versus the struggling Houston Rockets on Wednesday. As for Portland, they're off until Thursday when they travel to face the Los Angeles Clippers.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Chicago Bulls, 108-95, at Banker's Life Fieldhouse on Sunday.

The Pacers (3-3) started their season with an 0-3 mark, but they have bounced back thanks to three straight wins, although things have not been easy for them since they have dealt with injuries of late. The Bulls (2-5) never had an answer for Indiana's offense, and the best example for that was the fact that Indiana dominated the contest right from tip-off. Indiana jumped to a 24-18 lead after the first quarter, and they would never look back afterwards. They extended their lead to a 13-point edge at the halftime break after a 31-24 second quarter. While Chicago won the third quarter by a 32-31 score, their comeback fell short. The Pacers won the final quarter 22-21, and they didn't have problems to close the game out.

T.J. Warren paced the way for the Pacers, who didn't have Domantas Sabonis and Myles Turner, with 26 points, five rebounds and three assists. Malcolm Brogdon chipped in with 22 points and seven assists. Jeremy Lamb had 11 points, six rebounds and five assists. T.J. Lead had a good game off the bench, posting a 13-point, 15-rebound effort in 22 minutes of action.

Zach LaVine was the top scorer for the Bulls after finishing with 21 points, six rebounds and two assists. Wendell Carter Jr. had 20 points with 10 rebounds. Lauri Markkanen chipped in with 11 points and six boards. Thaddeus Young had a good game off the bench with 12 points, three boards and three steals in 26 minutes of action.

The Miami Heat defeated the Houston Rockets, 129-100, at American Airlines Center on Sunday evening.

The Heat improved to 5-1 and extended their current winning run to three games with an absolutely dominant performances against the Rockets (3-3), a team that currently has the worst defense in the NBA by a considerable margin. The game was done -- as a competitive contest -- following the first quarter, where Miami somehow built an impressive 32-point lead (46-14). The Rockets bounced back in the second quarter and showed some signs of life, but only managed to reduce the gap by seven points (32-25). Miami won the remaining two quarters, 28-25 and 30-29 respectively, but they had secured the win following the first 12 minutes of action. They were no match for a Houston defense that keeps looking worse and worse after each game.

Six Miami players scored in double digits. Duncan Robinson led the way with 23 points and six rebounds. Jimmy Butler chipped in with 18 points, nine assists, seven rebounds and four steals. Meyers Leonard had 21 points, four boards and three steals. James Johnson had 17 points off the bench, while Goran Dragic (15 points) and Tyler Herro (12 points, seven rebounds) also reach double-digit scoring. Kendrick Nunn only scored five points.

James Harden had 29 points, although 14 of those came from the line. Russell Westbrook, however, struggled badly and while had 10 points with six assists, he went 3-for-11 from the field. Chris Clemons (16 points), Ben McLemore (14 points) and Danuel House Jr. (10 points) all scored in double figures, but most of those points came when the game was already decided.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the New York Knicks, 113-92, at Madison Square Garden on Sunday evening.

The Kings (2-5) came in looking to right their ship after stumbling to four losses in their first five games, and they set the right tone with a 61-41 halftime lead. By the conclusion of the third quarter, they'd added another six points to their advantage, leaving them poised for the easy victory. As the final score implies, Sacramento got the best of the Knicks (1-6) in the majority of categories, with particularly sizable advantages in shooting percentage (48.2 percent-40.0 percent) and rebounds (49-39). 

De'Aaron Fox led the way for the Kings with 24 points, adding six assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block. Buddy Hield poured in 22 points and added four rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Harrison Barnes produced 19 points, four boards, one assist, one steal and one block. Richaun Holmes generated a 14-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one block. Nemanja Bjelica turned in 10 points, eight rebounds, six assists and one steal. 

Marcus Morris paced the Knicks with 28 points, complementing them with six boards, two assists and one block. R.J. Barrett produced 22 points, five boards, three assists and one block. Allonzo Trier delivered 11 points, four rebounds, four assists and one block. Mitchell Robinson managed 10 points, five rebounds, two blocks and one steal. 

The Kings remain on their East Coast swing and take on the Toronto Raptors on Wednesday evening, while the Knicks pay a visit to the Detroit Pistons on Wednesday night as well.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the host San Antonio Spurs, 103-96, at AT&T Center on Sunday evening 

The Lakers got out to a good start on the road, with a seven-point lead mid way through the first quarter but the Spurs pushed back to make it a one-point game heading into the second. The Lakers outscored the Spurs 26-12 through the final seven minutes of the second quarter to take a 13-point lead into halftime. The Spurs came out with a sense of urgency in the third and chipped the deficit down to just five points by the end of the quarter. They carried some momentum into the fourth and continued to chip away until they tied it up at 90, with four minutes to go. However, the Lakers responded immediately with a 7-0 run, from which they did not look back, as they closed out the contest for their fifth straight win. 

LeBron James tallied a triple-double with 21 points, 11 rebounds and 13 assists, in 37 minutes for the Lakers. Anthony Davis added a double-double with 25 points and 11 rebounds, while Dwight Howard tallied a double-double off the bench, with 14 points and 13 rebounds. The Lakers shot 48 percent from the field, including 6-of-24 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Dejounte Murray led the Spurs with 18 points, 11 rebounds, four assists, two steals and a block. Rudy Gay added a double-double off the bench, with 16 points and 10 rebounds, while DeMar DeRozan finished with 14 points, seven rebounds and five assists. The Spurs shot 40 percent from the field, including 6-of-25 from long range. 

The Spurs (4-2) will look to bounce back as they take on the Hawks in Atlanta on Tuesday. The Lakers (5-1) take on the Bulls in Chicago on Tuesday.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the host Cleveland Cavaliers, 131-111, at Rocket Mortgage FieldHouse on Sunday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start, as the Mavericks led by three at the end of one quarter. The Cavs pushed back to take a four-point lead mid way through the second, but the Mavs went on a 22-13 run, to push their lead to five by halftime. Both teams came out hot in the third and the score stayed close until the Mavericks blew open a 10-point lead with just 1:39 left in the quarter. However, the Cavaliers went on a 10-4 run to end the quarter and cut the deficit to four points heading into the final frame. The Mavericks turned it up a notch in the fourth and pushed their lead to 11, just minutes into the quarter. They poured in a total of 41 points in the quarter secure their third road win and remain undefeated on the road. 

Luka Doncic tallied an impressive triple-double for the second straight game, with 29 points, 15 assists and 14 rebounds, in 34 minutes. Kristaps Porzingis finished with 18 points and nine rebounds, while five other players scored in double digits for Dallas. The Mavericks shot 53 percent from the field, including 20-of-41 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Kevin Love led the Cavaliers with 29 points, eight rebounds, two assists, a block and a steal, in 35 minutes. Tristan Thompson finished with 11 points and 12 rebounds, while Jordan Clarkson chipped in 17 points off the bench. The Cavs shot 41 percent from the field, including 18-of-48 from long range. 

The Cavs (2-4) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Celtics on Tuesday. The Mavs (4-2) play host to the Magic on Wednesday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting Utah Jazz, 105-94, at Staples Center on Sunday.

While there were eight ties in this game, Los Angeles took control in the final quarter. In fact, the Clippers outscored the Jazz, 40-25, in the fourth quarter. Los Angeles' bench was critical, outscoring Utah's bench, 50-19. In addition, the Clippers outrebounded the Jazz, 54-37, while winning the turnover differential, 14-9. 

The Jazz (4-3) were led by Donovan Mitchell, who tallied 36 points, four rebounds, six assists and two steals. Bojan Bogdanovic accrued 19 points, three rebounds and four assists. Rudy Gobert amassed 12 points and 14 boards. Mike Conley's struggles continued with eight points and one assist on 2-of-10 from the field.

The Clippers (5-2) were led by Kawhi Leonard, who collected 30 points, six rebounds, three assists and three steals. Ivica Zubac amassed 11 points and nine boards. Patrick Beverley accumulated four points, nine rebounds, three assists and two steals. Montrezl Harrell led the bench with 19 points, eight rebounds and two assists while Lou Williams provided 17 points, five rebounds and three assists. 

Both teams return to action on Wednesday, with Utah playing host to the undefeated Philadelphia 76ers and Los Angeles staying home to face the Milwaukee Bucks.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 115-104, at Smoothie King Center on Saturday.

While there were seven ties and nine lead changes in this game, Oklahoma City led throughout. In fact, the Thunder held the lead for the final 18 minutes of play, outscoring the Pelicans by at least three points in the first, third and fourth quarters. Defense was the difference in the game, with OKC recording eight steals and 11 blocks while winning the turnover differential, 16-12. In addition. the Thunder shot 46 percent from the field and 41 percent from three-point range while the Pelicans shot 43 percent from the field, 34 percent from long range and 59 percent from the free-throw line.

The Pelicans (1-5) leading scorer came off the bench, with J.J. Redick providing 17 points and three boards. Josh Hart also played well off the bench, accruing 12 points, 15 rebounds and three assists. Jrue Holiday led the starters with 16 points, three rebounds and six assists. Jahlil Okafor amassed 15 points, 12 rebounds, three assists and two blocks while Lonzo Ball accumulated 10 points, eight rebounds, seven assists and three steals. Brandon Ingram left in the second quarter due to an unknown injury.

The Thunder (2-4) were led by Shai Gilgeous-Alexander, finishing with 23 points, eight rebounds and four assists. Chris Paul accrued 15 points, nine assists and three steals. Danilo Gallinari totaled 16 points and four boards while Dennis Schroder led the bench with 17 points and nine rebounds. Nerlens Noel got a rare start and collected eight points, three rebounds and six blocks. 

New Orleans will return to action on Monday, traveling to face the Brooklyn Nets. As for Oklahoma City, they play host to the Orlando Magic on Tuesday for their next outing.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 113-109, at Little Caesars Arena on Saturday night.

A rollercoaster first half culminated with the Nets (2-4) holding a 54-46 lead. However, the Pistons (3-4) erased that deficit and built a six-point advantage heading into the final period, where the tide would turn once more. After Detroit had expanded its edge to 12 points with 6:49 remaining, Brooklyn went on a 22-11 run that got them to within one point at 106-105 with 41.6 seconds remaining following two Kyrie Irving free throws. Detroit was able to separate just enough from that point forward to close out the narrow victory. 

Irving led the Nets with a 20-point, 11-rebound, 10-assist triple-double. Taurean Prince matched Irving's scoring tally and added one rebound, one assist and one steal. Joe Harris poured in 18 points, adding two rebounds and two assists. Spencer Dinwiddie provided 16 points, six assists and three rebounds. Caris LeVert furnished 14 points, six rebounds and one assist. DeAndre Jordan generated a 10-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included three assists, one steal and four blocks. 

Andre Drummond paced the Pistons with a 25-point, 20-rebound double-double that also included six assists, three steals and five blocks. Luke Kennard followed with 24 points, four assists and three rebounds. Bruce Brown supplied 22 points, seven assists, two rebounds and two steals. Markieff Morris registered 13 points, four rebounds, two assists and one steal. Langston Galloway led the bench with 12 points.

The Nets return home and take on the New Orleans Pelicans on Monday night, while the Pistons hit the road to tangle with the Washington Wizards on Monday evening as well.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the host Golden State Warriors, 93-87, at Chase Center on Saturday evening. 

The first quarter featured multiple lead changes before the Warriors took a 30-25 lead into the second. The Warriors pushed their lead to 10 but the Hornets closed the gap back to five by the end of the half. The third quarter was a low-scoring one, as the two teams combined for 34 point, while the Hornets closed the gap by two, to make it three-point game heading into the final frame. The contest went right down to the wire as the Hornets led 88-87 with 12 seconds left and hit four free throws to secure their second straight road win. This marks the third straight loss for the Warriors. 

Dwayne Bacon led the Hornets with 25 points on 10-of-21 shooting, six rebounds, two assists and two steals, in 37 minutes. Terry Rozier added 20 points, seven assists and five rebounds, while three other players scored in double digits for Charlotte. The Hornets shot 42 percent from the field, including 5-of-29 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Eric Paschall led the Warriors with 25 points on 10-of-18 shooting, in 35 minutes. Glen Robinson III added 16 points, nine rebounds, three assists and two steals, while Ky Bowman tallied 16 points, seven rebounds, four assists and two steals. The Warriors shot 45 percent from the field, including 9-of-28 from long range. 

The Warriors (1-5) will look to end their slide as they play host to the Trail Blazers on Monday. The Hornets (3-3) play host to the Pacers on Tuesday.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Orlando Magic, 91- 87, at Amway Center on Saturday evening. 

The Magic got out to a good start at home, as they never trailed in the first quarter and took a 26-17 lead into the second. They held the lead through the entire second quarter, while the Nuggets managed to trim the deficit to five by halftime. The Magic came out strong in the third and pushed their lead back to nine, but the Nuggets kept chipping away to finally take the lead with four minutes left in the quarter. The Nuggets held the lead for the rest of the quarter and took a 69-63 lead into the final frame. They pushed their lead to eight early the fourth and did not let up, as they held the lead the rest of the way, en route to their third road win. 

Jamal Murray led the Nuggets with 22 points, four rebounds, two assists and a steal, in 32 minutes. Nikola Jokic finished with 20 points, seven rebounds and four assists, while Gary Harris added 13 points, four rebounds, four assists and a steal. The Nuggets shot 37 percent from the field, including 9-of-28 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Nikola Vucevic led the Magic with 24 points, seven rebounds and two assists, in 33 minutes. Aaron Gordon added 21 points, nine rebounds and three assists, while Evan Fournier chipped in 11 points and five assists. The Magic shot 43 percent from the field, including 6-of-29 from long range. 

The Magic (2-4) will look to bounce back as they visit OKC to take on the Thunder on Tuesday. The Nuggets (4-2) play host to the Heat on Tuesday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the host Washington Wizards, 131-109, at Verizon Center on Saturday.

It's rare to see a road team win in wire-to-wire fashion but that's what Minnesota did here. In fact, the Timberwolves rode a 42-34 first quarter to a big lead and then carried a 28-22 second quarter and 36-16 third quarters to their dominating victory. That gave them a game-high 34-point lead heading into the fourth quarter. Minnesota won the defensive rebounding battle, 44-31 while out-assisting Washington 33-21. They also shot 54 percent from the field and 44 percent from three-point range while holding the Wizards to 39 percent from the field and 34 percent from long range. 

The Timberwolves (4-1) had to play this game without Karl-Anthony Towns but were led by Andrew Wiggins and his 21 points, five rebounds and six assists. Jeff Teague accrued 15 points, four rebounds, 13 assists and three steals. Gorgui Dieng started for Towns and provided 18 points, eight rebounds, two steals and three blocks. Jarrett Culver led the bench with 20 points and five boards.

The Wizards (1-4) were led by Bradley Beal, who scored 30 points but committed six turnovers. No other starter reached double figures in scoring but Thomas Bryant did amass three points, 10 rebounds, two assists and two steals. Isaiah Thomas led the bench with 16 points, four rebounds and seven assists. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Washington playing host to the Detroit Pistons and Minnesota welcoming the Milwaukee Bucks to Target Center.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the host Memphis Grizzlies, 114-105, at FedEx Forum on Saturday evening. 

The first quarter started out close until the Suns closed on an 18-11 run to take a 31-24 lead into the second. The Suns pushed their lead to 12 early in the second but the Grizzlies outscored the Suns 19-7 through the final seven minutes of the quarter to take a two-point lead into halftime. The Suns came out on fire in the third and outscored the Grizzlies 37-22 in the quarter to take an 82-69 lead into the final frame. The Suns stayed on top for the rest of the way, holding a double-digit lead for most of the quarter, before settling on the nine-point victory, for their second straight win. This marks the second straight loss for the Grizzlies. 

Devin Booker led the Suns with 21 points on 8-of-13 shooting. Aron Baynes followed up with 20 points, four assists and two rebounds, while Kelly Oubre Jr. tallied 15 points on 7-of-14 shooting. Frank Kaminsky added 14 points and five rebounds off the bench. The Suns shot 50 percent from the field, including 14-of-34 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Ja Morant led the Grizzlies with 24 points on 9-of-16 shooting, seven assists, three rebounds and one block, in 29 minutes. Dillon Brooks finished with 16 points on 6-of-12 shooting, while Jonas Valanciunas added 13 points, seven rebounds and two assists. The Grizzlies shot 49 percent from the field, including 9-of-28 from deep. 

The Grizzlies (1-4) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nuggets on Monday. The Suns (4-2) play host to the Sixers on Monday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Toronto Raptors, 115-105, at Fiserv Forum on Saturday night.

The Bucks (4-2) seeming opened the contest ready to make a statement, building an impressive 36-17 lead through 12 minutes. The Raptors (4-2) were much better in the second quarter while compiling 33 points, but they only shaved three points off their deficit. However, they came out of the halftime locker room just as hot and entered the final period trailing by just five points. That's when Milwaukee turned up the defensive dial, limiting Toronto to just 15 points during the fourth quarter and going on a 13-7 run over the final 5:41 to seal the home win.

Kyle Lowry led the way for the Raptors with 36 points, adding six assists, four rebounds and one block. Pascal Siakam delivered 16 points, five boards, one assist and one steal. Fred VanVleet totaled 12 points, seven assists and six rebounds. Serge Ibaka furnished 11 points and four boards off the bench. Marc Gasol generated a 10-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included three assists and one block. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo paced the Bucks with 36 points and complemented them with 15 rebounds, eight assists, four blocks and one steal. Eric Bledsoe registered 14 points, nine rebounds, five assists and one steal. Brook Lopez and Khris Middleton generated matching 11-point tallies, with Middleton also dishing out seven assists. 

The Raptors return home to take on the Sacramento Kings on Wednesday night, while the Bucks pay a visit to the Minnesota Timberwolves on Monday night.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Portland Trail Blazers, 129-128, at Moda Center on Saturday night.

The 76ers (5-0) came into the night knowing they'd be facing an uphill battle to keep their record unblemished without the services of Joel Embiid (suspension). Philadelphia had won one game without Embiid already this season, however, but they quickly fell behind by a 68-57 margin to the Trail Blazers (3-3) at halftime. The visitors would then begin their comeback in the third quarter, setting up a wild fourth quarter. The Sixers were down by as much as 125-118 with 3:25 remaining, but an 11-3 run culminating in Furkan Korkmaz's 24-foot three-point jumper with 0.4 seconds left won the game for Philadelphia.

Al Horford led the way for the 76ers with 25 points, adding seven assists, five rebounds, two blocks and one steal. Tobias Harris followed with 23 points, seven boards, three assists, two blocks and one steal. Ben Simmons delivered 18 points, 11 rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Josh Richardson poured in 17 points and also furnished six assists, four rebounds, one steal and one block. Mike Scott led the bench with 12 points, while Korkmaz tallied 11 points, three rebounds, two assists and two blocks.

Damian Lillard paced the Trail Blazers with 33 points and supplemented them with nine assists, five rebounds and two steals. Rodney Hood poured in 25 points and added two rebounds, one assist and one steal. C.J. McCollum pitched in 16 points, three boards and one assist. Skal Labissiere led the bench with 15 points and also pulled down four boards, while Anfernee Simons put up 13 points. Mario Hezonja drew the start with Hassan Whiteside (knee) out of action and mustered an 11-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included four assists and two steals. 

The 76ers remain on the road and visit the Phoenix Suns on Monday night, while the Trail Blazers pay a visit to the Golden State Warriors on Monday evening.

The Brooklyn Nets defeated the Houston Rockets, 123-116, at Barclays Center on Friday night. 

Two teams with tremendous offensive firepower fittingly combined for 120 first-half points, with the Nets (2-3) holding a slim 61-59 lead. Brooklyn managed to add 10 points to its advantage during the third quarter, seemingly leaving them in the driver's seat heading into the final period. However, the Rockets (3-2) managed to close to within 111-106 with as little as 3:50 remaining before Brooklyn pulled away sufficiently to earn the hard-fought home win.

James Harden led the Rockets with 36 points, adding eight assists and five rebounds. Russell Westbrook followed with 27 points, eight assists, seven rebounds, four steals and one block. Danuel House, Jr. delivered 15 points, five rebounds, one steal and one block. Clint Capela tallied 10 points, four rebounds and one steal. P.J. Tucker and Ben McLemore contributed nine points each, with Tucker also pulling down eight rebounds. 

Taurean Prince paced the Nets with a 27-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included one assist, one steal and one block. Caris LeVert managed 25 points, four rebounds, four assists and one steal. Kyrie Irving generated a 22-point, 10-assist double-double that also included four rebounds and one block. Garrett Temple poured in 16 points while adding seven rebounds, three assists, two steals and two blocks. Joe Harris pitched in 15 points, nine rebounds, two assists and three steals. 

The Rockets next pay a visit to the Miami Heat on Sunday evening, while the Nets pay a visit to the Detroit Pistons on Saturday night.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 102-95, at Bankers Life Fieldhouse on Friday night.

The Pacers (2-3) had gotten their season off to an uncharacteristically poor start, but Friday, they were returning to the scene of the majority of their successes last season. Indiana had a bit of revenge to extract on the Cavaliers (2-3) after Cleveland had already handed them a loss in the second game of the campaign.
