The visitors looked to be on their way to getting the better of Indiana again early by building a 26-19 lead through 12 minutes, but the home squad managed to turn the tables and then some in the second to take a 42-37 lead into halftime. Indiana then preserved their lead by holding off an early fourth-quarter surge by Cleveland with the help of a 12-3 run later in the period.

Kevin Love paced the Cavaliers with a 22-point, 17-rebound double-double that also included four assists and one steal. Collin Sexton followed with 21 points, complementing them with three rebounds, two assists and two steals. Jordan Clarkson led the bench with 20 points and also posted five assists, two rebounds, one steal and one block. Cedi Osman contributed 10 points, four rebounds, one assist and three steals. Tristan Thompson mustered just seven points but also pulled down 10 rebounds. 

Malcolm Brogdon led the Pacers with 25 points and supplemented them with nine rebounds, six assists, one steal and one block. Jeremy Lamb generated a 21-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one assist, two steals and one block. Domantas Sabonis provided 18 points, 17 boards, four assists and two blocks. Justin Holiday and Doug McDermott contributed eight points apiece.

The Cavaliers return home to face the Dallas Mavericks on Sunday evening, while the Pacers remain home to tangle with the Chicago Bulls on Sunday afternoon as well.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the host Orlando Magic, 123-91, at Amway Center on Friday evening. 

The Magic got out to a good start at home with a 20-7 lead five minutes into the contest, but the Bucks outscored the hosts 24-7 through the rest of the quarter to take a 31-27 lead into the second. The Bucks continued to dominate in the second, where they outscored the Magic by 17 in the quarter, to take a 21-point lead into halftime. The Magic came out better in the third quarter and managed to outscore the visitors by four, to cut the deficit to 17 entering the fourth. The Bucks would not leave anything to chance as they kicked it up a gear in the fourth and outscored the Magic by 15 in the quarter to run away with the road win. 

Giannis Antetokounmpo led the Bucks with 29 points, 14 rebounds, six assists and two steals, in 30 minutes. Eric Bledsoe followed up with 18 points, six rebounds and six assists, while Khris Middleton added 16 points on 7-of-9 shooting. The Bucks shot 50 percent from the field, including 17-of-47 from long range. The Bucks out rebounded the Magic by 16 and scored 40 fast-break points. 

Meanwhile, Evan Fournier led the Magic with 19 points on 7-of-12 shooting, in 21 minutes. Nikola Vucevic added 14 points, seven rebounds, two assists, two steals and a block. The Magic shot 37 percent from the field, including 12-of-37 from long range. 

The Magic (2-3) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nuggets on Saturday. The Bucks (3-2) play host to the Raptors on Saturday.

The Boston Celtics defeated the visiting New York Knicks, 104-102, at TD Garden on Friday evening. 

The Celtics jumped out to a quick 10-4 lead, but the Knicks kept with it and rallied back to take a 23-22 lead by the end of the first quarter. The score stayed tight through the second, while both teams tallied 27 points in the quarter, to give the Knicks a 50-49 lead by halftime. The third quarter featured more hard-fought basketball, with the Celtics managing to claim a one-point advantage heading into the final frame. The Knicks did not let up and forced the game down to the wire, as they tied it at 102 with 4.7 seconds left. However, the Celtics went to Jayson Tatum, who sank the game winner for Boston with one second left on the clock. This marks the fourth straight win for the Celtics and the second straight loss for the Knicks. 

Kemba Walker led the Celtics with 33 points on 8-of-19 shooting, in 35 minutes. Jayson Tatum followed up with 24 points on 9-of-17 shooting. Gordon Hayward and Grant Williams were the only other players to score in double digits for Boston. The Celtics shot 45 percent from the field, including 11-of-34 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Marcus Morris led the Knicks with 29 points on 8-of-17 shooting, in 39 minutes. R.J. Barrett added 15 points, seven rebounds and five assists, while Kevin Knox II chipped in 12 points off the bench. The Knicks shot 40 percent from the field, including 14-of-39 from long range. 

The Knicks (1-5) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Kings on Sunday. The Celtics (4-1) take on the Cavs in Cleveland on Tuesday.

The Chicago Bulls defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 112-106, at United Center on Friday evening. 

The Bulls got out to a good start at home, with a 10-4 lead early and took a 30-23 lead into the second. The Bulls pushed their lead to 12 early in the second, but the Pistons outscored the hosts 23-17 through the rest of the quarter, to cut the deficit to five by halftime. The Bulls reclaimed control early in the third, as they pushed their lead to 16 mid way through the quarter, but the Pistons trimmed it back to a six-point game going into the final frame. The Pistons kept pushing and tied it up at 96 with five minutes left but the Bulls closed the game on a 16-10 run to secure their first home win of the season. 

Zach LaVine led the Bulls with 26 points on 8-of-20 shooting, in 32 minutes. Otto Porter Jr. had a solid outing with 22 points, six rebounds and four assists, while Wendell Cater Jr. tallied 16 points, 11 rebounds and two assists. The Bulls shot 44 percent from the field, including 16-of-40 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Andre Drummond led the Pistons with 25 points, 24 rebounds, three blocks, two steals and two assists, in 35 minutes. Derrick Rose added 23 points, seven assists and three steals, in 24 minutes off the bench, while four other players scored in double digits for Detroit. The Pistons shot 48 percent from the field, including 6-of-29 from deep. 

The Pistons (2-4) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Nets on Saturday. The Bulls (2-4) take on the Pacers in Indiana on Sunday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the host Dallas Mavericks in overtime, 119-110, at American Airlines Center on Friday. 

There were seven ties and 12 lead changes in the second half alone, as that eventually led to an overtime session. Danny Green actually hit a game-tying three-pointer at the end of regulation to send the game into OT and then the Lakers started the overtime session on a 7-0 run to take command. Dallas never tied or re-captured the lead from there, with Los Angeles outscoring them in the OT session, 16-7. Defense was critical for the Lakers, holding the Mavericks to 39 percent from the field while winning the turnover differential, 22-11. Much of that was due to Los Angeles recording 11 steals and seven blocks to Dallas' five steals and one block. The Lakers ended up shooting 49 percent from the field too.  

The Lakers (3-1) got a triple-double from LeBron James, who accumulated 39 points, 12 rebounds, 16 assists and four steals. Anthony Davis accrued 31 points, eight rebounds, two assists, two steals and two blocks. Green scored 14 points while Avery Bradley totaled 11 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. 

The Mavericks (3-1) also got a triple-double from their best player, with Luka Doncic collecting 31 points, 13 rebounds and 15 assists. Kristaps Porzingis amassed 16 points and nine boards. Dwight Powell finished with 14 points and five boards while Delon Wright led the bench with 12 points, one rebound and two assists.

Both teams will return to action on Sunday, with Los Angeles traveling to face the San Antonio Spurs and Dallas facing the Cleveland Cavaliers on the road as well.

The Sacramento Kings defeated the visiting Utah Jazz, 102-101, at Golden 1 Center on Friday.

While Sacramento held the lead for the entirety of the first half, this game wasn't decided until the final shot. In fact, Harrison Barnes made a putback lay-up with three seconds left to give the Kings a one-point lead and their first win of the season. There were 11 ties and 12 lead changes in total with neither team leading by more than 12 points. That putback emphasized the key for Sacramento, winning the offensive rebounding battle, 11-6. The Kings had two bench players reach double figures in scoring while the Jazz had none.

The Jazz (4-2) were led by Donovan Mitchell, who tallied 24 points, four rebounds, two assists and three steals. Mike Conley collected 19 points, four rebounds, four assists and four steals. Bojan Bogdanovic amassed 17 points, six rebounds and two assists while Rudy Gobert totaled 15 points, 16 rebounds and two blocks.

The Kings (1-3) were led by De'Aaron Fox, who generated 25 points, five rebounds and four assists. Buddy Hield finished with 18 points and five boards. Barnes accumulated 13 points, six rebounds, three assists and three steals in addition to his game-winner. Dewayne Dedmon and Bogdan Bogdanovic were the two bench players to score in double figures, combining for 24 points and nine boards.

Both teams return to action on Sunday, with Utah traveling to face the Los Angeles Clippers. As for Sacramento, they travel to face the New York Knicks.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the host Golden State Warriors, 127-110, at Chase Center on Friday.

While there were eight ties and nine lead changes in the first 30 minutes of this game, San Antonio dominated from there. In fact, the Spurs rode a 40-31 third quarter to take an 11-point lead and capped things off with a 30-24 fourth quarter. San Antonio actually won all four individual quarters. Their bench was huge, dropping 68 points while grabbing 24 boards. In addition, the Spurs won the rebounding battle, 51-39 while shooting 48 percent from the field, 37 percent from three-point range and 87 percent from the free-throw line.

The Spurs (4-1) were led by Patty Mills, who provided 31 points, three rebounds and two assists off the bench. LaMarcus Aldridge tallied 22 points and eight rebounds. DeMar DeRozan amassed 13 points and 11 assists. Bryn Forbes scored 14 points while Trey Lyles led the team with 14 rebounds. Rudy Gay scored 16 points off the bench while Jakob Poeltl generated nine points and 10 boards.

The Warriors (1-4) were led by D'Angelo Russell, who finished with 30 points, three rebounds and eight assists on 9-of-24 shooting. Jordan Poole totaled 20 points and one assist. Draymond Green accumulated six points, eight rebounds and seven assists. Damion Lee led the bench with 16 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

Golden State will have to play the second half of a back-to-back set on Saturday against the Charlotte Hornets. San Antonio returns to action on Sunday, playing host to the Los Angeles Lakers.

The Miami Heat defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 106-97, at State Farm Arena on Thursday night.

The Heat (4-1) came into the Halloween night affair looking to get the best of the Hawks (2-3) for the second time this week and sweep the home-and-home series. Miami had a sizable personnel advantage going in with Trae Young ruled out for Atlanta due to the ankle injury he'd suffered in Tuesday's matchup. After a strong start by the home team, the visitors took control and didn't really look back. After the Heat found itself down 14-8 with 6:50 remaining, they outscored their hosts by a 98-83 margin the rest of the way. With Young out, the Hawks' bench did the majority of the scoring for the team on the night, compiling 60 of the team's 97 points. 

Kendrick Nunn paced the Heat with 28 points, complementing them with two rebounds and two steals. Tyler Herro furnished 17 points, four rebounds, three assists and one steal. Meyers Leonard registered 16 points, eight rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Bam Adebayo and Duncan Robinson, the latter who started for Justise Winslow (back), posted 12 points each, with Adebayo also dishing out seven assists and pulling in six boards. Jimmy Butler shot just 2-for-10 on his way to five points, but he added 11 assists, nine rebounds, six steals and three blocks. 

Jabari Parker led the way for the Hawks with 23 points, adding eight rebounds and two assists. DeAndre' Bembry provided 18 points, 10 rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Tyrone Wallace and John Collins contributed matching 12-point tallies while pulling down three and seven rebounds, respectively. Cam Reddish's shooting struggles continued with nine points on a 2-for-11 mark from the floor. 

The Heat heads back home to take on the Houston Rockets on Sunday evening, while the Hawks are off until Tuesday night when they host the San Antonio Spurs.

The New Orleans Pelicans defeated the visiting Denver Nuggets, 122-107, at Smoothie King Center on Thursday evening. 

The contest got out to a competitive start as the Pelicans held a slight edge for most of the first quarter before taking a two-point lead into the second. They pushed their lead to nine early in the second but the Nuggets trimmed it back to a four-point game by halftime. The Pelicans kept the intensity up in the second half as they outscored the visitors 30-23 in the third, to take an 86-75 lead into the final quarter. The Pelicans pushed their lead to 14 just minutes into the fourth and went on to outscore the Nuggets by four in the quarter and secure their first win of the season. This marks the second consecutive loss for Denver.

Jahlil Okafor led the Pelicans with 26 points on 8-of-13 shooting, in 34 minutes. Brandon Ingram followed up with 25 points, five assists and three rebounds, while Jrue Holiday stuffed the stat sheet with 19 points, seven assists, five rebounds and two steals. The Pelicans shot 53 percent from the field, including 15-of-33 from long range. 

Meanwhile, in his first action of the regular season, Michael Porter Jr. was the high-point man for the Nuggets with 15 points on 5-of-8 shooting, in 21 minutes off the bench. Jamal Murray and Jerami Grant added 14 points each, while Nikola Jokic finished with 13 points, six rebounds and six assists. The Nuggets shot 48 percent from the field, including 7-of-26 from deep. 

The Nuggets (3-2) will look to bounce back as they take on the Magic in Orlando on Saturday. The Pelicans (1-4) visit OKC to take on the Thunder on Saturday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the visiting San Antonio Spurs, 103-97, at Staples Center on Thursday.

There were 10 ties in this game, with neither team winning any quarter by more than three points. With that said, the Clippers won each of the final three quarters, holding the lead for the entirety of the second half. Turnovers were the difference in the game, with Los Angeles winning that battle, 18-11. Both benches came up big, with the Clippers scoring 44 bench points and the Spurs dropping 42 points off their bench. Three-point shooting kept San Antonio around, with Los Angeles shooting just 5-of-27 and the Spurs connecting on 7-of-21.

The Spurs (3-1) were led by DeMar DeRozan, who tallied 29 points, seven rebounds and two assists. No other starter reached double figures in scoring. Derrick White was the only other player in double figures, providing 20 points, five rebounds, two assists and two blocks off the bench. LaMarcus Aldridge finished with just five points, five rebounds and three assists.

The Clippers (4-2) got a gem from Kawhi Leonard, with the former San Antonio player collecting 38 points, 12 rebounds and four steals. Parick Beverley accumulated eight points, four rebounds and five assists. Montrezl Harrell led their bench with 24 points and four boards while Lou Williams amassed 12 points and five assists.

The Spurs have to play the back end of a back-to-back on Friday, traveling to face the Golden State Warriors. The Clippers are off until Sunday when they face the Utah Jazz at home.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the Chicago Bulls, 117-111, at Quicken Loans Arena on Wednesday night.

The Bulls (1-4) came in looking to capitalize on an opportunity against a fellow losing squad in the Cavaliers (2-2). However, the two teams proved to be closely matched from the start, with Chicago holding a slim 53-50 halftime advantage. They continued to match each other basket for basket in the third period before Cleveland finally found a way to pull away late. The home squad finished the game on a 9-5 run after the Bulls had managed to pull to within 106-104 with 2:52 remaining, leading to the hard-fought home win. 

Lauri Markkanen and Zach LaVine co-led the Bulls with 16 points apiece, with Markkanen adding eight rebounds. Wendell Carter, Jr. and Otto Porter, Jr. followed with matching 15-point tallies, pulling down eight and five rebounds, respectively. Thaddeus Young paced the second unit with 14 points, five rebounds, one assist and one steal. 

Tristan Thompson paced the Cavaliers with 23 points, complementing them with 10 rebounds, two assists and five blocks. Collin Sexton furnished 18 points, two rebounds and two assists. Kevin Love and Jordan Clarkson went for 17 points each, with Love also pulling down 20 rebounds, dishing out six assists and recording one steal. Cedi Osman and Larry Nance, Jr. posted 12 points apiece.

The Bulls head back home to take on the Detroit Pistons on Friday night, while the Cavaliers hit the road and tangle with the Indiana Pacers on Friday evening.

The Orlando Magic defeated the New York Knicks, 95-83, at Amway Center on Wednesday night.

The Magic (2-2) were coming off back-to-back losses and recently lost against the reigning NBA champions, the Toronto Raptors, on Monday night. But Orlando bounced back with a strong performance against a Knicks (1-4) squad seriously hampered by injuries. However, the Knicks got off to a better start here, winning the first quarter by three points (25-22) and leading by two at the half-time break (44-42). The Magic would break free in the second half as they flipped the script with a 30-23 third-quarter score, and closed things out with a 23-16 edge in the final 12 minutes of action. New York didn't have answers to contain Orlando in the second half.

Nikola Vucevic led the way for the Magic with 21 points and 13 rebounds, while adding four assists. Aaron Gordon had a double-double as well, finishing with 15 points and 11 rebounds. Jonathan Isaac filled the stat sheet admirably for the Magic, as he ended the contest with 10 points, seven rebounds, four assists and three blocks. Evan Fournier had 14 points, three rebounds and three assists. All 10 Magic players that stepped on the hardwood had at least two points.

Julius Randle was New York's biggest scoring threat since he finished with 16 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists. Mitchell Robinson had 12 points, five rebounds, three blocks, and two assists. Bobby Portis had 12 points and 10 rebounds off the bench, while Kevin Knox contributed 10 points. Marcus Morris Sr. disappointed, though, after going 2-for-11 from the field and finishing with only nine points.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the visiting Minnesota Timberwolves, 117-95, at Wells Fargo Center on Wednesday.

A 32-24 first quarter really set the tone in this game and then a 30-19 second quarter put the game to bed. In fact, the Sixers held a double-digit lead for the entirety of the second half. Philadelphia ended up shooting 47 percent from the field and 36 percent from three-point range while holding Minnesota to 40 percent from the field and 29 percent from long range. The Sixers doubled up the T'Wolves in assists 24-12 while out-rebounding them, 56-34. Both Karl-Anthony Towns and Joel Embiid got ejected in the third quarter due to a scuffle. 

The Timberwolves (3-1) were led by Andrew Wiggins, who tallied 19 points, five rebounds and two assists. Jeff Teague amassed 15 points and five assists. Towns accrued 13 points, six rebounds and two steals before being ejected. Shabazz Napier led the bench with 13 points and two steals. 

The Sixers (4-0) were led by Embiid, who accumulated 19 points, five rebounds and two assists. Tobias Harris totaled 18 points, nine rebounds and two assists. Ben Simmons generated 16 points, three rebounds, seven assists, three steals and two blocks. Al Horford finished with 12 points, 16 rebounds and four assists. James Ennis III nearly double-doubled off the bench, totaling eight points and 11 rebounds. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Philly traveling to face the Portland Trail Blazers and Minnesota facing the Washington Wizards on the road as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 116-105, at TD Garden on Wednesday night. 

Following a humiliating loss to the 76ers on Opening Night, the Celtics (3-1) had seemingly righted their ship by notching victories in their next two games. However, a difficult challenge in the form of the Bucks (2-2) awaited Wednesday, and things looked bleak for the home squad early when Milwaukee forged a 34-19 lead through the first 12 minutes. Then, the surge that would result in Boston outscoring their visitors by a 97-71 margin the rest of the way began with a much more competitive second quarter. The Celtics were at their best in the third, erasing a 16-point halftime deficit and entering the final period with a four-point lead. Eventually, a 13-7 run over the first 5:25 of the fourth quarter helped the Celtics gain enough separation for the victory.

Khris Middleton led the Bucks with 26 points, adding six boards and three assists. Giannis Antetokounmpo generated a 22-point, 14-rebound double-double that also included five assists, two blocks and one steal. George Hill delivered 12 points, five rebounds and two assists. Brook Lopez collected 10 points, three rebounds, two assists and two blocks. Eric Bledsoe mustered just seven points, five rebounds and five assists. 

Kemba Walker led a big night for the first unit with 32 points, supplementing them with six rebounds and six assists. Jayson Tatum totaled 25 points, four boards, two assists and one block. Gordon Hayward contributed a 21-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included seven assists, one steal and one block. Marcus Smart chipped in 19 points, six assists and four rebounds, while Daniel Theis drew the start at center and put up 11 points, nine boards, one assist and one block.

The Bucks continue on the road and head south to play the Orlando Magic on Friday night, while the Celtics remain home to tangle with the New York Knicks on Friday evening.

The Indiana Pacers defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 118-108, at Barclays Center on Wednesday night.

The Pacers (1-3) finally secured their first win of the season and it couldn't have come at a better time, as they did on the road and against one of the -- at least on paper -- top teams in the Eastern Conference such as the Nets (1-3). Despite the fact Indiana lost Myles Turner to injury early in the first half and the fact Brooklyn were leading after the first two quarters by three points (63-60), the Pacers didn't rattle and used a big performance in the second half to turn things around. Indiana won the third quarter by a 30-20 score, and sealed the deal with a 28-25 effort in the final 12 minutes of action. Their second-half turnaround was pivotal to seal the deal.

Domantas Sabonis was Indiana's best player since he finished with 29 points, eight rebounds, four assists and one block. Jeremy Lamb had 25 points and seven rebounds, while Malcolm Brogdon came just two boards shy of a triple-double -- he finished with 21 points, 13 assists and eight rebounds. T.J. Warren had 20 points. Myles Turner had seven points in 10 minutes before leaving the game with a right ankle injury.

Kyrie Irving led the Nets once again since he finished with 28 points, seven rebounds and six assists. Caris LeVert had 15 points with six rebounds, and Joe Harris chipped in with 13 points. DeAndre Jordan only scored eight points, but grabbed a game-high 17 rebounds. Spencer Dinwiddie had 20 points and seven assists in 27 minutes off the bench.

The Charlotte Hornets defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 118-111, at Golden 1 Center on Wednesday evening. 

After a tight start the Kings opened up a 12-point lead late in the first but the Hornets mounted a 13-4 run to cut the deficit to three by the end of the quarter. The Kings reclaimed some momentum early in the second as they pushed their lead to 11, but the Hornets rallied back to make it a five-point game by halftime. The Hornets came out strong in the third and had the game tied up at 75, mid way through the quarter. They kept pushing and outscored the Kings 32-18 in the quarter, to take a nine-point lead into the final frame. The Hornets increased their lead to 14, four minutes into the fourth. The Kings kept fighting but could not make up the difference, as they dropped their fifth straight game to start the season. 

P.J. Washington led the Hornets with 23 points on 10-of-13 shooting, in 36 minutes. Terry Rozier tallied 22 points, six assists, five rebounds, three steals and two blocks, while Cody Zeller added 12 points, 15 rebounds and five assists. The Hornets shot 55 percent from the field, including 16-of-32 from deep. 

Meanwhile, Buddy Hield was the high-point man for the Kings, with 23 points on 8-of-22 shooting. Harrison Barnes followed up with 22 points, seven rebounds and three steals, while De'Aaron Fox tallied 16 points, 10 assists, seven rebounds and two steals. The Kings shot 46 percent from the field, including 14-of-46 from long range. 

The Kings (0-5) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Jazz on Friday. The Hornets (2-3) take on the Warriors in Golden State on Saturday.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the visiting Detroit Pistons, 125-113, at Scotiabank Arena on Wednesday.

While there were four ties and five lead changes in the first quarter, that was the only time the lead changed hands in this game. In fact, Toronto held the lead for the final three quarters, as a 37-28 first quarter set the tone while a 37-27 third quarter put the game to bed. The Raptors shot a season-best 59 percent from the field and 48 percent from three-point range while holding Detroit to 47 percent shooting. Toronto also recorded 12 steals to Detroit's five while winning the turnover differential, 20-14. 

The Pistons (2-3) were led by Andre Drummond, who accumulated 21 points, 22 rebounds and three assists. Markeiff Morris amassed 16 points, five rebounds and two assists. Langston Galloway led the bench with 17 points while Derrick Rose provided 16 points and 10 assists. 

The Raptors (4-1) were led by Pascal Siakam, who generated 30 points, five rebounds, five assists and two steals with 18 of those points coming in the fourth quarter. Kyle Lowry accrued 20 points, five rebounds, eight assists and two steals. Fred VanVleet totaled 13 points and 11 assists while Serge Ibaka led the bench with 19 points, six rebounds, two assists and two steals. 

On deck for the Pistons is a road matchup with the Chicago Bulls on Friday. As for Toronto, they return to action on Saturday when they travel to face the Milwaukee Bucks.

The Houston Rockets defeated the Washington Wizards, 159-158, at Capital One Arena on Wednesday night. 

A game that will likely go down as one of the most exciting in NBA regular-season history showed its colors right from the start, with the two teams combining for 69 first-quarter points and the halftime score reading a very third-quarter-like 77-76 in favor of the Wizards (1-3). After Washington added another five points to their advantage during the third, they appeared in position to pull away. However, James Harden, who totaled a game-high 59 points, wouldn't let the Rockets (3-1) give up, and ultimately, it was his ability to draw a foul with 2.4 seconds remaining, make one of two free throws, and then secure the ball to run off the final ticks after missing the second one that secured the wild win for Houston.

Harden added nine assists, three rebounds and one steal to his game-high scoring tally. Clint Capela generated a 21-point, 12-rebound double double that also included three assists, one steal and one block. Russell Westbrook contributed a 17-point, 12-assist, 10-rebound triple-double that also included two steals and one block. Danuel House, Jr. followed with 16 points, seven boards, one assist, two steals and one block. Eric Gordon led the bench with 15 points, while Austin Rivers pitched in 11.

Bradley Beal led the Wizards with 46 points and also dished out eight assists, pulled down six rebounds and recorded three steals. Rui Hachimura continued the strong start to his career with 23 points and five rebounds. Davis Bertans tallied 21 points, three boards and two assists. Isaiah Thomas managed a 17-point, 10-assist double-double that also included two rebounds and one steal. Troy Brown supplied 14 points in his season debut, while Thomas Bryant posted a 13-point, 12-rebound double-double.

The Rockets next pay a visit to the Brooklyn Nets on Friday night, while the Wizards are home against the Minnesota Timberwolves on Saturday evening.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the host Oklahoma City Thunder, 102-99, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Wednesday. 

There were nine ties and 15 lead changes in this competitive game, with neither team ever attaining a double-digit lead. With that said, OKC led by three points with six minutes remaining but Portland went on a 15-6 run after that to take control of the game with just three minutes remaining. The key for the Trail Blazers was three-point shooting, with Portland hitting 17-of-35 and Oklahoma City connecting on just 4-of-27. In addition, the Blazers quadrupled the Thunder in blocks, 8-2. 

The Trail Blazers (3-2) were led by Damian Lillard, who tallied 23 points, seven rebounds, 13 assists and two steals. C.J. McCollum amassed 22 points, four rebounds and three assists. Hassan Whiteside totaled 12 points, 12 rebounds, two steals and two blocks while Kent Bazemore led the bench with 14 points and five boards. 

The Thunder (1-4) were led by Chris Paul, who accrued 21 points, five rebounds, five assists and two steals. Danilo Gallinari generated 15 points and six boards. Nerlens Noel got a rare start and finished with 15 points and 14 rebounds. Shai Gilgeous-Alexander accumulated 13 points, eight rebounds and three assists. 

Both teams return to action on Saturday, with Oklahoma City playing host to the New Orleans Pelicans and Portland welcoming the Philadelphia 76ers to Moda Center.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting Los Angeles Clippers, 110-96, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Wednesday evening. 

After trailing early on, the Jazz closed the first quarter on a 12-2 run to take a 10-point lead into the second quarter. The Clippers answered in the second as they outscored the Jazz by nine, to make it a one-point game by halftime. The Jazz burst out of the gates in the third with a 16-6 run and took an 11-point lead before the halfway mark in the quarter. They went on to outscore the Clippers by 18 in the quarter and take a 19-point lead into the fourth. The Clippers kept fighting but had no answer, as the Jazz held on for their third straight win. 

Mike Conley had his best game so far as a member of the Jazz, as he led the way with 29 points on 11-of-17 shooting, in 32 minutes of action. Donovan Mitchell tallied 24 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals, while three other players scored in double digit to lift the Jazz. The Jazz shot 55 percent from the field, including 11-of-24 from long range. 

Meanwhile, with Kawhi Leonard (rest) out, Lou Williams got the start and led the Clippers with 24 points on 9-of-17 shooting, in 27 minutes. JaMychal Green tallied 23 points and eight rebounds, in 27 minutes off the bench, while Montrezl Harrell was the only other player to score in double digits for L.A. The Clippers shot 48 percent from the field including 8-of-23 from deep. 

The Clippers (3-2) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Spurs on Thursday. The Jazz (4-1) take on the Kings in Sacramento on Friday.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the host Golden State Warriors, 121-110, at Chase Center on Wednesday evening. 

The Suns got out to a blazing start as they poured in 43 points in the first quarter. The Warriors picked it up in the second but despite a hard-fought quarter, trailed 72-46 at halftime. The Suns did not let up and added another two points to their lead through the third quarter to take a 95-67 lead into the final frame. The Warriors kept fighting and poured in 43 points in the fourth but the Suns were still able to maintain a healthy lead and held on for their third win of the season. Unfortunately for the Warriors, Stephen Curry was forced to leave the contest in the third quarter after suffering an injury to his hand.

Devin Booker led the Suns with 31 points on 10-of-21 shooting, in 36 minutes. Aron Baynes had himself a monstrous outing with 24 points, 13 rebounds, seven assists and three blocks, while Dario Saric chipped in 16 points, nine rebounds, five assists and five steals. The Suns shot 46 percent from the field, including 15-of-37 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Eric Paschall led the Warriors with 20 points on 7-of-9 shooting, in 37 minutes. D'Angelo Russell tallied 15 points, six rebounds and six assists, while Stephen Curry was quiet with nine points on 3-of-11 shooting, in 21 minutes before exiting the match. The Warriors shot 44 percent from the field, including 8-of-28 from deep. 

The Warriors (1-3) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Spurs on Friday. The Suns (3-2) take on the Grizzlies in Memphis on Saturday.

The Miami Heat defeated the Atlanta Hawks, 112-97, at American Airlines Arena on Tuesday night.

The Heat (3-1) was coming off a loss the last time out, but they did a great job to bounce back at home and in the season debut of Jimmy Butler, who missed the team's previous three games due to paternity leave. Miami quickly jumped to a 29-26 lead in the first quarter, and Miami never looked back afterwards. Atlanta saw star point guard Trae Young leave the game due to an ankle injury in the second quarter, and the Hawks couldn't adjust to the absence of their top scorer. Miami won the subsequent three quarters 30-23 and 29-21 respectively, essentially putting the game out of reach with 12 minutes left to play. Atlanta won the final quarter 27-24, but the Heat didn't lose grip of the game and cruised towards a comfortable 15-point win.

Tyler Herro was Miami's top scorer after scoring 29 points with seven rebounds off the bench. Jimmy Butler enjoyed a strong debut with the Heat, scoring 21 points to go along with five rebounds, three steals and two assists. Kendrick Nunn had 17 points with three assists, while Bam Adebayo delivered 17 points, 10 rebounds, three blocks, three assists and two steals. Goran Dragic had 21 points, three rebounds and three assists off the bench.

John Collins was Atlanta's main offensive threat and finished with 30 points, seven rebounds and four assists. Trae Young only had five points in 11 minutes before leaving due to injury. Jabari Parker had 12 points off the bench, and was the only other Atlanta player who scored in double digits. However, it's worth noting that all 12 Atlanta players that saw action scored at least three points.

The Dallas Mavericks defeated the host Denver Nuggets, 109-106, at Pepsi Center on Tuesday evening. 

The Nuggets jumped out to a quick 10-point lead to start the contest but the Mavericks stayed within reach as they managed to make it a four -point game heading into the second. The scored stayed tight in the second, while the Mavs tied it up at 45 half way through the quarter and briefly held a small lead before the Nuggets closed the half with a one-point advantage. The Nuggets pushed up to a nine-point lead mid way through the third but once again the Mavs would not lose touch and cut the deficit to five heading into the fourth. The Mavs began the fourth on a 17-4 run and took a 100-92 lead four minutes into the quarter. The Mavs did not look back as they held on for their second road win of the season. This marks the Nuggets' first loss of the season. 

Nine different players scored in double digits for the Mavs as it was a total team effort that lifted them past their formidable opponent. Kristaps Porzingis tallied a double-double with 10 points and 14 rebounds, while Tim Hardaway Jr. and Maxi Kleber led the way in scoring with 14 points each. The Mavs shot 49 percent from the field, including 13-of-37 from deep. They tallied 29 assists on 41 field goals and limited themselves to just eight turnovers.

Meanwhile, Paul Millsap was the high-point man for Denver with 23 points on 9-of-17 shooting. Nikola Jokic tallied a triple-double with 10 points, 10 rebounds and 10 assists, while Will Barton finished with 19 points and 11 rebounds. The Nuggets shot 47 percent from the field, including 11-of-32 from deep. 

The Nuggets (3-1) will look to bounce back as they take on the Pelicans in New Orleans on Thursday. The Mavericks (3-1) play host to the Lakers on Friday.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Memphis Grizzlies, 120-91, at Staples Center on Tuesday.

While there were 10 ties and seven lead changes in the first 31 minutes of this game, Los Angeles took control in the third quarter. In fact, the Lakers finished that quarter on a 29-2 run across the final seven minutes, giving them a game-high 21-point lead at the time. That was simply too much for the Grizzlies to overcome, never getting the game within 18 points from there. Los Angeles dominated the paint, winning the defensive rebounding battle, 44-33, while out-blocking Memphis, 8-3. The Lakers ended up shooting 47 percent from the field while holding the Grizzlies to 33 percent from the field and 21 percent from long range. 

The Grizzlies (1-3) got a double-double from Jonas Valanciunas, who totaled 14 points, 11 rebounds and two assists. Ja Morant accrued 16 points, three rebounds, two assists and two steals. Derrick Brooks collected eight points, three rebounds and four assists while Grayson Allen led the bench with 13 points, five rebounds and two steals. 

The Lakers (3-1) were led by Anthony Davis who finished with 40 points, 20 rebounds, two assists and two blocks while going 26-of-27 from the free-throw line in just three quarters of action. LeBron James accumulated 23 points, two rebounds and eight assists. Avery Bradley amassed 12 points, three rebounds and two steals. Kentavious Caldwell-Pope led the bench with 13 points, six rebounds and three assists.  

On deck for the Lakers is a road matchup with the Dallas Mavericks on Friday. As for the Grizzlies, they're off until Saturday, when they play host to the Phoenix Suns.

The Detroit Pistons defeated the Indiana Pacers, 96-94, at Little Caesars Arena on Monday night.

The Pistons (2-2) moved back to .500 with a solid performance although the game was far from settled until the final minutes of the contest. The hosts, however, came out on top thanks to a huge driving layup from Derrick Rose with less than 30 seconds left that kept the Pacers (0-3) winless thus far. The game saw Detroit starting the contest on top, however, as they jumped to an eight-point lead after the first quarter. Indiana, however, won the second quarter to keep things close. A low-scoring third quarter saw Detroit up by one in the third period (19-18) and while Indiana won the final quarter (23-18), it wasn't enough to turn things around and the Pistons secured their second win of the campaign.

Derrick Rose might have made the winning bucket, but he struggled throughout the game and finished with 10 points (on 16 shots) and six assists. Andre Drummond had a double-double of 18 points and 18 rebounds, as well as two blocks. Christian Wood had a double-double off the bench with 19 points and 12 rebounds off the bench. Luke Kennard delivered 14 points, four assists and three rebounds.

Domantas Sabonis led the way for the Pacers with 21 points and 14 rebounds. T.J. Warren had 19 points, five rebounds and five steals. Myles Turner delivered 16 points while also grabbing five rebounds. Malcolm Brogdon chipped in with 15 points, and also added 11 assists with eight rebounds. Edmond Sunmer disappointed in the starting lineup with only five points.

The New York Knicks defeated the visiting Chicago Bulls, 105-98, at Madison Square Garden on Monday. 

Despite the fact that Chicago had an eight-point lead with 3:10 left, the Knicks were able to prevail in this game. They actually finished the game scoring 15 unanswered points, forcing the Bulls to miss their final five shots while grabbing three offensive boards in that span. That capped off a 33-18 fourth quarter in favor of the Knicks. Chicago actually led 33-15 after the first quarter and that late run was the only time the Knicks led. Rebounding was the clear-cut difference for the Knicks, out-rebounding the Bulls, 63-38. 

The Bulls (1-3) were led by Zach LaVine, who tallied 21 points, five rebounds and three assists. Wendell Carter Jr totaled 20 points, 10 rebounds, two assists and three blocks on 7-of-9 from the field. Lauri Markkanen amassed 18 points, six rebounds and two assists. Thaddeus Young led the bench with 15 points and four rebounds. 

The Knicks (1-3) were led by Bobby Portis, who came off the bench to provide 28 points, 11 rebounds and two assists. R.J. Barrett led the starters with 19 points, 15 rebounds and five assists. Julius Randle accumulated 13 points, 14 rebounds and five assists while Mitchell Robinson totaled 10 points, nine rebounds and two blocks.

Both teams return to action on Tuesday, with Chicago traveling to face the Cleveland Cavaliers and New York playing the Orlando Magic on the road as well.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the host Atlanta Hawks, 105-103, at State Farm Arena on Monday. 

There were nine ties and nine lead changes in this competitive matchup, as it wasn't decided until the final shot. In fact, Joel Embiid hit two free throws with five seconds left to break a tied game and then Vince Certer missed a three at the buzzer to give Philly the win. The key for the Sixers was their rim protection, recording 11 blocks while the Hawks had just three. In addition, Philly hit 78 percent from the free-throw line while Atlanta connected on just 69 percent from the charity stripe.

The Sixers (3-0) were led by Embiid, who finished with 36 points, 13 rebounds, five assists and three steals while hitting those game-winning free throws. Josh Richardson accrued 14 points, five rebounds, three assists and three blocks. Tobias Harris amassed 13 points, five rebounds and five assists while Ben Simmons accumulated 13 points, six rebounds and six assists. 

The Hawks (2-1) were led by Trae Young, finishing with 25 points, four rebounds and nine assists on just 7-of-20 from the field. John Collins totaled 16 points and eight boards. De'Andre Hunter generated 14 points and nine rebounds while Bruno Fernando led the bench with 11 points, four rebounds and two assists. 

Atlanta has a quick turnaround, as they have to travel to face the Miami Heat on Tuesday. As for Philly, they play host to the Minnesota Timberwolves on Wednesday for their next fixture.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the Orlando Magic, 104-05, at Scotiabank Arena on Monday. 

The Raptors (3-1) continued their strong start to the season and remain undefeated at home as they cruised their way against the Magic (1-2), where a strong start was everything the reigning NBA champions needed to secure their second home victory is as many games on Canadian soil. Toronto jumped to a 31-22 lead after the first quarter, but the Magic showed a will to fight and reduced Toronto's lead to five points after a 24-20 second quarter. Toronto came out firing in all cylinders after the break (27-21) and while Orlando won the final quarter 28-26, it wasn't enough. Toronto cruised their way down the stretch in a comfortable win.

All five starters from Toronto scored in double digits in this game. Kyle Lowry led the way with 26 points, six assists and five rebounds, while Pascal Siakam delivered 24 points while grabbing nine boards. Fred VanVleet chipped in with 14 points, six assists and five boards. O.G. Anunoby thrived on both sides of the ball, notching 12 points, eight rebounds, five steals and two dimes. Marc Gasol had 10 points with 10 rebounds.

Jonathan Isaac was Orlando's best player since he finished with 24 points, but he also added seven rebounds, three steals and two blocks. Evan Fournier had 18 points, while D.J. Augustin had 10 points. Markelle Fultz scored 13 points while adding five assists, and Terrence Ross had 11 points -- both off the bench. Nikola Vucevic disappointed, however, with five points (1-13 from the field) while adding 12 boards.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting Oklahoma City Thunder, 116-112, at Toyota Center on Monday evening. 

The first quarter started off close until the Thunder went on a 21-8 run in the final four minutes to take a 35-22 lead into the second. They held strong and maintained a double-digit lead for most of the second quarter before taking a 10-point lead into halftime. The Rockets came alive in the third and outscored the visitors by 21 in the quarter to take an 11-point lead into the fourth. They held a good cushion to start the fourth but the Thunder managed to cut it to a three-point game with four minutes to go. The Thunder battled right down to the wire and only trailed by two with seven seconds left but James Harden hit two free throws to seal the second straight win for the Rockets. 

Harden led the Rockets with 40 points on 8-of-21 shooting, while Russell Westbrook finished with 21 points, 12 rebounds and nine assists. P.J. Tucker had a solid outing with 17 points and nine rebounds, while Clint Capela tallied 15 points, seven rebounds an three blocks. The Rockets shot 43 percent from the field, including 10-of-44 from long range. 

Meanwhile, Shai Gilgeous-Alexander and Dennis Schroder led the Thunder with 22 points each. Danilo Gallinari tallied 17 points, five rebounds and three assists, while Chris Paul finished with 15 points, five rebounds, four assists and two steals. The Thunder shot 44 percent from the field, including 13-of-35 from long range. 

The Thunder (1-3) will look to bounce back as they play host to the Trail Blazers on Wednesday. The Rockets (2-1) take on the Wizards in Washington on Wednesday.

The Milwaukee Bucks defeated the Cleveland Cavaliers, 129-112, at Fiserv Forum on Monday night.

The Bucks (2-1) won their first home game of the season in dominant fashion, as they cruised their way towards a strong over a Cavaliers (1-2) team that started strong, but faded away down the stretch. Cleveland won the first quarter 31-30, but that was the only advantage they would get during the contest. The Bucks won the remaining three quarters 29-21, 32-28 and 38-32, respectively, as they dominated the final 36 minutes of action towards an easy win in front of their crowd.

Seven Milwaukee players scored in double digits ahead of this game. Khris Middleton led the way for the Bucks with 21 points, eight rebounds and two assists. Brook Lopez had 16 points with five boards, while Giannis Antetokounmpo delivered 14 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists. Eric Bledsoe had 14 points with eight assists and four rebounds, while Wesley Matthews had 14 points with three boards. George Hill chipped in with 19 points and Pat Connaughton added 17 points off the bench.

Kevin Love and Tristan Thompson were once again the best players for the Cavaliers in this match as both posted double-doubles here -- while Love had 15 points and 16 rebounds, Thompson chipped in with 17 points and 13 boards and four assists. Collin Sexton had 18 points with three rebounds, and Cedi Osman delivered 10 points. Jordan Clarkson had 17 points and four assists coming off the bench.

The Golden State Warriors defeated the New Orleans Pelicans, 134-123, at Smoothie King Center on Monday night.

The Warriors (1-2) came into the night in the completely unfamiliar position of being winless two games into the campaign, but they were impressive while forging a four-point lead through one quarter. It was in the second when Golden State took control of the game, racking up 45 points to establish a 17-point halftime advantage. After adding another seven points to their edge in the third, the Warriors coasted through a fourth quarter that saw the Pelicans (0-4) compile 44 points to make the final margin of defeat for New Orleans a bit less lopsided.

Stephen Curry paced the Warriors with 26 points, adding 11 assists, three rebounds and three steals. Backcourt mate D'Angelo Russell followed with 24 points, eight assists and seven rebounds. Damion Lee led the bench with 23 points, complementing them with 11 rebounds and two assists. Draymond Green contributed a 16-point, 17-rebound, 10-assist triple-double that also included two steals. Jordan Poole poured in 13 points, while Glenn Robinson fell just short of a double-double with 12 points and nine rebounds.

Brandon Ingram led the Pelicans with 27 points, 10 rebounds, six assists and two steals. Jaxson Hayes furnished 19 points, three rebounds, one assist, one steal and one block. Kenrich Williams totaled 16 points, six boards, two assists, three steals and one block. Nickeil Alexander-Walker followed with 15 points, nine assists, four rebounds and one steal. Lonzo Ball and Josh Hart had matching 12-point tallies, with Ball adding nine assists.

The Warriors head back home to face the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday night, while the Pelicans remain home to tangle with the Denver Nuggets on Thursday night.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Portland Trail Blazers, 113-110, at AT&T Center on Monday evening. 

The Trail Blazers got out to a blazing start with a 24-4 lead halfway through the first quarter. The Spurs began chipping away and cut it to a six-point game by halftime. The Spurs came out strong in the third and outscored the visitors by 17 in the quarter to take an 11-point lead into the final frame. The Spurs led by 17 halfway through the fourth but the Trail Blazers closed the game on a 24-10 run that finished just short of an epic comeback. The Spurs held on to earn their third straight win and third home win of the season. 

DeMar DeRozan led the Spurs with 27 points on 10-of-16 shooting, seven rebounds and two steals, in 33 minutes. Derrick White added 21 points, five rebounds and three assists off the bench, while LaMarcus Aldridge tallied 15 points, seven rebounds, five blocks and three assists. The Spurs shot 48 percent from the field, including 7-of-22 from deep. They tallied 25 assists on 41 field goals, but gave up 18 turnovers. 

Meanwhile, Damian Lillard led Portland with 28 points, nine rebounds, seven assists and two blocks, in 39 minutes. C.J. McCollum added 27 points, five assists and three rebounds, while Anthony Tolliver tallied five points, 10 rebounds and three assists. The Blazers shot 39 percent from the field, including 10-of-33 from deep. They limited themselves to 10 turnovers and tallied 18 fast-break points. 

The Trail Blazers (2-2) will look to bounce back as take on the Thunder in OKC on Wednesday. The Spurs (3-0) take on the Clippers in L.A. on Thursday.

The Utah Jazz defeated the Phoenix Suns, 97-95, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Monday night.

The Suns (2-2) had looked like an improved team throughout their first three games despite the absence of Deandre Ayton (suspension) for two of those contests, but the first quarter played out much like past games against the Jazz (3-1). Utah forged a 28-21 lead after the first 12 minutes, but Phoenix managed to prevent the deficit from getting any larger prior to halftime and then eliminated it altogether during the third period. That set up a back-and-forth final period, which boiled down all the way to the final second. That's when Devin Booker was whistled for a shooting foul against Donovan Mitchell, who drained both subsequent free throws to snap a 95-95 tie and clinch the win.

Bojan Bogdanovic paced the Jazz with 29 points, adding five rebounds, two assists, two steals and one block. Mitchell finished with 26 points, three assists, two rebounds and two steals. Rudy Gobert generated a 15-point, 18-rebound double-double that also included one assist, two steals and one block. Jeff Green led the second unit with eight points.

Booker led the Suns with 21 points, supplementing them with three rebounds, one steal and one block. Kelly Oubre, Jr. delivered 18 points, three rebounds, three assists, two steals and one block. Jevon Carter managed 15 points, four boards, three assists and two steals. Aron Baynes collected 12 points and three rebounds, while Ricky Rubio generated a 10-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included eight assists. 

The Jazz head back home to take on the Los Angeles Clippers on Wednesday night, while the Suns travel to face off with the Golden State Warriors on Wednesday evening as well.

The Denver Nuggets defeated the host Sacramento Kings, 101-94, at Golden 1 Center on Monday evening. 

The Nuggets got out to a quick start on the road with a 12-3 lead early on but the Kings rallied back to take a 28-21 lead into the second quarter. The Kings held the lead through the second and took a six-point advantage into halftime. The Nuggets came out strong in the third and tied the score at 65 halfway through the quarter. They then closed the quarter on a 12-5 run to take a seven-point lead into the final frame. The Kings cut the deficit to two late in the fourth but Nuggets held on for their third straight win, while this marks the fourth straight loss for the Kings.

Gary Harris was the high-point man for the Nuggets, with 17 points on 5-of-9 shooting. Jamal Murray finished with 18 points, while Nikola Jokic tallied nine points, 13 rebounds, two assists and two steals. The Nuggets shot 37 percent from the field, including 10-of-36 from long range. They hauled in 56 rebounds, including 21 offensive. The Nuggets also limited themselves to 11 turnovers. 

Meanwhile, Richaun Holmes led the Kings with 24 points, 13 rebounds and two blocks in 30 minutes. De'Aaron Fox followed up with 20 points, nine assists, three rebounds and a steal, while Harrison Barnes and Nemanja Bjelica tallied 12 points each. The Kings tallied 25 assists on 36 field goals and scored 21 fast-break points. 

The Kings (0-4) will be searching for their first win as they take on the Hornets in Charlotte on Wednesday. The Nuggets (3-0) play host to the Mavericks on Tuesday.

The Los Angeles Clippers defeated the Charlotte Hornets, 111-96, at Staples Center on Monday night. 

Despite the difference in their records and talent, the Hornets (1-3) and Clippers (3-1) played a highly competitive first half. Los Angeles held a modest 57-54 halftime lead, but the home squad began to assert itself in the third quarter by widening their advantage to 12 points entering the final period. The Clippers were then able to tread water during the fourth quarter, leading to a comfortable home victory.

Terry Rozier led the Hornets with 17 points, adding three rebounds, two assists, one steal and one block. Malik Monk furnished a bench-leading 15 points, complementing them with one rebound, one assist, one steal and one block. Cody Zeller and Devontae Graham generated matching 14-point tallies while pulling down 13 and 12 rebounds, respectively. PJ Washington posted 11 points, seven rebounds and two steals. Bismack Biyombo collected 10 points, three rebounds and three assists. 

Kawhi Leonard led the Clippers with 30 points and also turned in seven rebounds, six assists, three blocks and two steals. Lou Williams followed with a bench-leading 23 points and also supplied four rebounds, four assists and one steal. Montrezl Harrell chipped in 19 points, seven rebounds, two assists and two steals. Landry Shamet registered 16 points, four rebounds, two assists and one steal. 

The Hornets remain on their West Coast swing and tangle with the Sacramento Kings on Wednesday evening, while the Clippers hit the road and face the Utah Jazz on Wednesday night as well.

The Oklahoma City Thunder defeated the Golden State Warriors, 120-92, at Chesapeake Energy Arena on Sunday.

The Thunder (1-2) claimed their first win of the season thanks to an impressive effort on both sides of the court, as the Warriors (0-2) looked overmatched on both ends of the court as soon as the ball started bouncing in front of a sell-out 18,203 crowd at Oklahoma City. The Thunder quickly jumped to a 35-20 lead after the first quarter, and they never looked back. In fact, Oklahoma City scored exactly 35 points in each of the first three quarters, while the Thunder topped the 21-point mark just once. The result was Oklahoma City building a 105-68 lead entering the final 12 minutes of action. The Warriors won the final quarter 24-15, but that wasn't enough to mount a comeback and the Thunder won deservedly.

Despite coming off the bench, Dennis Schrder was the best player for the Thunder since he finished with 22 points, eight rebounds, six assists and four steals. Danilo Gallinari had 21 points, while Shai Gilgeous-Alexander finished with 19 points, nine rebounds and four dimes. Veteran point guard Chris Paul had 10 points in 19 minutes, while Terrance Ferguson chipped in with 13 points and four assists.

Stephen Curry was the top scorer for the Warriors since he finished with 23 points, eight rebounds and five assists. Draymond Green contributed 10 points but also added six rebounds, two steals and two assists. Marquese Chriss and Eric Paschall also contributed 10 points to the mix. No other Golden State player reached the 10-point mark. D'Angelo Russell only finished with six points while going 3-for-10 from the field.

The Memphis Grizzlies defeated the Brooklyn Nets, 134-133, at FedEx Forum on Sunday evening.

The Grizzlies (1-2) and the Nets (1-2) played one of the most intense games during the 2019-20 young NBA season so far, as this contest was decided down the stretch thanks to a buzzer-beating three-pointer from Jae Crowder when the clock expired during the overtime period. Memphis jumped to a six-point lead after the first quarter, but the Nets won the following two quarters, 28-24 and 40-33 respectively, so they had a five-point lead entering the final 12 minutes of action. Memphis stormed back, though, and a driving layup from Ja Morant sent the game to overtime. The game was about to expire in overtime with the Nets leading by two points, but Crowder scored a buzzer-beating three-pointer to lift the hosts towards a huge win.

Rookie point guard Ja Morant led the way for Memphis with 30 points, nine assists and four rebounds. Dillon Brooks scored 21 points, and Jonas Valanciunas chipped in with 16 points, 11 rebounds and four assists. Jaren Jackson Jr. had 12 points, and three bench players scored in double digits as well. These were Kyle Anderson (13 points, four rebounds), Solomon Hill (13 points, five rebounds) and Brandon Clarke (10 points, seven rebounds).

Kyrie Irving led the way for the Nets with 37 points, seven rebounds and seven assists. Caris LeVert had 27 points with five assists. Joe Harris had 13 points, while Taurean Prince had 12 points, six rebounds and two assists. Spencer Dinwiddie had 16 points with eight assists, while Jarrett Allen chipped in with 14 points and 13 boards.

The Los Angeles Lakers defeated the visiting Charlotte Hornets, 120-101, at Staples Center on Sunday.

While there were 10 ties and 11 lead changes in the first half, the Lakers took care of business in the second half. In fact, Los Angeles held the lead for the entirety of the second half, thanks to a 24-18 third quarter and a 33-21 fourth quarter. Los Angeles' defense was the difference, holding Charlotte to just 39 percent from the field and 29 from three-point range. The Lakers ended up shooting 53 percent from the field and 36 percent from long range while out-assisting the Hornets, 30-19. In addition, Los Angeles outscored Charlotte in the paint, 74-44. Bench production was also critical, with the Lakers bench outscoring the Hornets bench, 48-17.

The Hornets (1-2) were led by Miles Bridges, who totaled 23 points, six rebounds and three assists. Cody Zeller amassed 19 points, 14 rebounds, three steals and three blocks. Terry Rozier accumulated 19 points, six rebounds and four assists while Dwayne Bacon generated 15 points, six rebounds and two assists. DeVonte' Graham led the bench with nine points, three rebounds and five assists. 

The Lakers (2-1) were led by Anthony Davis, who collected 29 points, 14 rebounds, three assists and three blocks. LeBron James finished with 20 points, six rebounds and 12 assists. Dwight Howard was huge off the bench, providing 16 points, 10 rebounds and four blocks on 8-of-8 from the field. Quinn Cook accrued 12 points, three rebounds and eight assists off the bench as well.

Things won't get any easier for the Hornets, as they have to play the Clippers in the second half of a back-to-back set on Monday. As for the Lakers, they play host to the Memphis Grizzlies on Tuesday for their next fixture.

The Portland Trail Blazers defeated the host Dallas Mavericks, 121-119, at American Airlines Arena on Sunday evening. 

The Mavericks got out to a scorching start as they poured in 40 points in the first quarter, while holding the visitors to 25 points. The Trail Blazers picked it up in the second and outscored the Mavs 34-31 in the quarter, but still trailed by 12 at halftime. The Blazers kept the momentum going in the third quarter and outscored the Mavs by exactly 12, to tie the score at 95, entering the fourth and final frame. Portland pulled ahead by six early in the fourth but Dallas had it tied up at 113 with four minutes remaining. The Mavs led by one with 35 seconds left, before Damian Lillard hit the go-ahead bucket for the Trail Blazers. Dallas ended up with one last shot after a missed free throw by Portland, however, they were not successful and tallied their first loss of the season. This marks the second win in a row for the Trail Blazers, as they improve to 2-0 on their current four -game road trip. 

C.J. McCollum led the Trail Blazers with 35 points, six rebounds, four assists and two steals, in 41 minutes. Damian Lillard tallied 28 points, while Rodney Hood added 20 points. The Trail Blazers shot 52 percent from the field, including 9-of-22 from long range, and tallied 24 fast-break points. 

Meanwhile, Kristaps Porzingis led the Mavs with 32 points, nine rebounds, five assists and two blocks, in 34 minutes. Luka Doncic finished with 29 points, 12 rebounds, nine assists and three steals, in 38 minutes. The Mavs shot 39 percent from the field, including 13-of-50 from deep, and tallied 27 assists in comparison to 11 turnovers. 

The Mavericks (2-1) will look to bounce back as they take on the Nuggets in Denver on Tuesday. The Trail Blazers (2-1) take on the Spurs in San Antonio on Monday.

The Minnesota Timberwolves defeated the Miami Heat, 116-109, at Target Center on Sunday night.

It was an interconference battle of undefeated squads, with the Timberwolves (3-0) establishing superiority early by forging a 36-23 lead through the first 12 minutes. However, the Heat (2-1) came back with equal ferocity in the second period and headed into halftime with a slim two-point advantage. After adding another five points to their edge in the third, the visitors subsequently saw Minnesota go on a 28-15 run over the final 7:37 to seal the win.

Kendrick Nunn paced the Heat with 25 points, adding four rebounds, two assists and two steals. Duncan Robinson furnished 21 points, two rebounds, one assist and two blocks. Justise Winslow continued his strong start with 20 points, adding eight rebounds, six assists, two blocks and one steal. Bam Adebayo and Goran Dragic generated matching 13-point tallies while pulling down nine and five rebounds, respectively. 

Andrew Wiggins led the Timberwolves with 25 points, including four three-pointers in the final six minutes, and also tallied six rebounds. Karl-Anthony Towns generated a 23-point, 11-rebound double-double that also included four assists, two steals. and one block. Jeff Teague went for 21 points, eight assists, one rebound and one steal. Shabazz Napier paced the second unit with 12 points, while Robert Covington contributed an 11-point, 10-rebound double-double.

The Heat returns home to face the Atlanta Hawks on Tuesday evening, while the Timberwolves hit the road to take on the Philadelphia 76ers on Wednesday night.

The Miami Heat defeated the Milwaukee Bucks, 131-126, in overtime at Fiserv Forum on Saturday evening. 

The Heat (2-0) once again took the floor without Jimmy Butler (personal) and Dion Waiters (suspension/coach's decision), but the same formula that worked in an impressive opening night win over the Grizzlies came through again. Goran Dragic continued to thrive in a bench role by scoring a team-high 25 points, and four of the five members of the starting five notched double-digit scoring. Miami mounted a furious comeback from a 70-53 halftime deficit, but four consecutive missed free throws at the end of regulation left the door open for a Giannis Antetokoumpo tip-in at the buzzer to send the game to overtime. In the extra period, the Heat's 8-1 run left the Bucks (1-1) too far behind to catch up.

Dragic added eight assists, six rebounds and one steal to his team-leading tally. Bam Adebayo followed with a 19-point, 13-rebound, eight-assist double-double that also included one block. Kendrick Nunn poured in 18 points and added five assists, four rebounds and two steals. Tyler Herro, Derrick Jones, Jr. and Kelly Olynyk all contributed 14 points apiece. Justise Winslow pitched in a 10-point, 13-rebound, seven-assist effort.

Antetokounmpo paced the Bucks with 29 points, complementing them with 17 rebounds, nine assists, three steals and two blocks. Khris Middleton managed 25 points, four rebounds, three assists and one steal. Wesley Matthews and Kyle Korver provided 14 points each. Brook Lopez contributed 12 points and seven rebounds, while Ersan Ilyasova managed 11 points, five boards, one assist and one steal.

The Heat remain on the road and next face the Minnesota Timberwolves on Sunday evening, while the Bucks remain home and tangle with the Cavaliers on Monday night.

The Philadelphia 76ers defeated the Detroit Pistons, 117-111, at Little Caesars Arena on Saturday night.

The 76ers (2-0) came in facing an uphill battle to a road win, considering Joel Embiid (ankle) was ruled out in the hours prior to tip-off. However, as has been the case in the past, that simply meant the rest of the starting five had to pick up the slack. Tobias Harris was certainly up to the task, putting up a team-high 29 points and adding seven rebounds, one assist and two steals. The game was a back-and-forth tussle through four quarters, but a 10-2 Philadelphia run in the latter stages of the final period helped seal the win over the Pistons (1-2). 

Al Horford followed Harris with 23 points, adding nine rebounds, five assists and one steal. Mike Scott furnished 17 points, three rebounds and one assist. Ben SImmons generated a 13-point, 10-assist double-double that also included four rebounds and seven steals. Josh Richardson and Shake Milton posted matching 10-point tallies.

Derrick Rose paced the Pistons with 31 points, adding three rebounds, three assists, three steals and two blocks. Markieff Morris managed 17 points, six rebounds, one assist, two steals and one block. Luke Kennard supplied 16 points, two assists and one rebound. Andre Drummond posted a 13-point, 12-rebound double-double that also included one assist and two blocks. Christian Wood collected 11 points and five rebounds. 

The 76ers remain on the road and take on the Atlanta Hawks on Monday night, while the Pistons remain at home to take on the Indiana Pacers on Monday evening as well.

The Atlanta Hawks defeated the Orlando Magic, 103-99, at State Farm Arena on Saturday night. 

The Hawks (2-0) erased an early three-point deficit to forge a two-point halftime advantage. The back-and-forth tussle persisted through the third quarter, and following a Michael Carter-Williams dunk with 6:43 remaining in the final period, the Magic (1-1) held a 90-85 lead. Atlanta then finished the contest on an 18-9 run, including a 6-2 tally after the game was knotted at 97 with 1:55 to go. 

Evan Fournier led the Magic with 23 points, adding three rebounds, two assists and one steal. Nikola Vucevic generated a 16-point, 10-rebound double-double that also included one assist, one steal and one block. D.J. Augustin delivered 14 points, four assists and two rebounds. Markelle Fultz led the bench with 12 points, while Aaron Gordon tallied 10 points, seven rebounds, three assists and two steals.

Trae Young paced the Hawks with 39 points, complementing them with nine assists, seven rebounds and two steals. Jabari Parker and Kevin Huerter poured in 10 points apiece. John Collins posted nine points, 12 rebounds, one assist and four blocks. De'Andre Hunter and Cam Reddish delivered six points apiece while in the starting five.

The Magic pay a visit to the Toronto Raptors on Monday night, while the Hawks remain home to tangle with the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday evening as well.

The Boston Celtics defeated the host New York Knicks, 118-95, at Madison Square Garden on Saturday evening. 

The Knicks got out to a great start at home and led 13-2, four minutes into the first quarter. The Celtics battled back, but the Knicks held on to a two-point lead at the end of one quarter. The home team kept their focus through the second quarter and pushed their lead to 51-46 by halftime. However, the Celtics came to play in the third and outscored the Knicks 36-25 in the quarter, to take an 82-76 lead into the final frame. The Celtics held nothing back as they poured in another 36 points in the fourth and held the Knicks to just 19 in the quarter, to secure the 23-point road win. This marks the second win in two nights for the Celtics and the second loss in two nights for the Knicks. 

Kemba Walker led the Celtics with 32 points on 11-of-17 shooting, in 30 minutes of action, while four other players scored in double digits to complete the effort. The Celtics shot 45 percent from the field, including 15-of-421 from long range. They tallied 25 assists in comparison to 12 turnovers and tallied 21 fast-break points. 

Meanwhile, R.J. Barrett continued an impressive start to his career as he led the Knicks with 26 points on 9-of-20 shooting, seven rebounds and three assists, in 37 minutes. Julius Randle added 10 points and 10 rebounds, while Mitchell Robinson tallied 17 points six rebounds and three blocked shots. The Knicks shot 39 percent from the field, including 7-of-27 from long range. 

The Knicks (0-3) will look for their first win as they play host to the Bulls on Monday. The Celtics (2-1) have a nice break before they play host to the Bucks on Wednesday.

The Cleveland Cavaliers defeated the visiting Indiana Pacers, 110-99, at Rocket Mortgage Fieldhouse on Saturday.

While Indiana came into this game as the favorite, a 39-20 second quarter in favor of Cleveland was too much to overcome. In fact, the Cavaliers led by at least six points for the entirety of the second half. Cleveland dominated down low, winning the rebounding battle, 44-36 while out-blocking them, 7-3. The Cavaliers also ended shooting 50 percent from the field while holding the Pacers to under 45 percent shooting. Cleveland drew a lot more whistles too, hitting 19-of-29 and Indiana connecting on 11-of-13.

The Pacers (0-2) were led by Malcolm Brogdon, who tallied 30 points, two rebounds and 10 assists. Domantas Sabonis finished with 14 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. Myles Turner amassed 11 points and 11 boards. Justin Holiday led the bench with 10 points, five rebounds, two assists and two steals. 

The Cavaliers (1-1) were led by Tristan Thompson, finishing with 25 points, 13 rebounds and three blocks on 11-of-16 from the field. Kevin Love totaled 21 points, 13 rebounds, nine assists and two steals. Collin Sexton accrued 18 points, five rebounds and three assists. Jordan Clarkson led the bench with 15 points, two rebounds and two steals.

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Indiana traveling to face the Detroit Pistons and Cleveland playing the Milwaukee Bucks on the road as well.

The Toronto Raptors defeated the host Chicago Bulls, 108-84, at United Center on Saturday evening. 

The contests got out to a competitive start as the Bulls held their own in the first quarter, before the Raptors took a one-point lead into the second. The Bulls kept up the tempo and led for most of the start of the second, however, the Raptors pulled ahead again as they closed the quarter on a 12-4 run. The Raptors came out on fire in the third where they outscored the Bulls 36-22 to push their lead to 22, heading into the fourth. The Raptors maintained their cushion through the fourth and held on for their second win of the season. 

Despite dealing with foul trouble early on, Pascal Siakam managed to lead the Raptors for the third straight game, as he finished with 19 points on 7-of-15 shooting, in 28 minutes. O.G. Anunoby had a solid outing with 17 points, six rebounds, four blocks, two assists and a steal, while Serge Ibaka added 18 points and seven rebounds, in 21 minutes off the bench. The Raptors shot 46 percent from the field, including 15-of-42 from long range. They tallied 27 assists but also 21 turnovers. 

Meanwhile, Wendell Carter Jr. led the Bulls with 12 points and 11 rebounds, in 23 minutes. Zach LaVine was the only other player to score in double digits for the Bulls as he followed up with 11 points on 4-of-13 shooting. The Bulls shot 30 percent from the field, including 9-of-35 from long range. They grabbed 12 offensive rebounds and scored 15 second-chance points. 

The Bulls (1-2) will look to bounce back as they take on the Knicks in New York on Monday. The Raptors (2-1) play host to the Magic on Monday.

The Houston Rockets defeated the visiting New Orleans Pelicans, 126-123, at Toyota Center on Saturday evening. 

The contest got out to a tight start before the Rockets pulled ahead to take a five-point lead by the end of the first quarter. The Pelicans fought hard through the second and managed to tie it up at 61 by halftime. They kept up the intensity in the third as they matched the Rockets bucket-for-bucket through the quarter and added one extra to take a three-point lead into the final frame. The Rockets used a 12-6 run in the fourth to gain a seven-point advantage with six minutes to go. The Pelicans kept chipping away and forced the Rockets to the edge as they made it a one-point game with six seconds left. However, Russell Westbrook went 2-of-2 from the foul line to secure the Rockets' first win of the season. 

Westbrook tallied a triple-double with 28 points, 13 assists and 10 rebounds, while James Harden tallied 29 points, five assists and four rebounds. Four other players scored in double digits for the Rockets, while as a team they shot 46 percent from the field, including 13-of-45 from long range. The Rockets tallied 27 assists on 43 field goals and scored 60 points in the paint. 

Meanwhile, Brandon Ingram led the Pelicans with 35 points, 15 rebounds and five assists, in 39 minutes. Josh Hart followed up with 23 points on 8-of-17 shooting, while Lonzo Ball finished with 18 points and 10 assists. The Pelicans shot 46 percent from the field, including 18-of-50 from long range. They tallied 27 assists on 46 field goals and scored 25 points off turnovers. 

The Pelicans (0-3) will be back in action on Monday when they play host to the Warriors. The Rockets (1-1) play host to the Thunder on Monday.

The San Antonio Spurs defeated the visiting Washington Wizards, 124-122, at AT&T Center on Saturday.

There were 17 ties and 23 lead changes in this tightly-contested game, with neither team ever attaining a double-digit lead. DeMar DeRozan played the hero, hitting a game-winning lay-up with five seconds left to break a tied game. Bradley Beal tried to respond with a contested lay-up but was unsuccessful.  Offensive rebounding was the difference in the game, with San Antonio winning that battle, 21-8. The Spurs ended up winning the turnover battle, 12-9, which allowed them to take 108 shots while the Wizards took just 95 shots. 

The Wizards (1-2) were led by Beal, tallying 25 points, five rebounds and 11 assists. Davis Bertans led the bench with 23 points and two rebounds on 7-of-7 from the field. Ish Smith accrued 19 points, five rebounds and four assists while Rui Hachimura totaled 16 points, eight rebounds and three assists. Isaiah Thomas made his season debut to finish with 16 points, three rebounds and five assists off the bench.

The Spurs (2-0) were led by LaMarcus Aldridge, as he collected 27 points, nine rebounds and three assists. DeRozan had 26 points, four rebounds and three assists in addition to that game-winner. Dejounte Murray accumulated 19 points, 10 rebounds and four assists while Bryn Forbes amassed 16 points, four rebounds and three assists.  

San Antonio will return to action on Monday, playing host to the Portland Trail Blazers. The Wizards won't play again until Wednesday, welcoming the Houston Rockets to Verizon Center.

The Utah Jazz defeated the visiting Sacramento Kings, 113-81, at Vivint Smart Home Arena on Saturday.

Utah came into this matchup as the favorite and a 32-point victory vindicates that notion. A 35-25 first quarter really set the tone and then a 31-16 second quarter put the game to bed. They weren't done there though, outscoring the Kings, 27-17 in the third and carrying a 35-point lead into the fourth quarter. Utah ended up out-rebounding Sacramento, 43-30 while out-assisting them 28-16. The Jazz shot 57 percent from the field and 49 percent from three-point range while holding the Kings to 37 percent from the field and 27 percent from long range. 

The Kings (0-3) had no player score more than 11 points, with Dewayne Dedmon leading the team with 11 points and six boards. De'Aaron Fox collected nine points and five assists. Bogdan Bogdanovic led the bench with 10 points, two rebounds and two assists. No player had more than 11 points, six rebounds, five assists, one steal or one block in the embarrassing loss.

The Jazz (2-1) were led by Bojan Bogdanovic, totaling 26 points and four rebounds on 10-of-18 from the field. Donovan Mitchell accrued 15 points and four assists. Mike Conley totaled 12 points, three rebounds and eight assists. Emmanuel Mudiay played well off the bench, providing 10 points, four rebounds and four assists. 

Both teams return to action on Monday, with Utah traveling to face the Phoenix Suns and Sacramento playing host to the Denver Nuggets.

The Phoenix Suns defeated the visiting Los Angeles Clippers, 130-122, at Talking Stick Resort Arena on Saturday.

There were five ties and nine lead changes in this tightly-contested game, but Phoenix was able to prevail. The Suns did most of their damage in the second half, outscoring the Clippers, 75-67. Ball movement was the difference for Phoenix, out-assisting Los Angeles, 32-20. That allowed the Suns to shoot 50 percent from the field and 40 percent from three-point range while holding the Clippers to 46 percent from the field and 34 percent from three-point range.
